<HEADLINE>
FORMER ASU PLAYER FIGHTS LEUKEMIA  
 PLUMMER, KUSH JOIN BENEFIT TO FUND BONE MAR ROW TESTING 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-CAJIC-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It climbed into Joe Cajic's car after a doctor's visit and
hasn't left his side since.
</P>
<P>
   Leukemia. It's what defines him.
</P>
<P>
   Cajic (pronounced CHYCH) is no longer simply the former Arizona
State lineman with a quick smile. He is the former Arizona State
lineman with a quick smile and a disease that makes him wait on a
very public death row.
</P>
<P>
   His only reprieve: a bone marrow transplant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready for the leukemia part,'' he said. ``I wasn't ready
for the `three years' part.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how long Cajic, 27, has been told he will live unless a
match is found for a transplant. No members of his family proved a
fit.
</P>
<P>
   His ``extended family,'' as he calls ASU, has teamed with United
Blood Services and the Joe Cajic Foundation to host a benefit at 5
p.m. today at Karsten Golf Course. Money raised from the autograph
party featuring Cardinals Jake Plummer, Pat Tillman, Mario Bates,
Frank Sanders, former ASU Coach Frank Kush and former quarterback
Jeff Van Raaphorst will be used to subsidize bone marrow testing
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Cajic had been bothered by back pain late last year, and it
became so severe that a co-worker called paramedics just days
before Christmas. Tests revealed an elevated white blood cell
count, and doctors delivered the news in a subsequent office visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't remember anything about the visit,'' he said.
``I'm amnesic about it. I remember before, telling everyone at the
office that I had to go out for lunch. And after, going back to
work. I can't remember everything else. I guess because it's kind
of scary.''
</P>
<P>
   For a week, he told no one. He was afraid of ruining the
holidays. On Dec. 30, he finally broke down and told his father,
Mike, because he needed someone to take him to the hospital for a
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation still haunts him:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad, I need your help. I need to have something done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have . . . leukemia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the hardest thing in the world to tell your parents you
might die,'' he said recently. ``I just remember the look on my
dad's face.''
</P>
<P>
   After the procedure, Cajic joined some friends at a cabin in
Payson for a few days. He had his father break the news to his
mother, Carol, while he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   His type of leukemia doesn't respond to chemotherapy, so he
takes medication daily. He does not wear the face of cancer, if
there is such a thing, but he is often exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a difficult adjustment for someone whose passions
include Russian literature and sports. Now, his athletic endeavors
are limited to bike rides, and even those wipe him out.
</P>
<P>
   He was Arizona's two-time 5A state discus champion and a
standout offensive lineman at Shadow Mountain High. He is 6 feet 5
now, only two inches taller than he was in seventh grade. His size
made for a challenging, albeit interesting, childhood.
</P>
<P>
   His first kiss, at 12, was with a 16-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't know how old I was,'' he said mischievously.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of the state's hottest recruits as a senior. One
afternoon while watching Southern California and Penn State play,
the phone rang. It was USC's recruiting coordinator, who handed the
phone to head Coach Larry Smith . . . ``during'' the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Hi, we really want you to come here,' '' Cajic said.
</P>
<P>
   He was sold, but USC proved a poor fit. After two seasons, he
transferred to ASU, where he started fives games during 1993 and
1994.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating, he tried his hand at several careers before
landing in the wholesale roofing business.
</P>
<P>
   He now generates his energy toward improving awareness for the
The National Marrow Donor Program. While the procedure to be placed
in the candidate pool is a simple blood test, the $40 cost that
accompanies it prevents many from testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The odds are slim,'' said Judy Bartholomeaux, Arizona's
National Marrow Donor Program presentative. ``But when you do find
that match . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Cajic understands that his odds are slim, but he's hoping for a
break. And he wants to help others as well.
</P>
<P>
   Cajic's parents are from Croatia. Even though a donor match
wouldn't have to be Croatian, Cajic's odds increase if there are
more Croatians in the pool.
</P>
<P>
   The Croatian community, which has some representation in the
Valley, has been notified.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was devastating for a while,'' Cajic said. ``And then you
realize you just have to take it one day a time, a lot like we
talked about when I played at ASU.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU Coach Bruce Snyder remembers Cajic as someone ``very
positive, upbeat. No chip on his shoulder at all. We felt he bought
into what we were trying to teach him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he seems to be handling what he's facing now much the same
way. He has the same spirit. Live for today.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
