<HEADLINE>
KEALY TO START AT QUARTERBACK VS. COUGARS  
</HEADLINE>
  STATE-QB-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ryan Kealy is back at starting quarterback, but he may not be
joined in the backfield by J.R. Redmond for Saturday game's at
Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond is ``50-50'' to play against the struggling Cougars,
Arizona State Coach Bruce Snyder said Monday. He was unable to
practice Sunday because of a sore toe on his left foot and a
sprained right ankle. He sat out the second half of ASU's 44-38
overtime victory against Stanford on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils were rallied to victory by Kealy, a sophomore who
completed 8 of 15 passes for 153 yards and two touchdowns,
including the game-winning 25-yard scoring pass to Tariq McDonald
in overtime. Kealy entered the game late in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went in there and looked like a quarterback who was really
alive,'' Snyder said. ``His arm was good, his tempo was good.
Something was right, because he played extremely well.''
</P>
<P>
   Redshirt freshman Chad Elliott was 9 for 17 for 92 yards in his
first start. Although Elliott left the field quickly after the game
and didn't linger for the players' post-game celebration, Snyder
said there is no animosity between the quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and I talked about it,'' Snyder said. ``I think he was
going through a lot of pain, or whatever that feeling is of
starting but not finishing a game. I believe him, that he was truly
happy for the football team, and he congratulated Ryan Kealy in his
own way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did what he felt was appropriate and right, and Ryan Kealy
will acknowledge that. I don't have a problem. I think he was
disappointed he didn't have the opportunity to finish it, which is
OK. And I think he is very supportive of Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder also backed Elliott's play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not displeased at all with Chad Elliott's preparation
for the game,'' he said. ``He did a nice job of preparing himself.
He did a nice job of managing the club in terms of signals and
clocks and formations. He threw the ball at about a 50 percent
completion rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy did not start for the first time in his career Saturday
after struggling much of the season. When he came in against
Stanford, he had the sharpness he displayed during much of the 1997
season.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder said he still believes strongly in committing to one
quarterback but acknowledged he won't be afraid to make a switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that as I look at my two quarterbacks, both of them are
talented young players with good arms, quick feet,'' he said. ``I'm
not so rigid that I don't see myself saying, `Hey, somebody's got a
hot hand, let's go with it,' because the bottom line, regardless on
my philosophy of playing one quarterback, is to figure out the very
best percentages to win the football game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a change is required, I would do that because the team
deserves that kind of a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils (3-4, 2-2 Pac-10) face a Washington State team
(3-4, 0-4) that has lost four consecutive conference games but
ranks fourth in the league in pass defense (and third in
interceptions with 11).
</P>
<P>
   ASU's defense, which has intercepted just three passes this
season, could find itself short-handed in the secondary again.
Starting strong safety Christon Rance is questionable because of a
strained left hamstring. If he is out, freshman Willie Daniel will
start.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Stephen Trejo, who has been sidelined much of the
season because of a knee injury, is expected to be available if he
recovers from a foot injury that has bothered him on and off
recently. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
