<HEADLINE>
BAIUL, MOCEANU FIND REALITY THE TOUGHEST CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oksana Baiul is in her hotel room, finally. For days we have
played phone tag, with the front desk staff at a Delaware Howard
Johnson's trying to flag down the now-in-serious-training skater.
</P>
<P>
   Now corraled, she is gushingly apologetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so sorry. I have been to the rink seven or eight hours a
day. I'm getting back into shape for my exhibition (which was this
past weekend in Boston) and a show coming up in November. I love
skating so much. I have been so hard practicing but my legs, they
feel good,'' Baiul said, her voice low and scratchy, a little
weary, but who would not be, after all she has been through?
</P>
<P>
   True to the achingly emotional persona Baiul portrayed during
her days as one of the world's best female figure skaters, nothing
this now 20-year-old woman does comes without overwhelming flashes
of raw honesty and vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of emotion and waifish spirit that helped the
then-16-year-old Baiul glide past Nancy Kerrigan at the 1994 Winter
Olympics in Lillehammer and win the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   But the glitter of gold for this teenage orphan could not
prevent the eventual crash and burn of a post-Olympic reality
check.
</P>
<P>
   With no family, with no secure, happy personal history to cling
to like a safety raft, Baiul became another symbol of teenage
female athletes whose best years are those before puberty, before
the mind and body break out and demand accountability for all those
years spent shuttling to practice.
</P>
<P>
   Just returning to the rink this past September felt like walking
through a minefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``My coach, Natalya Linichuk, she called and asked what I am
doing. I said not much. For 20 years of my life I am skating for my
family, for friends and I never had time for myself. So nothing.
That's what I am doing. I was too scared. I had so many burnouts, a
nervous breakdown.''
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible not to look at every female teenage skating
champion or gymnast or even tennis stars and not wonder when the
disaster will come? There has to be a cost for being so good, so
young. The mind and body can't bend that far without breaking.
Something has to give.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the news late last week that 17-year-old Olympic
gymnast Dominique Moceanu is suing her parents did not come as a
complete shock.
</P>
<P>
   At first, yes, there was surprise at the news. What other
response can a person have to the revelation that a very prominent,
seemingly well-adjusted teenager has instead been living with such
anxiety and distress that she is moved to legally separate from and
accuse her own parents.
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu, who won a gold medal at the 1996 Olympics in Atlanta
and whose autobiography was a bestseller, has asked the court in
Texas to grant her adult status. In her suit, Moceanu and her
attorney claim that Moceanu's parents have used most or all of the
money she has earned since winning her gold medal, including money
in a trust fund earmarked for the gymnast.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Moceanu nor her attorney know for sure how much money is
in question, but it could be in excess of $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   However, in a sport where an athlete peaks between ages 12 and
16, it is not surprising to see an elite gymnast like Moceanu make
a vigilant claim to what is rightfully hers.
</P>
<P>
   Did she have a childhood? In her court papers and in interviews,
Moceanu says absolutely not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always about the gym,'' she told reporters last week
and, for anyone who was looking, Moceanu had been exhibiting signs
of stress since at least 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm not in the gym, one of my favorite things to do is
just to relax quietly in my room, listening to music. Sometimes it
seems as if I hardly ever have time to do this! The demands of
training, schoolwork, competitions, public appearances _ they all
leave me with very little free time,'' Moceanu wrote in her best
seller.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my parents and I try to make sure I do get the occasional
chance to decompress.''
</P>
<P>
   In June 1996, Moceanu was one of the most heralded athletes at
the Olympic gymnastics trials in Boston. She had a stress fracture
in her leg and was having difficulty completing many of the
required moves. But she demonstrated enormous resolve for such a
young athlete.
</P>
<P>
   During those trials, Moceanu impressed me as one of the most
focused and poised athletes I had ever interviewed _ regardless of
the fact that she was only 14.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I was fooled, though. Maybe this girl with such awesome
athletic talent really was a tragedy waiting to happen, since up
until then her life had been nothing except gymnastics, about
becoming an Olympic champion _ as much for her driven father,
Dumitru, as for herself.
</P>
<P>
   In her book, Moceanu at least hints at the changes that will
grip her life and twist it into something so different from the
narrow, driven and hard-working world she had known.
</P>
<P>
   ``A gymnastics career won't last forever, as my body ages and
changes, gymnastics will become less of an option for me. When that
time comes, I have another life, another career planned,'' she
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Moceanu has gotten up the courage to lift her head
and get a broader view of her life. And apparently, what she sees
in the rear-view mirror is not all good.
</P>
<P>
   If this lawsuit is the start of a new beginning, it probably
will not be that easy. The road is difficult for these teenagers
whose lives narrow into a dead end from which they are almost
desperate to escape.
</P>
<P>
   That's the story Baiul is telling, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Though the circumstances of their lives are different, Baiul and
Moceanu share the same fate. They are teenage phenoms who came to
some sort of emotional, psychological crash upon reaching
adulthood, mostly because of their compromised growth experiences
as kid superstars.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two years ago, Baiul was spiraling into the depths of
alcoholism, which almost took her life. One late night in January
1997, she drove her new Mercedes into a tree alongside a
Connecticut road. She got 14 stitches and a benevolent judge who
sentenced her to community service.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the wide-eyed 18-year-old said she understood that
this accident was a sign that she needed help, it took months more
of personal anguish before Baiul removed herself from a
professional skating tour, declaring she could not take it anymore,
and sought professional help. This past summer, she checked herself
into a clinic in New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was supposed to stay 20 days. I stayed there much longer,
almost two and half months. So much damage done,'' said Baiul, who
could not come to grips with the losses in her life and found the
clinic's counselors extremely helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Baiul's mother died when she was 13. The young skater moved from
the Ukraine to Moscow, only to have her coach leave her too. Then
she hit the jackpot with her Olympic gold, which turned into
millions of dollars. By now she was living in America, home of the
free and the free-spending. All of her money was spent on a home,
her Mercedes, gifts for ``friends'' and trips into Manhattan for
nightclubbing and selections from the Versace racks.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the skating was just something her agent or friends
would push her to do. It became the thing that was killing Baiul,
entwined with her alcoholism. It was no longer the gift that set
her free.
</P>
<P>
   ``On tour, I was sitting by myself after shows, drinking a
lot,'' Baiul said. ``I was thinking suicidal things. About killing
myself. One day, I woke up at 9 a.m. and made a phone call (to her
agent). I said I have to get out of here. I don't want to die.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, after her agonizing struggle, Baiul is back on the
ice. She is talking about wanting to return to the Olympics in 2002
for a shot at another gold, though she knows skating officials will
have their say in that decision. She is no longer the 16-year-old
innocent she was when she won that first gold medal, with all the
world watching. Her body has grown five inches. She is now a
5-foot-5, 120-pound woman _ not a whirling dervish the way she once
was, the way Tara Lipinski was last February in Nagano, when
Lipinski became the latest teenage Olympic champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a very artistic person. I like to create new numbers and
new styles. I like to give everything inside me during a
performance, so that when they judge me and the people clap for me
I know I am doing this from inside me,'' Baiul said.
</P>
<P>
   But her first priority is to make sure that she is as whole and
as healthy as she can be. That is her biggest competition now, just
as it is for the 17-year-old Moceanu, whose entire life is supposed
to be ahead of her.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
