r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BICKLEY_BCSRATING     10-27 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BICKLEY_BCSRATINGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BCS RATINGS MAKE A BAD SYSTEM WORSE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ambiguity is for ice skating and ballroom dancing, not for a
sport dripping with machismo. Subjectivity is for gymnastics and
synchronized swimming, not for a sport that defines our country.
</P>
<P>
   Football demands finality. And it's completely un-American to
allow writers, coaches, computers and any bias that may exist
determine a national champion.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the world was treated to the first edition of the
Bowl Championship Series rating. Take the Championship away from
the BCS, and you get a better idea what this concept is all about.
And with UCLA on the top rung, you have the last piece of evidence
needed to warrant a playoff system.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State could finish No. 1 in both polls and get aced out of
the Fiesta Bowl. All because the Big Ten stinks and strength of
schedule might catapult Florida State all the way to Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Ohio State received 64 out of 70 first-place votes.
Its defense has held its past four opponents to 80 rushing yards or
fewer. But even with a 36-10 drubbing of Northwestern, it lost
ground in the BCS formula.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, two teams considered among Ohio State's toughest
opponents _ West Virginia and Missouri _ lost last weekend. So
while UCLA allows 408 yards per game and benefits from a conference
buoyed by Oregon and Arizona, Ohio State has one Top 25 opponent
left. The Buckeyes must beat Michigan and hope the formula works
out.
</P>
<P>
   It may not. Over the final five weeks, West Virginia and
Missouri play a combined six games against teams currently ranked
in the Top 25. Strength of schedule, one of four major criteria
used in the BCS formula, might sink the Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   It gets even worse. Even if Ohio State runs the table, it could
finish tied with Wisconsin atop the Big Ten. But because the two
teams won't play this season and because Ohio State has visited
Pasadena more recently than the Badgers, Wisconsin would get the
Rose Bowl bid.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, a broken system gets even worse.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough that we've seen two teams share the national
championship three times this decade. It would be even worse if the
best team were denied the opportunity to win the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   The solution seems so obvious. College football needs a playoff
system.
</P>
<P>
   It seems so easy. Take the top eight teams and put them in a
bracket. Designate seven sites and rotate them yearly. Run the
tournament over three weeks, watch the ratings and advertising
dollars soar, watch a country gravitate to the payoff of a real
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, watch the debate go from who's No. 1 to who's
No. 9.
</P>
<P>
   The suits that run college football don't want this because they
fear it would render all the other bowls useless, the ones that
boost the economy in remote outposts. They cry that a playoff
system would be far too demanding for student-athletes who can't
forget their studies.
</P>
<P>
   Such garbage. If they wanted, they could allow all the
lower-level bowls to remain intact, accommodating the alumni who
want their postseason road trips, pacifying the corporations that
give you gems such as the Weedeater Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   As for this genuine concern about a quarterback's GPA . . .
</P>
<P>
   Really. Do they care that a basketball road trip in the Pac-10
requires two days of missed classes? In the Big Ten, do they care
about the late-night bus trips from Illinois to Indiana? If so, why
is a playoff system OK in Division I-AA?
</P>
<P>
   All it would take is chopping one week off the season. And with
a month of inactivity, a month when most colleges are on Christmas
break, the system could be easily enacted.
</P>
<P>
   As the NFL wallows in mediocrity, filled with bad teams and
conservative coaches, the college game is missing a huge
opportunity. It is a game with more creativity, with hash marks and
the triple-option, with the unpredictability of college athletes.
In short, it is a better game than its professional counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   College football could be king.
</P>
<P>
   If it only had a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   If it only had a brain. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
