r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWELL-TVMORALS-LADN     10-27 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWELL-TVMORALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIRED GEN. COLIN POWELL ENTERS CULTURE WAR TO CLEAN UP HOLYWOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY IVAN SCIUPAC  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Retired Gen. Colin Powell is urging Hollywood
entertainment industry leaders to turn away from dysfunctional
images that he said permeate television airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   The former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff was speaking
Monday as the current chairman of Virginia-based America's Promise
_ The Alliance for Youth. Powell told industry executives,
producers, agents and writers to create more positive images for
the nation's youth in their programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have such power. Children watch what you put on the air _
they listen to you,'' Powell said at a luncheon at the Beverly
Hills Hilton Hotel sponsored by the Hollywood Radio and Television
Society.
</P>
<P>
   Powell urged the audience to crusade for children by being
positive role models and using television as a medium to focus on
character building for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a responsibility not only to satisfy the market that
is out there, but to help shape that market,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Perth, former president of USA Network, called the general's
speech ``sensational'' and agreed with his message.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a message of individual effort and individual
connection to our future, which is our children,'' Perth said.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said African-Americans can sometimes play roles on
television that can be dysfunctional and can have negative effects
on children.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is what it's all about then we might as well go back
to `Amos `n' Andy,''' Powell said, referring to a controversial
1950s television sitcom many civil rights groups believed fostered
racial stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to himself as an ``at-risk kid'' while growing up in
the New York's South Bronx, Powell credited his church group, an
after-school job and caring adults in the neighborhood for keeping
him out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   America's Promise _ The Alliance for Youth is a nonprofit
umbrella group to smaller organizations. The alliance's mission is
to improve the lives of the nation's kids through mentorship and
outreach programs.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, who has been the group's chairman since April 1997, used
the platform to echo five primary goals of the alliance, which he
said are necessary for children to lead a successful life:
</P>
<P>
   _ The expansion of existing mentorship and outreach programs.
</P>
<P>
   _ An increased number of safe havens such as the Boys &AMP; Girls
Club.
</P>
<P>
   _ A healthy start through vaccinations and medical exams.
</P>
<P>
   _ Extensive intern- and apprenticeships.
</P>
<P>
   _ More service-oriented programs for high school students.
</P>
<P>
   ``No child should be left at risk if there are those of us in
society who can do something,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Black, president and general manager of KNBC-TV in Los
Angeles, said television can help children by showing adults as
positive role models in the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can reflect to the community as a whole that if
they reach out to a young person at risk they can change the life
of that young person,'' Black said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
