</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGACE LIVING A DREAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Manny Legace ran out of clean clothes a couple of
cities ago. That's what happens when you pack for a few days and
are gone for two weeks. The Los Angeles Kings' goaltender has had
to wear the same moldy golf shirt four days in a row (no wonder
he's rooming alone). Luckily, Legace is holding up better than his
wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   What started out as an excursion with the Long Beach Ice Dogs
has turned into the experience of a lifetime for the 25-year-old
rookie who will make his fourth NHL start tonight in Long Island in
emergency relief of Stephane Fiset and Jamie Storr, both of whom
are nursing groin injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Legace (pronounced LEG-uh-see) has been a fine fit for the
Kings, stopping 92 of 96 shots for a save percentage of .958. He
faced 50 shots in his NHL debut against Florida last Wednesday and
stopped 49, all the while struggling to keep his pregame meal down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time I've felt nauseously nervous,'' Legace
said Monday by telephone from the team's hotel in Long Island.
``The (nausea) didn't go away until the second period.''
</P>
<P>
   The waves of familiar faces also left Legace slightly
disoriented. He could have sworn a hand had come bursting out of
his television screen at home and pulled him him into the set.
</P>
<P>
   Legace said he saw veteran Kirk Muller skating toward him at one
point and thought, ``I've been watching this guy play in the NHL
for years and now he's coming in on me. This is phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   By the third period, Legace had the Panthers muttering to
themselves. He heard one player say something to the effect of
``Geez, what does it take to get the puck past this guy?'' after
the player took a shot, collected the rebound off to the side and
tried unsuccessfully to wrap it around the goal.
</P>
<P>
   That night Legace was the windshield. Two days later he would
know what it was like to be the bug. He suffered a concussion in
the second period of the Kings' game at Tampa Bay when Darcy Tucker
rolled over him like a tank on his way to a short-handed score.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings went on to lose 3-2. Legace was back in the net for
the Kings' game Sunday at Carolina. The way he looked at it, given
the week he'd had, who was to say where the haziness ended and the
concussion began?
</P>
<P>
   Legace had another reason to feel better in a hurry. The
Hurricanes (nee Hartford Whalers) had left Legace to languish for
four years in the American Hockey League, the East Coast Hockey
League and the IHL. Even when it became clear their 1997-98 season
was beyond salvaging, the Hurricanes auditioned everybody, it
seemed to Legace, but him.
</P>
<P>
   So he was gleeful when he was dealt to the Kings on the last day
of July and gratified beyond words not quite three months later
when he stopped 29 of Carolina's 31 shots to post his first NHL
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question I'm happy to be out of that organization,'' said
Legace, who knew he wasn't with Carolina any more in September when
he was assigned to the Ice Dogs of the International Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Legace was planning to fly home to Massachusetts at his own
expense to see his wife Karen, their 3-year-old daughter Sabrina
and their son Manny III, who was born on Sept.6, when the Kings
intervened. They paid for his airline ticket and sent him off with
their blessings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just little things like that make players want to play harder
for a team,'' said Legace, who since has moved his family to Long
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The next soft NHL goal Legace lets in will be his first, which
makes you wonder: is it a dilution of talent or an abundance of
good goaltenders that's holding down the scoring in the league?
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Legace said, today's goaltenders are a
different breed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the '70s, they would say, `you can't skate, then you
have to play goalie,' '' Legace said. ``Now goalies are more agile
and more athletic.''
</P>
<P>
   To watch Legace in action is to marvel at his dexterity. But
he'll hear none of that. His wife, he'll tell you, is the really
nimble one in the family. It's beyond him how she juggles caring
for an infant and a 3-year-old in his absence.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, their rented apartment is never as quiet as the
visitors' dressing room was at the Panthers' new arena in Sunrise,
Fla., when Legace straggled in after his 49-save performance.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody said a word for what seemed like an eternity but was
probably more like 10 seconds. ``I thought somebody had died,''
said Legace, who began to sweat anew. He sat down, shifted
uncomfortably and thought, ``What? Are they mad at me for letting
in one goal?''
</P>
<P>
   That's about the time he heard a rumble coming from Craig
Johnson's direction. Johnson congratulated him in his best
``Fargo'' twang and everybody merrily joined in.
</P>
<P>
   Those Kings, they're such kidders.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a thick skin,'' Legace said, chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   And a quick glove hand doesn't hurt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
