<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOLEDO RESENTS RECEIVER REMARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Their bulletin board is filling up fast.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Bob Toledo took exception to a postgame comment
from Cal receiver Dameane Douglas, who said UCLA looked more like
the nation's No. 27 team than its No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas' remark _ five days after USC coach Paul Hackett called
Oregon the best team in the Pacific-10 _ followed UCLA's 28-16
victory Saturday in Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable to me,'' Toledo said. ``The guy catches 10
passes for 70 yards. My daughter can catch 10 passes for 70 yards
and lose. For guys to pop off when they lose doesn't show me
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas also made a throat-slitting motion while passing in
front of the UCLA bench with four minutes left and the Bruins in
control, according to a member of UCLA's travel party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's frustrating is when you're on top everybody
takes shots at you,'' Toledo said. ``But we aren't going to let it
affect us.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruised, not beaten: Quarterback Cade McNown absorbed more
pounding at Cal than any game this season _ perhaps any game of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   McNown arrived for his weekly media conference Monday with
protective padding on his left hand, the result of two bruised
knuckles and subsequent swelling. The padding was gone for
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``At no time was I at the point where I couldn't play,'' he
said. ``I'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Photogenic?: McNown got plenty of reaction to Sports
Illustrated's full-color photo of him vomiting in the Oregon game.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people wanted to know what I thought: Was it in poor
taste, or cool?'' he said. ``I thought it was a little of both. It
was funny to see other peoples' reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Roster changes: Toledo announced two depth-chart changes: Oscar
Cabrera will replace penalty-plagued Jim Ghezzi at left guard, and
Jermaine Lewis is once again the top tailback.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the starter until a one-game suspension for fighting,
gained 60 yards and threw a touchdown pass against Cal. Keith Brown
rushed for minus-4 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Top 10: McNown is one of 10 finalists for the Davey O'Brien
Award, given to the nation's top quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   His competition includes Kansas State's Michael Bishop,
Kentucky's Tim Couch, Central Florida's Duante Culpepper, Oregon's
Akili Smith and Ohio State's Joe Germaine.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Numerous players have bumps and bruises, strains
and sprains. But only one regular has been ruled out of the
Stanford game: freshman tailback DeShaun Foster, who's out at least
another week with a sprained knee suffered against Oregon. Foster
jogged during practice Monday but is not ready for full speed and
contact.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers Mike Wiley (ankle), Ramogi Huma (hip) and Tony White
(thigh, ankle) center Shawn Stuart (ankle), fullback Craig Walendy
(back) and kicker Chris Sailer (groin) are probable./``This is the
most beaten up we've been in my three years at this stage of the
season,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Short stuff: Tight end Ryan Neufeld and defensive end Vae Tata
are the captains this week, joining season-long selections McNown
and Larry Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   Atkins (fumble recovery, interception) was named Pac-10
defensive player of the week.
</P>
<P>
   McNown, defensive end Kenyon Coleman and Marques Anderson
(special teams) were named UCLA's players of the week.
</P>
<P>
   As the nickel back, Anderson also had five tackles and three
passes broken up in what Toledo called, ``his best game this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got an intensity to him. He's playing hard,'' Toledo
said. ``The other two guys (Ryan Roques and Jason Bell) are playing
so well at cornerback it's hard for him to get back in the
lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   If UCLA defeats Stanford, Oregon State and Washington, it'll
clinch the Pac-10 title regardless of the outcome of the USC game.
</P>
<P>
   Kickoff for the Nov. 7 game at Oregon State is 3:30 p.m. No word
on the television situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 0043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
