<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8467 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-RANK-LADN     10-27 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-RANK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS PULLOFF UPSETOF OHIO STATE IN PLAYOFF RANKINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news
files.) 
BY JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's a complicated formula that mixes opinion,
computer-generated rankings and something called ``quartile rank,''
but it has a simple explanation: If the college football season
ended today, UCLA would play Ohio State for the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   The undefeated Bruins, 6-0, are No. 1 in the nation in the only
poll that matters _ the initial Bowl Championship Series rankings
that were released Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Updated BCS polls will be released periodically until Dec. 6.
The teams with the fewest points in the final poll will play for
the national title Jan. 4 in the Fiesta Bowl in Tempe, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   The University of California, Los Angeles, football team greeted
the news with a small dose of satisfaction and a load of
indifference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the point that we're not celebrating any polls,''
said senior Shawn Stuart, a Saugus, Calif., native who plays center
for the Bruins. ``When Dec. 6 comes, we'll look at it and see where
we're ranked. Right now, we can't pay attention to it. Every team
we play is coming after us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had 3.04 points in the BCS poll, followed by Ohio
State (4.31), Tennessee (6.5) and Kansas State (8.79). But they
realize the loftiest perch means nothing if they lose any of their
remaining games: Stanford, Oregon State, Washington, USC and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   One defeat means they'll plunge in the poll and watch the Fiesta
Bowl from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're flattered to be selected No. 1, but it doesn't mean a
thing,'' said Bruins coach Bob Toledo, a Westlake Village resident.
``The key is to be No. 1 or 2 after our five remaining games, so we
can play in the championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the players not to worry. We need to focus on the
Stanford game. It can slip away real fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The BCS poll was created this year by Roy Kramer, commissioner
of the Southeastern Conference. It's goal: eliminate the loopholes
in a system that used the opinion-based top-25 polls to crown a
national champion.
</P>
<P>
   There are four parts to the BCS formula:
</P>
<P>
   _ A team's average ranking in the Associated Press' media top-25
poll and the USA Today/ESPN coaches' top-25 poll.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked No. 2 in both, UCLA received two points for that
component.
</P>
<P>
   _ A team's average ranking in three computer polls: the New York
Times, the Seattle Times, and Jeff Sagarin's power ratings
published in USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked No. 1 in each of those computer polls, UCLA received one
point.
</P>
<P>
   _ A schedule-strength rank determined by the win-loss record of
each team's opponents (66.6 percent) and each team's opponents'
opponents (33.3 percent). That number is divided by 25 to produce a
quartile rank. Each place is worth .04 points.
</P>
<P>
   With the nation's toughest schedule to date, UCLA received .04
points.
</P>
<P>
   _ One point is added for each loss. The Bruins are 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   Add 'em up _ two points for their top-25 average, one point for
their computer average and no losses _ and UCLA has 3.04 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``With so many factors, how can you control anything?'' Stuart
said. ``It's pointless to try. All we can do is play hard and see
where we land.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
