<HEADER>
A8470 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      10-27 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDER CASE SHOWS FLAWS IN SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The double murderer Michael Poland should be seven days a
corpse, yet he breathes and eats and wakes each morning from a
sleep that's not eternal in the Arizona State Prison, which is one
level above the hell where he belongs.
</P>
<P>
   Poland was to have been executed last Tuesday for the murders of
two armored-car guards but was spared by a last-minute appeal.
</P>
<P>
   It was torture for the families of the victims, who'll suffer
all their lives no matter what happens to the killer.
</P>
<P>
   It was an irresistible opportunity for politicians and
prosecutors to make speeches about how tough they are _ or would be
_ on crime.
</P>
<P>
   It was a chance for the rest of us to take to the streets over
the seemingly endless delays of this and every other death penalty
case.
</P>
<P>
   To form a mob.
</P>
<P>
   Light some torches.
</P>
<P>
   Git a rope.
</P>
<P>
   But . . . we didn't. &QL; 
It's not as if we'll weep when Poland is executed, as he will be,
eventually. Stone cold killers don't deserve sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   But Poland alive doesn't bother us much, either. What we want,
and need, is for Poland to be out of circulation. And he is.
</P>
<P>
   The system worked.
</P>
<P>
   It's the death penalty that doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   This has nothing to do with morality or religion.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is we can't agree on who should live and who should
die. Sentencing men like Poland to life without parole is something
just about everyone can agree on. Choosing those we want to execute
is what leads to the arguments, the appeals, the moral indignation.
</P>
<P>
   Is Poland worse than Theodore Kaczynski, the ``Unabomber,'' or
the 15-year-old who gunned down three students and wounded five
others at Heath High School in West Paducah, Ky.?
</P>
<P>
   They got life.
</P>
<P>
   Is he worse than the Menendez brothers, who murdered their
parents for money and also got life?
</P>
<P>
   Is he worse than Jack Ray Hudson, the former Yuma County
sheriff's deputy convicted of murdering two fellow members of a
drug-enforcement task force? He got life, too.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they all should get the needle.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't matter. Eventually, we'd have to draw a line
somewhere to determine who lives and who dies, and the arguments
would start all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, the problem solves itself. Antonio Sapien, who
stabbed a Phoenix man 29 times and castrated him, received a life
sentence but hung himself with a bedsheet in prison. &QL; 
Most often, the problem isn't so easily resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Benjamin Smith was an 18-year-old Mesa High School senior
in 1966 when he ordered five women and two children to lie on a
floor and started firing. Only one woman and one child survived.
</P>
<P>
   Smith got life.
</P>
<P>
   We got protected from Smith.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a perfect trade-off. Not for the families of the
victims, who must believe Smith is more evil than Poland. I would
if I were them. And I'd want him dead.
</P>
<P>
   But life-without-parole works.
</P>
<P>
   And it eliminates the potential horrors described in a U.S.
Justice Department report that came out a few years ago, which
detailed 28 cases of men who had served a total of 197 years,
including three on death row for more than 25 years, before DNA
tests proved they were innocent.
</P>
<P>
   The guilty get what they deserve.
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter of time and degree.
</P>
<P>
   The double murderer Michael Poland breathes and eats and sleeps
in a bed in the Arizona State Prison, one level above the hell
where he belongs. He's been there for more than 20 years, which to
the families of his victims must seem like a very long time.
</P>
<P>
   Like forever.
</P>
<P>
   It must seem that way to Poland, too.
</P>
<P>
   At least, it will until he takes his final breath, either by
natural causes or injection, and finds out what eternity really
means. &QL; 
(E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 0050EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0014 </DOCNO>
