<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LASHERIFF-HURT-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. COUNTY SHERIFF UNDERGOES SURGERY AFTER FALL IN BATHTUB
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attention editors: Tonight in story refers to Oct. 27.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY LEE CONDON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles County Sheriff Sherman Block underwent
surgery Monday to remove a blood clot from his brain that developed
after he fell in the bathtub at his home over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Block's hospitalization came just one week before the
culmination of the 74-year-old sheriff's toughest re-election
campaign in which rival Lee Baca repeatedly questioned Block's
health and fitness to serve in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The four-hour operation was successful and completed without
complications,'' said Dr. Srinath Samudrala, assistant professor of
neurological surgery at USC University Hospital, who issued a
statement on the sheriff's condition following the operation Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sheriff Block tolerated the procedure well and is
recovering,'' Samudrala said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is too early to speculate on the length of his hospital
stay or recovery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Block's wife, Alice, who was in the hospital during the
operation, compared her husband of 52 years to the Energizer Bunny.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to know how gutsy he is. When the battery does run
down, I replace it,'' Block said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Block's campaign consultants spent Monday preparing
contingency plans should his health deteriorate further.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are unchartered waters when something like this happens.
People in the campaign feel strongly about completing the campaign
like he is here,'' said Joe Scott, a consultant working on the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said Undersheriff Jerry Harper would fill in for Block at
a fund-raiser tonight hosted by U.S. Sen. Dianne Feinstein,
D.-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fund-raising events are going on as scheduled,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, a longtime public relations professional, said his
business cards advertise that he handle's crisis management.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought crisis management would take on ... capital
letters. No one has been through anything like this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Shallman, another consultant for Block, said the campaign
would continue regardless of whether the sheriff is still in the
hospital Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to let it slip away to someone he has no faith
in,'' Shallman said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expects Block to make a full recovery, much like he
has from other ailments in the past.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether voters will be more concerned about the sheriff's
health and his ability to serve four more years, Shallman said even
if Block eventually has to give up the post, a new sheriff
appointed by the Los Angeles Board of Supervisors would be better
than Baca.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, god forbid, something should happen to the sheriff, any
number of people could step forward to be a much better future
sheriff than Lee Baca has offered himself to be,'' Shallman said.
</P>
<P>
   Block has been locked in a fierce battle to retain his job
against Baca, a former department regional chief who in June forced
Block into the first run-off to lead the nation's largest sheriff's
department since he was elected in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Baca announced late Monday that he would suspend all personal
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of respect and concern for Mr. Block, his family and the
Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department, I will not make any public
appearances as a candidate, nor attend scheduled debates until the
condition of Mr. Block is known,'' Baca said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have directed my campaign staff to alter as soon as possible
my media advertising so it no longer makes reference to Mr. Block.
My prayers are with Mr. Block and his family. I wish him a full and
speedy recovery,'' Baca said.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Flores, a campaign consultant for Baca, said a radio spot
focusing on Block's previous health problems would be pulled and
that new radio ads would not mention Block. However Baca's media
campaign will continue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS.)  &QL;
</ANNOTATION>
</TEXT>
