<HEADER>
A8476 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBA-LABOR-1STLD-WRITE     10-27 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-LABOR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG TALKS YIELD LITTLE SIGN OF PROGRESS IN LOCKOUT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Representatives of the National Basketball
Association and its locked-out players on Monday held the longest
negotiating session in their labor dispute, which has brought the
cancellation of the season's first two weeks, but chief negotiators
said that no progress was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met all day and we didn't accomplish anything,'' Patrick
Ewing, the union president, said. ``We're going to meet tomorrow
and Wednesday, and hopefully we can come up with something. No
progress was made. They made a proposal, we made a proposal, we
made over various points, but nothing is concrete.''
</P>
<P>
   Russ Granik, the NBA's deputy commissioner, said: ``We really
haven't made any progress. I don't want to call it a waste of time
_ that would be too strong. But it's hard for me or anybody to come
out of this meeting encouraged. Talking about systems is a nice
thing, but we're not going to have a deal until we look at some
real issues about how to fix the current climate. Right now we're
nowhere near that.''
</P>
<P>
   Granik said on Monday night that he expected to announce more
game cancellations on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for both sides will meet on Tuesday, with the next major
bargaining sessions scheduled for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some players provided a more positive assessment of Monday's
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say there has been minor progress, but we still have a
very long way to go,'' said Danny Schayes, one of 12 players who
attended the meeting, which lasted for about seven and a half hours
and adjourned about 10 p.m. ``We haven't agreed on one specific
yet, but it was definitely moving in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most productive talks, only because the other talks
went nowhere. We're finally in the same arena, but we're not in the
same section yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Schayes said a hard salary cap, something the players adamantly
oppose, was not discussed during the session, adding that David
Stern, the NBA commissioner, was willing to entertain other
proposals that might let the players keep their flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, David has been willing to talk about other issues, and
we're working to address their cost controls,'' Schayes said. ``We
always felt that the NBA's prior proposals all looked for a way to
back into a hard cap. But that wasn't the case today.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the two sides could be zeroing in on an agreement in
the next two weeks, Schayes replied: ``I wouldn't want to put a
date on it right now, but then again it could be one of those
things where there's three months of nothing and a day and a half
of getting a deal done. But my personal feeling is, some limited
progress was made today.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Before, we were 1,000 miles apart. Now, we're maybe
800 miles apart.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, at a midtown hotel, came one day before the
league's labor relations committee was scheduled to meet in
Manhattan to discuss the stalemate that has led to the cancellation
of the first two weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Before last weekend, there had been no substantive negotiations
since Oct. 13. But Stern and Granik met with the union's chief
negotiators, the executive director Billy Hunter and Ewing, for
three and a half hours on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The second meeting in three days indicates the growing concern
over lost games and the potential for losing the entire season
should the dispute continue.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have indicated flexibility on many of the key
economic issues that have held up previous negotiations. While the
players have said they will not tolerate a hard salary cap, the
owners have indicated they are willing to discuss any proposal that
might increase their total share of the basketball revenue. This
includes a tax on clubs with salaries above a certain level, a
proposal by the players that has been bandied about by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The owners want certainty on costs, while the players have said
they want to keep their right to earn as much as they can through a
clause known as the Larry Bird exception.
</P>
<P>
   Modifications to the clause were discussed. Also, a participant
in the meeting said, both sides have talked openly about raising
the minimum salary for veterans with 10 or more years of experience
to more than $750,000. The minimum salary last season was $272,500,
a figure that 20 percent of players earned.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's meeting of the NBA board of governors could be a key
to the negotiations. The union has invited all 400-plus members to
attend talks that will also include owners and ownership
representatives from the league's 29 teams.
</P>
</TEXT>
