<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CHIEFS-STEELERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEELERS DEFEAT CHIEFS, 20-13 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Pittsburgh and Kansas City have met for three
consecutive seasons on Monday nights in Arrowhead Stadium. By now,
the dance is familiar: play it close, grind it on defense and make
something good happen at the end. And maybe most important: watch
the turnover battle.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's game followed the formula. But it was Pittsburgh
that made something happen on offense late. And then the Steelers
gained the game's big turnovers _ two, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   It wound up a 20-13 Pittsburgh victory before 79,431 fans,
Arrowhead's fifth-largest crowd ever. The Chiefs are 4-3 and have
lost to Pittsburgh (5-2), Jacksonville (5-2) and New England (4-3),
all American Football Conference playoff favorites who have the
head-to-head tie-breaker edge on Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh led by 10-6 at halftime and nearly lost the lead on
the second-half kickoff, but a holding penalty negated a 95-yard
touchdown return by the Chiefs' Joe Horn.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers made it 13-6 late in the third quarter on a Norm
Johnson field goal set up by a 17-yard pass from the rookie Hines
Ward _ a running back-receiver-quarterback at Georgia _ to the
Steelers' quarterback, Kordell Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   After the Chiefs' Andre Rison scored on a 2-yard pass from Elvis
Grbac with 2 minutes 28 seconds left in the third quarter, the
score was tied at 13-13.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh made the next move. Stewart passed 5 yards to Charles
Johnson with 10:05 remaining, and the Steelers led, 20-13.
</P>
<P>
   Then with 4:28 left, Pittsburgh cornerback Carnell Lake
intercepted Grbac's pass at the Steeler 38. With 57 seconds left,
linebacker Jason Gildon forced Grbac to fumble and Lethon Flowers
recovered near the Kansas City 20.
</P>
<P>
   The dance was over with the usual ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to come up with some big plays, particularly
defensively,'' Steelers Coach Bill Cowher said. ``Tonight we were
able to finish things off. A good football team reacts and
responds, and we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Bettis ran 33 times for 119 yards as Pittsburgh ground
out 182 yards on 43 carries. The Chiefs ran only 19 times, for 72
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of place you can't come in to and
overreact,'' Gildon said. ``They've got the crowd and they've got
the noise, but if you're able to play defense and stop the run,
then it gives you a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers took the opening kickoff and ran nine plays before
punting from the Kansas City 48. Chiefs kick returner Tamarick
Vanover signaled for a fair catch but at the last second moved up,
away from the ball, and let it bounce. It hit just inside the
Chiefs' 10-yard line and rolled, and the Steelers downed the ball
inside the 1.
</P>
<P>
   Four plays later, the Chiefs were punting from their end zone,
the Steelers swarmed punter Louie Aguiar, and Lance Brown easily
blocked the punt. Fred McAfee recovered the ball in the end zone
for a touchdown. Pittsburgh led by 7-0 with 8:05 left in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Aguiar had not had a punt blocked in 587 previous attempts as a
pro. It was Pittsburgh's first blocked punt for a touchdown since
Jan.2, 1983, against Cleveland. It was the first block against
Kansas City since Dec. 12, 1993, in a game with Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they were punting from the end zone,'' McAfee said, ``for
our punt team it was like the dog going after the mailman.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs wanted desperately to respond, but did so in an odd
way.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City started its next drive at its 29 and stalled at the
Pittsburgh 37. The Chiefs then took a risky shot on fourth-and-5.
Grbac passed to tight end Tony Gonzalez for 31 yards to the
Pittsburgh 6. Kansas City then moved only to the 3 and settled for
a Pete Stoyanovich 20-yard field goal. Pittsburgh led, 7-3, with
5:08 left.
</P>
<P>
   To begin the second quarter, Kansas City again moved inside of
the Pittsburgh 20, to the 11, but the drive stalled again.
Stoyanovich kicked a 28-yard field goal and it was 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly the final 13 minutes of the half, the score remained
7-6. Stewart was 5 of 11 passing for 47 yards in the half, and 24
of those yards came on one play. Stewart's 24-yard pass to receiver
David Dunn to the Kansas City 30 with 13 seconds left gave
Pittsburgh a chance to score the final points before halftime, Norm
Johnson's 34-yard field goal as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outcome of the game was driven by two things: our
penalties and our turnovers,'' Chiefs Coach Marty Schottenheimer
said. ``Until we understand the importance of that and accept that
and do something about it, we're going to continue to have the same
problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
