<HEADER>
A8480 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LASHERIFF-HURT-2ndTak     10-27 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LASHERIFF-HURT-2ndTake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES:   campaign will continue. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shallman, though, continued to criticize Baca.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just last week they called him a sick old man. Now they're
trying to backpedal from those offensive remarks,''Shallman said.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan called the hospital and
offered Block's top aides his best wishes for a speedy recovery,
said the mayor's spokeswoman, Noelia Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Block fell Saturday and needed 10 stitches to close a wound to
his head. He was released from a Humana Columbia Hospital in the
L.A. suburb of West Hills that day, but began feeling dizzy and
disoriented about four hours later as he prepared to go to a
fund-raiser, according to Sheriff's Department officials.
</P>
<P>
   His family called 911 and he was taken to USC University
Hospital in Boyle Heights, a Los Angeles suburb, where surgeons
operated on him Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Block already has fought off prostate cancer and non-Hodgkins
lymphoma and currently undergoes dialysis three times a week for
treatment of a serious kidney ailment. He has said he wanted a
kidney transplant after the election.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his health problems, Block has run a vigorous campaign
for a fifth term as part of his efforts to deflect Baca's assertion
that it is time for him to retire because of his health.
</P>
<P>
   Baca also claimed that Block planned to quit after winning
re-election, forcing the Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors to
appoint his handpicked successor to the job. Former Los Angeles
Police Department Capt. Mark Kroeker's name has surfaced as a
likely candidate, and he has said he would consider the
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Block has denied those claims.
</P>
<P>
   Block's name will appear on the ballot Nov. 3, regardless of his
physical condition.
</P>
<P>
   If he is re-elected but is unable to serve for any reason, the
supervisors are required to pick a successor, said Conny McCormack,
the county's registrar-recorder-county clerk.
</P>
<P>
   A special election would be held in November 2000 if the sheriff
were to leave office in the first two years of his four-year term.
</P>
<P>
   McCormack said county lawyers would have to research whether the
supervisors could appoint a successor if a sheriff became
incapacitated.
</P>
<P>
   McCormack noted that her office has already received some
115,000 absentee ballots. But anyone who wants to change their vote
in any contest because of recent developments is out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you send in a ballot, you can't get it back,'' McCormack
said.
</P>
<P>
   Block is the nation's highest-paid elected official, earning
$234,016 a year _ more than the president's $200,000-a-year annual
salary.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff supervises 12,400 employees, including 8,000
deputies, and is responsible for providing police services to 2.5
million people in unincorporated areas of Los Angeles County and 40
incorporated cities that contract for services. The department also
operates the nation's largest urban jail system, with 19,000
inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Myles Saunders, a neurosurgeon with Cedars Sinai Medical Center
who was not involved in Block's surgery, said the swift treatment
of Block's condition should help lead to successful recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of these patients, barring some
complication, will retain normal brain function,'' he said.
``That's what I fully expect of him. I expect him to return to work
in an estimated three weeks, four weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   He cautioned that there is a risk of brain swelling several days
after surgery. But barring such a complication, he said the surgery
should not interfere with Block's duties as sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many patients at his age, and with the type of problem that he
has could return to a highly rigorous, intellectual and physical
job of that type,'' Saunders said.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders said that patients suffering kidney failure are at
greater than average risk of brain bleeding after head injuries.
But he said Block's kidney disease should not significantly affect
his recovery. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
