<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-STADIUM-MEETING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE FIGHT FOR FRANCHISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The work, conducted at a breakneck pace,
wasn't completed until the weekend, just beating the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   But proponents of an NFL expansion team in the Coliseum got what
they desired: an entirely new design for a renovation of the
ancient facility, and, more important, something to counter the
dazzling stadium mock-ups of expansion proposals in Carson and in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The high-stakes game of show and tell officially kicks off
today, as all three prospective expansion groups make presentations
at the fall meeting of the NFL's owners and chief executives.
</P>
<P>
   The league is hopeful of awarding its 32nd franchise next year
and having it on the field in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   There is considerable curiosity about what kind of Hollywood
flair Michael Ovitz might demonstrate on behalf of the Carson
project, which proposes a hacienda-style stadium on a landfill at
the junction of the San Diego and Harbor freeways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it will be very interesting and I would like to see
it myself, but I haven't been invited,'' said Houston
multimillionaire Robert McNair, whose group will counter with a
design for a retractable-roof stadium next to the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our perspective is, this is really a business, and
there has to be substance to it.''
</P>
<P>
   All three groups can expect pointed questions _ now and in the
coming months _ on how they intend to crunch their numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But a little flash won't hurt any causes today. That's why the
Coliseum group, faced with Ovitz's tolling mission bells and
Houston's giant moonroof, signed with the architectural firm NBBJ
Associates just a few weeks ago and begged for a dramatic makeover
of their previous design. They can only hope the NFL owners can be
fooled into thinking it isn't the Coliseum anymore.
</P>
<P>
   New Coliseum Partners released photographs of the model Monday,
while NBBJ employees began to assemble it in a hotel ballroom here.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hallmark, NBBJ's principal architect on the project, and
John Semcken, New Coliseum Partners executive vice president,
pointed out the new wrinkles:
</P>
<P>
   _The south and north portions of the stadium constructed in
three levels, with three levels of luxury suites rather than the
previous two.
</P>
<P>
   _A canopy over each of the two structures.
</P>
<P>
   _A grove of palm trees just inside the peristyle end, with a
restaurant and a Hollywood Bowl-like box seating area between the
trees and the east end zone.
</P>
<P>
   _A park-like area and affordable family seating at the west end.
</P>
<P>
   _Facility for expandable seating at the west end for Super Bowls
and major college games like USC-Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the expansion of the venue,'' said City Councilman Mark
Ridley-Thomas, ``we'll have the largest club lounge in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this would be positioned within the gutted walls of the
current stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, our issue was to try to preserve the peristyle
and the exterior wall,'' Hallmark said. ``It costs a tremendous
amount of resources to develop these kinds of entrances and these
kinds of exterior expressions in new stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've determined that, in fact, those elements are in exactly
the right place for us to do what we want to do with this design.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that perhaps 80 percent of the seating would be along
the north and south sides of the playing field, with high end zone
and high corner seating eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL owners are likely to be impressed by all three
expansion-site designs. But this is a group that divides its
windfall of television revenues equally, so it will also want to be
certain each proposal is on solid footing for ultimate financial
success. That likely will mean inquiries about Carson's sudden
pledge of $180 million in bonds for a stadium and mall, and about
the Coliseum group's insistence that Los Angeles fans will line up
to pay dearly for a club seat at ... well, the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is,'' said Houston's McNair, ``can you build the
project? Do you have the money? Do you know how to operate it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
