<HEADER>
A8493 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     10-27 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVITZ TO SHOW HACIENDA MODEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It's show time!
</P>
<P>
   And who better to put on a show than Michael Ovitz?
</P>
<P>
   After all, he built the Creative Artists Agency (CAA) into the
biggest and most successful in Hollywood, he helped launch the
acting careers of Tom Cruise and Kevin Costner, took David
Letterman to CBS and picked Disney's pocket for a $128 million
severance package. That alone should win him a few fans in
America's most exclusive sport's fraternity, the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the league's owners will entertain presentations from
three groups seeking an expansion franchise _ Ovitz/Carson, the New
Coliseum and Houston. Each group gets an hour to show its best
open-field moves and answer owners' questions.
</P>
<P>
   The Ovitz hour will include a model of The Hacienda, the
proposed stadium in Carson _ a model that is so big it has to be
dismantled to fit in a freight elevator. The presentation will also
include a film that Ovitz aides describe as ``evocative.'' It will
extol the virtues of a multinational Los Angeles, link the
experience to family values and hammer home that L.A. is the No. 2
market in America and the world's 11th-richest economy.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL will not decide on its 32nd team this week, but Ovitz is
clearly hoping to be a showstopper and leave Kansas City as the
front-runner. But Kansas City is not Cannes and NFL owners are not
a sentimental bunch. Mostly, the owners want to be sure any
proposal has financial backing.
</P>
<P>
   The league once gave lukewarm support to a proposed stadium near
Hollywood Park but bailed as soon as it realized R. D. Hubbard
didn't have the money to make it happen. It threw out author Tom
Clancy's bid to buy the Minnesota Vikings for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   The Ovitz group has had a stock answer for every question since
its campaign began: ``We have it covered.'' But at today's
meetings, the league will want facts and figures. Anyone caught tap
dancing will get the hook. The owners will want to know exactly how
much money Ovitz will be contributing to the project; a list of his
fellow owners and their finances; details on the involvement of
Herbert Glimcher, the realtor who holds the option to buy the land
and a construction timetable.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the owners, will be more circumspect about Los
Angeles than any other prospective city because of the experiences
with the Rams and Raiders. ``If we return to Los Angeles, it's
critical the situation does not fail,'' said Roger Goodell, the
NFL's vice president of development.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz's biggest edge is the stadium. The league's No.1 goal is
to have every team in the league playing in a new or near-new
stadium. The four teams that have pulled the plug _ Rams, Raiders,
Browns and Oilers _ left for new or renovated stadiums and big
up-front bucks. The only protection a city has is its willingness
to make a sizable donation to the NFL coffers.
</P>
<P>
   Look at Cleveland. One day it has the Browns and a fanatical
following. The next, it's without a team and, a few years later, a
new owner has to pony up a $535 million expansion fee. Ovitz is
willing to play the game because after years in Hollywood he's used
to it and does it well.
</P>
<P>
   The New Coliseum can't compete because, in part, it's not new.
Kings owner Ed Roski could show the league a zillion sketches of a
renovated Coliseum, but the owners still acquaint it with the
departure of the Rams and Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   And when Roski takes the stage, he will do so without L.A. Mayor
Richard Riordan (he'll say hello via videotape), without his hockey
partner, Philip Anschutz (who is too busy buying soccer teams) and
without Peter O'Malley (who the NFL once thought would be a swell
partner). The NFL is simply not going to turn over the nation's
No.2 market to someone this shorthanded.
</P>
<P>
   An existing team is another matter. Five teams want a new
stadium _ Denver, Chicago, Philadelphia, New England and Arizona _
and the situations in San Francisco and Buffalo are worth watching
because stadium plans are notoriously shaky. Don't be surprised if
Cardinals owner Bill Bidwill starts getting cozy with Roski and the
New Coliseum group reciprocates. Arizona ranks last in the league
in attendance. That might be the only way the Coliseum beats Ovitz
to a NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   The show opens today. We'll know by Wednesday whether any of the
locals get two thumbs up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
