<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_AVALANCHE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES PUT ON SHOW FOR BOSS, BURY AVALANCHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Bobby Smith wasn't planning on being at McNichols Arena
on Monday night. But after Valley thunderstorms canceled his flight
to Anaheim to see Sunday's game against the Mighty Ducks, the
general manager for the Coyotes decided to change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Was he ever glad he did.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, shaking off a tough loss in Dallas and a disturbing
tie in Anaheim, jumped all over the sliding Colorado Avalanche and
pounded the former Stanley Cup champions, 5-1, in their best effort
so far this season.
</P>
<P>
   Smith had a feeling it was going to be a good night for his
club. When asked before the game if he was concerned about the
Coyotes' 2-2-1 start, he replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not. I like the way this team is playing . . . I'm
very optimistic about things right now. Very optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   There was every reason to feel that way Monday, as the Coyotes
shelled goalie Patrick Roy and a Colorado defense that was missing
a few key players.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Keith Tkachuk led the way with two goals and an assist,
and the Coyotes also got goals from Jeremy Roenick, Rick Tocchet
and Cliff Ronning to beat the Avalanche for the second time in two
weeks after going 0-7-1 against Colorado since relocating to
Phoenix from Winnipeg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a legitimate reward for the way our guys have been
playing the last nine periods,'' Coach Jim Schoenfeld said. ``It
was nice to see them have a game where they were able to score some
goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Jimmy Waite, meanwhile, was nearly perfect in his first
start of the season, stopping every shot he faced until Keith Jones
finally snapped the shutout on the power play with 3:21 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have stopped that shot,'' Waite said. ``It's a little
frustrating (losing the shutout), but I'm happy with the win. . . .
I didn't see too many shots (he faced only 20), but I'd like to
have all my games like that, it would be great.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Coyotes' largest margin of victory since they
defeated Anaheim, 5-1, on April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, the Coyotes now have scored 10 goals in two games
against the team they couldn't seem to beat. Even more amazing, the
goalie who never seems to lose to them, is in one of the worst
slumps of his career. Roy had owned the Coyotes. In 21 previous
games against the franchise, he was 18-1-2.
</P>
<P>
   Just like their past two games in Dallas and in Anaheim, the
Coyotes jumped to the early lead. But this time they just kept
pouring it on.
</P>
<P>
   The Tkachuk-Roenick-Dallas Drake line got it started four
minutes into the game when Tkachuk zipped a one-timer from the top
of the left circle that went through Roy's pads. Drake and Roenick
got the assists.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick made it 2-0 at the 9:44 mark as Phoenix finally
converted on the power play, ending an 0-for-9 drought. The Coyotes
added another one, when Ronning beat Roy on a pass from Tocchet
midway through the second. With 31 seconds left in the period,
Tocchet stuck a dagger into the Avalanche, putting the Coyotes up,
4-0, by wristing in a feed from Ronning.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk added to the deluge with his second goal and fourth of
the season at 5:49 of the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how he is when he gets on one of those rolls,''
Schoenfeld said of Tkachuk, a two-time 50-goal scorer. ``They
usually last a couple of months.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
