r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-COLUMN-LADN     10-27 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLANDERS FRANCHISE SINKING FAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ To be fair, it was the night the New York
Yankees ended their sweep of the San Diego Padres, so a lot of Long
Islanders understandably opted to sit in front of their
televisions.
</P>
<P>
   But that same night last week at Nassau Coliseum, an
embarrassingly small crowd _ fewer than 3,000 _ turned out to watch
the Edmonton Oilers beat the New York Islanders, who play host to
the Kings tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Official attendance was ``not available'' according to Islanders
officials, who probably would somehow manage to count to 16,297 if
they had a sellout, but couldn't count to 2,800 when their building
was 80 percent empty.
</P>
<P>
   The ``crowd'' was the latest sign of decay for a once-proud
franchise that captured four consecutive Stanley Cups from 1980-83.
The low turnout, however, shouldn't have come as a huge surprise.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the Islanders haven't made the playoffs since
1994, and their best and most exciting player _ scoring ace Zigmund
Palffy _ remains an unsigned, restricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the Islanders owners tried, and failed, to get the
Coliseum condemned as unsafe before the season began. Now Islanders
management is asking fans to turn out to watch a team that tried to
move out of a building the franchise's owners call unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   How's that for a marketing nightmare?
</P>
<P>
   The days of Denis Potvin, Bryan Trottier and Mike Bossy seem
distant, though Islanders coach and general manager Mike Milbury is
maintaining some optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we could have won every game,'' said Milbury, whose
team is 3-4. ``There's no doubt in my mind we can compete with
anybody _ anybody we've seen so far, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   No end in sight?: In less than three months, Wayne Gretzky will
turn 38. He has just begun his 20th season in the NHL. Nonetheless,
there are signs that Gretzky is going to continue to play for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always asking me,'' said Gretzky, who has seven
points in the New York Rangers' first eight games. ``My kids ask
every day. I honestly don't know. I do know if I decide to quit, I
won't tell anybody until there's about a month to go in the season.
I don't want a farewell tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only thing my agent, Mike Barnett, and I argue
about. I've had victory laps for 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers coach John Muckler said, ``He walked into the practice
rink the other day and said, `Who do I complain to about my ice
time? I'm not getting enough.' I'd just played him 28 minutes on
back-to-back nights. Believe me, he's still having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfair criticism: When Phoenix's Keith Tkachuk rushed out of
practice recently, refusing to sign autographs, he incurred the
wrath of several fans, one of whom wrote a letter that was
published in a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The letter referred to Tkachuk as ``the biggest jerk in the
game'' and a ``disgrace to the sport and the Phoenix Coyotes.''
</P>
<P>
   It turns out Tkachuk was rushing to a Phoenix hospital, where
his wife, who was five weeks pregnant, was having a miscarriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knew what was going on except me, and I didn't even
know how bad it was until I got there,'' said Tkachuk, whose
exhibition season holdout hadn't endeared him to Coyotes fans in
the first place. ``Being a hockey player was the least on my mind
that day. What was important, what is important, is my family,
first and foremost.''
</P>
<P>
   Taxi driver: When the Kings were at Florida last week, several
of their broadcasters wanted to go to practice the day before the
game. They told their cab driver to take them to the National Car
Rental Center, the Panthers' new arena.
</P>
<P>
   Either misunderstanding or not familiar with the corporate
takeover of professional sports, the driver instead took them to
the rental-car area at the Fort Lauderdale airport.
</P>
<P>
   A year from now, when the Kings move into their new arena, it is
almost inevitable that some poor sap will be taken by a taxi driver
to an office-supply store.
</P>
<P>
   Clean and sober: The Kings visit New Jersey on Wednesday, and
it's nearly a year since Devils defenseman Ken Daneyko had his last
drink. He underwent alcohol rehabilitation last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a fun drunk, never got too rowdy,'' Daneyko said. ``But
I knew my problem was deep inside. I felt empty. I'd be lonely all
the time even if I was surrounded by lots of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Daneyko said he carries an article about the late Mickey Mantle
in his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd take it out every couple of months and say, `Gee, that
sounds like me,' '' Daneyko said. ``I wasn't an everyday drinker
then, but I knew I would be when I quit. I also read where Mickey
said he wasn't close to his family because of his drinking. That
was me, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: San Jose opened Thursday's game against Chicago
with two goals in the first 47 seconds, the fastest anyone had done
that to the Blackhawks in nearly 18 years. The Sharks then settled
for a 2-2 tie. Chicago coach Dirk Graham benched veteran defenseman
Chris Chelios for 7 minutes after the Sharks' first goal. ``I don't
have to sit Chris Chelios for him to understand what's going on,''
Graham said. ``I did that for a while because I thought some of our
other players were better prepared. We'll do that with any player
we think is not ready to play _ whether it's Chris Chelios or
anyone else.''... Dallas' Joe Nieuwendyk had the winning goal and
an assist in his first game back in the lineup, which came six
months to the day after he suffered injuries requiring
reconstructive surgery on both knees when checked by San Jose's
Bryan Marchment....
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix's Jeremy Roenick on having four wisdom teeth extracted:
``It was a piece of cake. They put you out, you wake up, and you
chew on one side of your mouth a little bit and drool a lot. No big
deal.''... Pittsburgh defenseman Darius Kasparaitis, returning to
the lineup following a knee injury, was asked if he expected
opponents to target the injured area. `My whole body is a
bull's-eye,' Kasparaitis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 0132EST &QL; 
