</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ROSEBOWL-SEATS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TIGHT SQUEEZE AT ROSE BOWL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Seat 101 in Row 17 at the Rose Bowl looks
harmless enough.
</P>
<P>
   But that seat, and the thousands like it, has been drawing mixed
reviews since the UCLA football team opened its home season five
weeks ago. There just doesn't seem to be enough leg room for some
people.
</P>
<P>
   Like his friends, Chris Bartold, a 19-year-old biochemistry
major at UCLA, had his legs draped over the seat in front of him on
Saturday when the Bruins played Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The seats) looked nicer,'' said Bartold, who is from Woodland
Hills, ``but when you actually sat down, it was not comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the popular opinion in the student section, where
Bartold was sitting. But across the stadium, H.M. Wammack and his
wife Beth could not have been happier.
</P>
<P>
   The Wammacks, who live in Glendale, have been season-ticket
holders since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is wonderful because you're not touching your neighbors
anymore,'' Beth said. ``How can you complain about seats like
this?''
</P>
<P>
   But UCLA athletic director Peter Dalis said people have
complained.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have written to me,'' Dalis said. ``Some say
they are not going to renew their season tickets next year (because
of the new seating). But a lot of time people get upset and say
those things, and then they come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Jacobs, the Rose Bowl general manager, came up with a
33-point plan in 1993 to modernize the 75-year-old stadium. Seats
were put at the top of the list. Despite hosting four Super Bowls
and a World Cup, the Rose Bowl had only bleacher seating prior to
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-decade, when there were seeds of interest in luring an NFL
team to play in the Rose Bowl, new seats were a priority. When the
NFL deal fell through, Jacobs still wanted to make the stadium more
fan-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a college facility,'' he said. ``Our goal is to be the
best college facility possible.''
</P>
<P>
   A $6 million seat renovation project began in February. It
wasn't finished until August (there was a a delay when the first
batch of seats were, ironically, too small in width). When the
installation was complete, Rose Bowl capacity had decreased from
100,807 to 92,000. There are about 60,000 of the new seats.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Rick Purdy, associate athletic director at UCLA,
expressed concern about moving season-ticket holders' seats for the
new configuration. After the season's first month, he found out
what people were really concerned about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear I had about people being concerned about their
location was much less than I anticipated,'' he said. ``What
certainly has been more of a problem has been the comfortability.''
</P>
<P>
   The architecture of the Rose Bowl simply cannot afford seats
with more leg room, Jacobs said. There won't be another project to
increase the length between the rows of seats.
</P>
<P>
   Purdy said the ``vast majority'' of season-ticket holders have
been pleased with the new seats. When the choice is less stress on
the back or increased leg room, the new seats are winning by a
landslide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so much better on your back,'' said Jeff Scanlan, one of
the dozens of UCLA game-management officials who work home games.
``On the bench seats, my knees go into the person's back, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said during the Texas game, there were about 60
complaints. The attendance that day was 73,060.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's less than 1 percent,'' he said. ``If you talked to
99.99 percent of the people that come here, they would tell you
those seats are very comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who are complaining _ people who are 6-foot or taller or
severely overweight _ are being accomodated. Ushers like Scanlan
are letting people who cannot fit into the seats sit in the
handicapped sections that were also created in the renovation.
</P>
<P>
   The students who pay $6 to sit in the student section don't like
the new seats for another reason: In the bleachers, more fans than
actually fit can occupy a row. In many cases, fans were packed in
like sardines.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said that was a common problem around the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you got in, you were locked in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Purdy said there may have been unrealistic expectations for fans
when they heard last summer that new seats were being installed in
the Rose Bowl. Even he equated ``new'' with ``roomier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably the logical thing for people to think,'' he
said. ``For people who are 6-2, 6-3... it's tough. I don't deny
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
