<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANKLE STORY CHANGES AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The mystery surrounding Dallas Drake's ankle injury
seems to grow wackier by the day.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Coyotes announced that the right wing would miss four
to six weeks after suffering a fracture during a freak mishap in
the final seconds of a recent practice. Two days later, they
announced the medical staff had made a mistake, that tests
eventually revealed it was simply remnants of an old injury.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, but before Monday's game against the Colorado Avalanche,
Drake said he doesn't remember having suffered a fractured ankle
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I did, I don't remember it hurting me very much because I
can't remember missing a bunch of games,'' Drake said. ``Who knows?
Maybe I was born with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Drake said the ankle felt sore both during and after Sunday's
2-2 tie at Anaheim. But it won't be enough to keep him out of the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' he said. ``Not after getting such great news. I was
ecstatic when I got the call from (team trainer) Gord (Hart).
Christmas came early for me that day. I was jumping for joy. I was
home alone and just started going nuts. My dog thought I was
whacked.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Waiting for No. 1 &QL;  &QL; 
Veteran left wing Greg Adams, who signed as a free agent this
summer, is still searching for his first goal in a Phoenix uniform
after six games. The off-ice officials inadvertently credited him
with one last week in Dallas, but it was reversed and given to
defenseman Oleg Tverdovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Adams has only one assist and is a minus-4, but General Manager
Bobby Smith isn't concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I've been quite pleased with Greg Adams,'' Smith
said. ``He is probably our best forward in terms of hockey
sense.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Nasty Nik &QL;  &QL; 
Goalie Nikolai Khabibulin, who was given the night off Monday,
doesn't back down when an opposing player strays into his territory
and tries to take a few liberties. The 25-year-old Russian proved
that again Sunday in Anaheim, when he drew a roughing minor for
retaliating against Stu Grimson after the Mighty Ducks' enforcer
plowed into him early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Khabibulin had 22 penalty minutes last season, which ranked
among the league leaders for goalies. &QL;  &QL; 
Slapshots &QL;  &QL; 
Center Jeremy Roenick took a hard slapshot off the foot in the
final moments of Sunday's game, but X-rays proved negative.
</P>
<P>
   Center Cliff Ronning reached one milestone Sunday by appearing
in his 700th NHL game, and he's approaching another. He needs two
goals to reach the 200 mark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
