</P>
<P>
   Boxer and her supporters gleefully piled on as Fong tried to
limit the damage from the financial disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   Fong's support for Sheldon's group shows how far out of step he
is with most Californians, Boxer said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer took her re-election campaign to a Santa Monica women's
health clinic, where she and feminist author Gloria Steinem charged
that Fong was helping drive people in the state apart by backing
Sheldon's organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``His support for a group that calls abortion murder doesn't
help bring us together and find a common ground,'' Boxer told about
30 sign-waving supporters in the parking lot behind the cramped,
single-story clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday's fatal shooting of an upstate New York doctor who
performed abortions makes the women's choice issue even more
important in the Senate campaign, Boxer said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Schmidt said, ``Matt Fong is a unifier able to work
with people from all sides of the issues, and he will fight bigotry
and intolerance with his dying breath.''
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, a coalition of community groups demanded
Monday that Fong take back his donation to Sheldon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt Fong has aligned himself in secret with the most
reprehensible group,'' said Episcopal Bishop Otis Charles.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Wong, a San Francisco City College commissioner, said
Asian American groups plan to contact Fong's backers in the local
Asian community to ask them to rethink their support.
</P>
<P>
   The support of Sheldon, he said, ``encourages the kinds of
actions that prey on minorities, women . . . and the
disenfranchised.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
