<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8746 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-TEEPEN-COLUMN28     10-27 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-TEEPEN-COLUMN28 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN. EDS: This is a bonus column written by Tom Teepen,
national correspondent for Cox Newspapers
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Press need to change attitude on Glenn mission
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The press run-up to John Glenn's second space ride tells us
something about the nation's passage since his first ride 36 years
earlier. What it tells us is not altogether pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days before NASA lights the fuse on Glenn's
rocket, coverage has finally begun to warm to the mission.
</P>
<P>
   But for months after Glenn's participation was announced, the
news coverage _ especially though not only television's _ treated
the mission with the kind of deep-seated suspicion usually reserved
for vagrants seen hanging around playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The mission could have been an occasion all along for some low
key national pleasure at the prospect of what promised, at a
minimum, to be a crackling good story _ epic, even, like one of
those ancient sagas.
</P>
<P>
   Here, a hero stands to bring his own adventure full circle
within his lifetime. The triumph of rash youth will be resolved in
a coda of aged accomplishment. A supposed impossibility is to be
unmasked as possible after all. A brave step into the unknown
evolves _ as at the first we could only hope it would _ into an
excursion into the nearly commonplace. The two generations of the
space age travel together in an adventure that binds the younger to
its source in an act of human as well as technological continuity.
Few torches have ever been so intimately passed.
</P>
<P>
   In olden days, at hearthsides and around campfires, poets would
have sung these themes into long skeins of wonder. These days, our
TV anchors, who tutor our attitudes, were having none of it.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't Glenn just a creaky old politician using his office to
muscle his way into a mission where he has no good business?
</P>
<P>
   Aren't these ``experiments'' he allegedly will participate in
only cover to excuse his presence? And doesn't the fact that a
health reason caused one experiment to be dropped prove his
unfitness? And since he and NASA won't say what the reason is,
what's being covered up here?
</P>
<P>
   Just how much taxpayer money is being wasted so this freeloading
pol can catch a joy ride? Aren't workaday folks being skinned for
nothing?
</P>
<P>
   And don't you suppose this is all a stunt by NASA to rip off
some free publicity from honest journalists who've stopped paying
the agency much attention? The real game is to squeeze more money
out of Congress, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Journalism has gone from being willing, bless it, to stand
against the popular mood when the mood turned ugly or foolish to
being unwilling join the popular mood even when the mood is benign
and wanting the best. Our credentials, we sometimes seem to think,
lie not with a healthy skepticism but with a cranky contrariness.
Everyone has to be patted down for weapons, rummaged for ulterior
motive, parsed for prevarication.
</P>
<P>
   We are not, by God, going to let anybody get away with anything,
including a good time.
</P>
<P>
   When John Glenn first went up, even journalists held their
breath and hoped. When it was said he would up up again, we sucked
our teeth and curled our lip.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
