<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8864 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-ACHESON28-COX     10-27 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ACHESON28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dean Acheson left a large American footprint on the world
 &HT;    By Tom Blackburn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ACHESON: The Secretary of State Who Created the American World,
by James Chace. Simon &AMP; Schuster; 512 pages; $30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at that fellow,'' said Sen. Hugh Butler. ``I watch his
smart-aleck manner and his British clothes and that New Dealism in
everything he says and does, and I want to shout, `Get out. Get
out. You stand for everything that has been wrong with the United
States for years!' ''
</P>
<P>
   He was talking about Dean Acheson. Sen. Butler, it goes without
saying, was a Republican of his time _ the 1950s _ and place _
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Butler was only frantic. Rep. Joe McCarthy, R-Wis., was crude,
and Richard Nixon earned his medal for right-wing invective by
calling Adlai Stevenson a graduate of ``Dean Acheson's Cowardly
College of Communist Containment.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long view, it's clear that Nixon, like most of Acheson's
critics, was misinformed. Acheson was no Stevenson supporter. But
what did the son of a Connecticut Episcopal bishop do to make
people hyperventilate so?
</P>
<P>
   He helped sell the Lend Lease program that saved Britain in
1941. He was an architect of the Marshall Plan, which saved Europe
from communism after the war, and of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, which kept it saved. As president, Nixon heartily
approved of NATO; later, Ronald Reagan practically claimed his
party invented it.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans still are not so sure about another Acheson
accomplishment, although it enriched many of their supporters _ the
world trade and monetary system set up after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if the claim on the dust jacket of James Chace's
biography _ that he ``created the American world'' _ goes over the
top, the title of Acheson's autobiography _ Present at the Creation
_ is indisputable.
</P>
<P>
   So, again, what got his enemies so aroused? We won the Cold War,
didn't we?
</P>
<P>
   Well, there was his mustache and the British clothes. And his
education at Groton, where he almost flunked out, and Yale, where
he partied away his time, rowing boats with Averell Harriman and
listening to Cole Porter noodle on the piano. Young Mr. Acheson
doesn't seem to have buckled down until he got to Harvard Law and
met Professor Felix Frankfurter.
</P>
<P>
   Frankfurter sent Acheson ahead of himself to the Supreme Court
as clerk for Justice Louis Brandeis. From there, although he
occasionally tried to practice law, his interest and the excitement
of the jobs kept pulling him into public service. Serving with
people of the quality of Gen. George Marshall would, of course,
make public service attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Acheson was a big fan of Harry Truman, who made him secretary of
state. Truman was a big fan of Acheson. Considering Truman's time
and place, that could make them an odd couple. But both of them
understood and respected the republic and their offices.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans couldn't stand Truman. They hated Franklin
Roosevelt, too, but Acheson could restrain his enthusiasm for FDR.
He found FDR devious and too reliant on charm. Of course, FDR fired
Acheson when he opposed the president's plan to manipulate the
price of gold.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the reason Acheson had enemies was because he didn't
coddle fools. And then, as now, there were more than enough fools
to go around.
</P>
<P>
   Chace, a Bard College professor and author of a half-dozen books
on foreign policy, could have livened this biography with more of
Acheson's contemporary caustic comments. As it is, there are barely
enough.
</P>
<P>
   The book is generally admiring, although Chace does criticize
Acheson for some things. He writes, for instance, that when Gen.
Douglas MacArthur tried to conquer Korea without watching out for
the Chinese Army, Acheson seemed mesmerized. The Chiefs of Staff
also sat, mouths agape, until the Chinese charged and MacArthur
retreated, blaming Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Acheson was a surer hand with Europe than with Asia,
and he devoted too little attention to Latin America and Africa.
But the issue during his years on the bridge of state was whether
there would be a war between the superpowers and, if not, what
would replace it.
</P>
<P>
   There was no war, and Acheson played the major role in putting
the substitutes in place. That they were still there when the
communist empire went into probate suggests that Acheson, whatever
his critics said, got a lot of things right.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Blackburn writes for the Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 1037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
