<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8865 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-AMES-COX     10-27 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-AMES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sly comic touch turns into something else
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE EXTRA MAN, by Jonathan Ames. Scribner's; 333 pages; $23.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Ives wants to be a young gentleman. He has read The
Razor's Edge and Brideshead Revisited and has moved on to
Wodehouse, Wilde, Mann and Fitzgerald and has come to the
conclusion that he wants to be like the characters in their books,
except without the drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Louis is neat, he is polite, he writes thank-you notes, he
shaves every day. He is ripe for membership in some kind of
literary salon, if only somebody would start one. Louis has come to
New York, not to start a career, not to become successful, but to
bask in its aura.
</P>
<P>
   Louis has lived rather too much with fiction and too little with
the real world.
</P>
<P>
   This beguiling, quietly disturbing novel by a gifted young
writer introduces Louis _ and us _ to Henry Harrison, who needs
someone to share the rent in his hovel. These two eccentric eunuchs
become roommates of convenience.
</P>
<P>
   Henry is a writer, working on a sex comedy about the Shakers,
making eds meet by teaching at a community college that sounds
nearly as disreputable as him. He is perpetually impoverished,
hasn't paid taxes in years, is of an uncertain age and uncertain
sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he's probably untouched by human hands, even his own.
He dances attendance on a succession of elderly women with homes in
Palm Beach, so he at least has a place to get out of the winter.
</P>
<P>
   This is a harder job than it sounds, because you have to be
eternally vigilant. Elderly women fall down a lot. If they fall
down too hard, they can die. Or they can get an infection in their
hip replacement, and where are you then? Stranded in Palm Beach
without money for food or plane fare.
</P>
<P>
   Henry is Quentin Crisp run through a blender, but that is to
trivialize Ames' achievement here. There are a lot of Henry
Harrisons in the world, quiet wrecks who spend their lives visiting
friends and dispensing light entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of The Extra Man is a two-hander in which Louis
lobs questions and Henry hits them over the center-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you like Fitzgerald?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course . . . His prose is like cocktail music. But there
won't be any more Fitzgeralds. You need an all-male environment . .
. the Muslims might produce a Fitzgerald. They're good at
separating the sexes.''
</P>
<P>
   Or this, after Louis asks Henry why everybody is so crazed about
sex:
</P>
<P>
   ``People have too much to eat. They don't have the survival
problem which would keep them sane. We need to cut the rations.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry eats well only during the winters in Palm Beach, where he
can average four dinners and three cocktail parties a week. With
some discreet doggie-bagging, he can get by without ever buying a
meal.
</P>
<P>
   Louis is fascinated by this outre character, worships him. Louis
is in the grip of a particularly damaging kind of literary fantasy,
in which he sees himself as a moon for someone else's planet, a
character in someone else's story.
</P>
<P>
   Sexually, Louis likes men who dress in women's clothes. In a
funny/sad scene, Louis even tries on an unflattering outfit
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, both these men are in limbo. As a transsexual tells
Louis: ``You're not really straight, you're not really gay. You're
straightish.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several antecedents for this story _ Of Mice and Men
and Harold and Maude, among others. Sex is not the issue;
incompletion is. All these books are about two crucially damaged
people who come together to form a stronger unit.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound pompous orstuffy, but The Extra Man is neither.
It starts out as high comedy _ in the age of There's Something
About Mary, an endangered species _ but it evolves into something
else.
</P>
<P>
   Henry moves from a stand-in for Auntie Mame, a larger-than-life
theatrical turn bristling with campy one-liners, to a human being.
</P>
<P>
   Ames lets us see the desperation beneath the brittle surface,
and we come to appreciate Henry for his twisted gallantry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all inherit something,'' he tells Louis. ``I inherited a
mind. They inherited money. I inherited a certain charm . . . and a
joie de vivre, which is nice to have. I give them wit and
conversation and they give me food. It's a fair exchange.''
</P>
<P>
   Ames' novel is too funny to be called compassionate, too dark to
be considered uplifting. But in Henry and Louis, Ames has created _
or transcribed _ two of the most startlingly human characters in
recent fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Eyman writes for the Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
