<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8866 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-RUNWAYMADNESS-C     10-27 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-RUNWAYMADNESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Photographer: `I never became adept at understanding fashion'
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   His assignment: Go to New York and Milan and Paris and London
and shoot clothes for The Washington Post. He didn't know which
outfits were important, so he shot them all, just in case. Four to
six rolls of film per fashion show.
</P>
<P>
   Then Lucian Perkins began watching the people who sat beside the
runway. When he had a split-second to spare, he started shooting
them.
</P>
<P>
   This was a decade ago, before Kate Moss and House of Style.
Photographers could line up along the runway. No crouching at the
end of it under another guy's armpit, like now. Designers even let
him stay backstage during shows.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a book of Perkins' photographs, called Runway
Madness (Chronicle Books, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   It has, for example, Naomi Campbell in curlers. Good luck
getting that anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess about one or two years ago, she started having people
with her to tell photographers not to photograph her,'' Perkins
says. ``It was really weird.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not sure how long he will keep shooting these things.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he has to. Perkins won a Pulitzer Prize in 1995 for a
story on poverty in a Washington, D.C., family. He was Newspaper
Photographer of the Year in 1994 and won World Press Photo of the
Year in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   His big interest is Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But fashion gave him his first book.
</P>
<P>
   He's no clotheshorse himself. ``I usually just buy khakis,'' he
says. ``Nothing exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   But he likes the exciting designers _ Todd Oldham, Issac
Mizrahi, Betsey Johnson and her somersaults on the runway. Those
who put on a good show.
</P>
<P>
   The most boring: Calvin Klein. ``His models have a total blank
expression on their faces.''
</P>
<P>
   The last good photo he got from a Calvin Klein show was around
1987, when the Somali-born Iman was still modeling. It's in the
book.
</P>
<P>
   Others in there: RuPaul with a videocam, Donna Karan in dorky
glasses, and a row full of surly fashion editors, with Vogue's Anna
Wintour right in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the models hardly smile either during shows. After a
decade, Perkins still doesn't understand why. With all those
cameras?
</P>
<P>
   ``It amazes me,'' he says. ``They walk out there looking like,
`I don't want to be here, leave me alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Some day he will.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
