<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8867 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS-COX     10-27 1741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roth scores points in his 22nd novel
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his 65th year, Philip Roth has written his 22nd novel. I
Married a Communist is a very good book _ brisk, sad and, in spots,
wildly funny. Roth expertly juggles characters, cultural sociology
and what seems to be a veiled response to ex-wife Claire Bloom's
cause celebre about their marriage, Leaving a Doll's House.
</P>
<P>
   Sentence by sentence, idea by idea, I Married a Communist could
have been written by no one but Philip Roth; it's a virtual
anthology of the concerns that have animated his entire career.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, American writers concerned about the Jewish
experience had social or class concerns _ Henry Roth's Call It
Sleep, an avatar of the proletarian novels of the '30s, was
typical.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1959, when he arrived with Goodbye, Columbus, Roth, and a
few others like Saul Bellow and Bernard Malamud, brought the
literary Jew into the middle class. And then Roth went the others
one better and sexualized him.
</P>
<P>
   For several generations of writers who had spent their lives
emulating Hollywood moguls by finessing their Jewish identity,
books like Columbus and the uproarious Portnoy's Complaint, Roth's
commercial and cultural break-through of 1969, were a tsunami of
eros.
</P>
<P>
   Roth's subjects have always been Jews, Sex and Making It, if
possible all three at once. And just like Budd Schulberg, who wrote
What Makes Sammy Run?, Roth has been accused of giving aid and
comfort to the enemies of his people _ an early version of
political correctness, here masquerading behind racial paranoia.
</P>
<P>
   Roth has always ignored the criticism and gone his own way.
There was a furiously inventive satire of the Nixon years called
Our Gang, a surreal, marginal Kafka take-off called The Breast. I
also have happy memories of a book called The Great American Novel
that nobody seems to remember, but contains one of my favorite
opening lines: ``Call me Smitty.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming after anything but American Pastoral, Roth's masterpiece
of last year, I Married a Communist would be a triumph. The two
books are structurally similar _ essentially long monologues about
the tragedy of a man who is already dead as the book opens.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, that man is Ira Ringold, a New York leftie who
becomes a radio star after World War II under the name Iron Rinn.
Ira fronts a show called The Free and the Brave, in which various
episodes of American history are dramatized.
</P>
<P>
   When Ira's not before the microphone, he's capitalizing on his
resemblance to Lincoln by visiting schools and other public places
in full 1863-era regalia, giving an anti-capitalist spin to
Lincoln's words.
</P>
<P>
   But Ira is destroyed by the confluence of the Red Scare, his own
single-minded obstinacy, and the woman he self-destructively
chooses as his wife, Eve Frame, a former silent film star and
anti-Semitic Jew.
</P>
<P>
   The man who tells the story is Ira's 90-year-old brother Murray,
a schoolteacher who has his life derailed by proximity to his
brother. The man he is telling the story to is Nathan Zuckerman,
Roth's alter-ego of the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   With rather more dead-pan wit than his bawdy nature usually
allows for, Roth appropriates the title of a grotesque, thankfully
forgotten 1950 Red Scare movie produced by Howard Hughes. The movie
is a metaphor for the insanity of the period. Hughes used the
project as a litmus test; if a director refused the atrocious
script, he was graylisted or blacklisted; if a director accepted,
he was politically OK, but the project was taken away from him and
handed off to the next man on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   The eventual victim, the man who actually made the movie, was
Robert Stevenson, who did what he was told and ended up directing
Mary Poppins. The movie was impossible to take seriously even in
1950, but despite the silly title, Roth isn't after bleak sarcasm
or even crazed farce. He's going for writhing anguish.
</P>
<P>
   The blacklist period is like the American Revolution _ wonderful
material, but for some reason, rarely touched. Roth brings the
tenor of the times back: Norman Corwin's hortatory radio plays,
FDR-worship, Paul Robeson standing tall, the novels of Howard Fast,
the ardent belief in a coming society of the proletariat.
</P>
<P>
   Ira is a true believer, a take-no-prisoners Commie who talks
about Churchill the same way he talks about Leo Durocher _ a
no-good bastard beyond redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Although I Married a Communist is not a particularly large
novel, it contains multitudinous ideas, and some wonderful extended
riffs.
</P>
<P>
   There's Murray Ringold's taxonomy of Jewish types beyond the
angry Jew: ``The inappropriate-laughing Jews, the
I-love-everyone-deeply Jews, the Momma-and-Poppa-were-saints Jews,
the I-do-it-all-for-my-gifted-children Jews, the
I'm-sitting-here-listening-to-Itzhak-Perlman-and-I'm-crying Jews,
the entertaining Jew of perpetual punning, the serial Jewish
joker.''
</P>
<P>
   And here's Murray talking about the psychology of informing:
</P>
<P>
   ``When before had betrayal ever been so destigmatized and
rewarded in this country? It was everywhere during those years, the
accessible transgression, the permissible transgression that any
American could commit. Not only does the pleasure of betrayal
replace the prohibition, but you transgress without giving up your
moral authority. You retain your purity at the same time as you are
patriotically betraying _ at the same time as you are realizing a
satisfaction that verges on the sexual with its ambiguous
components of pleasure and weakness, of aggression and shame: the
satisfaction of undermining.''
</P>
<P>
   A Nixon-hater of long standing, Roth can't resist a diversionary
but delightful screed in the new book about Nixon's funeral, where
Murray ticks off the list of repulsive mourners, especially
``sparkly Dan Quayle, looking as lucid as a button. The heroic
effort made by that poor fellow: always staging intelligence and
always failing.''
</P>
<P>
   I Married a Communist continues Roth's remarkable resurgence of
the past decade. In the '70s and '80s, Roth occupied himself with a
series of books involving Nathan Zuckerman. There are those who
love them, but I find them turgid and heavy _ joyless,
post-modernist word games about identity, a strange detour for a
writer whose great gift is satire and antic realism. But in this
decade, Roth turned a corner and went back to bedrock.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote Patrimony, a passionate, moving memoir about his
father's long dying, followed it with Sabbath's Theater and
finished it off with American Pastoral. This is an astonishing
trilogy for a writer of Roth's age, when even the best writers
begin to coast on their reputations and backlist.
</P>
<P>
   Of these books, I'll put my money on Patrimony and American
Pastoral as lasting works. Sabbath's Theater is too extreme in its
sexuality and too scabrous in its characterizations to ever be
embraced by a wide audience.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of book that, had it been written by someone 30
years younger _ David Foster Wallace or T. Coraghessan Boyle _ it
would have been praised for its brave disinterest in anything
approaching middle-class mores. But I get a sense that people in
their 20s and 30s aren't interested in Roth _ 15 years of the
Zuckerman books cost him a generation of readers.
</P>
<P>
   As for American Pastoral, it deservedly won the Pulitzer Prize
for fiction, up against some heavy competition _ Don DeLillo,
Thomas Pynchon, etc. It was a slight departure for Roth, because
the central character, one Swede Levov, is far more sweet-natured
than most Roth protagonists, as well as far more passive. He's a
nice guy, not exactly a richly populated category in Roth's books,
and it costs him everything.
</P>
<P>
   Ira Ringold is no Swede Levov, which is where I Married a
Communist falls a bit short of its predecessor. He's a humorless
ideologue, and like most of that all too-common breed, he verges on
the tedious. Ira's rage, doctrinaire Communism and narcissistic
inability to see the big picture guarantees that he will hit the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   But Ira's brother Murray is a wise riot, another of those funny,
verbal old Jews that Roth channels at will, and his analysis of why
his long-dead brother never left his wife carries a devastating
charge of pity and resigned compassion:
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's dissatisfied, but by and large not leaving is what
people do. Especially people who've been left themselves. Come
through what you two came through, and you value stability very
highly. Probably overvalue it. The hardest thing in the world is to
cut the knot of your life and leave. People make ten thousand
adjustments to even the most pathological behavior. Why,
emotionally, is a man of his type reciprocally connected to a woman
of her type? The usual reason: their flaws fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like any prolific artist, Philip Roth has had flops both
aesthetic and commercial, but he's also sent ripples across the
cultural pond.
</P>
<P>
   Roth gave writers like Joseph Heller emotional leave to deal
with the issues of religion and rage. Likewise, Woody Allen's dips
into misanthropy that are always so off-putting to what's left of
his audience _ Stardust Memories, Crimes and Misdemeanors, and,
especially, Deconstructing Harry _ couldn't exist without the
example of Roth's characters flailing in a sea of self-loathing.
</P>
<P>
   Art, of course, is cross-pollination, and Roth's tone owes a
good deal to the free-form monologues of Lenny Bruce, with both men
putting special emphasis on the terrible things mothers do to their
sons. Indeed, most of Roth's books tend to revolve around the
accumulating horror found in a badly matched family unit.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, Roth's 22 novels seem to me to form a teeming
portrait of what it means to be alive in the latter half of 20th
century America, of the inherent failure of the American dream,
especially the part about ``pursuit of happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Portnoy's complaint turns out to be, more or less, that nobody
understands him. Roth's people are alienated and, ultimately,
alone. That Roth has managed to spend 40 years telling stories of
desperation and panic without spinning out of control, always
maintaining a tight hold on his art, is amazing.
</P>
<P>
   I Married a Communist proves again that Roth remains the champ,
the best writer we have.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Eyman writes for the Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
