<HEADER>
A8868 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATE-THE-50S-COX     10-27 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-THE-50S-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    50 reasons to hate the '50s
 &HT;    Staff report
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the new movie ``Pleasantville,'' two
colorful, modern teens slip into life with a black-and-white,
small-town '50s TV family. They find it all pretty darn dreamy
until, gasp, reality hits.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the '50s weren't as cozy as we've been told.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, sometimes they were downright awful.
</P>
<P>
   So to get in the proper mood for ``Pleasantville,'' we've come
up with 50 REASONS TO HATE THE '50s (in no particular order).
</P>
<P>
   1. When you wanted to change channels on your TV set or turn up
the sound over your father's snoring, you had to get up and use the
knobs on the set. There were three channels from which to choose,
if your antenna could pick up all the stations.
</P>
<P>
   2. Buddy Holly was putting Texas on the rock 'n' roll map when
he decided to try to fly through an Iowa snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
   3. The really cool look of a cigarette dangling from lips or
waving in one's hand was jeopardized when a committee of experts
appointed by the American Heart Association and the American Cancer
Society reported the link between smoking and lung cancer as a sure
thing.
</P>
<P>
   4. To gas up your car, you had to wait for some guy to come out
of the station to pump it for you. And he was always asking dumb
questions such as, ``Check those tires, mister?''
</P>
<P>
   5. There were few seat belts and no airbags to protect you when
fast, heavy, two-tone cars with fins crashed into each other.
</P>
<P>
   6. Boxing was like a real sport, without ear-biting.
</P>
<P>
   7. Fresh vegetables were pretty much limited to lettuce and
potatoes. Everything else cooked by your mom came from cans or
frozen blocks. Even some meat and lots of fruit came in cans.
</P>
<P>
   8. Disneyland opened in California, forcing parents who
otherwise could have taken vacations by themselves to pack along
the kids, who chanted, ``We want to see Mickey'' after watching
TV's ``The Mickey Mouse Club.''
</P>
<P>
   9. Charlton Heston was our history teacher, showing us what
Moses and Ben Hur were really like.
</P>
<P>
   10. Bras were pointy, and 18-inch waists were achieved through
the miracle of girdles.
</P>
<P>
   11. Ketchup was a big deal, so was Jell-O. Your mother even
seemed to combine the two in something wiggly and red that came out
of a mold and was called tomato aspic.
</P>
<P>
   12. A ``gourmet'' food revolution gave us escargot, fondue and
souffles.
</P>
<P>
   13. Bomb drills at school were stupid, as if huddling under a
Formica lunch-room table would save you from incineration or
radiation poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   14. If you were a kid, and you wanted to do something fun, you
had to get permission from both of your parents, since both of them
lived with you.
</P>
<P>
   15. If you wanted to listen to a 45 rpm record, and the record
player your parents bought at Sears didn't have the right spindle,
you had to stick one of those plastic thingies in the hole to make
it fit on the turntable.
</P>
<P>
   16. There were no videos, so if you wanted to see a movie, you
had to go to a theater, which had one screen and one movie for
about a month. Unless it offered a double feature.
</P>
<P>
   17. The big controversy on the radio was: Who's better? Pat
Boone or Elvis Presley?
</P>
<P>
   18. In ``girls'' basketball, the guards weren't allowed past
midcourt because people thought running was hard on women.
</P>
<P>
   19. You had to wait an hour after lunch to go swimming, or you
would seize up from cramps and drown. That was true because that's
what your mother told you.
</P>
<P>
   20. The McCarthy era, which had nothing to do with Jenny
McCarthy, ruined the promising careers of government officials,
Hollywood writers and broadcasters as a senator from Wisconsin
found Communist sympathizers everywhere he looked.
</P>
<P>
   21. Ovaltine came in one flavor, and it wasn't even Diet.
</P>
<P>
   22. Look-alike suburbs boomed almost everywhere and led to the
decay of some perfectly good cities.
</P>
<P>
   23. Texas A&AMP;M was all-male.
</P>
<P>
   24. Kids who had just learned where all the states were on a map
got thrown a curve when Alaska and Hawaii were added to the Union.
</P>
<P>
   25. With the collapse of ``The $64,000 Question,'' we learned
that all those TV quiz shows that we imagined as a way to get rich
were rigged.
</P>
<P>
   26.That insipid tune about the hills being alive with the sound
of music was launched on Broadway and would not stop being sung for
years and years to come.
</P>
<P>
   27. No voicemail or answering machines existed to screen your
telephone calls, but then without telemarketers there weren't so
many calls coming in. Party lines meant you had to wait your turn
to call out.
</P>
<P>
   28. Women stayed home, took care of the kids and cooked a lot of
unhealthy stuff without the benefit of microwaves.
</P>
<P>
   29. Only boys got to wear Army boots.
</P>
<P>
   30. Petticoats were almost as great an inhibition to sex as
pantyhose in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   31. Richard Nixon earned a decent enough reputation as vice
president under Ike.
</P>
<P>
   32. With no birth control pills, men were supposed to be
responsible for avoiding unwanted pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   33. The Korean War taught us absolutely nothing about messing in
a civil war between the north and south of an Asian country.
</P>
<P>
   34. Harsh, smelly, frizzy permanents made hairstyling a
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   35. Fluoride was the vile stuff that the dentist swabbed on your
teeth instead of hidden in toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
   36. Saddle shoes, bobby sox and poodle skirts were what passed
for fashion in high school.
</P>
<P>
   37. Ernest Borgnine won an Academy Award.
</P>
<P>
   38. Aquamarine was a popular interior decorating hue.
</P>
<P>
   39. Milton Berle was the funniest thing on television, and he
sometimes wore a dress.
</P>
<P>
   40. Sexual repression meant J. Edgar Hoover could wear a dress
only in his home, but we didn't know that until many years later.
</P>
<P>
   41. Perky hygiene filmstrips were shown in schools, even
college.
</P>
<P>
   42. Children were still taken out of school in warm months, were
forbidden to go swimming in summer and were hidden away in small
towns to protect them from a mysterious disease called polio.
</P>
<P>
   43. Women were called girls, broads, dear and, if they didn't
give up their careers when they got married, they were chased
around the proverbial desk at work.
</P>
<P>
   44. Your mom was convinced calves liver was a necessary part of
your diet.
</P>
<P>
   45. Unless you lived in a city with a large Italian population,
spaghetti came in a Franco-American can and pizza was tough to
find, let alone get delivered to your house.
</P>
<P>
   46. It took a long time to call a telephone number because you
had to switch between letters and numbers and turn that rotary dial
with your finger.
</P>
<P>
   47. Butch wax and Brylcreem made men's hair disgusting.
</P>
<P>
   48. Haircuts were cheap at the barbershop, but you got what you
paid for. Otherwise you had to endure a parent who thought anyone
could cut hair with scissors and -- razor.
</P>
<P>
   49. The African American population was treated separately and
unequally when it came to schools, buses, hotels, water fountains,
voting, housing, jobs and almost everything else. 50. You couldn't
educate yourself about adultery, incest and the Ku Klux Klan by
watching daytime television.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
