</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8869 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLD28-COX     10-27 1400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    eniors enjoy improved lives by keeping active
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sneakers squeak as guys in their 20s and 30s sprint up
and down the basketball court, passing, shooting, high-fiving _ and
in a few cases _ huffing and puffing. But Richard Miller is hardly
breaking a sweat. Which is noteworthy because, at age 75, he's been
running longer that most of his pals have been breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Ivano Newbill, a former Georgia Tech star who played last year
with the NBA's Vancouver Grizzlies and often is one of Miller's
teammates, is in awe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He rebounds. He hits jump shots. If there was a league for
people 70 and older like the NBA, he would be the Michael Jordan,''
Newbill says.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's not alone. As the United States prepares to send a
77-year-old astronaut, Sen. John Glenn, into orbit, millions of
ordinary older Americans are likewise attending to physical
pursuits once thought for youngsters only.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who is 6-foot-2, weighs in at a trim 183, and he plays
despite health problems. ``I'm recovering from two cancers, but
nobody knows it,'' he says. ``Out here I'm a player, not a
patient.''
</P>
<P>
   He shows up three times a week at the YMCA in east Cobb County
for pickup games with guys of all ages, sometimes even teenage
stars of area high school teams.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago he broke his right wrist ``after a guy charged
me.'' But Miller, like Glenn, is more than willing to take chances.
Maybe eager.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with older people is, they give up,'' says Miller,
a divorce with four children and six grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can outrun most of them. I'm not going down without a
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   This Y and many other health clubs are packed daily with men and
women who qualify for senior-citizens discounts, but don't act the
part. Here, Fred Poore, 62, is on staff, a stocky, muscular man who
specializes in weight training for older folks. He assists people
such as Les Petherick, 68, a retired Navy pilot whose biceps bulge
as much as those young jocks' on TV health shows.
</P>
<P>
   Though some have been inspired by Glenn's upcoming spaceflight,
it's been television and heavily promoted health campaigns pushed
by agencies such as the National Institute on Aging that have made
older people more aware of the benefits of exercise, says Elaine
Cress of the Exercise Sciences &AMP; Gerontology Center at the
University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn has been a major player in the NIA's push, supporting its
agenda in Congress for more than a decade and demanding increased
funding. By maintaining the hard body he had as America's first man
in orbit 36 years ago, as well as a high public profile, he's also
become a role model for the geriatric set, a very visible example
that it is possible to stay ahead of the Grim Reaper on life's
ever-accelerating treadmill.
</P>
<P>
   Increased physical activity, not just scientific breakthroughs,
is a major reason Americans are living longer, with the average
lifespan rocketing from 69 in 1960 to 76 today. In the last
Peachtree Road Race, which attracted 55,000 runners, 1,061 were 60
or older, and 138 older than 70, says Julia Emmons of the Atlanta
Track Club, which puts on the event. Those numbers are increasing
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Pilgrim, a 47-year-old executive with the state Department
of Human Resources who's coordinated the Georgia Golden Olympics
for years, says more and more people are competing each year.
Contestants range from 55 to their 90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've shown that aging doesn't mean you're over the hill,''
Pilgrim says. ``Fifty-five or 60 is no longer the end of the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, at the Golden Games in Warner Robins, 560
people participated, and some qualified to attend the national
Golden Olympics next year in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 85 and old enough to be over the hill,'' says Marvin Loyd
of Brookhaven, one of the participants. ``But I qualified to run in
the 5- and 10k (kilometer) races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to doctors, and they say I'm in great shape. I ran the 5k
in 30 minutes flat, just slightly under 10-minute miles. I make it
to nationals just about every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Loyd hasn't stopped running since he was a track star in high
school. He says he's almost as fast as he was in 1944, when he
sprinted over the beaches and hedgerows of Normandy after D-Day. He
also claims he can outrun two of his three children _ and both of
his grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when you get old _ and I don't feel old _ it's clear that
physical fitness is good for the mind, body, soul and spirit,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy L. White, a relative youngster at 61, has been competing
in athletic events since high school. He now teaches phys ed at
Palmetto Elementary School in south Fulton County and runs at a
track daily. He's been competing for years in the Golden Olympics
and any other age-group events he hears about. His specialty: the
pentathlon, a combination of long jump, discus, javelin, triple
jump and a metric-mile run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get old,'' he declares.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude toward staying physically active is no anomaly,
says Douglas Kleiber, head of recreation and leisure studies at
UGA.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents are still playing golf and tennis at 80,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many elders do fall by the wayside physically.
</P>
<P>
   Many, Kleiber maintains, have been indoctrinated by a culture of
``ageism'' that stresses youth and devalues the elderly. ``Not as
many older people do physical activity as they could,'' Kleiber
says.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, chronic health problems move people from
treadmills to recliners.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 30 percent of adults older than 65 report no physical
activity at all, according to the American Medical Association, and
38 percent suffer chronic illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But the trend is toward more activity, and it's showing up in
various ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disability rate as we increase in our numbers of older
people being active is actually declining,'' UGA's Cress says. ``We
are seeing a decline in heart disease. Hypertension is getting
under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glenn is a motivator,'' she adds, ``but the real motivator is
that people don't want to go live in some nursing home.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence that workouts benefit older folks abounds:
</P>
<P>
   _ The average lifespan for Americans has soared from 66 for
males and 73 females in 1960 to 73 for men and 79 for females.
</P>
<P>
   _ A study of 101 men and women ages 60 to 83 found that regular
aerobic exercise for four months increased heart and lung function
up to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ A study of 8,000 Japanese-American men ages 45 to 68, begun in
the mid 1960s, found recently that five hours a day of moderate to
heavy activity reduced the incidence of heart disease by 17 percent
and the death rate from heart disease by 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Tufts University study of people 60 to 72 who trained with
weights found that most were able to boost the strength of their
hamstring muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Kleiber hopes Glenn's mission will help scientists gain more
control over aging.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he says, after only a few days of weightlessness,
astronauts lose up to 10 percent of their muscle tissue. But will
Glenn lose bone and muscle mass more rapidly, because he is older,
or more slowly, since he already has lost some mass with aging? The
answer could provide clues about how to treat bone loss.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, people such as Helen Moore will continue to
fight aging on their own. The 90-year-old Atlantan goes to tai chi
classes twice a week and practices daily in her home, flailing her
arms and legs like a karate expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``It clears your mind. Your body feels better. It can make you
feel positive,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Or Iris Sandham, 72, of Snellville, the state's champion
horseshoe tosser for several years running.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walk. I run. I bowl two, three times a week,'' she says. ``I
have a room full of trophies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a horseshoe court in my basement and throw the heaviest
you can have, 2 pounds and 10 ounces. I play against men in the top
class and win.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Harrell, 76, of Eastman has always been active, but Glenn's
trip has inspired her to new heights. In a couple of weeks, she
plans a trip to Kitty Hawk, N.C., where the Wright Brothers first
flew, for a flight of her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so proud of John Glenn,'' she says. ``Least I can do is a
little hang-gliding.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
