<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETER-PAUL-MARY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    '60s idealism drives Peter, Paul &AMP; Mary
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``Please call me back on the other
line,'' Peter Yarrow says with a hint of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the call has arrived on the business phone in
Yarrow's New York apartment. And when you're in the business of
promoting the world's most successful folk trio _ Peter, Paul &AMP;
Mary _ things can get, well, busy.
</P>
<P>
   Now in its 38th year, Peter, Paul &AMP; Mary remains more than a
throwback to the long-haired idealism of the '60s: It's a thriving
institution. The trio _ composed of Yarrow, Noel Paul Stookey and
Mary Travers _ just released its 20th album, Around the Campfire, a
collection of favorites that's designed to encourage fans to sing
along. Its most recent PBS special, Lifelines, garnered an Emmy
nomination. And it continues to speak out on a variety of causes,
from championing the rights of strawberry pickers in California to
supporting the peace process in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   How does the 60-year-old Yarrow account for Peter, Paul &AMP; Mary's
enduring popularity?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a greater value being attached to people who defined
the folk renaissance of the '60s,'' he says. ``Some of us are
passing away, like John Denver (whose Leaving on a Jet Plane the
trio turned into a No. 1 hit in 1969). Others are not able to sing
with the same kind of energy and impunity.''
</P>
<P>
   But what it really comes down to, Yarrow adds, is celebrating
that '60s idealism. ``I think in a world that's increasingly
homogenized, there is a greater value (being placed) on people who
made very individual statements and who did create a stream of some
kind of innovative efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter, Paul &AMP; Mary's ``stream'' was part musical, part
political. Founded in the creative cauldron of the Greenwich
Village '60s folk scene, the trio provided a sweet voice to an era,
turning songs like Bob Dylan's ``Blowin' in the Wind'' and ``Don't
Think Twice, It's Alright'' and Pete Seeger's ``If I Had a Hammer''
into unlikely radio hits. And that's to say nothing of its classic
original, ``Puff, the Magic Dragon,'' which climbed to No. 2 on the
pop charts in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Critics described the group's sound as ``two cellos and an
angel,'' with Yarrow, a one-time Ivy League psychology major, and
Stookey, a budding stand-up comic, providing the mellow backdrop to
Travers, the Village veteran with the airy soprano. ``It was all
intuitive,'' Yarrow says of the trio's signature vocal blend.
</P>
<P>
   But for Peter, Paul &AMP; Mary, music was also the means to a
message. From its inception, the group was at the forefront of the
political protests that shaped the '60s. In 1963, it marched with
The Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., in Selma, Ala. In 1969, Yarrow
co-organized the anti-Vietnam War March on Washington _ and the
trio sang for the half-million people who gathered for the event.
</P>
<P>
   Yarrow says you can't separate the singing from the social
causes. ``You feel in somebody's voice the seriousness of their
concerns,'' he explains. ``The fact that we have a sense of mission
is fundamental to our survival. There is not a group in the world
that has reached the kind of acclaim we did that is still together
in its original form.''
</P>
<P>
   But if you throw out the term ``nostalgia act'' to Yarrow, don't
expect a polite response.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been nostalgia at all,'' he says of the trio's
appeal. ``There are four generations that come to hear us sing. A
lot of them remember when they first heard the songs, but an equal
number have just recently experienced them.''
</P>
<P>
   The group's history can be traced on Around the Campfire, which
includes vintage recordings of such Peter, Paul &AMP; Mary favorites as
``Puff, the Magic Dragon,'' ``Leaving on a Jet Plane'' and ``If I
Had a Hammer'' as well as four new tracks. The idea, says Yarrow,
is not so much for people to listen, but for them to take an active
part in the musical experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea was the Pete Seeger idea of getting America
singing again. That's such an important tool for recreating a
connection at a time when we are besieged by extraordinary
problems,'' he says, before citing a litany of figures relating to
violence and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   But can singing a folk song really change the world? Yarrow
still thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It embraces your heart and reactivates your sensitivity to
friends and family,'' he concludes. ``In its own way, it's an act
of consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
