<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    65 is just the start of a new lifetime
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio. _ Last week, in a fit of ``fogo'' (fear of
growing old), I was bellyaching about a friend's 4-year-old
grandson who'd climbed onto my lap, taken my face between his
hands, looked me square in the eye and declared, ``You're really
getting old.''
</P>
<P>
   Good taste dictated I couldn't dump the kid on his backside, nor
could I suggest his parents ground him until his 42nd birthday.
Dignity spared the moment. But that didn't stop me from writing
about it and now, thanks to a reader named Jeanne in Florida, I'm
feeling a whole lot better. Here's what she had to say:
</P>
<P>
   ``Once upon a time I knew a very depressed lady. Her time was
up. Life was over. Her chest sagged, her tush was flabby, thighs
had relocated somewhere around her ankles, jowls ruffled around her
neck, and her crow's feet had turned into ostrich claws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty-five. Her birthday stared her square in her now
dim-sighted, faded blue eyes. She exercised, but the flab, bags,
and sags wouldn't budge. She dieted. As she got slimmer, the
wrinkles got deeper. Life was not good. The sunshine was gone. Only
dark clouds on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, on a day like any other, eight weeks before this
deplorable birthday was to arrive, the postman came at noon.
Nothing unusual about that, but this day, mixed in with the pile of
junk mail and bills, was an envelope from the
</P>
<P>
   U.S. government. Inside, a red, white, and blue card from
MEDICARE.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolute proof that she was old, and to increase her agony,
she was informed her Medicare would start a month early since her
birthday fell on the 1st. She wondered: Was there any other
indignity left to endure?
</P>
<P>
   ``The day of disgrace and humiliation arrived. Self-pity and
gloom hung heavy in the air as she sat on the sofa, barely glancing
at the morning newspaper. No magic. No forecast of promised
miracles. Even her horoscope was bland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flipping through the pages, her dimmed blue eyes scanned a
headline that sent a rush through her body. A message surely meant
for her: `Still punching a time clock at 103.' She read on. A
gentleman by the name of Milton W. Garland
</P>
<P>
   has been punching the same time clock at a Pennsylvania
refrigeration business for 78 years and has no intention of
quitting. Says working builds character. His advice: `Don't worry
about anything. Worry never solved anything. All it
</P>
<P>
   does is distort your mind.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Slowly the thought began. She reread the article. Maybe!
Maybe! She put down her coffee and began to reorganize her
distorted mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The human body is made to function on into the 120s, so
research has stated. Gracious, she thought, with that in mind she
has another 55-65 years. Almost another lifetime. Life is only
beginning. After all, she didn't even go to college until she was
49. Got her first job at 54. Just a late bloomer. Maybe there is
still a little blush left on the rose yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then too, she wondered, is the U.S. government ever right?
Seldom. Silly woman. Why hadn't she thought it through? She was in
such discord, so out of rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you Milton W. Garland. The government is wrong.
Sixty-five is not old - only middle-aged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sags, bags, and wrinkles are still there, the walk a
little slower, and men don't whistle anymore, but what do they
know?
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside this saggy, baggy, body is a young woman saying, `Let
me out.' With defiance, these blue eyes plan to look at 65 and say,
`Get out of my way. I have a lot to do. Haven't got time to worry
about you.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne, I'm with you. We're far from alone in this boat and it
makes a whole lot of us feel better to have you as a traveling
companion.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett, a writer and teacher in Gibsonburg, Ohio,
writes for Cox News Service. She may be reached at 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, Ohio, 43431 or eschuett(at)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
