<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NO-LOCKERS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High school students lose their lockers
 &HT;    By Pamela LeBlanc
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRANGER, Texas _ Students hoping to skip out on a few moments of
class in Granger can no longer use the time-honored excuse that
they left something in their locker.
</P>
<P>
   That's because school officials removed the lockers at Granger
High School this summer in an effort to clean up hallways, reduce
noise levels and trim the number of students tardy to class.
Administrators say they'll never go back to using lockers again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere and environment are so much more conducive to
learning,'' Principal James Bartosh said.
</P>
<P>
   It's an idea that's playing out across the state, as school
administrators look for ways to keep schools safe and teach
students to plan ahead. But it's also a program that's not popular
with many students, who like having a place to stash their
belongings.
</P>
<P>
   Tana Loving, 16, who is involved in several extracurricular
activities at Granger High, says she simply can't carry everything
she needs. ``You have all this stuff you need to put somewhere, and
there's nowhere to put it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing from a concept instituted by a middle school in
Victoria, Granger administrators removed the lockers hoping to
increase student responsibility. The two districts are among about
a dozen in Texas that don't have lockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students would have to be organized when they left the
house,'' Bartosh said. ``They would have to think about the day and
plan ahead instead of rolling out of bed and coming to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Other advantages quickly became clear at Granger, a 1A high
school with about 140 ninth through 12th-graders. Students no
longer gathered by their lockers to socialize, meaning fewer were
late to class. Tardies dropped by two-thirds, and without the
banging of metal doors, the hallways grew quieter.
</P>
<P>
   That lull surprised Peter Reese, who graduated from Granger last
year and recently dropped by the campus. ``We would slam the locker
doors on purpose,'' he said. ``The teachers went crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   The theft problem has been almost eliminated since lockers were
taken out, and school officials no longer worry as much about
students bringing drugs, alcohol or other contraband to school.
``They don't have the place to put it,'' Bartosh said.
</P>
<P>
   The district even quit contracting for drug-sniffing dogs, which
by law can only search lockers and cars.
</P>
<P>
   To make the concept work, the school had to buy an extra set of
textbooks to keep in the classroom. That way, students could have
one book at home, and another while they were at the campus. But
some classes have not received the extra books yet, leaving
students to lug classroom editions back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Textbooks have been a problem, but it's a one-time problem,''
said Superintendent Gus Hollomon.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of buying extra books is no more than the cost of
maintaining the 240 lockers, many of which had been vandalized or
broken, he said. The discarded lockers are piled in a parking lot
outside the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all my years of education, never have I seen anything that
changes things for the positive like taking out lockers,'' Hollomon
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the system probably wouldn't work at larger schools, said
Julian Shaddix, executive director of the Texas Association of
Secondary School Principals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some advantages, but you have to consider the
disadvantages,'' Shaddix said. ``It's much easier to do that in a
small school, where the building is not large and the students
don't have far to go. You take a large high school and you're
talking about a hardship on kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In Austin public schools, individual campuses can decide whether
or not to use lockers. While all the high schools use them, many
middle schools do not, said Catenya McHenry, district spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Covington Middle School stopped using lockers three years ago.
``We found lockers to be a hindrance to instruction rather than an
asset,'' said Principal Bergeron Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Dobie Middle School quit using them for security reasons, said
Principal Patrick Patterson, who believes it's easier to search
backpacks for contraband than lockers. ``We've been able to secure
the building a little better and clear the halls,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to convince students they don't need someplace to
store their books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love having lockers,'' said Granger sophomore Jillian
Pauley, 15. ``It hurts my back to carry a backpack, and I don't
like having to carry books because sometimes I don't need them.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior Lisa Wolf, 17, says her calculus class has a classroom
set of books, but none for students to take home. ``It's really
hard because we don't have a book to refer back to,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And lockers or not, students will socialize in the hallways,
said sophomore Jessica Repa, 15. ``They say it's going to keep us
from being late, but we still hang out in the hallways and
bathrooms anyway. We're still late,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bartosh says some students simply aren't planning ahead
enough. ``Some kids, they're just not finding all the best ways to
do things,'' he said. Even those who carry backpacks carry them
only briefly between classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're carrying it around 16 minutes a day,'' he said. ``If
you go to college, you're going to carry that much weight for a
longer time. You might as well get used to it now.''
</P>
<P>
   American-Statesman staff writer Sharon Jayson contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
