<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8874 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK28-COX     10-27 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Declining interest rates can threaten retirees
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Declining interest rates can be a major threat to retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Often retirees depend on investment income right now _ not
growth in years ahead _ to pay their living expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they wanted to invest for growth, they can't risk taking
a loss from which it would take years to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, many retirees tend to be ultraconservative, clustering
around safe investments like certificates of deposit and government
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   That is why they get worried when interest rates drop, as they
have in recent months. At the most recent peak, six-month
certificates of deposit were paying, on average, 5.89 percent
interest in April 1997. Late last week, Bank Rate Monitor put the
national average at 4.88 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That's enough of a plunge to make even the most timid investor
look for alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   There are options out there. But investors will have to accept
some changes in their investing patterns to get to them. For one
thing, it may require moving money from an old, familiar bank that
sells CDs to a different manager, perhaps a mutual fund or a stock
broker.
</P>
<P>
   For another, you may in all likelihood have to bow to the
ironclad rule of investing: If you want to make more, you have to
risk more. The table suggests just how extreme the levels of risk
can get.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to take big, big risks. Investment experts
suggest a number of investments that might be good replacements for
CDs:
</P>
<P>
   _ CDs from other banks. Bank Rate Monitor keeps frequently
updated lists of the best available rates. You can check the Web
site at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .bankrate.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bonds. Unless you are an experienced investor with a lot of
money, the best idea is to stick with a mutual fund or unit
investment trust. These alternatives give you a professional
manager and a diversity of investments that would be hard to match
buying individual bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Look for low-cost fund managers that won't eat up too much of
your income, and stick with high-quality bond funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junk bonds'' will give you a higher yield, but there's a
reason why they're called junk. Don't depend on them for safe,
current income.
</P>
<P>
   For a look at the current yields from the Vanguard family of
funds, check out http://www.vanguard.com
</P>
<P>
   /daily/pricesyields.htm-- on the Internet. On Friday, the yield
on a total-market bond fund was 5.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Smith, a certified financial planner with Financial
Vision Advisors in Atlanta, recommends unit investment trusts
rather than mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   His reasoning is that bond buyers are looking for a guaranteed
yield and a guarantee they will get their principal back when their
bonds mature. But a mutual fund buys and sells bonds every day,
with the result that both yield and maturity dates change
constantly.
</P>
<P>
   A unit investment trust, by contrast, buys a given set of bonds,
holds them until they mature, then cashes them in and pays off the
investors. When you buy shares in the trust, you know exactly what
your interest payments will be and when you will get your principal
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``For interest rate protection, I would 'ladder' several of them
with different maturity dates,'' Smith said. ``That gives you some
protection against changes in interest rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Unit investment trusts are usually sold through stock brokers or
financial advisers.
</P>
<P>
   One other possibility is closed-end mutual funds specializing in
municipal bonds. A closed-end fund owns a given set of securities
and sells shares in that portfolio. If investors have their doubts
about the portfolio, the fund will trade at less than its fair
market value.
</P>
<P>
   ``These (bond funds) trade on yields,'' noted Steve Goldberg,
author of a recently published book on mutual fund investing.
``With a high-quality fund, it will trade at a discount. You can
almost always find a bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Stocks. The risk vs. reward trade-off can be more daunting in
the stock market. But there are some stodgy corners of the market
that emphasize current income and are not as flighty as the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Preferred stocks, for example, have a pre-set dividend yield.
That is as close to a guarantee as you will get in the stock
market. The dividend also comforts investors when the market gets
crazy, meaning the price of the stock usually will not vary as much
as other stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Utility stocks are another area to look into. The utility
companies tend to be steady performers, appealing to investors
because they have steady dividends rather than promises of future
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Again, mutual funds are the best alternative for those without
much experience.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail:hezell(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
