<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   HATE-THE-50S_AUSTIN, Texas _ In the new movie ``Pleasantville,''
two colorful, modern teens slip into life with a black-and-white,
small-town '50s TV family. They find it all pretty darn dreamy
until, gasp, reality hits. Maybe the '50s weren't as cozy as we've
been told. Heck, sometimes they were downright awful. So to get in
the proper mood for ``Pleasantville,'' we've come up with 50
REASONS TO HATE THE '50s (in no particular order). (Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GHOUL-SCHOOL _ The Secrets of Being Spooky. Reporter Doug
Kalajian has gone to Ghoul School at Universal Studios, where he's
learned how to scare the bejesus out of people. (Kalajian, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OLD _ ATLANTA _ Is 77 old? We look at others, besides John
Glenn, who are doing physically and mentally challenging jobs well
past 70. According TO stats/experts these people aren't just
anomolies; many people really are living ``better'' into what was
once considered old age: The gym smells a tad like sweat as a bunch
of guys in their 20s and 30s sprint up and down the basketball
court, passing, shooting, high-fiving, and _ in a few cases _
huffing and puffing. But not Richard Miller. At 75, he's been
running longer than most of the others have been living, which
makes him not only a valued player, but also a role model. It's
happening everywhere _ gyms are full of older people. (Hendrick,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
