<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8881 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GHOUL-SCHOOL28-COX     10-27 1606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GHOUL-SCHOOL28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grim reaper? no, writer gives 'em laughable joker
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service-Palm Beach Post
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ A public apology to the several people who got
scared when some idiot made up like the Grim Reaper crept up behind
them while they were touring Universal Studios in Orlando:
</P>
<P>
   I'm the idiot, and I'm sorry.
</P>
<P>
   As for the far greater number who simply laughed, I'm even
sorrier. You paid $30 or $40 for a jolt of terror, and all you got
was a short snort. But you can take any further complaints to
Universal's publicity department, which should have known better.
</P>
<P>
   After making movies like Dracula, Frankenstein and The Creature
From The Black Lagoon, it's hard to believe Universal allowed me to
stumble across the fine line between horror and hilarity.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I'm afraid I permanently erased it with my one-night
role in the month-long pageant of fear billed as Halloween Horror
Nights VIII.
</P>
<P>
   My assignment is to be one of 450 costumed ``scare-actors''
(pronounced like characters with an ``s'' in front) who are divided
among the park's five haunted houses and the outdoor theme areas.
My territory is the streets of New York, which strikes me as one
place the walking dead would have to work hard to get noticed, much
less frighten anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The Grim Reaper, I gather, is a one-size-fits-all persona that
can be easily grafted onto guest performers. You've seen the
character many times: the tall, bony figure in black carrying a
scythe.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, that doesn't sound like short, wide me. ``Leave it to
the make-up artist,'' I'm told. Amy Klaus, working her fourth
Halloween at Universal, sets right to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think you can make my face scary?'' I ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' she says, a bit too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder if my beard will detract from the Reaper's ghastly
visage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make the beard work,'' she says. ``All I have to do is
whiten it up.''
</P>
<P>
   I think about the white beard and the black robe. Suddenly, I'm
picturing myself as the Ayatollah.
</P>
<P>
   It takes Amy about 35 minutes of paint-and-putty work to make me
look sufficiently decayed. She adds a last-minute gash oozing
gelatinous blood over my left eyebrow before the hooded frock is
lowered over my head. I stumble over the hem on my first step.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the make-up makes me no taller, but it is making my
face itch. I wonder if this stuff's been tested on live people as I
unconsciously scratch at my caked-on wound. The look on Amy's face
proves that I can indeed scare someone.
</P>
<P>
   She has me oozing again in a jiffy, and I fold my hands together
as one of the entertainment directors instructs me in the subtle
art of ghoulery. A silent ghoul is more effective than a chatty
one, he says, although it's OK to throw in a moan, groan or even a
hoarse ``Help me!'' But simply staring at people long enough can
give them the heebie-jeebies, and when all else fails, try sneaking
up behind and startling them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just don't touch anyone,'' he says. ``And don't let anyone
touch you.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of lawsuits, it seems, is too scary even for
Halloween. I'm crushed to learn that also means no scythe.
</P>
<P>
   This is going to be tough, but I assure everyone I'm ready and
follow the publicity team into a corridor connecting the rooms that
serve as the scare-actor make-up center.
</P>
<P>
   I got the personal treatment, but the working ghouls are moving
swiftly along a paint-and-prosthetics assembly line. Fairly
normal-looking, 20-to-30-year-old men and women walk in one door
and come out looking like the cadaverous offspring of Klingons and
Marilyn Manson. There's not a Dracula, Wolfman or Frankenstein
monster in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those characters don't scare people any more,'' I'm told.
``We're too sophisticated today.''
</P>
<P>
   This is giving me second thoughts about the Grim Reaper routine,
but it's too late. We're out the door just as the crowd is
building. It's dusk, and the turn-of-the-century brownstone facades
are looking especially eerie in the last, low streaks of
pink-orange light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember,'' the publicity rep tells me. ``People are paying to
be scared.''
</P>
<P>
   I walk straight toward a couple rounding a corner. I think I
look menacing. They smile and nod as though we're small-town
neighbors passing along Main Street. I walk past them toward two
young women, glaring into their eyes. They look at me as though I'm
crazy and step swiftly out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   I decide to try another couple standing in line for one of the
haunted houses, but this time from the side. I manage to get within
a few feet before they spot me. They both scream! Then, almost
immediately, their screams turn to laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is this funny?'' I ask.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure if they're trying to answer me or if they're
commenting on my ridiculous appearance, but I do know they're not
speaking English. They continue to point and laugh as I move down
the line, and their laughter is annoyingly contagious. With the
entire line chuckling and pointing, I retreat to confer with the
Universal team.
</P>
<P>
   Their unanimous opinion: I'm too nice. ``Even if you're not
smiling, people can tell you're not mean,'' one says.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure I buy this. Even though the sun is going down, it's
still 80-some degrees and I'm wearing a wool cloak suitable for
arctic excursions. Every time I breathe, I get a nose full of
make-up dust, and the goo on my forehead is starting to melt into
my eyes.
</P>
<P>
   I'm feeling meaner by the second. ``Let me try this again,'' I
say.
</P>
<P>
   I recall the entertainment director's advice that burly guys are
the ones most likely to get spooked. I walk up behind the burliest
guy I see and grunt. He apparently mistakes the Grim Reaper for
Friar Tuck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bless you father,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Another group dissolves in laughter. I turn and spot a woman
sitting on a bench. I sneak up behind and utter my one sure-fire
scare line: ``Boo!'' She looks, she screams, and then she shouts at
me in Spanish. I smile and move quickly on.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of my tour, I succeed in scaring only a handful of
people _ all from behind, all foreign. The Reaper, I decide, must
have some mystical, xenophobic power. The Universal rep sets me
straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not their holiday,'' she reminds me. ``People from other
countries aren't used to seeing anyone dressed up like this.
Americans see it every year.''
</P>
<P>
   They're done seeing me. A hired ghoul would head to the make-up
room for a fresh coat of slime and a short rest before the next
performance; they're on for four sets a night, 19 nights, at about
$7 an hour. I'm ready for a good scrubbing, but I'm not quite ready
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   With my eyes burning from the soap and make-up, I'm escorted
through a fog-machine mist for a haunted house tour so I can see
how the real scare-actors get screams. A publicity rep leads me
through a dark, narrow maze of shadows, flashes and screeching
echoes.
</P>
<P>
   She keeps her eyes fixed on the floor and screams when a
menacing figure jumps into her path. I'm scanning the dark recesses
when a slasher leaps out and swings his blade toward my head. I
look him in the eyes and laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Serves him right, I think, and not just because it happened to
me.
</P>
<P>
   I might scream at a monster whose only weakness is a stake
through the heart or a silver bullet, but I just can't get worked
up about one who's afraid of being sued.
</P>
<P>
   `Fear of unknown'
</P>
<P>
   a Universal feeling
</P>
<P>
   Costumes and characters change with the times, but the essential
element of terror is timeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fear of the unknown,'' explains Jerry Abercrombie, who heads
the creative team behind Universal Studios' holiday horror pageant.
</P>
<P>
   Film-quality sets and make-up blur the distinction between
reality and illusion, but there are many means of subtle
manipulation that keep people on edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The snakes in the trees are really air hoses, so they not only
move, you feel something uncomfortable,'' Abercrombie says. Slime
along the walls of the haunted houses is really food-grade
cellulose thickener used in soups, but the imagination makes it
seem far creepier.
</P>
<P>
   Howling music, musty odors and sudden blasts of heat are also
part of the formula. ``We disorient you,'' Abercrombie says.
</P>
<P>
   But the most important ingredient is darkness. ``You fear what
you can't see,'' he says. ``You fear what goes bump in the
closet.''
</P>
<P>
   To enhance the effects, the corridors narrow, and the ceilings
drop, adding claustrophobia to the jitters. And, of course,
strange-looking creatures are suddenly illuminated and then vanish
in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   Guests are funneled through the houses at a swift but measured
pace in groups of nine, reacting predictably to the three scares in
every room. Abercrombie tunes the entire show to the 18-35 age
range of horror movie audiences.
</P>
<P>
   It's all harmless, of course, and everyone knows that, but most
people willingly suspend common sense in return for a good shiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love to be scared,'' Abercrombie says.
</P>
<P>
   SCARY TIP
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want to spring for professional makeup this
Halloween, or just feel like being creative, the kitchen is a good
place to start. Lots of possibilities are obvious: spaghetti, for
example, works equally well as worms and brains.
</P>
<P>
   Makeup artist Amy Klaus offered this recipe for Halloween blood:
Karo syrup and red food dye. She likes the bright, glistening
appearance, although others add chocolate syrup to deepen the
color. Amy's special tip: Add some oatmeal for a professional,
coagulated look.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 1041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8882 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN28-COX     10-27 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is testing killing education?
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I imagine an alarm went off somewhere in the Texas
education firmament. Maybe a ground sensor signaled a satellite
which triggered a probe which launched an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   And I figure Mrs. Mansfield is in a heap of trouble _ ground
zero _ for bringing a piano into her sophomore English class last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Alert. Alert. Incoming missive: ``Class does not correspond to
Texas Assessment of Academic Skills.'' Scramble. Code purple. To
the bomb shelters, children.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but I couldn't get my son to share in the gravity. To
him, it was ``the best day I've had at Waco High.'' What? And not
accomplish a TAAS objective?
</P>
<P>
   The class guest was Kurt Kaiser, Waco's world-renowned Christian
music composer. He's penned 200 songs including contemporary
favorites like ``Tell It Like It Is'' and ``Natural High.''
</P>
<P>
   For my son it was a special treat to hear a professional
composer discuss his craft and plink some keys. Kaiser allowed the
students to do some plinking and composing as well. This connected
with the 15-year-old composer I know. He has original tunes and
lyrics criss-crossing in his head in search of fusion.
</P>
<P>
   Having someone like Kaiser on hand to discuss a lively art is
not uncommon for Mrs. Mansfield, who's taught generations in Waco
schools. In these nine weeks her fifth- and sixth-period class has
traveled far and wide, including Shakespeare's haunts and those of
the ancient Greeks. It's an honors course merging history and
English.
</P>
<P>
   TAAS. TAAS. Wherefore art thou?
</P>
<P>
   Obviously any direct connection between TAAS and composing music
is strained. We cannot have this, of course. We want our children
filling in bubbles _ tests and sample tests about where Ps go, and
Qs. All that matters ultimately is those bubbles. Funding,
reputation, careers, success, failure. They're all on the bubble.
</P>
<P>
   Well, all right. This isn't your average class. Obviously, Mrs.
Mansfield _ Sharon is her name _ exercises some license in teaching
composition or history. And thank goodness she does.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky Mrs. Mansfield. There are some teachers in Texas who can
only dream in Technicolor. They feel themselves shackled, the
grindstone of ``TAAS objectives'' spinning before them, a device
designed to sharpen only the serioulsy dull.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is not alone. Kent State professor James Delisle, in
Teacher Magazine, writes about a sabbatical teaching South Carolina
fourth- and fifth-graders and the stifling weight of the Basic
Skills Assessment Program _ South Carolina's TAAS.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 90 minutes each morning for five days, students in grades
2-5 stopped learning and began bubbling in circles, an arduous job
in itself for some, whose chubby fingers tried mightily to color
within the lines, a task not yet mastered with big-page coloring
books.''
</P>
<P>
   The real thing, of course, is preceded by practice tests, and
rote drilling, and formulas for acing the test. In Texas
elementaries, the formulaic approach to passing the TAAS writing
portion produces abominable repetition, replete with compelled
counting of lines and words. It's not writing. It's regurgitation.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, it passes TAAS.
</P>
<P>
   So, you might ask, in this environment, what business does a
songwriter have in an English class? After all, how many
songwriters do we need? What's the cost-benefit ratio?
</P>
<P>
   Heaven forfend that we should inspire children by the muse, by
the senses, by human potential that knows no percentile breakdown
and can't be quantified by the Texas Education Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for making my son's day, Mrs. Mansfield and Mr. Kaiser. I
hope this doesn't cost anyone his or her job.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
