<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8962 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     10-27 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Oct. 27, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLENN-AGING (San Francisco) _ The remarkable thing about
septuagenarian John Glenn's impending rocket ride to space is that
it's not remarkable at all, according to specialists in aging and
several residents who are older than America's oldest astronaut. By
MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SENATE (San Francisco) _ Republican Senate candidate Matt
Fong has told gay Republicans that if elected he would work to pass
a wide range of federal gay rights laws _ even though he gave
$50,000 to an anti-gay group earlier this year. By LANCE WILLIAMS
and ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   PEPPER-SPRAY (San Francisco) _ Environmental protesters vowed to
appeal a judge's order allowing law enforcement officers to apply
pepper spray directly around the eyes of non-violent demonstrators
who refuse to leave private property. By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THAI-ECONOMY (Bangkok, Thailand) _ More than a year after the
financial meltdown began in Thailand, observers say they see signs
of recovery. As Thailand restructures its economy according to the
dictates of the International Monetary Fund in return for a $17.2
billion bailout, there is plenty of work for U.S. lawyers and
bankers. By DAVID ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ People are asking whether it's time to
get back into the stock market after it has inflicted so much pain.
Honestly, the market is sending signals to investors who have fled
that this is a good time to step back in. By PAMELA YIP.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSPAPER-APPOINT (San Francisco) _ Stephen C. Johnson has been
named vice president of circulation for the San Francisco Newspaper
Agency, which oversees advertising, circulation and printing for
The San Francisco Examiner and Chronicle. By The San Francisco
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-POSTERS (Undated) _ Movie posters have become big
business, though not for today's films. The big bucks go to
decades-old movie paper items _ usually 27-by-41-inch posters or
``one sheets,'' but also photo stills, oversized color ``lobby
cards'' and other posters. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   HOFFMANN-OPERA-REVIEW (Houston) _ Vocally, Jacques Offenbach's
opera ``The Tales of Hoffmann'' is unusual: A few singers portray a
multitude of main characters in great tests of musical flexibility
and dramatic versatility. Using stories by 19th-century German
writer and composer E.T.A. Hoffmann, French librettist Jules
Barbier created a web of revelations aimed ultimately at allowing
listeners to see Hoffmann's life from many perspectives. By CHARLES
WARD.
</P>
<P>
   PHANTASM-FILM-PROFILE (Undated) _ As Angus Scrimm sees it, the
fiendish Tall Man of ``Phantasm'' fame is simply misunderstood. ``I
always think he's like a civil servant, just doing his job _ at
least in his mind,'' Scrimm said of the black-clad villain bent on
populating Earth with reanimated corpses. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   LION-KINGII-REVIEW (Undated) _ When a movie makes $772 million
worldwide, wins two Oscars, and becomes the top-selling video of
all time (at 30 million), making a sequel is a no-brainer. But the
surprise of ``The Lion King II: Simba's Pride'' is that this
follow-up to 1994's ``The Lion King'' is being offered here solely
on video. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   STUPID-PET-TRICKS (Houston) _ The mood wasn't right for Josie,
the slow-dancing poodle. Babe, a Jack Russell terrier dressed in
Yankee pinstripes, couldn't perform a perfect back flip. And Aman,
a 14-foot python, didn't know what to do beyond clinging closely to
his owner. Yes, it was difficult to tell the stupid pet tricks from
the stupid human tricks at ``Late Show With David Letterman''
auditions. But it was fun trying. By MIKE McDANIEL.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-REPORTING (New York) _ Four television networks will pay a
combined $17.6 billion over the next eight years for the privilege
of televising National Football League games. For broadcast
reporters, the partnership is forgotten. Ask any network personnel
who work the trenches and they'll tell you which league is the most
difficult to cover. By PETE DOUGHERTY.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-FLUTIE (San Francisco) _ The Buffalo Bills have won three
straight games under Doug Flutie's command, since Rob Johnson
injured his ribs. They have gone from 0-3 to 4-3. They are fun to
watch. Flutie bedevils opponents and bewitches everyone else. By
GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Have you noticed that everybody
running for office this year seems so-o-o-o sensitive? Oh, sure,
you've heard some chatter about issues in this year's election
season. Frankly, though, most candidates seem more interested in
portraying themselves as victims of mean, nasty, unprincipled
opponents bent on sullying their reputations. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 1120EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
