<SLUG> BC-FBN-REPORTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTING ON THE NFL REQUIRES A STRONG OFFENSE  
 NFL STILL HOLDING REPORTERS TO SIDELINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PETE DOUGHERTY  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four television networks will pay a combined $17.6
billion over the next eight years for the privilege of televising
National Football League games.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of sideline reporting, the partnership is
forgotten. Ask any of the handful of network personnel who work the
trenches _ at least in the broadcasting sense _ and they'll tell
you which league is the most difficult to cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``By far, the NFL is the most restrictive,'' said ABC's Lesley
Visser, a veteran in the sidelines game who now fills the role on
``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think because you're a rightsholder you'd get a little
more access,'' said Bonnie Bernstein, in her first year of work for
CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the level of cooperation has improved. Sideline
reporting, a long-time staple of many college, NBA and baseball
telecasts, was given approval grudgingly by pro football only a few
years ago. Even then, it was on a highly restricted basis.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has opened up to the point of allowing network reporters
on the field, as long as they aren't stationed between the 20-yard
lines. They are not permitted to interview coaches on camera but
they can try to get a quick comment, which they can relay to
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've opened up a lot the last couple of years,'' said Mark
Wolff, lead-game producer for CBS. ``We've made some proposals to
them that they'll take under consideration next year, but that
doesn't preclude us from following the stories going into the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Armen Keteyian, sideline reporter for the lead CBS game each
week, spent eight years with ABC News, reporting on hard-edged and
issue-related sports stories for ``World News Tonight.'' Those may
feel like the good ol' days compared to what he faces now in the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't hear anything in the huddles,'' Keteyian said.
``There's no access to the coaching staff. There's really no access
to the trainers. My main thing is to get interesting information
from the coaches coming off the field and going on the field. Maybe
two or three other times during the game I'll provide not
analytical insight, but reporting information that I was able to
dig up during the days prior to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The job of the on-field reporter is to provide information the
announcers in the press box can't get. Much of it is related to
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things happen on the field, I should try at least to get
in close proximity to the players who are involved,'' said ESPN's
Solomon Wilcots, a former defensive back for the Cincinnati
Bengals. ``I can overhear conversations, I can see things being
done and have a better understanding of what's happening than the
guys upstairs in the booth. Then I'm to relay that message.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilcots scored in one of his early broadcasts when he followed
injured New York Giants cornerback Jason Sehorn into the tunnel
during an exhibition game. Wilcots was the first to report that
Sehorn's knee injury likely ended his season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched him get off the cart and try to walk on that leg
going into the locker room,'' Wilcots said. ``He was very unstable,
very unsure of himself. He looked at me. I asked him, `How's the
knee,' and he didn't want to answer my question, but he gave me
that look. As a former player, I know that look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to come on and say, `He's done,' but I said
I've talked to Jason Sehorn and he was very unsure and he had to be
helped inside. Later, because of the report I had given earlier in
the game, we were all waiting for the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   In the broadcast field, nailing that report can be akin to
intercepting a Brett Favre pass and running it back for a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not quite that good,'' Wilcots said. ``I felt great, but
that's my job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 1158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
