<SLUG> BC-THAI-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BIRTHPLACE OF FINANCIAL CRISIS, OPTIMISM EMERGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ As a metaphor, nothing could be starker:
Towering, isolated support columns, marching across the cityscape,
connected to nothing, going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   These columns are the bones of an unfinished elevated rail and
road system for this congested hothouse of 10 million people. Its
construction came to a screeching halt when the Asian fiscal crisis
began last year. The authorities in Thailand vow to resume
construction of the badly needed $3.2 billion transportation
project, but they don't say when.
</P>
<P>
   Thailand, a southeast Asian nation of 60 million people, is
Ground Zero for the financial crisis that began July 2, 1997, when
Bangkok devalued its currency, the baht.
</P>
<P>
   That move quickly and unexpectedly set off a round of
devaluation in other countries, shaking world financial markets,
causing rampant currency speculation, spooking investors and
inspiring neighboring Malaysia to impose controls on the outflow of
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Now, nearly 16 months after the meltdown started, observers here
say they can see the first signs of recovery. As Thailand
restructures its economy according to the dictates of the
International Monetary Fund in return for a $17.2 billion bailout,
there is plenty of work for U.S. businesspeople. Lawyers and
bankers are especially busy.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Donovan, president of New York-based Donovan Consulting
Group, said he went to Bangkok to help the Bank of Thailand
restructure its assets.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan, hunkered down in the riverside Shangri-la Hotel,
arrived in July, intending to stay two weeks. He's been living in
the hotel ever since. ``Business here moves like the traffic,'' he
said, alluding to the Thai capital's notorious snarl of autos,
scooters, coughing trucks and fuming buses.
</P>
<P>
   Although Donovan declines to say exactly what he's advising the
Bank of Thailand to do, he makes it clear in words and gestures
that it's serious business. Snapping off the filters from his
cigarettes, Donovan chain-smokes as he talks, saying of his
company, ``We generally show up when you've had a meltdown. We're
the last people you ever want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   While asserting that Thailand has a long way to go to match
international business procedures and standards, Donovan praised
the year-old government of Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai: ``From
where they were 18 months ago, it's really a different country.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas D. Mancill, who joined the Bangkok office of the
international law firm Deacons Graham &AMP; James in August as a
consultant on debt restructuring, said that Thailand is just now
writing effective foreclosure and bankruptcy laws. It is also just
starting to meet international standards of accounting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scary thing right now in Thailand is some debtors have the
ability to pay, but have decided not to pay,'' Mancill said. ``If
their competitors are paying their debts, the non-payer can
undercut them by 20 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, the Thai parliament is writing legislation with
sharper teeth to regulate commerce, Mancill said. ``It's a
challenge,'' he said of his job as an expatriate American lawyer.
``The law is changing before your eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   All these changes are aimed, of course, at sparking a recovery.
``The signs are there that we have probably touched bottom,'' said
David Hendrix, an executive vice president with the Bank of Asia
and a member of the American Chamber of Commerce in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leading indicators are good. The stock market is better.
Interest rates have come down, and there is pent-up demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix predicted possible growth in the gross domestic product
in the second or third quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bouncing baht, worth 25 to the dollar when Thailand devalued
it, went as high as 53 to the dollar. Recently, it has been running
at 39 to the dollar. As a consequence, doing business in Thailand
is a decidedly up and down experience.
</P>
<P>
   At Horizons International Accents, a San Francisco accessories
company that imports 80 percent of its products from Thailand,
proprietors Jeffrey Walsh and Mona Sheerr say the fiscal crisis has
both helped and hurt them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of devaluation of the baht, we can buy everything
cheaper,'' said Walsh, who visits Thailand four times a year, but
``there's a downside to the upside.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem: some skilled carvers who sculpt wooden animals that
Horizons sells to Gumps, Neiman-Marcus and Bloomingdale's are
leaving the trade because they can't earn a living anymore, raising
concerns about product quality.
</P>
<P>
   Horizons, a 12-year-old company with a warehouse in Daly City,
Calif., and showroom in High Point, N.C., operates in what Sheerr
calls ``the medium to high end'' of the market. An elephant head
carved from wood and given a fine finish can command $300 from an
upscale American retailer.
</P>
<P>
   But, with demand for cheap Thai goods running high, just getting
adequate supplies of shipping containers from multinational
shipping lines can be a problem, Sheerr and Walsh say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no stability, and we have no security,'' Walsh said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 1200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9052 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-27 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL'S FAIR IN POLITICS AND WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Have you noticed that everybody running for
office this year seems so-o-o-o sensitive?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, you've heard some chatter about issues in this year's
election season. Frankly, though, most candidates seem more
interested in portraying themselves as victims of mean, nasty,
unprincipled opponents bent on sullying their reputations.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, for example, Republican Gov. George Pataki refuses
to debate Peter Vallone, the New York City Council speaker. This is
not, the governor assures us, because Pataki is so far ahead that
it would be strategic insanity to endanger that lead. No, it's
because Vallone, a Democrat, said something unkind about the
governor in a magazine interview.
</P>
<P>
   And Republican Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, who literally wept in front
of television cameras six years ago after his then-opponent, Robert
Abrams, called him a fascist, is now deeply wounded that Rep.
Charles E. Schumer, a Democrat, keeps calling him a liar. This guy
is a real putzhead, says the sensitive D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, this is tactics. It's about rallying the
sympathy vote _ or, at least, about erecting a screen or moral
outrage to avoid confronting opponents directly. Every once in a
while, though _ even though they're politicians _ some of these
people do deserve a little sympathy. That's when their families get
dragged into it. John Sweeney, Republican candidate for New York's
22nd Congressional District _ the seat being vacated by House Rules
Committee Chairman Gerald B.H. Solomon _ is furious because one
Democratic county chairman in his district wrote a letter to a
newspaper over the weekend demanding that Sweeney answer a nasty
rumor about Sweeney's personal life.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney has been the target of an unremitting stream of vile
rumors ever since he got into this thing. Most of them accuse him,
essentially, of being a guy who works too hard at having a good
time in life. They were first brought up by the forces of the
conservative primary opponents that Sweeney handily trounced in
September. They got little press attention then _ and, candidly,
deserved even less. But this letter to the editor from Saratoga
County Democratic Chairman Tom Bayly added one rumor that hadn't
seen print before, namely, that Sweeney's estranged wife had
obtained an order of protection against him. Betty Sweeney
immediately staged a news conference to deny that and to denounce
the charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' Bayly said Monday, ``I'm an American. I have a right to
ask the man who would be my congressman to clear up something like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The key element of all this, though, is that Sweeney views that
public question not as legitimate curiosity on the part of one
county chairman but as a planned tactic of his Democratic opponent,
Jean Bordewich, to smear him in the campaign's final week. Not
true, Bordewich says. She didn't know Bayly was going to do that.
That's right, Bayly says. He's a county chairman, and he didn't ask
her permission.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, this has been a genteel general election
campaign. Bordewich and Sweeney are both moderates, candidates
about 15 degrees apart on the issues. He hasn't criticized her, and
her only real complaint about him has been that Sweeney is a
lifetime political operative _ a guy who has devoted his entire
career to working within the machinery of the democratic process.
As political attacks go, that's fairly tepid stuff. In this case,
though, Sweeney says he was essentially accused of beating his
wife, which isn't true, and he didn't like the fact that this was
one charge that his kids asked about. This one, Sweeney says, was
personal. Political pro or not, he's taking it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Which illustrates, essentially, that democracy is a contact
sport, and that everybody feels the pressure as election day draws
near. I saw Peter Vallone Monday morning. How's it going, I asked?
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven days, 12 hours and 47 minutes to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah. And counting.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
