<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FLUTIE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUFFALO BILLS AND THE MAGIC FLUTIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Supermarkets had to start rationing Flutie
Flakes almost as soon as they came out, one box per customer. The
grocers couldn't keep them in the stores.
</P>
<P>
   The breakfast treat was released only in Buffalo and Boston, but
there could be a national market developing for the flakes, just as
there could soon be a national infatuation with the Little
Quarterback Who Could.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Bills have won three straight games under Doug
Flutie's command, since Rob Johnson injured his ribs. They have
gone from 0-3 to 4-3. They have become an endearing amalgamation of
misfits _ a Rust Belt town, a chronically frustrated franchise (see
Super Bowl, losers) and a shunned quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, they are fun to watch. Flutie bedevils
opponents and bewitches everyone else. On Sunday night, he turned a
30-14 win over Carolina into a piece of pure theater.
</P>
<P>
   He scooted and twisted and spun and wriggled. He threw long,
tight spirals, and little soft rainbows that touched down exactly
where they belonged.
</P>
<P>
   It was all remarkable, even if you didn't know the background _
how the NFL had little patience for the 5-foot-10-inch (in heavily
padded stockings) quarterback, and how Flutie was exiled for eight
years in the Canadian Football League. And how he added six
Canadian MVP trophies to the Heisman he won in college before a
team south of the border deigned to offer him a backup job.
</P>
<P>
   The only history anyone needed was a sampling of NFL football
this year _ dull, plodding, uninspired. There are about six or
seven good teams, the commentators say, and they are being
generous. Watching is an exercise in tedium. A 30-14 game? Where's
the remote? Then along comes Flutie, full of surprises, an
original.
</P>
<P>
   Against Jacksonville a week ago, he was rushed by a huge
defensive lineman who blocked his view _ exactly what the scouts
and coaches feared when they said he could never make it in the
NFL. Flutie jumped into the air as if to look for a receiver over
the defender's head. The big man froze, thinking the quarterback
had flung a pass. Flutie came down, ball still in hand, and started
running into a nice stretch of open field. The play gave new
meaning to the term ``pump fake.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Carolina, he looked as quick as ever. Two days after his
36th birthday, he could still make defensive linemen dive and miss.
</P>
<P>
   One Panther, obviously frustrated, hit him late on a play,
dragging him down like a ragdoll. A Buffalo lineman came over to
protect him, to retaliate. Flutie popped up from the turf and
wedged himself between the two giants, practically disappearing
from view, engulfed.
</P>
<P>
   Almost instantly, the Buffalo lineman backed away. The pipsqueak
had prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the game, on the Bills sideline, coaches and players
grinned in spite of themselves. These were not the smug grins of a
contented winner. They were the smiles of jaded people witnessing
something fresh and different.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie isn't the only comeback quarterback this season. Randall
Cunningham, forced on sabbatical the year before last, has been
revitalized at age 35 in Minnesota. Steve DeBerg, 44, shook off
formaldehyde to start Sunday for the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   But those two had their chances before. And neither of them
looks microscopic in the huddle.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday, the Bills meet Miami, coached by Jimmy Johnson, who
has a history with Flutie. Back in 1984, when Johnson was a coach
on the move at the University of Miami, his Hurricanes lost a
nationally televised spectacle to Boston College. Flutie ended the
game with a touchdown pass widely remembered as the greatest
collegiate football play not involving a member of the Stanford
marching band.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dolphins prepared to meet Buffalo in an earlier game
this fall, Miami's coach bridled at questions about that
14-year-old loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't the only team we lost to,'' Johnson said of
Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he had met up with Flutie since, he said: ``Well,
I never coached Canadian football, so no.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Flutie loses one game, he could be back on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   But right now, he is a phenomenon. His Flutie Flakes, put out by
a specialty food company in Pittsburgh, promise to raise a ton of
money for his foundation to fight autism, which afflicts one of his
children. The cereal has become a collector's item, part of the
Flutie legend, which is as large as he is small.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Dalton, of the Bills public relations staff, tells a story
with a hint of myth to it.
</P>
<P>
   A Bills employee drove to the airport on an errand last week,
left the company car at the curb illegally for a minute or so, came
back and found a police officer writing a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The employee tried to plead with the officer, who wouldn't
budge. Then the policeman noticed the Bills' staff sticker on the
car. The team employee sensed a change of heart. He waited for the
officer to ask for good seats to the next home game. But that
wasn't the sort of graft the officer had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could make this go away,'' he reportedly said, ``if you can
get me two boxes of Flutie Flakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
