</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MAKING TRACKS ACROSS EUROPE: A standout in Monte Carlo
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (EDITOR'S NOTE: Joe Murray has been traveling around Western
Europe by train. This is one in a series of stories.)
</P>
<P>
   MONTE CARLO, Monaco _ I sit in the outdoor cafe in the shadow of
the Casino du Monte Carlo surrounded by the beautiful people of
Monaco. If I am ever to stand out in a crowd, this is the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   I think I could get to like these folks who drape themselves
with silk scarves and cashmere sweaters looped loosely about the
neck. Silly me, I wore a tie.
</P>
<P>
   If I had it to do over again I'd have worn sunglasses and a deep
tan.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the beautiful people don't look all that beautiful to
me. The ladies, in particular, look as if they may have stayed out
in the sun too long _ say about 50 years too long.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. They still have that rich sheen about them. Maybe
it's the same thing, being pretty rich.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the rich are different from you and me. They live in
Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   All about me is much ado, hugging and kissing and carrying on
with great flourishes of foreign verbiage, such is the ritual of
their assembling with those of their own kind, as if they are all
long-lost brothers and sisters.
</P>
<P>
   If they notice me at all, no doubt, it is to wonder, ``C'est le
bastard at zee family reunion?''
</P>
<P>
   I envy them their fellowship and wish I could join in their
conversation, or at least listen in.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, but the French language. It is music to the ear, poetry to
the eye but a tanglement to the tongue.
</P>
<P>
   I like what Mark Twain had to say about it: The French speak
beautifully. They just don't spell very well. Or was it the other
way around?
</P>
<P>
   These days I get a bit confused in my English as well.
</P>
<P>
   I took a car down from Nice, which is just up the road if any
place was ever just up the road.
</P>
<P>
   The trip was as advertised, breath-taking. Indeed, I gasped
every couple of minutes as the driver propelled us along the
twisting two-lane road through mountain tunnels and zigzag curves,
to deliver me at the doorstep of the casino by the sea.
</P>
<P>
   It's a beautiful day in the world's richest neighborhood, a
Kodachrome kind of day when sea and sky blend at the azure juncture
of the horizon, each bluer than the other as you look from one to
the other.
</P>
<P>
   I celebrate my being here in my own small way.
</P>
<P>
   Though I usually refrain from drinking, I am having a glass of
white wine, and though I usually refrain from eating meat, I am
having a plate of oysters, which is followed by a tureen of the
best French onion soup the world has ever known.
</P>
<P>
   (Something about those French onions that beats the heck out of
anything out of Vidalia, Ga., or Noonday, Texas.)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe later I'll smoke a Monte Christo and sip a cup of cafe au
lait, anything to prolong the experience.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, too, I'll drop in at the casino for a bit of baccarat in
the private rooms.
</P>
<P>
   If they stop me at the door to ask my name, I'm ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name is Bond,'' I'll reply. ``Bubba Bond.''
</P>
<P>
   At which point the music will rise to a crescendo, not the 007
theme but ``Foggy Mountain Breakdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Am I dreaming? Of course I am. Like every country boy, I've been
dreaming about this kind of place all my life.
</P>
<P>
   For a fact, leaving the cafe, I catch myself singing under my
breath ...
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the good ol' boy who broke the bank at Monte Carrr-lo.''
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
