<HEADER>
A9090 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-WEB-ELECT28-COX     10-27 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-WEB-ELECT28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas politicians venture out onto the Web
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When Mindy Tucker listens for the sound of the
political future, she hears millions of screeches _ the screeches
of modems all over Texas logging onto the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely see a time, not so far away, where Web sites are
a permanent part of any and all campaigns,'' said Tucker, deputy
communications director of Gov. George W. Bush's re-election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 7 million people connected to the Internet in
Texas, the Web is quickly becoming the newest pulpit for candidates
preaching the word. More candidates than ever are using
communication tools such as e-mail and Web pages to further their
political platform.
</P>
<P>
   While many experts predict the 2000 election will be the first
election deeply affected by the Internet, impatient, trailblazing
candidates are testing the Web with the hope that being in
cyberspace will translate into votes.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent national survey done by Campaigns and Elections, a
trade publication for the political industry, 63.3 percent of
candidates polled said they already had a Web site, with another
20.7 percent saying they expected to have one.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Faucheux, editor-in-chief of Campaigns and Elections, added
that more Republicans than Democrats have sites and that
Republicans were spending more on the design of their sites.
Candidates on the East Coast were more likely to have a campaign
site than those elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a site doesn't so much say whether a candidate is
technologically hip as it answers to the general population whether
or not a campaign is connected to the real world,'' said Jonathan
Coopersmith, an associate professor of history at Texas A&AMP;M
University. Coopersmith's academic focus is on how technology
affects politics.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Shafer, deputy editor of Slate, an online political
magazine, agreed with Coopersmith but said he's not seeing
sophisticated use of the medium yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still waiting for a political entrepreneur to combine a
potent message with the right Internet technology and connect with
voters,'' Shafer said.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, Bush and his Democratic opponent, Gar-- y Mauro, have
Web sites that approach the potential seen by experts. Bush's Web
designer based his technologically advanced site on one maintained
by brother Jeb Bush, Republican nominee for governor of Florida.
Jeb Bush's site is considered one of the best on the Web and cost
his campaign $26,000, one of the most expensive political sites in
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's site includes up-to-date poll information and
multimedia clips, including a five-minute biographical video and
the campaign's television commercials, all on a nifty, easy-to-use,
light-up menu. The site also provides direct access to the campaign
by posting direct -- -mail links to Bush and campaign
administrators, and a secure link to make contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker said the governor's site was put together for $4,000,
``roughly the price of one television commercial.'' The money was
spent on the site's slick design, and campaign workers now update
it for no cost. To date, the site has been visited by more than
60,000 users, which is a trickle compared with news sites such as
CNN.com, which attracts more than 200,000 users a day.
</P>
<P>
   But Faucheux said a true tally of users and the site's
effectiveness in reaching voters won't be possible until after the
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to interpolate how many people are using these
sites'' because use is building steadily and likely won't peak
until Nov. 3, Faucheux said. ``After the election, we'll have a
better idea of who and how many were using the sites.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush site has raised more than $3,000 in online donations,
which Tucker said is below expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Most campaigns want to raise enough money online to pay for
their sites, Fa-- cheux said. If they succeed, online campaigning
is basically free.
</P>
<P>
   The Mauro campaign site, designed by a few Web-savvy campaign
workers, cost the campaign nothing and is updated in-house. The
site includes interactive links to pages telling how to volunteer,
where to donate to the campaign and how to get in touch with Mauro.
John Hannah, Mauro's press secretary, said the site has been used a
lot, though he won't give specific numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The site has been used mostly for information purposes and not
specifically for raising money, though it does provide phone
numbers on how to donate to the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities inherent in such a cheap, powerful tool will
be especially attractive to candidates of the future. A Web-savvy
intern using a basic Internet connection can create and maintain a
political site on the Web for about $25-$50 a month. With campaign
finance reform around the corner, Shafer predicted, candidates will
be driven to use the Web as a campaign tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this big hue and cry that there's too much money in
elections,'' said Shafer from his Washington office. ``But one of
the reasons there is so much demand for cash is because television
time is so expensive. The Web is this incredibly low-priced
alternative. Next to television, it's almost costless.''
</P>
<P>
   The question remains whether voters are ready for a cyberspace
campaign. Faucheux thinks they are, but to a limited degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``While this medium will never supercede television or radio, if
done in the right way it can effectively disseminate information
and mobilize voters,'' Fa-- cheux said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Price, a business development manager for Austin Title who
surfs the Net seven days a week and votes in every election, said
he has never looked at a political site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for more straight news than political advocacy,''
Price said. ``Besides, when you combine the skepticism everyone has
towards politics and the distrust we have towards the Internet,
it's a double whammy. You've got to question the source and be very
careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Slate editor Shafer sees another problem with campaigning on the
Web. The Internet is vast, and it's easy for a campaign site to get
lost in the universe of World Wide Web addresses alongside the
millions of personal, sports and pornographic Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   According to Shafer, time won't solve this problem, but money
will. Shafer's solution lies in online advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there are certain sites, like a lot of the popular news
Web pages, where you can buy banner ads which can pinpoint users in
certain ZIP codes,'' Shafer said. ``Campaigns will need to purchase
these focused ads and deliver them in such a compelling way that
people will click through the banners to get to the actual site,''
thus delivering tightly targeted audiences to campaigns and
improving the effectiveness of spending.
</P>
<P>
   Even with political skepticism and distrust of the Internet
slowing advancement, both Shafer and Coopersmith think online
campaigns will play an essential part in the 2000 elections. That
year, Shafer predicted, the Internet will yield at least 10 percent
of grass-root donations, and getting the word out about candidates
will be done primarily through -- -mail. He went on to predict that
we are only four years away from voting by computer.
</P>
<P>
   Coopersmith was a little more cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``2000 is when you'll see the true birth of Internet campaign,''
Coopersmith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a presidential year, so the money will be there to
really advertise the sites. More importantly, the candidates will
have the benefit of two years to learn more about the Internet and
build on their experience, resources and the public's interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
