</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9091 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-WEB-SIDE-COX     10-27 0231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-WEB-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reviews of Texas political web sites
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With the Internet's popularity growing by the
day, politicians are beginning to post Web sites and take advantage
of the medium to campaign. Here are a couple of exemplary sites and
the addresses of the Democratic and Republican parties' sites:
</P>
<P>
   _ www.Bush98.com _ The best campaign Web site in Texas (top
right). The site, which was put together for $4,000, has all of
Gov. George W. Bush's speeches and television commercials. It also
includes -- -mail links to him and a how-to on donating money to
his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.Mauro.org _ An amazing effort for a site that cost nothing
(bottom right). This site posts Garry Mauro's positions, photos
from the campaign and a Q&AMP;A that is periodically updated with
readers' inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.TexasGOP.org _ This site is the official home of the Texas
Republicans. Here, you can access all Republican Web sites. You can
also check up on races and make contributions to the party.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.TxDemocrats.org _ The official home of the Texas
Democratic party is not as impressive as the Republican Web site,
but it is just as informative and gives all available direct links
to Texas Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
