<HEADER>
A9143 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEPPER-SPRAY-HNS &LR;      10-27 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPPER-SPRAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE THROWS OUT POLICE BRUTALITY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SETH ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lawyers for environmental protesters say they
will appeal the dismissal of a lawsuit that accused law enforcement
officers of using excessive force by applying pepper spray directly
around the eyes of nonviolent demonstrators who refused to leave
private property.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Cummings, a Berkeley lawyer representing the protesters,
said Monday that the ruling would increase the use of the caustic
chemical by the police and chill civil protest. He said he would
appeal the order.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Delaney, an attorney for the law enforcement officers in
Humboldt County said the decision was well reasoned and vindicated
officers who had dabbed the pepper spray liquid around the eyes of
demonstrators. It was not ``some rally point to use more'' of the
spray, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling Monday by U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker of San
Francisco came in a case that had drawn international attention
after the airing of videotapes of law enforcement officers wiping
the liquid around the eyes of crying protesters. The demonstrators
had locked themselves on private property in the Northern
California county in 1997 to protest logging of ancient redwood
trees.
</P>
<P>
   Several protesters then sued the Humboldt County Sheriff's
Department and the Eureka Police Department, claiming the use of
excessive force in violation of the Fourth Amendment of the U.S.
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   But in what attorneys for both sides said appeared to be the
nation's first ruling to condone such use of pepper spray on
nonviolent civilians, Walker concluded the officers had acted
reasonably.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper spray (made from cayenne pepper and called OC for its
chemical name, oleoresin-capsicum) is generally used to subdue
suspects who are resisting arrest and threatening public safety.
The spray has been linked to more than 40 deaths in California,
usually involving suspects who are mentally ill or intoxicated with
illicit drugs, according to the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   In the Humboldt County case, a jury deadlocked 4-4 in August,
and a retrial was set for Nov. 16. But at the defendants' request,
Walker dismissed the suit, saying no reasonable jury could find the
officers had acted improperly.
</P>
<P>
   While noting it was usually up to a jury to decide whether
officers had used excessive force, Walker said judges may assume
that role when there was ``but one reasonable conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The uncontroverted evidence presented at trial,'' he wrote,
``unequivocally supports the conclusion that the officers acted
reasonably in using OC as a pain compliance technique in arresting
plaintiffs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The officers did not threaten or use deadly force, or even
employ a significant level of physical force,'' he said. ``Rather,
the force used was merely the infliction of transient pain without
significant risk of physical injury.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit stemmed from three incidents in September and
October 1997, when Humboldt County officers swabbed the liquid
around the eyes of anti-logging protesters.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the demonstrators trespassed on private property
and locked themselves together using ``black bears,'' welded pieces
of heavy pipe through which they could join arms and resist arrest.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, officers cut the pipe to remove the protesters, but
the cutting tools posed a risk of slicing their arms and shooting
sparks that could cause fire, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the videotapes of the incidents, which were played at
trial, Walker said the officers had first pleaded repeatedly with
the protesters to leave.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the officers always rinsed the eyes of the
protesters with water after they were unlocked to ease the pain.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiff Noel Tendick, 21, said he was shocked by the order.
``That's contrary to what much of the nation felt ... what we felt
... what half the jury felt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Van Jones, executive director of Bay Area PoliceWatch, called
Walker's refusal to let a jury retry the case outrageous. He said
he feared the ruling would prompt other police departments to
directly apply OC.
</P>
<P>
   ACLU lawyer John Crew, however, said that though he disagreed
with the ruling, it appeared to narrowly apply to circumstances
surrounding the logging protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law enforcement should not be mistaken and think the court has
given the green light to using pepper spray on all nonviolent
protesters involved in civil disobedience,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
