<HEADER>
A9156 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDSBOOKS-AZR &LR;      10-27 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDSBOOKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cute scarecrows and spooky ghosts are among October's crop of
characters in new children's books. Other standouts include an
impressive world atlas and a collection of touching stories about
friendship written by and for kids. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE LITTLE SCARECROW BOY &QL; 
 &UR; Margaret Wise Brown; illustrated by David Diaz (HarperCollins,
$15.95)
</P>
<P>
   This scarecrow coming-of-age story is set in a brightly colored
cornfield with autumn hues of gold, orange and brown and green. The
tale begins with father teaching son the finer points of scaring
crows. One morning, the boy sneaks past his sleeping parents and
runs to the cornfield, where he makes his debut as the scariest
scarecrow in the land. Proud Papa, watching from a distance, then
takes the boy home for a celebratory breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, best known for penning ``Goodnight Moon,'' wrote this
story in the 1940s. HarperCollins has published it for the first
time as a picture book, with bold and amusing illustrations by
Diaz. For ages 3-7. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 10 MINUTES TILL BEDTIME &QL; 
 &UR; Peggy Rathmann (G.P. Putnam, $16.99)
</P>
<P>
   Are you ready for wacky?
</P>
<P>
   Just after an oblivious Dad with his nose in a newspaper
declares it's 10 minutes till bedtime, the boy's pet hamster
welcomes a family of visiting hamsters at the front door and gives
them a tour of the house. The boy and the hamsters get a nighttime
snack, brush their teeth, get their jammies on and settle in for a
story _ when billions and jillions more hamsters show up, clogging
the hallways with their vehicles and the bathtub with their rafts,
boats and lounge chairs.
</P>
<P>
   As the clock ticks on, the boy gets a bit worried and finally
screams: BEDTIME! The hamsters scamper away, and still clueless Dad
tucks his son in bed. Guaranteed giggles, by the author of ``Good
Night, Gorilla.'' For ages 3-7. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; A GIFT FOR ABUELITA: CELEBRATING THE DAY OF THE DEAD &QL; 
 &UR; Nancy Luenn; illustrated by Robert Chapman (Northland, $15.95)
</P>
<P>
   This touching story about Rosita and her ``Abuelita'' _
grandmother _ is multilayered in meaning and quite literally in its
artwork.
</P>
<P>
   The plot revolves around the Day of the Dead, the Hispanic
community's memorial celebration that usually takes place between
Oct. 31 and Nov. 2. Rosita loses and mourns her grandmother, then
heals herself by making preparations with her family to honor the
memory of ``Abuelita.'' memory. The text, in English and Spanish,
is both culturally and emotionally instructive.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix artist Chapman's extraordinary work reflects the colors
and styles of the Mexican-American culture. His process involves
creating handcrafted molds from which paper casts are made, dried
and painted. The pieces then are photographed against tile
backgrounds. ``Magnifico!'' For ages 4-8. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THANK YOU, MR. FALKER &QL; 
 &UR; Patricia Polacco (Philomel, $16.99)
</P>
<P>
   Trisha looked forward to going to school so she could learn how
to read. But when she opened a book, all she saw were wiggling
shapes. Other kids made fun of her, and she started to feel
different. By the time she reached fifth grade, she felt totally
stupid, and she hated school.
</P>
<P>
   Along came a new teacher, Mr. Falker. He raved about Trisha's
artwork, and held it up for the whole class to admire. He protected
her from kids who teased her. And one day, after school, he figured
out why Trisha couldn't read: She was dyslexic. Mr. Falker worked
every day with Trisha until the world of reading opened to her.
</P>
<P>
   This autobiographical tribute to the special teacher in
Polacco's life is a real-life demonstration that non-readers not
only can become readers, but can go on to become published writers
who also can draw! Kids facing similar challenges will feel
inspired. For ages 6-10.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ANNABEL LEE &QL; 
 &UR; Edgar Allan Poe; illustrated by Gilles Tibo (McClelland &AMP; Stewart,
$5.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``But we loved with a love that was more than love _ I and my
Annabel Lee. With a love that the winged seraphs of heaven coveted
her and me.''
</P>
<P>
   Poe's classic ode to love and loss is beautifully depicted in
the soft paintings of Quebec artist Tibo, who created two children
playing in the tide, with gliding sea gulls, blue sky and fickle
seas that eventually claim Annabel Lee. Her death is handled with
grace, and the poem's message is that the two children remain
connected in spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The book was named to American Bookseller's Pick of the List
when it first was published in 1988. Now, it has been redesigned
and issued in paperback at a lower price. For ages 8-11. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; EVEN STEPHEN &QL; 
 &UR; Johanna Hurwitz (Beech Tree Books, $4.95)
</P>
<P>
   This is the perfect middle-grade read for youngsters with
perfect older brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny adores Stephen, who is smart, popular and athletic. She
wants to be like him, but feels she'll never measure up. One day,
tragedy strikes, and Stephen fails in his attempt to save the day.
Though the failure is no fault of his, Stephen becomes depressed
and withdrawn. Sunny empathizes with her brother and figures out
how to help him. The story teaches good lessons about family,
understanding, self-esteem and growth. For ages 8-11. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; GREAT GHOST STORIES &QL; 
 &UR; Selected and illustrated by Barry Moser (William Morrow &AMP; Co., $22)
</P>
<P>
   Curl up by the fireplace and get ready to get scared with this
collection of _ naturally _ 13 ghost stories by such masters of
suspense as Arthur Conan Doyle, Joyce Carol Oates, Bram Stoker (of
``Dracula'' fame), and H.G. Wells. These tales cover the terrain of
terror: haunted houses, the spirit world, and plenty of bodies. Not
for the easily spooked. For ages 8-12. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; NATIONAL GEOGRAPHIC WORLD ATLAS FOR YOUNG EXPLORERS &QL; 
 &UR; (National Geographic Books, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Aerial views of the continents, every conceivable type of map,
and photographs of world wonders ranging from the Lost City of the
Incas to the Grand Canyon are depicted in this comprehensive
collection published by the prestigious National Geographic
Society.
</P>
<P>
   The atlas contains information on every continent's physical
features, societies, economic and creative activities, and
political subdivisions. Fun facts that accompany each map help
students find information on various world regions, such as highest
mountains, longest rivers, most populous cities and major products.
People pictures put a human cast on global diversity, from Ninga
tribal drummers in Africa to bicyclists jamming China's busy
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Visually mesmerizing, the 176-page, large-format book would make
an ideal gift for adventurous spirits. For ages 8 and up. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE STONE SOUP BOOK OF FRIENDSHIP STORIES &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by William Rubel and Gerry Mandel (Tricycle Press, $8.95)
</P>
<P>
   These tales about friendship are special because of who wrote
them: authors between the ages of 8 and 13 who contribute to
``Stone Soup,'' a literary magazine by and for young people. These
best picks on the topic of friendship from the magazine's past 25
years are inspiring examples for all writers.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Winds of Africa,'' 13-year-old Abbie Gunn sets her
story about tested friendship in the African savannah. ``Dandelion
Seeds'' captures a moment familiar to all of us: blowing dandelion
fluff. ``On the Headland'' begins with a girl and her dog walking
along the Maine coast: ``The Headland was gray and deserted, almost
sinister, with the heavy silver clouds gathered overhead.'' The
girl and her dog are headed toward trouble that day, but a handsome
stranger pulls them to safety. For ages 8-12. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SNOW, SNOW: WINTER POEMS FOR CHILDREN &QL; 
 &UR; Jane Yolen; pictures by Jason Stemple (Boyds Mills Press, $16.95)
</P>
<P>
   This slim volume of poetry and stunning photos will put you in
the mood for winter. The diverse scenery includes snow-covered
Colorado Rockies, ice-covered rivers, ice-tipped branches and a
roaring snowmobile. Yolen, author of nearly 200 books, collaborated
with her photographer son to produce this work that will appeal to
young poets and snow fans. For ages 10-12. &QL; 
(Beverly Medlyn can be reached at bevmedlyn(AT)aol.com via e-mail.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 1330EST &QL; 
