<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9159 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      10-27 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE CLINTON ENIGMA &QL; 
 &UR; David Maraniss (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $17)
</P>
<P>
   Maraniss covered Bill Clinton for the ``Washington Post,'' wrote
a biography of him and became one of television's talking heads
when the Monica Lewinsky affair took over the news. Here he
dissects Clinton's Aug. 17 speech _ the infamous non-apology _ but
not before he grouses at length about the fact that Clinton refused
interviews with him when he was researching the biography ``First
in His Class.'' He tries to portray Clinton as evasive but sounds
so petty that you begin to think Clinton was smart to avoid him.
This slender volume, in which the author manages to plug his next
book repeatedly, is for those among you who are hungry for more
analysis of Clinton's troubles, more informed comment on his psyche
and more effort to keep the spin alive. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TWINS &QL; 
 &UR; Ruth and Rachael Sandweiss (Running Press, $27.50)
</P>
<P>
   The publishing world has birthed twin books, and they are so
alike that it's embarrassing. This one (on the cover is actress
Jill Hennessy, late of television's ``Law and Order,'' and her
sister, Jacqueline) arrived two days before its soul mate, ``The
Book of Twins'' (Delacorte, $27.50) by Debra and Lisa Ganz. Yes,
twin authors and twin prices, and inside more of the same: actress
twins, doctor twins, police officer twins, twins who married twins,
pole-vaulting twins, belly-dancing twins, Bosnian twins, Siamese
twins, sets of twins in which one sibling is in a wheelchair, twins
whose siblings have died (with photos of the solitary survivors,
gazing into the distance). Both volumes have forgettable text and
too many photos in which everyone is laughing heartily. Another
coincidence: The oldest twins in each were born in 1904. Isn't it
eerie? If we dropped one book on the floor, the other would surely
feel its pain. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; GOD OF THE RODEO &QL; 
 &UR; Daniel Bergner (Crown, $24)
</P>
<P>
   ``The rodeo, to us, is kind of like making a good cake,'' Warden
Burl Cain told Bergner. ``Some of the ingredients by themselves
wouldn't be fit to eat. But you put them all together and you have
a nice cake.'' A nice cake _ there could not be a less appropriate
description of the rodeo at Angola, Louisiana's maximum-security
state penitentiary, where the ``ingredients'' were men incarcerated
for murder and rape with little or no chance for parole. When
Bergner first spoke to Cain, he was writing an article about the
rodeo _ a brutal event with obvious gladiatorial overtones _
for``'' ``Harper's'' magazine. With time, the story became a book
project, Bergner and Cain became enemies (Cain wanted a portion of
the book's proceeds in exchange for Bergner's continued access to
inmates), and Bergner's search came to include his own ``visions of
redemption.'' The result is a chilling portrayal of prison life and
a humanizing portrait of brutal men. Bergner's efforts to give his
story the deeper meaning than that is superfluous. Angola and the
inmates who spend their lives there are meaningful enough. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; JOURNEY TO BELOVED &QL; 
 &UR; Oprah Winfrey (Hyperion, $40)
</P>
<P>
   The star and chief financier doesn't usually write the movie
tie-in, so this has more than the usual clout behind it. It's a
handsome book, with somber photographs taken by Ken Regan on the
set of ``Beloved.'' The text, except for a brief essay by director
Jonathan Demme, is a first-person account by Winfrey, much of it
from a journal she kept during filming. There's no escaping the
fact that it is a self-congratulatory endeavor _ we would like to
tell you to save some money and buy a copy of Toni Morrison's novel
instead. And yet. Winfrey describes the Saturday long ago when she
read ``Beloved'' in one sitting. She was so moved that she set out
to find the author and get film rights, but she could not reach the
publisher on a weekend and she had no luck when she tried to get
Morrison's number through other people. Finally, she looked in her
copy of ``Beloved'' and found mention of the town where Morrison
lived, then called the fire department there and asked them to
contact Morrison with her intentions. Later, when it was time to
talk money, Winfrey told her attorney to give Morrison whatever she
wanted. The day she signed the check, she says ``was one of the
happiest days of my life.'' This is not just about a movie but
about a novel's hold on one of the most powerful women in the
world. That's not a bad story in itself. All good books should be
so lucky as to have Oprah Winfrey read them on a Saturday
afternoon. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BIG LEAGUE, BIG TIME &QL; 
 &UR; Len Sherman (Pocket, $23)
</P>
<P>
   Here is the story of Bank One Ballpark and the Arizona
Diamondbacks, set against the larger issue of Big Bucks in
Baseball. Don't be put off by Sherman's early sentences, which
invoke the stars, the planets, the universe and the Big Bang, not
to mention those jazzy clouds over Arizona (``long, elegant, pastel
swirls inside swirls, wispy puffs of pure white cotton candy;
flat-bottomed, multicolored mushrooms rising into the
stratosphere''). The author quickly settles down into a more
straightforward account of how big league baseball came to the
desert via ``the most powerful man in Arizona,'' Jerry Colangelo,
with help from fawning government officials and overzealous media.
If you followed the story as it was happening, you won't find
surprises here.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Correspondent Anne Stephenson can be reached at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 1331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
