<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9162 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-RAINBOW-AZR &LR;      10-27 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-RAINBOW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLANCY NOT HIS COLORFUL SELF IN `RAINBOW' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
RAINBOW SIX 
Tom Clancy (G.P. Putnam's Sons, $27.95) 
 
 By MONTY PHAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Madmen want to destroy the world, and it's up to an elite team
of supertroopers to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like the plot to some half-baked TV movie of the week,
and that's the sad part. It's actually the very boiled-down plot of
Tom Clancy's latest 740-page effort, ``Rainbow Six.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, summing up any 700-plus-page work in one sentence
will result in some gross oversimplifications. The longer version
of the plot summary is that ex-CIA agent John Clark, a character
familiar to Clancy fans from previous novels (particularly
``Without Remorse'') is named to head up an international task
force, called Rainbow, created to fight terrorism. Clark has the
highest, or ``six,'' position, hence ``Rainbow Six.''
</P>
<P>
   The team is called into action three times _ in Switzerland,
Germany and Spain _ all in close succession, prompting concern
among the protagonists. Meanwhile, an American billionaire has his
biotech company develop a strain of the Ebola virus that's
untreatable by any means of conventional medicine. The company has
the only vaccine, too.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the billionaire and his legion of faithful
followers are zealous environmentalists who are preparing the virus
for its unleashing at the 2000 Olympics in Sydney, Australia. Their
plan is to kill 99 percent of the human population, which, give or
take a few 10 million, is how many people are hostile or
indifferent toward the environment.
</P>
<P>
   After the humans are gone, nature will take over, allowing
Mother Earth to heal herself. The billionaire and his legion of
faithful followers will repopulate the world, teaching the children
to care about the planet. And it'll all happen, too, unless an
elite team of supertroopers can stop them.
</P>
<P>
   See, Clancy novels never used to elicit such sarcasm. Since his
first novel, ``The Hunt for Red October'' (decorated Russian Navy
officer defects using prototype Soviet submarine), Clancy has posed
original, yet seemingly plausible, questions. What if a warhead
from a downed fighter plane got into terrorists' hands (``The Sum
of All Fears'')? Or if the United States and Japan again went to
war (``Debt of Honor'')?
</P>
<P>
   But after picking on the Soviets, the IRA, the Japanese and the
Iranians, Clancy seems to be running out of enemies in his
fictional world. Not only is his latest question _ what if biotech
engineers used a virus to commit mass genocide? _ unoriginal by
technothriller standards, it's unoriginal by Clancy standards.
</P>
<P>
   In his last novel, ``Executive Orders,'' Iran tried to unleash a
milder form of ``Rainbow Six's'' Ebola virus on the United States.
And, if you want to get picky, terrorists in ``The Sum of All
Fears'' attempted to use another globally seen sporting event, the
Super Bowl, to make its statement, like the bad guys in ``Rainbow''
use the Olympics to make theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Even the trademark of all Clancy novels, detail, takes a hit.
The billionaire builds a gigantic complex, complete with airstrip,
on 20-plus acres in the middle of Kansas for the selected survivors
to live in, and no one, including the press, notices.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the environmentalists move in, they repeatedly use
Hummers to go from the building to the horse stables. If they care
so much about the environment, why do they needlessly pollute the
air with a Hummer, when a bicycle seemingly would suffice?
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Clancy does keep us informed of the latest
gadgetry _ such as a device that tracks people by the
electromagnetic field generated by a human heart, and a
cell-phone-jamming contraption that foils the plans of one team of
terrorists. But then, who needs gadgets when Clancy's cardboard
characters are the kind who never miss and always get their men?
</P>
<P>
   Like so many other authors, Clancy's name alone will sell books.
But where previous efforts used a spectacular climax to reward the
reader for enduring the dictionary-size heft, this one merely
fizzles out.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 1332EST &QL; 
