<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9164 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-ROADHOME-AZR &LR;      10-27 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ROADHOME-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JIM HARRISON CATERS TO FANS' APPETITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
THE ROAD HOME 
Jim Harrison (Atlantic Monthly Press, $25) 
 
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It is easy to forget that in the main we die only seven times
more slowly than our dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   A rather curious outlook on life, but one that suits John
Northridge II in ``The Road Home,'' the latest novel by Jim
Harrison and his first full-length novel since ``Dalva'' 10 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   To his family and the people who know him, Northridge is
something of a monster, or at least half-crazed. But his journals,
through which we get to know him, reveal someone else _ a
semi-serious art student, a man with a healthy attitude toward
money and the spending thereof (even if he has rather questionable
methods of making it) and a hearty eater with a voracious appetite.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you knew he'd have that last. This is a Jim Harrison
book, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison, author of ``Legends of the Fall'' and ``Julip,'' among
many other things, manages to work a good deal of food into
everything he writes. (His late, lamented food column, ``The Raw
and Cooked'' in ``Esquire,'' was a special treat. The man had gout,
for goodness sake. Who besides Henry VIII gets that?)
</P>
<P>
   Northridge's journals make up just a part of the book, which
takes us from the early part of this century on through the late
'80s. We also hear from Nelse, his great-grandson given up for
adoption; Naomi, Northridge's daughter-in-law; Paul, his son; and
Dalva, Northridge's granddaughter and Nelse's mother (as well as
the subject of Harrison's previous novel).
</P>
<P>
   Northridge's sheer force of larger-than-life personality has
rubbed off on all of them in varying degrees, so that all are at
least in part that particular type of character found only in good
books and bad movies: the learned rogue. All are equally at home
cleaning a fish or quoting Aristophanes.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing Harrison's love of food, perhaps it's useful to look
at the novel as a five-course meal. No appetizers here _ the novel
kicks off with Northridge's journals, which are far too meaty to be
considered anything other than the main course.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge is a half-Sioux with an abiding respect for native
cultures. His good horse sense and strong arm-twisting have brought
him money and land. Yet he believes he has the soul of an artist
and indeed studied art for a time. He married the sister of his
true love; he fathered two sons, one killed in the Korean War; he
conducted affairs both business and sexual seemingly all over
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   However, although compelling _ ``. . . there is nothing quite so
destructive as an artist acquiring common sense before he has
utterly blown up the world of his perceptions and acquired the
grace to put it back together again,'' he writes _ Northridge's
journals are almost too rich and gamy, like a too-large serving of
veal.
</P>
<P>
   Nelse, Northridge's great-grandson given up for adoption, is a
wanderer of the first order. For years, he has traveled the
country, studying nature by living in it and, naturally, keeping
journals. He has determined to reunite with his natural mother,
Dalva, and does so. Hard-headed, hot-headed and claustrophobic (one
reason he sleeps outside so much), his section is like a spicy
enchilada _ tasty, but a little goes a long way, and it can bother
you hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, the most normal of the lot, owing to her not being
blood kin of Northridge, is Naomi. Her story is like a good dose of
cilantro _ it's clean and unobtrusive, and just the ingredient to
freshen things a bit. A teacher nearing retirement, she has at
least as much love for nature as her grandson Nelse, but lives in
the real world, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Which doesn't keep her from sharing a bed on occasion with Paul,
her late husband's brother. How to describe his contribution to the
tale? A bland wine, perhaps? Paul is a geologist and a bit of a
traveling man himself, although not to Nelse's extent.
</P>
<P>
   To call Dalva's narrative dessert captures its delight but not
its weight. Great changes have taken place for her, not the least
of which are meeting the son she had never known and getting laid
off from her job as a social worker; more are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Here Harrison's writing is at its best. ``We certainly don't
know how old we are unless we remind ourselves,'' Dalva thinks.
``For a half hour or so I was five, lacking only my bright red
boots, and little Ruth tagging along beside me, squealing `hundred'
for how many times she wanted to be pushed in the tire swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Her tale encompasses the ambitious scope of the entire book _
gain, loss, life, death, the burdensome but beautiful weight of
family. And to a large degree she is what makes the meal ultimately
so delicious. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
