   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Pristina) _ Developments in the Yugoslav province:
Ethnic Albanian refugees are reported flooding back to their homes
as Serb forces withdraw. By Mike O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Washington) _ Developments as NATO meets in
Brussels to consider extending its deadline for Serb withdrawal
from Kosovo; other Washington developments. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL (Jerusalem) _ Under pressure to carry out security
crackdown, Palestinian police arrest two men they say confessed to
killing a Jewish settler on Monday. Also, security is increased
around Prime Minister Netanyahu as harsh far-right criticism
prompts reminders of the Rabin assassination. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RIGHTS (Beijing) _ China takes new steps to suppress
political organization and debate, detaining people and banning a
book, two weeks after signing th U.N. Covenant on Human Rights. By
Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-U.N. (United Nations) _ Because of the huge impact of AIDS,
the United Nations revises its population estimates and
projections, showing a big effect on life expectancy in much of
Africa. By Youssef M. Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-SCHROEDER (Bonn) _ Gerhard Schroeder is sworn in as
Germany's seventh postwar chancellor. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-BOOKS (Undated) _ The winner of Britain's No. 1 book
award, the Booker Prize, is to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SHUTTLE-NOSTALGIA (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ There must be
something here that invigorates the likes of John Glenn and T.J.
O'Malley. Thomas J. O'Malley, known to missile colleagues as T. J.,
was the man who on the morning of Feb. 20, 1962, pressed the black
button to start the Atlas booster's engines and send Glenn on his
way in a Mercury capsule to be the first American to orbit the
planet. He is 83 now, still full of sass and gruff charm, and
brimming with stories of the old days. Like O'Malley, many of those
who shared the anxiety, thrill and glory of the first Glenn flight
in 1962 are gathering here again to sip at the fountain of their
youth. For this moment at least, their years seem to decline in
number like a launching clock, counting down instead of up. By John
Noble Wilford. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL DISPLAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLO-GAYS (Ft. Collins) _ Fort Collins, which just experienced
the death of openly gay college student Matthew Shepard, is about
to vote on a municipal hate crimes law that was placed on the
ballot before Shepard's death. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   NY-VALLONE-PROFILE (New York) _ A profile of Peter Vallone,
speaker of the N.Y. City Council and the Democratic challenger to
Gov. George Pataki. By Abby Goodnough. (2500 words)
