<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1 p.m., the industrial average was up 17
points. Elsewhere, prices were off 0.2 percent in Tokyo and up 1.5
percent in Hong Kong. They gained 2.3 percent in Frankfurt, 1.8
percent in London, and 0.1 percent in Mexico, while falling 2.4
percent in Brazil. On the American debt market, the long bond was
up 19/32 point, with the yield at 5.09 percent. By Kenneth N.
Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Day six of the Microsoft
antiturst trial. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-INVESTORS (Rome) _ The European shareholders who have
bought stock for the first time in the bull market of the 1990s do
not appeared to have been frightened by the recent battering of
stock markets. Recent data suggest there has been no net outflow of
money in stocks. Part of the explanation is the low level of
interest rates in Europe. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DEFAULT (Undated) _ The Guangdong International Trust and
Investment Corp. has failed to make a scheduled interest payment of
$8.75 million on a bond. This could make it the first Chinese
company to default since the Communist revolution despite some
earlier indications that the central government would cover some of
Gitic's debts. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-EARNINGS (Undated) _ America Online is expected to report
earnings after the close. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   IBM-BUYBACK (Armonk, N.Y.) _ In its latest big repurchase of its
stock, IBM says it will spend $3.5 billion to buy back shares. By
Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-MUSIC (Undated) _ Over the objection of the music
recording industry, a federal judge has ruled that Diamond
Multimedia Systems can start shipping a handheld device that
records and stores music in digital form and then plays in back
over headphones. The industry said the device would encourage
people to download pirated music stored on the Internet, instead of
buying compact disks.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Two of Japan's vaunted high-tech companies
_ Toshiba and Hitachi _ are reporting losses for the six months
that ended Sept. 30. The companies cited the worldwide decline in
sales of bread-and-butter memory chips, weak consumer demand in
their home market and falling capital investment in Japan for the
bulk of their problems. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
