<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON NAMED VICE PRESIDENT FOR CIRCULATION AT SAN FRANCISCO
AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Stephen C. Johnson has been named vice president
of circulation for the San Francisco Newspaper Agency, which
oversees advertising, circulation and printing for the San
Francisco Examiner and the San Francisco Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson comes to the agency from Pittsburgh, where he was
president and chief executive of Thomson Newspapers' strategic
marketing group in Pennsylvania and Ohio, an area that includes six
daily and four weekly newspapers owned by Thomson. He was
previously corporate vice president of circulation for Thomson's
143 newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was born and grew up in the San Francisco area, and
began his newspaper career as a truck driver for the Oakland
Tribune. After military service, he returned to the Tribune and was
named to positions with increasingly greater management
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   His role in launching the Tribune's Eastbay Today led to his
being promoted to senior distribution executive for the Gannett
Satellite Information Network to complete planning the launch of
USA Today, which began publishing in 1982. He then spent six years
in various positions for Gannett Co. Inc. before returning to
California to work for the San Bernardino Sun and then the Los
Angeles Times, where he was circulation manager for six years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he has been active in the newspaper industry and
with university journalism and marketing programs. He and his wife,
Robin, have two teen-agers, son Eric and daughter Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's appointment was announced by Steven B. Falk, president
and chief executive of the San Francisco Newspaper Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson succeeds Stephen T. Hearst, who was recently named vice
president and general manager of the Hearst Corp.'s Sunical Land &AMP;
Livestock division and its San Francisco Realties division.
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst Corp. owns the Examiner and 11 other daily
newspapers.
</P>
</TEXT>
