million into a virtual-reality project before abandoning it. In the
1980s, the videogame business bankrupted Coleco, the maker of
Cabbage Patch Kids and ColecoVision, and nearly brought Mattel to
its knees.
 &HT;    But the recent success of toys containing microprocessors, from
Tickle Me Elmo to Tamagotchi to Barney, has buttressed the belief
that technology will be the industry's savior. While earlier
generations of high-tech toys were clunky and unresponsive to a
child, the newer ones insinuate themselves into their owner's life
in sometimes alarming ways.
 &HT;    Some schools banned virtual pets because children were more
focused on ``feeding'' them than on paying attention to the
teacher. Many parents fretted when their kids began to mourn
digital creatures that had ``croaked.'' Toys like Furby, which
exhibit rudimentary artificial intelligence, integrate themselves
