</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-THENANDNOW-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN-THENANDNOW-2TAKES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  EDITORS: This story is a resend and part of a GLENN-LAUNCH package
sent out for Oct. 25. 
 
 
 
CHANGING COURSE: WITH THE COLD WAR LONG THAWED, NASA HAS FOUND A
NEW FOCUS 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 25) 
 
By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The embryonic NASA of John Glenn's heyday as a Mercury astronaut
in the early 1960s pushed the envelope of human spaceflight, boldly
teaching itself to pilot in a treacherous new realm and eventually
to walk on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   The middle-aged space program of today has long retreated from
the lunar frontier and focused itself instead on filling the gap
between the Earth and moon with a less glamorous international
space station.
</P>
<P>
   The two very different eras converge late this month when Glenn,
now 77 and in the twilight of a lengthy U.S. Senate career, soars
once again into space for a nine-day mission aboard the space
shuttle Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 20, 1962, Glenn made history when he became the first
American to orbit the Earth, his only flight in five years with the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration. His encore will make
him by far humanity's oldest emissary in space.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's solo Mercury flight established that an astronaut could
cope with a nervous system turned upside down in the absence of
gravity, retain sharpness of vision and be able to make decisions
necessary to control and fly a spacecraft into unexplored
territory.
</P>
<P>
   With his second flight, Glenn plans to again play the role of
medical subject, though not pilot, on behalf of an emerging
scientific premise that there is a medical link between the
physical stresses of space flight and those of aging.
</P>
<P>
   His latest contribution, the senator believes, may awaken an
aging national populace to the need for more research into the
ailments shared temporarily by healthy young astronauts and the
elderly. They include weakened immune and cardiovascular systems,
brittle bones, balance disorders and trouble sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to go back up,'' Glenn said in January as his
four-year, behind-the-scenes campaign in Washington to fly again
bore fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Cheered by the throngs who lined New York's Wall Street for a
ticker-tape parade and by a joint session of Congress after his
three orbits of the Earth, Glenn believes his hero status prevented
him from taking another mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was overwhelming, a shock almost,'' Glenn said of the
outpouring that dwarfed anything that contemporary shuttle crews
receive. ``There would be people crying along the street, sobbing
and wiping their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were tenuous times we were living in, the competition
with the Soviets,'' Glenn said of the early '60s-era
boisterousness. ``We look at that now and think, oh well, the
Soviets are down the tubes and that was bound to happen. But we did
not know that then.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was dog-eat-dog,'' Glenn recalled. ``Americans had begun to
doubt themselves as far as leadership in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   America's space program sprung to life in the aftermath of the
October 1957 launch of Sputnik, the first man-made satellite, by
the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The United States was striding toward a decade of political
assassination, racial strife and protracted combat in Southeast
Asia. The threat of nuclear annihilation from a face-off between
the United States and the communist Soviet regime loomed profoundly
over the globe.
</P>
<P>
   If the Soviets could launch a satellite on a rocket, they could
replace it with an atomic bomb aimed at the United States,
policy-makers reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   Domestically, the economy was robust as America entered the
1960s. The three-martini lunch was fashionable. Families gathered
before their televisions to watch ``Wagon Train'' and ``Bonanza,''
a pair of westerns whose themes celebrated a vibrant, young nation
settling its rugged frontier. On the dance floor, the rage was the
Twist, an aerobic oscillation in which the participants went
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Amid this invigorating chaos, the United States was also going
to the moon. Unprecedented in its risk and ambition, the expedition
was intended to reveal a national might and grace greater than its
superpower rival.
</P>
<P>
   As the decade of the '60s opened, the United States was clearly
behind in the space race. The Soviets followed their success with
Sputnik by launching the first human, cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin, who
circled the Earth once on April 12, 1961.
</P>
<P>
   America's first space traveler, the late Alan B. Shepard Jr.,
followed Gagarin less than a month later with a more modest
suborbital lob that spanned just 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, then-President John F. Kennedy spoke to Congress,
directing the nation to place an astronaut on the moon by the end
of the decade. The goal was achieved in July 1969.
</P>
<P>
   The program was called Apollo and was structured to build on the
accomplishments of Glenn and his Mercury colleagues and those who
participated in a second program called Gemini.
</P>
<P>
   The moon quest galvanized America. Kennedy battled with
lawmakers for the privilege of increasing NASA funding, not cutting
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environment was one of anticipation, expectancy and one of
doubt; one of wanting proof the United States could compete with
the Russians in space,'' said Christopher Kraft, who served as the
NASA flight director for Glenn's mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were tremendous days, particularly the flight of John
Glenn,'' he said. ``There was a tremendous feeling of
accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The (shuttle) flight of John Glenn has rekindled a spark that
was there a long time ago. He has inspired people,'' Kraft said.
``They are inspired by his intestinal fortitude. No matter how
trite that might seem, it's true.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 1358EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9202 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-27 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ They have trained and rehearsed.
</P>
<P>
   They have planned their order of appearance, their scripts, the
choreography, even the clothes they will wear today when they stand
before 31 NFL owners and plead for an expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   No detail is too small. ``Does this suit make me look fat? Do
these shoes go with these socks? Does this tie say, `We're Houston
_ take us?'''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston contingent of NFL dreamers has descended upon Kansas
City for today's NFL meetings. The theme it hopes to deliver was
best described by ownership hopeful Bob McNair when the Houston
stadium-financing plan was finalized last week: Houston has steak.
Los Angeles has sizzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ready to go right now,'' said Steve Patterson, who
helped coordinate the NFL pitch and has been in the middle of
stadium-financing negotiations from the start. ``We will build the
first and so far only retractable-roof, natural-grass football
stadium in the world. It will be the greatest stadium in the world.
It will be in the heart of football country _ football-crazy
country. We've got the commitment. We've got the resources. We've
got tremendous support and infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   But what the Houston group does not have is time. Or the LA
sizzle.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it has made up ground recently, Los Angeles is behind
Houston on virtually every front when it comes to presenting a
viable expansion package. But, oh, that sizzle. It tempts the NFL's
palate.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, there is a rock-solid stadium proposal _ dotted I's
and crossed T's, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Los Angeles has two proposals _ the one by former
super-agent and Walt Disney executive Michael Ovitz and the one
headed by Ed Roski, which is endorsed by the LA city council and
calls for the complete redesign of the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, there is public support and, more important,
governmental support. The way Mayor Lee Brown, McNair, County Judge
Robert Eckels, sports authority chief Jack Rains and Patterson came
together on the deal last week was hugely impressive. Individually,
each represented entirely different interests. One might have
believed it difficult for these five powers to agree on what to
order for lunch, much less a $310 million stadium. But they did it.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, Ovitz and the Coliseum partners have divided
loyalties with their NFL pitches, which on paper are equally
impressive but also equally riddled with holes, financing
shortcomings and political flash points.
</P>
<P>
   On top of everything, while Houston has voiced support for a
return of the NFL, a recent Los Angeles Times poll indicated that
nearly 60 percent of Southern Californians do not consider having a
football team important to them. Nearly 70 percent said they would
not support using public funds to build a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In so many ways, this looks like it should be a simple choice
for NFL owners _ Houston over Los Angeles. Steak over sizzle. But
this is Los Angeles sizzle, which cannot be underestimated. It is
flash and cash.
</P>
<P>
   It is why the Houston group will be hoping to swoop into KC
today and persuade the owners to make a quick decision regarding
expansion, giving Houston what it is ready to provide. Football.
</P>
<P>
   Some owners want it done fast, too. Concerned about scheduling
problems that the 31st team _ Cleveland _ will give the league next
year, some are pushing for a 32nd team to begin playing as early as
2000. This is great for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But other owners are listening to the sizzle and are being
swayed by the pomp, not the circumstance. They see the glamorous
stars involved in the Ovitz group _ Tom Cruise, Kevin Costner,
Jerry West and Magic Johnson _ and are wowed.
</P>
<P>
   They're thinking about the difference a Los Angeles NFL team
would have on television negotiations in 2004, compared to the
effect a Houston team might have.
</P>
<P>
   They realize Los Angeles might not be ready right now, but if it
can be ready in a couple of months _ six months, maybe even late
next year _ it could be worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that we want an NFL team in the second-biggest market
again, no question,'' Indianapolis Colts owner Jim Irsay said.
``There's no need to rush it.''
</P>
<P>
   For LA, there is no need at all. It is the sizzle. In fact, even
before these meetings opened, Ovitz criss-crossed the country
visiting NFL owners, showing them plans and designs for his
proposed Hacienda stadium in Carson, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz brought here those same drawings and computer-generated
images of the 78,000-seat stadium, which would be the centerpiece
of a 160-acre NFL Disneyland of sorts, with a giant mall,
entertainment center and Spanish-style stadium complete with a
church tower and bells that ring for every touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   It is impressive sizzle, no doubt. All McNair, Patterson and Co.
can hope for is that when in Kansas City, the NFL owners do like KC
folk and crave steak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
