u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-COMMENTARY-HNS &LR;      10-27 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-COMMENTARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERO WORSHIP: IT SOUNDED CORNBALL THEN AND DOES NOW, BUT GLENN TOOK
US INTO A NEW FRONTIER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  EDITORS: This story is resend and part of a GLENN-LAUNCH package
sent out for Oct. 25. 
 
 
By LEON HALE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1962, when John Glenn flew around the world three times in
that Friendship 7 capsule, I was conducting a search for heroes.
Glenn showed up at exactly the right time.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted better role models for my kids. They were then 11 and
9, and the people they admired didn't seem so admirable to me.
</P>
<P>
   My son was a disciple of Mickey Mantle and some long-haired drag
racer whose name I forget. My daughter was in love with a rock 'n'
roller. Maybe he was Elvis. Along about that time I remember
reading those two words, Elvis Presley, and I thought they made up
the dumbest name ever hung on a little baby. I said then that
nobody answering to a name like that would ever amount to anything.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted my children to have solid citizens for role models.
Mickey Mantle was good about hitting home runs, sure, but his
personal life wasn't so nice. And long-haired drag racers were
disgusting to me. At that time I was much smarter than I am now,
and I was able to judge the character of people by the length of
their hair.
</P>
<P>
   Then here came John Glenn, who climbed into that little capsule
stuck on the top of a rocket and let them shoot him 162 miles high
and he whizzed around the planet for three orbits and came blazing
back into the atmosphere and landed with a glorious splash in the
Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   I told my kids, Look, here's a genuine hero for you. Forget your
beer-guzzling athletes and your hip-grinding musicians and your
greasy-headed race-car drivers. John Glenn has done something no
American has ever done, and he has risked his hide to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, I said, he has taken us across the threshold of a
new frontier. (I did a good deal of lecturing in those days, before
my children got so big I couldn't make them sit still to listen.)
He has opened up a horizon, and ushered us into the Space Age.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds cornball now, as it did to my children in '62, and
yet I still believe it.
</P>
<P>
   A great thing about Glenn was that he looked like a hero. He had
that college halfback appearance, not pretty but not ugly, either.
And he had short hair.
</P>
<P>
   Also he'd already proven he had the right stuff. A combat pilot
in two wars, with something like 150 missions.
</P>
<P>
   But to me personally, the greatest thing about Glenn was this:
He and I were almost exactly the same age. Born in '21, less than
two months apart.
</P>
<P>
   My campaign to make Glenn a hero to my children was not
successful, but he has remained heroic to me. Not as a politician
but mainly for that historic ride he took in the capsule 36 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about laying your life on the line for your country. I
doubt there's ever been full public understanding of the grave risk
Glenn was exposed to on that mission. Even now, being shot into
space on a rocket amounts to an experimental test flight, so
imagine all the unknowns that went up with Glenn in that Friendship
7 capsule.
</P>
<P>
   I've always admired the way he talked about those risks. When he
was back home safely and doing all the interviews, I remember a
reporter asking him what would have happened if the capsule's heat
shield had failed, on reentry. That was pretty close to what space
exploration reporters call a sick question.
</P>
<P>
   Come on, if the heat shield had failed, Glenn would have been
fried. But he grinned and answered like this: ``It would have been
a bad day at Black Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Man, that was Roy Rogers talking. It was just the way we want
our heroes to talk about risk and danger. We needed that then, when
we were feeling inadequate to the Russians on space exploration.
</P>
<P>
   If there's politics involved in Glenn's ticket to ride on this
Oct. 29 mission, it doesn't make an ounce of difference to me. His
going up there, when both of us are 77, is like me going along as
well.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Glenn is in better physical condition than I am. I sure
hope so. I figure the launch will be the toughest test for him,
with all those G's pressing on his brave old heart. But once he's
in orbit, why can't a 77-year-old guy float around in a weightless
environment as easy as any pink-cheek rookie?
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be a news story if this old guy performed better in
a weightless environment than the young people?
</P>
<P>
   Then finally I've decided not to be embarrassed by this thought,
which I'm unable to resist:
</P>
<P>
   What if John Glenn returned from space younger than when he
left? &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
