<SLUG> BC-STUPID-PET-TRICKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE-TRICK PONIES: `LETTERMAN' SHOW LOOKS TO HOUSTON FOR STUPID
FEATS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MIKE McDANIEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The mood wasn't right for Josie, the slow-dancing
poodle. Babe, a Jack Russell terrier dressed in Yankee pinstripes,
couldn't perform a perfect back flip. And Aman, a 14-foot python,
didn't know what to do beyond clinging closely _ very closely _ to
his owner.
</P>
<P>
   Double-jointed Matt Grantham felt sure he could crush an egg
between arms twisted wrong-side out, but a test with several Grade
A's proved eggsactly the opposite. And John Ware's chainsaw
impression sounded suspiciously similar to his small-airplane
impression.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was difficult to tell the stupid pet tricks from the
stupid human tricks at ``Late Show With David Letterman''
auditions. But it was fun trying.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Molloy's cockatoo, Zsa Zsa, provoked laughs and applause
as she flipped herself upside down and stood on her head resting on
Terry's hand. Jennifer Cooney's German shepherd, Juliet, amused as
she crawled, combat style, underneath five chairs. And Kim
Hentschel's border collie, Whisper, amazed as she did crazy-8s
through Kim's legs.
</P>
<P>
   Stupid Pet Tricks/Stupid Human Tricks coordinator Bill
Langworthy patiently watched as each of 25 tricks were performed _
or sometimes only attempted. He was in town scouting for the show.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Jenkins' dancing bird, an African gray parrot named Baker,
wouldn't boogie on cue, so Langworthy suggested they come back
later for another try.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you tried shooting M&AMP;Ms into your mouth?'' he asked of
Dante Rodriguez. Dante's ``skill'' was flipping a penny by
``popping'' his thumb, but Langworthy wanted something more. So out
Dante went in search of candy.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Kidd, Sherrie Brogdon's parrot, was singing like an
opera star out in the hall, but when it was time to enter the
studio and audition, he turned prima donna. ``Maybe if everybody
sang along,'' Sherrie suggested to the few onlookers on hand. Sure
enough, the bird responded with gusto, belting out ``Singin' in the
Rain.''
</P>
<P>
   No one, not even Langworthy, can predict who will make the show.
Those who auditioned Saturday will have to wait until a ``Late
Show'' producer reviews the tryout tape before learning if they'll
appear on one of next month's shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave likes normal people doing odd things, and he likes big
dogs, especially golden retrievers,'' Langworthy said. But weird
people and small dogs have also made it to ``Late Show.'' The only
criteria are that acts be ``safe, funny, original and of no use to
anyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Langworthy is prepared for acts to freeze up during tryouts. Of
course, if you go stiff at audition, it's not likely you'll do well
in front of a national audience of millions.
</P>
<P>
   So Rosie the rat, who failed to run an obstacle course, and
Chelsea the wirehaired dachshund, who didn't go as nuts as usual
when an ironing board was produced, should not wait by the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Dubby Perry, on the other hand, might be getting a call. Perry,
a lawyer's videographer from Lufkin, Texas, presented a feat
Langworthy said ``was nothing like I've seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry can make three empty beer cans stick to his balding pate,
then he can down a brew and add the empty to his head. It's quite a
sight to see.
</P>
<P>
   And you thought you were the one with talent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
