<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-POSTERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM POSTERS LEAP IN VALUE AMONG COLLECTORS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How much is that poster in the window?
</P>
<P>
   It may cost you nothing _ or one day it could be worth hundreds
or even thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   If it's for a film such as ``Antz,'' now playing in theaters,
you might pick one up for free by politely asking the theater
manager, or perhaps later buy it from a specialty dealer for around
$20.
</P>
<P>
   But if you'd like a classic horror or sci-fi film poster, open
your vault. Those can cost many thousands of dollars, and often are
sold only by big auction houses.
</P>
<P>
   With current films, such posters, or ``one sheets,'' are often
tossed away after a movie leaves town, or they're taken home by
theater employees. Usually they're torn or faded, anyway,
especially if they've been displayed outside.
</P>
<P>
   But if ever the adage ``Today's trash becomes tomorrow's
treasure'' holds true, it's with movie posters.
</P>
<P>
   They have become big business today, though not for today's
films. The big bucks go to decades-old movie paper items _ usually
27-by-41-inch posters or ``one sheets,'' but also photo stills,
oversize color ``lobby cards'' and other sizes of posters called
``inserts'' (14-by-36 inches) and ``three-sheets'' (41-by-81
inches).
</P>
<P>
   ``The old horror films are beyond the reach of most
collectors,'' said Gene Arnold of Houston, owner of Arnold Movie
Poster Co. His business is not a store but a mail-order outfit,
though you can call at 713-524-9000 or check out the Web site at
www.movieposters.com.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold said original posters for 1933's ``King Kong'' and 1931's
``Frankenstein'' and ``Dracula'' cost $150,000-$200,000 per poster,
``and that's if you can find them. There's probably just a handful
in existence.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for such scarcity, beyond simple age, is the fact
that posters before 1945 were recycled as part of war drives.
</P>
<P>
   Also, posters weren't widely considered collectibles until the
1960s. ``They were thrown away by carloads,'' Arnold said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, most have had a gradual rise in popularity and
price. In the last 10 years, though, many have skyrocketed as
auction-house bidding has sparked interest and publicity.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just oldies that are rising in value. Some relatively
recent films are becoming what Arnold calls ``cult classics,''
generating a fever of fan interest and ``escalating dramatically''
in price.
</P>
<P>
   Among such films he names ``Chinatown,'' ``The Sting,'' ``Cool
Hand Luke,'' ``Ocean's Eleven,'' ``The Wild Bunch,'' ``The
Magnificent Seven,'' ``Bonnie and Clyde,'' ``Lawrence of Arabia,''
``To Kill a Mockingbird,'' the ``Rocky'' films and`` Breakfast at
Tiffany's.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen years ago you could buy `Breakfast at Tiffany's' (the
poster) for $35-$50, but it's selling now for about $1,000,''
Arnold said.
</P>
<P>
   Among other recent films, obvious choices such as the hit ``Star
Wars,'' ``Star Trek,'' ``Alien''and ``Indiana Jones'' also draw
favor.
</P>
<P>
   Sci-fi and horror do especially well, Arnold said, and horror
sells all year long, not just around Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   But collectors have varied interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come from all walks of life,'' said Kathleen Connaughton,
who owns Hollywood Frame Gallery, 2431 Bissonnet, with husband
Ricky.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our clients, a computer programmer, is building a
terrific film noir collection,'' she said. ``Another is a huge
Hitchcock collector.''
</P>
<P>
   She and Arnold say more and more young people are joining the
hobby, which attracts several hundred collectors in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Many attend Stargazer, a movie poster show that's promoted here
each March by Houston collector/dealer Robert Cullen. (The next
Stargazer is March 13-14; call 713-365-0266 for information.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great market here, and we draw dealers from all over
the country,'' Cullen said.
</P>
<P>
   While many items are moderately priced, a one-sheet of
``Jailhouse Rock'' sold for $3,500 at last year's show.
</P>
<P>
   Cullen and Arnold attribute the rise in interest among young
people to vintage-movie channels such as TNT, TMC and AMC.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really stir the pot for old movies,'' Arnold said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I credit the growth in young fans 100 percent to them,''
Cullen said.
</P>
<P>
   Younger fans also buy posters for current films, like
``Titanic'' or ``Saving Private Ryan,'' Connaughton said. (The
original ``Titanic'' poster costs around $50, while reprints go for
about $20.)
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of collectors do start with the newer stuff and then get
into the older stuff as well,'' Arnold said.
</P>
<P>
   The recent ``Swingers'' was the Frame Gallery's best seller last
year, thanks to revived interest in swing music and Frank Sinatra,
Connaughton said.
</P>
<P>
   As for starting a ``serious'' collection, she advises fans to
begin with '70s movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good place for young people to go,'' Connaughton
said. ``You had `Star Wars,' `Grease,' `Jaws,' `The Godfather,'
`Rocky,' `The Exorcist,' `Chinatown' _ you can just go on and on.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Jaws'' poster is big, going for $150-$200, based on
condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jaws'' has an illustration, not a photo, and older posters had
even more artwork and stylism, produced when studios had art
departments for such work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The older posters are works of art,'' Connaughton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put the original `Touch of Evil' poster up beside the
reissue poster, and people were blown away by the original,''
Connaughton said.
</P>
<P>
   Often such art also has personal appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say you grew up loving '50s sci-fi movies. Let's say you
also appreciate a good robot. Your poster of choice? ``Forbidden
Planet'' _ what else?
</P>
<P>
   As an anniversary present, Houstonian Tom Seiler's wife bought
him an original poster from the 1956 movie, which they had fully
restored and framed. It now hangs proudly in their den.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like owning a piece of 1956,'' Seiler said. ``It's got a
classic robot on it _ Robby the Robot _ with Anne Francis in his
arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike today's photo-based posters, this one is fully
illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like owning a rather limited art print,'' Seiler said,
``and the design of the robot is special. It's a classic movie
robot. The same guy designed the `Lost in Space' robot years
later.''
</P>
<P>
   Such posters often need restoration not just due to age but
because for decades they arrived in theaters flat and folded,
leading to creases and tears. Today's posters arrive in rolls.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of specialists around the country handle restorations.
Arnold doesn't do them, though his son, Dan, restores lobby cards.
</P>
<P>
   Restorations can be expensive in themselves _ just as frames can
cost as much as the material they display. But for fans of
movie-poster art, showing off a prize is a large part of its
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Fans' interests vary widely, with some seeking certain stars
while others hunt genres such as horror, titles such as ``Gone With
the Wind,'' studios such as Disney or even subjects such as
courtrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just sold a lot of stills to a law firm in Boston that's
going to decorate its new law offices with courtroom scenes,''
Arnold said.
</P>
<P>
   But old posters are still the biggest draw. The most expensive
ever, Arnold said, was for 1932's ``The Mummy'' with Boris Karloff.
It sold in auction for almost $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``A whole new market has developed in the last 10 years,'' said
Arnold, who began trading and selling posters as a hobby in 1965
and has sold posters full-time for about a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten very competitive, and much more expensive,'' he
said. ``So many celebrities buy now that regular folks just can't
compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's still a lot of fun, and it's remarkable that
something once considered as momentary enjoyment has become such
lasting art.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
