<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LION-KINGII-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO-ONLY `LION KING' SEQUEL A ROARING SUCCESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a movie makes $772 million worldwide, wins two Oscars, and
becomes the top-selling video of all time (at 30 million), making a
sequel is a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   But the surprise of ``The Lion King II: Simba's Pride'' is that
this follow-up to 1994's ``The Lion King'' is being offered solely
on video. It arrives Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, the film will get a wide theatrical release, followed
by a video campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, video makes more sense, since ``The Lion King II''
(not rated, closed-captioned, $26.99) lacks the first film's
sweeping visual majesty and the feel of big-movie ``event.''
</P>
<P>
   As with Disney's five other video sequels to its animated hits,
the creators came from Disney's TV animation studios, in this case
in Australia, Canada and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   They deliver quality movements and characterizations yet far
less lush background detail, and soft-focus is overused.
</P>
<P>
   But in other respects this 80-minute film is top-drawer, from
its voice-actors (with many from the original) to its story (mixing
rehashes with new spins) to its superb new songs and orchestral
score.
</P>
<P>
   In a repetitious opening scene, the circle of life continues as
Simba, the lion who came of age in ``The Lion King,'' presents his
own offspring and future heir to the Pridelands he rules.
</P>
<P>
   She's Kiara, destined to lead one day as queen. But like so many
Disney princesses _ in ``Aladdin,'' ``The Little Mermaid'' and
``Pocahontas'' _ she'd rather follow her heart.
</P>
<P>
   This leads to eventful adventures in the desolate Outlands and
an unlikely friendship with Kovu, the young lion who's successor to
his wicked father, the first film's Scar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lion King II'' then plays out somewhat like ``Romeo and
Juliet,'' as the bonding cubs try to unite their warring prides.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new voice talents, Neve Campbell (``Scream'') plays
Kiara and Suzanne Pleshette is the one-dimensionally evil Zira,
Scar's widow.
</P>
<P>
   Returning are Matthew Broderick as Simba; Robert Guillaume as
baboon Rafiki; James Earl Jones as fallen king Mufasa, heard in
spirit; Nathan Lane as wise-cracking meerkat Timon; and Ernie
Sabella as clueless wart hog Pumbaa.
</P>
<P>
   The last two alone make the movie worth watching. Whenever the
story sags with sentiment, their dependable comic relief is fun and
enlivening.
</P>
<P>
   It's most needed at story's start, when the film is alarmingly
regressive.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the first movie's broad-based family appeal, this one
begins with such a cuddly, fuzzy-wuzzy, precious approach that it
merits a surgeon general's warning about insufferable sweetness.
Thankfully, this bent soon subsides as baby Kiara _ who sounds like
a mall rat _ reaches adolescence and acquires a wider worldview.
</P>
<P>
   Among the film's strong songs, ``We Are One'' is a stirring
affirmation of interspecies harmony and ecological ideals, while
``Love Will Find a Way'' is a romantic and pretty duet. (Other
performers often do the singing.)
</P>
<P>
   There's also the inevitable Busby Berkeley-style big production
number, but it's a winner. In ``Upendi,'' rhinos, zebras, ostriches
and hippos form a conga line, like some mad revival of
``Fantasia.''
</P>
<P>
   These come from several composing teams; the first film's Elton
John and Tim Rice had no input. The original's Mark Mancina again
provides arrangements, using similar African rhythms and tribal
chants.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the true circle of life is how much and how often Disney
successfully recycles its own material. But its biggest animated
hit ever has provided territory worth revisiting. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
