<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW'S A GOOD TIME TO GET IN THE GAME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   People have asked me whether it's time to get back into the
stock market after it's inflicted so much pain.
</P>
<P>
   Honest, the market is sending signals to investors who've fled
that this is a good time to step back in.
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday, the market was up seven straight days.
</P>
<P>
   Investment experts said the time is ripe to buy stocks because
major decisions by policy-makers have made stocks attractive and
stocks also are at good prices.
</P>
<P>
   However, they also said another dip in the market is possible
this month, so be picky about where you put your money and be
patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would classify this market as an early bull market in the
making,'' said Hamilton Lewis, a Houston money manager and
technical analyst, who studies stocks using trading data such as
volume and price trends to make predictions.
</P>
<P>
   When stocks fall now, the magnitude isn't as severe, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lows begin to get higher and that automatically tells you
that money is beginning to sponsor these stocks that were hit at
one time,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   A bear market is generally defined as a 20 percent drop in
stocks. Depending on who's asked, that definition sometimes is
expanded to include a drop over an extended period of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone down the stairs, we've hit the basement and we're
beginning to climb the stairs again,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Market's response encouraging &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another optimistic sign is that major decisions by policy-makers
have boosted investor confidence, said Hugh Johnson, chief
investment officer at investment firm First Albany in Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Board recently cut interest rates, and
Japanese officials have finally voted to use public funds to bail
out Japan's sick banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was really encouraging was the response of the financial
markets,'' Johnson said. ``The markets responded positively and
that's what you see at the bottom of a bear market.''
</P>
<P>
   The market is telling investors that there's good news to offset
the bad arising from the Asian financial crisis, said Henry
Lartigue, chief investment officer at Chase Bank of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's saying to investors that although Asia is part of the
equation, it is far from all of the equation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As you look at what stocks you should be investing in, keep in
mind that the last shall be first.
</P>
<P>
   Investment professionals said investors should consider putting
their money in the stocks of small and middle-sized companies
because the market's decline has beaten them up so badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been hit hard and historically when the Fed eases,
small- and midcaps do better because credit is easier and they can
grow,'' said Ed Larsen, chief equity officer at Aim Capital
Management, a mutual fund company in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the last 11 times that the Fed has cut interest
rates, a year after the rate cut, small stocks gained an average
37.8 percent, compared with an average 24.8 percent for large
stocks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
September is the cruelest month &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many investors think October is the worst month for stocks, but
it's not. It's actually September, Larsen said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, market swoons do occur in October.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, many investors sell their losing stocks to take a
tax loss they can use to offset profits.
</P>
<P>
   And money managers get rid of their losers before preparing the
year-end statements they give to clients.
</P>
<P>
   Many large stocks also are still expensive, relative to
companies' ability to deliver the earnings growth investors expect,
Larsen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're willing to pay more for a future stream of earnings
because inflation and interest rates are low,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, corporate earnings are expected on average to have
fallen about 2 percent in the third quarter, compared with the same
time last year, and they may even be flat next year, Larsen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market can't grow at the double-digit returns that it used
to have until the earnings improve,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this environment poses a classic opportunity because
you'd be investing _ ``buying low'' _ when everyone else is
pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy is to buy at the end of October declines to take
advantage of the market rally that usually follows and can last
through January.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are entering the best time to own stocks,'' Larsen said.
``All the gains in a year are made between November and March.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to pamela.yip at chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
