<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHANTASM-FILM-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK IN BLACK: ACTOR RESURRECTS `PHANTASM' CHARACTER WITH MORE
LIVES THAN A CAT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Angus Scrimm sees it, the fiendish Tall Man of ``Phantasm''
fame is simply misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always think he's like a civil servant, just doing his job _
at least in his mind,'' Scrimm said of the black-clad villain bent
on populating Earth with reanimated corpses.
</P>
<P>
   Like many horror heavies, the Tall Man is killed but returns
again and again. Similarly, Scrimm has returned to the same role
for two decades. The 6-foot-4 actor has played the Tall Man ever
since the first ``Phantasm'' made an impact in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the No. 1 hit in Paris for most of that summer,'' he
said proudly.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Don Coscarelli, ``Phantasm'' was a weird
mix of funeral homes, dimensional gateways, crawling alien fingers
leaving trails of yellow goo and flying metal spheres drilling into
brains.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Tall Man, an overly ambitious mortician, with
his minions of tiny slaves in monks' robes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantasm'' was followed by sequels from Universal in 1988 and
1994. ``Phantasm II'' had a major theatrical campaign, and
``Phantasm III: Lord of the Dead'' went straight to video.
</P>
<P>
   Working independently, Coscarelli has made a third sequel,
``Phantasm: Oblivion,'' new on video (Orion, rated R, priced for
rental).
</P>
<P>
   Scrimm isn't the only one to return. The Tall Man's good-guy
foes have also stayed the course, aging 20 years in the process.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Phantasm: Oblivion,'' Reggie Bannister and Bill Thornbury
play Reggie and Jody, as they have in each film. Michael Baldwin, a
teen in the first film, has played Mike in all but the second
picture. He's assailed by the Tall Man with the bullying cry
``Boy!''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the second film, Universal wanted a hunk (in the Mike
role) and cast James Le Gros,'' Scrimm said. ``He's the only
`Phantasm' cast member who's broken through to the semi-big time.''
</P>
<P>
   (Le Gros has made more than 40 films, including ``Singles'' and
``Born on the Fourth of July.'')
</P>
<P>
   Scrimm says job doldrums have influenced other stars' repeated
returns to the ``Phantasm'' fold. With the series' disjointed
scripts, it's certainly not the plots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always have to hold out for a little more money, but it
hasn't been difficult to get us,'' Scrimm said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet luck and loyalty also are involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``These movies are great fun to make,'' said Scrimm, 72, who has
often watched crews make yellow alien blood out of yogurt and food
coloring. ``And we all love getting back together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantasm: Oblivion'' underscores time's passage. In
flashbacks, it shows scenes shot for the first film that were never
used but are known to fans via the rumor mill. One such scene has
Mike hanging the Tall Man from a tree with a rope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through the years, that had become almost legendary because
nobody had seen it,'' Scrimm said. ``It was deleted because the
Tall Man was killed off too many times in the picture. I've lost
count how many times I've been killed over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Using such old footage enabled Coscarelli to shoot ``Phantasm:
Oblivion'' even more cheaply than usual. (His biggest budget was $3
million for ``Phantasm II.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Don had to use his own money to get it off the ground, so he
devised a script using the old footage, meaning he only had to
shoot a little over an hour of new material,'' Scrimm said. ``But
the color quality had really held up, and I think he did it rather
cleverly.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent video reissue of the original ``Phantasm'' (MGM, rated
R, $9.94) adds still more unused footage. ``It's got two or three
scenes that aren't in any other `Phantasm,' '' Scrimm said. ``They
kill the Tall Man in another way!''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Phantasm: Oblivion,'' Scrimm finally gets to show a
different aspect of his character, perhaps his true nature. In a
time-travel scene set during the Civil War, he's a kind, solicitous
inventor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing evil is great fun, but I was really pleased to show my
nice side,'' Scrimm said. ``When I appear at fan gatherings, people
often say, `You're so nice.' Then I scare them by saying, `Oh, this
is just my public persona. The Tall Man really is me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Fans can follow ``Phantasm'' films via their website at
www.phantasm.com. But Scrimm's relatives won't be joining them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few of my relatives will watch these films,'' he said. ``With
the increasing violence in average films today, I don't know why
some people still say, `I won't go see a horror film.' You see more
gore in `Saving Private Ryan.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As for the loyalists, Scrimm feels ``Phantasm's'' appeals ``are
its unique combination of horror, fantasy and science fiction and
the fact that it deals with death _ not in the slasher way, but
with the actual subject of death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Tall Man, in many respects, is the grim reaper.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
