<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9233 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOFFMANN-OPERA-REVIEW     10-27 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOFFMANN-OPERA-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVENTURES IN SINGING: MULTIPLE `TALES OF HOFFMANN' ROLES DEMAND
FLEXIBILITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CHARLES WARD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Vocally, Jacques Offenbach's opera ``The Tales of
Hoffmann'' is unusual: A few singers portray a multitude of main
characters in great tests of musical flexibility and dramatic
versatility.
</P>
<P>
   A bass-baritone presents the four villains who rob Hoffmann of
his four loves. A soprano matches that by singing each of those
loves. A mezzo-soprano plays the role of Hoffmann's friend, who
turns out to be his muse. Even servants of the villains and
protagonists in Hoffmann's sad stories are sung by the same tenor.
</P>
<P>
   Using stories by 19th-century German writer and composer E.T.A.
Hoffmann, French librettist Jules Barbier created for ``Les Contes
d'Hoffmann'' a web of revelations aimed ultimately at allowing
listeners to see Hoffmann's life from many perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   His infatuation with Olympia is slightly perverse, for she turns
out to be a doll who ultimately is destroyed. His love for the
singer Antonia is real but thwarted by her death. His liaison with
the courtesan Guilietta, whose lover Hoffmann kills, ends when she
goes off with another suitor.
</P>
<P>
   At the opera's end, Barbier lets the audience realize that the
three women are aspects of Hoffmann's current love, the opera
singer Stella. Alas, he loses her, as well.
</P>
<P>
   These multiple roles require singers with a certain
devil-may-care adventuresomeness _ especially the soprano.
</P>
<P>
   When Houston Grand Opera revives ``Hoffmann'' Friday in its
co-production with Australian Opera, audiences will hear such a
daredevil: Spanish soprano Maria Bayo, who will sing all of
Hoffmann's four loves for the first time in her career.
</P>
<P>
   Bayo will join Mexican tenor Ramon Vargas (Hoffmann), American
bass-baritone Dean Peterson (the villains) and American
mezzo-soprano Beth Clayton (Niklausse/Muse). Vjekoslav Sutej will
conduct members of the Houston Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   In person, the diminutive Bayo (pronounced BUY-oh) radiates two
images: the international opera star and the down-to-earth human
being.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I step on the stage and people want a performance of a
diva, I give it to them,'' said Bayo, whose only other American
appearances have been a Metropolitan Opera debut and New York City
recital debut last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I step off the stage, I'm a normal person,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   Her stages include Paris' Opera de la Bastille and the Vienna
State Opera, where she has sung Antonia in ``Hoffmann.'' These
days, they are typical stops, far from the place that gave her such
a sense of stability.
</P>
<P>
   She hails from a small agricultural town, Fetaro, in the
province of Navarra in northern Spain, where everyone knows almost
everything about everybody. ``Too much,'' she quipped, adding the
Spanish word for gossip.
</P>
<P>
   For one month each year she is at home in Pamplona, the
provincial capital, where she visits with friends, enjoys drives
around the Navarra countryside, and goes out to restaurants with
her husband, an instructor of Basque folk music at the University
of Navarra.
</P>
<P>
   There were no musicians in her family. Her father, who had a
vineyard and grew fruit, did have ``a beautiful tenor voice'' but
he sang only for family on social occasions. Like Luciano
Pavarotti's father, he still does _ at age 75.
</P>
<P>
   From her father, Bayo, 40, inherited both a naturally
well-developed voice and an affinity for singing. ``I feel my
passion started with the passion for music of my father,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertain about a career, she started parallel tracks of study
at the University of Navarra in Pamplona: music and preschool
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not think about studying singing, but when Edurne
Aguerri a singing professor in the school heard me, she said I had
a voice with a lot of potential.''
</P>
<P>
   She later studied in Barcelona, and finally at a
``Musikhochschule'' in Germany. Her preparation was finished in
1988, when she won first prize in Vienna's Belvedere Competition,
one of the most important singing contests in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Her Bastille debut occurred in 1991, when she sang Susanna in
W.A. Mozart's ``The Marriage of Figaro.'' It was the culmination of
her breakout into international opera that year, she said. ``El
finito'' _ the final step.
</P>
<P>
   The list of conductors she has worked with contains many
important names: Claudio Scimone, Riccardo Chailly, Michel Plasson,
Giuseppe Sinopoli, Sir Colin Davis and, for Baroque operas, Rene
Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   Her repertoire includes the standard works and
less-often-performed ones such as George Handel's ``Julius
Caesar,'' Vincenzo Bellini's ``I Capuleti et i Montecchi'' and
Claude Debussy's ``Pelleas et Melisande.'' She proudly sings
``zarzuelas,'' the unique Spanish form of light opera.
</P>
<P>
   As her voice matures, becoming a little heavier and darker, she
is beginning to sing more dramatic roles. Next season, she makes
her San Francisco debut as Mimi in Giacomo Puccini's ``La boheme,''
moving on from the more coloratura role of Musetta. She also
performs Liu in Puccini's ``Turandot'' for the first time, at the
gala reopening of the Liceo Opera House in Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
   The most telling testament to Bayo's gifts is her friendship
with the great Spanish mezzo-soprano Teresa Berganza, who lives
north of Madrid. Berganza has become both an adviser and friend,
Bayo said.
</P>
<P>
   She met Berganza through friends soon after her career began to
explode. She went to the mezzo's home and sang. ``From that moment
on, we've been friends,'' Bayo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to have two or three persons who can help
you to maintain your focus,'' she said. Berganza has done that
through insights gleaned from her own international singing career.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the advice would seem predictable: Never force herself
to sing, never sing a role that doesn't fit her voice. Other
nuggets might not be so obvious: Never give every last ounce of
herself in a performance, for maintaining a reserve can keep the
performance from seeming nearly out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most of all, Berganza reinforced that natural instinct
Bayo inherited from her father. The mezzo said: Be true to
yourself. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
