<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-AGING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTRONAUT GLENN BECOMES A SYMBOL OF `SUCCESSFUL AGING' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The remarkable thing about John Glenn's
impending shuttle ride into space is that it's not remarkable at
all, according to some specialists in aging and a few people who
are older than America's septuagenarian astronaut.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, the 77-year-old senator from Ohio, is scheduled to return
to space on Thursday along with six other crew members of the
shuttle Discovery. It was 36 years ago that Glenn, riding a
telephone booth-sized Mercury capsule atop a thundering rocket,
became the first American to orbit the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have called the shuttle mission a publicity stunt. NASA
retorts that Glenn, who is retiring from the Senate this year, will
participate in valuable experiments on aging.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should his age be considered a deterrent to space travel.
Indeed, that is a misconception that stems from antiquated ideas
about growing older, said Bill Haigwood of the Buck Center for
Research on Aging in Novato, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an image about what old people should and shouldn't
be, and it derives from a time when people didn't live to the age
they do today,'' he said. ``Sometimes people in their 60s and 70s
who have taken good care of themselves are in better condition than
people in their 30s and 40s who have not.''
</P>
<P>
   Paola Timiras, 75, grasps that notion clearly. She is a
professor emeritus at the University of California at Berkeley who
maintains a full teaching and research schedule, and regularly
travels to professional conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Her specialty is the biological aspects of aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is very good for Mr. Glenn to go,'' she said. ``It
makes sense for someone who has dedicated part of his life to that.
That's why I'm still working here at the university _ because I
like to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Glenn was typical of many older Americans who were
maintaining their fitness levels in later years. ``The fact that he
is in good health represents the trend in prolonging life span,
which has been characteristic of this century,'' Timiras said.
</P>
<P>
   She calls it ``successful aging.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Glenn, ``He's just a kid,'' said Bill Godward, 85, after
arriving in his downtown San Francisco law office still aglow from
a morning workout at the gym.
</P>
<P>
   Godward travels each day from his San Francisco home to the
downtown office of Cooper Godward law firm and logs a full day of
work. ``I'm a trustee of a lot of trusts,'' he said. ``I've
outlived all my clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Godward, who joined the firm in 1941, said he had never
seriously contemplated retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in my 30s, I used to commute with a guy who could
hardly wait to turn 60 and retire,'' he recalled. ``I thought:
`What an awful life. Why doesn't he do something else?'''
</P>
<P>
   Should Glenn subject himself to the rigors of launch and
recovery?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' Godward said. ``You should do what you want to
do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
