<P>
   &UR; DINING &LR;  (``d'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-HAMBURGERS (Houston) _ What the croissant is to France,
what goulash is to Hungary, what pickled herring is to Sweden, the
hamburger is to Texas. It's a symbol, a necessity, and a triumph, a
part of the cultural patrimony so tightly woven into the fabric of
Texas life that Texans themselves do not even remark on it until
they are presented with the gray-tinged, underfurnished,
suspiciously geometric hamburger that the rest of America lives
with. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   HAMBURGER-HOW (Undated) _ Like so many other culinary pursuits,
making a hamburger that approaches the Platonic ideal means
starting from scratch: the juiciest, most flavorful burgers begin
with meat that you grind yourself. By John Willoughby.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-BLANC-CHEF (Milton, England) _ At 48, Raymond Blanc is
one of Britain's most honored chefs; sybarites from a dozen
countries beat a path to the door of Le Manoir aux Quat' Saisons,
his luscious, recently expanded and renovated country-house hotel
near Oxford. But he started neither at 15 nor in the kitchen. He
started at 21 as a commis debrasseur _ an apprentice busboy, a
waiter-in-waiting, clearing tables. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-9TH-AVE-FOOD (New York) _ Walking home from the green grocer
along Ninth Avenue, I pass from a sliver of Korea to outposts of
Pakistan, Thailand, Senegal, Sweden, Jamaica and Puerto Rico in six
blocks. Having lived in Hells Kitchen for 15 years, I've learned to
measure the world in mere steps. I've also also learned to stop and
smell the cooking. Despite the creeping Soho-ization of west
midtown Manhattan, there is no other street in the world that has
as much diversity in its ethnic fare. By Molly O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ Every prominent winemaker has one creation
of which he or she is particularly proud. Robert Mondavi has his
Reserve Cabernet, Francis Ford Coppola his Rubicon. And Bob
Trinchero has white zinfandel, America's most popular style of
wine. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TASTINGS (Undated) _ A capsule review: Martinez Bujanda
Grand Reserva 1990, Rioja, Spain. About $26.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Pasta with butternut
squash. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With Recipe.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ The column: Coco mamie.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   HALLOWEEN-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Florence Fabricant reviews
``Halloween Treats.''
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   YOGURT-EATING-WELL (Undated) _ The column: Tasting nonfat
yogurts. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-NOTES (Undated) _ News and notes on food and dining. By
Florence Fabricant.
</P>
