<P>
   Sports stories in sight at this hour from The New York Times
News Service for  &UR; WEDNESDAY &LR; , Oct. 28.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-ATLANTA-YOUTH (Atlanta) _ The PGA Tour comes to East Lake
for its Tour Championship, the last official event of the year. The
renovation of the course in the mid-1990s became the centerpiece
for revitalizing the neighborhood surrounding the course. That
revitilization includes new housing for both low-income and
middle-income families, a golf academy for neighborhood children
and, it is hoped, a new local YMCA. By Clifton Brown.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on
Bruce Arena, the latest U.S. soccer coach. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on the
NBA lockout. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NBA-LABOR (New York) _ Developments in the NBA lockout. Both
sides are now finally engaged in serious talks, but whether
progress is being made depends on whom you talk to. Meanwhile, the
league is preparing to cancel another round of regular-season
games. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-CONE (New York) _ David Cone has until Wednesday to
decide whether to accept a $5.5 million contract option for 1999.
If he accepts, he's a Yankee. If he doesn't, he becomes a free
agent. By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NFL-OWNERS (Kansas City) _ Doings at the NFL ownership
meetings, with Los Angeles and Houston bidding to become the 32d
team in the league. By Thomas George.
</P>
