<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9327 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIA-REBOUND-BOS &LR;      10-27 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-REBOUND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIA FELL FIRST, AND IT MAY LEAD THE RECOVERY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Asia's economic meltdown that began last year was
the first domino in a worldwide tumble in emerging markets that
fueled fears of recession from Frankfurt to New York. But it is
also Asia that many economists now believe will lead the way to
global recovery.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 15 months, currencies, stocks, and growth have
tanked across this once fast-growing region, bringing unemployment,
bankruptcy, and hunger for tens of millions of people across a
continent that is home to 60 percent of the world's population.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last few weeks _ almost as quickly as the Asian
crisis began with the crash of the Thai currency on July 2, 1997 _
confidence has started to rebound here as Asian shares and
currencies have rallied, with investors bringing money back into a
region that was seen as poisonous just a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts attribute the Asian stock pickup to last week's cut in
US interest rates and passage of a bank bailout in Japan, the
region's largest economy. And many are eager to view October's good
news as a portent of the bottoming-out of the regional crisis and
the start of a recovery cycle.
</P>
<P>
   But others who have watched sky-high share values and the
world's highest growth rates go up in smoke over the last year
remain skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   The danger of a rushed recovery is that reforms of conditions
that brought on the Asian crash _ cozy relations between government
and business, staggering levels of debt, lax lending practices, and
an inflated property market _ might now fall by the wayside. What's
more, pressure on Asian governments to spend their way into
recovery could bring short-term gain at the cost of long-range
deficits and shortfalls in monies needed for bailouts.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Duhamel, chief executive of Boston-based State Street
Globe Asset Management in Hong Kong, explains: ``Asia has been hit
tremendously in the last year, so relative to the rest of the
world, it's starting to look better.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that the latest rally is hardly proof that Asia's
tiger economies are about to land on their feet. To the contrary,
he said, ``I would call this `dead cat bounce.'''
</P>
<P>
   The image of a spike in Asian share values before markets settle
down to previous lows is a frightening one. But it is one supported
by the fact that the ``fundamentals'' of regional economies _ the
strength of banks, ease of raising capital, diversity of business
opportunities, levels of education _ haven't changed in three
weeks. Yet somehow, the mood has. The larger question for Asia is
whether this month's rally is sustainable, and whether it deserves
to be sustained if serious reforms have not yet been achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Since Oct. 1, the Indonesian rupiah _ Asia's worst-battered
currency, which has shed 80 percent of its value against the dollar
since last summer _ recovered 43 percent as of Friday. The
long-suffering Japanese yen has picked up 14 percent. Hong Kong's
stock index _ so shaky two months ago that the local government
intervened to buy $13 billion in shares _ hit a five-month high
yesterday, up 30 percent so far this month. Tokyo's Nikkei index,
which on Oct. 8 hit a 13-year low, was up 7.2 percent this month as
of yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Even the International Monetary Fund, which for the last year
has meted out harsh words and tough medicine with its rescue
packages, this week declared Indonesia's decline ``bottoming out''
and praised its reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Economist Jeffrey Sachs, director of the Harvard Institute for
International Development, recently told a World Economic Forum
conference in Singapore that the worst of the Asian crisis was
probably over, but cautioned that dangers remain in North and South
America. Fear of that contagion effect is probably what spurred the
US Federal Reserve Board's surprise 0.25 percent cut in interest
rates last week, a move that boosted Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
   The rate cut helped loosen credit to spur investment, encourage
the buying of shares, and halt the ``feedback effect'' from the
Asian crisis onto the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Verin, head of Asian equity trading for Credit Suisse
First Boston, said that because ``Asia was first into the problem,
people think it'll be the first out. I think that's a little
naive.'' The rise in Hong Kong's Hang Seng stock index of nearly
2,000 points in a week earlier this month was ``unbelievable,'' he
said. ``A week before you couldn't give that stock away.''
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts believe Asia may be bottoming out, but Guonan Ma,
regional economist for Salomon Smith Barney, cautioned that ``it's
one thing to bottom out and another to recover. ... There is a way
to go before meaningful recovery'' _ something he and many others
forecast for the second half of next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian crisis began last July with the collapse of
currencies, massive debt default, bank system collapse, and the
halting of growth. Duhamel says Asia has probably proceeded now to
a second stage, with the stabilization of currencies, the easing of
interest rates, and the beginning of bank bailouts. But the region
is far from the crucial third stage: a return in domestic demand, a
crash in real interest rates, a rise in inflation to encourage
consumer spending, and a rise in corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Lingle, author of ``The Rise and Decline of the
Asian Century,'' warns that interest rate cuts could have an
unwanted negative effect. Artificially low interest rates allowed
free-flowing credit that fed ``bad investment choices'' and
overheated economies that precipitated the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   One danger is that Asia will try to stimulate domestic demand
solely through interest-rate cuts and government spending. For a
healthy and sustainable recovery, countries would have to
restructure ailing banks and eliminate bad investment and lending
practices that brought on the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence of reform so far is not terribly convincing. Japan
has taken the better part of a decade since its economy slumped to
come up with a bank reform package and has yet to stimulate
domestic demand to the extent many think is necessary. Malaysia
imposed capital controls to keep out speculators rather than deal
with internal weaknesses. Cartels and nepotism remain in Indonesia.
Many trumpeted reforms to China's state sector have been put on
hold because of unemployment worries. In Thailand, not one of 353
companies identified for debt restructuring last summer has yet
sealed a deal.
</P>
<P>
   And yet Thailand _ the first to fall into crisis and the first
to genuinely embrace IMF bailout conditions _ is seen by many as
likely to be the first to emerge. Also praised is South Korea, seen
as having looked inward for ways to restructure rather than
postpone reform or blame outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL END)
</P>
<P>
   One indicator of how well an economy is recovering is occupancy
in hotels that serve business travelers. Joanne Watkins, director
of communications for Shangri-La, the largest Asia-based hotel
chain, says occupancy is sharply up in the hotel's Bangkok
property, while it is weak in Kuala Lumpur and Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers warn that because of volatility and sudden liquidity in
Asian markets, next week could bring a reverse of the recent gains.
``As much as the downside was too extreme,'' Duhamel said, ``this
upside is too extreme also.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
