<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL CURRENTS ARE SHIFTING ALONG THE OHIO RIVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HENDERSON, Ky. _ You could call the Ohio River the boulevard of
divided government, a crooked, meandering waterway that nature sent
west and south from what is now Pittsburgh into the Mississippi at
Cairo, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The Mississippi may have won the literary battle, and Vicksburg
and New Orleans cinched its central role in the Civil War, but it
is to the Ohio that the eyes of politicians have turned in this
decade of change marked by the contradictory successes of Bill
Clinton and Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   The president's famous postconvention bus tour with running mate
Al Gore in 1992 followed the Ohio closely, and for reasons that
involved a great deal more than the pictures. In the end, largely
because of his ability to run strong outside the large, Northern
cities and especially in the areas near the river, Clinton took
five of the six states that touch it. Both times, Pennsylvania,
West Virginia, Ohio, Kentucky, and Illinois supplied him with 79
electoral votes, and he forced George Bush and Bob Dole to spend
money to hold Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   But these same states have four of the Republicans' 32
governors, and the Gingrich revolution swept through the region
four years ago, toppling incumbents and winning open House seats,
all but one of which were held in 1996. The Senate seats are among
the most closely contested in the country, with the current lineup
of seven Democrats and five Republicans almost certain to change.
Three of the Republicans' best chances for gains are in Kentucky,
Ohio, and Illinois. And the Democrats are counting on former
governor Evan Bayh to get a seat in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky _ where Wendell Ford, a Democratic senator for 24 yers,
is retiring _ is pivotal. It is also an excellent example of how
the results next week will hinge on local factors and personality,
not grand concepts of government. The current, slight edge to
replace Ford goes to GOP Representative Jim Bunning _ a mean,
ornery man, as mean and ornery as when the Hall of Fame pitcher was
throwing sidearm for the Phillies and the Tiger in the '50s and
'60s. Bunning, whose district is by the river in East Kentucky, was
near this quiet river town the other day snarling at the press and
even at questioners in his audience.
</P>
<P>
   Bunning's campaign _ rolling in money largely because of his
big-bucks sponsor, Senator Mitch McConnell, who also runs the
national Republican Senate effort _ has flooded the state's
airwaves with ads. His opponent, Democratic Representative Scotty
Baesler, whose district is in central Kentucky, is hanging very
close but is still underfunded. Down the stretch, however, Bunning
and his ads have become the issue.
</P>
<P>
   At first, most people laughed when Bunning put up a commercial
showing Beasler wildly haranguing a get-out-the-vote revival to the
strains of Wagner's ``Ride of the Valkyries.'' But lately,
questions of taste as well as nativism have arisen. And those
questions became much louder over the weekend when Bunning began
attacking Baesler for supporting free trade agreements, using
Mexican and Chinese voices to make a point normally associated with
labor Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Bunning-Baesler battle is also significant because it has
put each of their House seats in serious play. Ironically, though
both contests are close, the slight edge goes to the Democrats,
though the main issue in Bunning's district appears to be the
falsely embellished military record of the Republican in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky, however, is Exhibit A in the dramatic Republican
realignment that occured in House districts along the river in the
'90s. When the decade began, Republicans held but two of the 16
congressional districts that touch the Ohio. Now they have seven,
and the question is how many more they will get. What's more, five
of the nine seats the Democrats hold are in western Pennsylvania
and West Virginia, where it is still barely legal to be a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The trend began with Bunning, who won an open seat in 1986 when
a veteran Democrat, Gene Snyder, retired. In the '94 earthquake,
Republicans won this district and the one next door to the East
when another longtime Democratic stalwart, William Natcher,
announced his retirement and then died; and they got the
historically Democratic Louisville area in '96. Four more seats
went Republican in southern Ohio in '94, from Cincinnati east to
Marietta, and the Democrats got only one of them back in '96 and
are in a too-close-to-call fight to keep that one this year.
</P>
<P>
   In southern Illinois, the two river districts have been
represented by conservative Democrats. In the southwest,
Representative Jerry Costello has had to struggle to keep a lead,
but the Republicans may have a shot at the seat vacated by
Representative Glenn Poshard, a nominee for governor.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for the heavily rural Indiana seat from which
Democratic foreign policy guru Lee Hamilton is retiring. And the
Democrats are at best 50-50 in trying again to unseat '94 freshman
John Hostettler just across the river from here, who runs to the
right of Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the muddled, close national picture, the Republicans
(best case) could net two seats more out of the region and become
the River Majority; or, somewhat less likely, the Democrats (best
case) could net two themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, though, Clinton carried fully 13 of these 16
districts. The economy that worked for him is less of a factor
today. Local issues and personalities are what matters, along with
the spread of suburbs and the rapid rise of the right along the
river.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist based in Washington.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
