<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARE AND FEEDING OF PET PEEVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I typed the words ``pet peeve'' in last week's column, I
realized that this  &UR;  &LR; overworked phrase has become one of mine.
There was no quick way around it, though, so I gritted my teeth and
wrote on. And a few days later, I got an e-mail response from
reader Jim Langell that made my stylistic sacrifice worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``When were all the peeves domesticated?'' he asked. ``They are
always `pets.' Are there no peeves running wild or at least kept
outside with the rest of the livestock?''
</P>
<P>
   He probably didn't expect an answer, but in fact there is one:
The peeve is an American breed, created here around the turn of the
century by ``back formation'' from the much older peevish
(``querulous, irritable; exhibiting petty vexation''). Almost
immediately, people made pets of their favorite peeves; a 1919
jargon dictionary defines pet peeve as ``the thing that provokes
you the most.''
</P>
<P>
   (Both halves of the phrase, as it happens, sneaked into the
language by a secret route: ``derivation unknown,'' says the OED of
both pet and peevish. The same is true of pet in the sense of
``huff'' _ ``She went back to the house in a pet'' _ though it
seems to be unrelated to the animal pet.)
</P>
<P>
   To earn its status, of course,the pet peeve has to hang around
and bother its owner, like a cat that can't decide whether it wants
to come in or go out. (The cat is ``it'' because it's a
hypothetical, nameless cat; Spike or Rose, real cats of my
acquaintance, would be called ``who,'' just like people.) Passing
peeves are just moments of irritation; the pet ones need to be
cosseted and fed in order to live a long and fruitfully annoying
life.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, why would anyone who enjoys language want to
keep such a pet? You may be a cat person or a dog person or a bird
person, but does anyone want to be thought of as a peeve person _
someone who walks this temperamental pet around town, letting it
bore and bother everyone it meets?
</P>
<P>
   Editors can't help themselves, of course; Language peevishness
is an occupational hazard. In hopes of achieving consistency,
newspapers and book publishers adopt a ``house style'' _ ruling on
whether it's ambience or ambiance or there's a hyphen in babysitter
_ and sometimes such arbitrary choices settle into institutional
habits and finally into ``rules,'' however dubious their origins.
(One widespread newsroom rule _ a ban on using over to mean more
than _ began as the unexplained dictum of a 19th-century newspaper
editor. Many others, like the rules against splitting infinitives
and ending sentences with prepositions, were invented by early
usage arbiters who thought that maybe, if they legislated carefully
and thoroughly, they could tidy up English into something more neat
and Latinate.)
</P>
<P>
   But for the ordinary citizen, too much awareness of such things
can be a burden. A peeve is a critter that snaps and scratches, not
something warm and furry to curl up with. Renaming it is not good
enough: What we need to do is reduce the peeve population, and
spend our time with more rewarding companions.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one suggestion: Many a pet peeve can be defanged by close
study of its origins. Go to the library and check out the past of
your most treasured language peeves. Some, you will find, are not
really ``wrong'' at all, or have become standard English since you
went to school.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have like what you learn: Nobody will force you to use
``hopefully'' as a sentence adverb, any more than you have to get
your nose pierced. But the more history you learn, the less you're
likely to feel that the end is near, that our doom is come upon us,
languagewise. Yes, there are real mistakes, and it's OK to notice
them, but they're just mistakes, like wearing unmatched socks _
they're not proof that civilization is in decline. Some of them
will one day be acceptable, even fashionable (and maybe you will
get your nose pierced); others will die in obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Most language peeves, though, turn out to be less absolutely
``wrong'' _ and far more interesting _ than their owners suspect.
Find out why try and find it is arguably as respectable as try to!
Explore the surprising history of dived and dove! A collection of
former peeves, now well groomed and obedient, will be much more
entertaining than they were as mere vexations.
</P>
<P>
   This new and improved animal deserves a new, more cheerful name,
as well. Until something better comes along, I'm calling it the pet
un-peeve _ or PUP, for short. Who wouldn't trade those tired old
peeves for some linguistic puppy love?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
