<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9348 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLAVERY-POPULAR-CULTU     10-27 1510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAVERY-POPULAR-CULTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBRACING THE GHOSTS OF SLAVERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a nation so in love with its history, America has never
quite known what to do about slavery.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a dozen or so decades since the ``peculiar
institution'' bent and nearly broke the back of this nation, nearly
136 years since hundreds of thousands of blacks tasted the freedom
denied them by the architects of American independence nearly 90
years before.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, slavery remains America's sorrow song, its melancholy
refrain a haunting echo in our relentless racial discord. It is a
wound still raw and tender, a scar that cannot fade if only because
many Americans, both black and white, have chosen to ignore it
rather than tend to its bitter, painful core.
</P>
<P>
   All the slaves are dead, and we do not have their voices to
remind us of their lives before emancipation. Yet during the past
year, whether by design or coincidence, several high-profile films,
books, and television programs have offered varied examinations of
slavery. Among the notables are the long-awaited screen adaptation
of Toni Morrison's Pulitzer Prize-winning novel, ``Beloved,'' and
the six-hour PBS documentary, ``Africans in America: America's
Journey Through Slavery,'' which concluded last week. Also on PBS
and concluding yesterday was Masterpiece Theatre's two-part ``A
Respectable Trade,'' which dramatized England's role in the
trans-Atlantic slave trade.
</P>
<P>
   Not since ``Roots'' _ the award-winning television miniseries,
and the Alex Haley bestseller on which it was based _ made Kunta
Kinte a household name in 1977 has slavery so permeated the
national consciousness through popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is fortuitous the way these things happen, but I
think there's probably something larger going on,'' said Ira
Berlin, a history professor at the University of Maryland and one
of the nation's foremost scholars on slavery. Berlin has two
worthwhile books released in recent weeks: ``Many Thousands Gone,''
a history of the first two centuries of slavery in North America,
and ``Remembering Slavery,'' in which he, along with Marc Favreau
and Steven F. Miller, compiled interviews conducted in the 1930s
and 1940s with former slaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably has to do with an attempt to wrestle with the
question of race, and an understanding that somehow, if you're
going to come to terms with race, you've got to address slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   During the civil rights movement of the 1960s and early 1970s,
attention was refocused on slave life and antebellum America,
especially through the works of scholars such as John W.
Blassingame. Whereas heightened black consciousness nudged the
issue toward the forefront then, some believe events such as the
Rodney King beating in 1991, the 1992 Los Angeles riots, the O.J.
Simpson trial, and, earlier this year, the racially motivated
dragging death of James Byrd Jr., a black man in Jasper, Texas,
served to highlight the chasm between the races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Race is a pervasive and perennial question, and it's not
something we've dealt with particularly well,'' Berlin said. ``So,
we see these periods when people try to grapple with it, and one of
the outcroppings of that attempt to address it is an attempt to
understand something about its origins.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Beloved,'' one of the year's most anticipated films, stars
Oprah Winfrey and Danny Glover as former slaves trying to make a
life in post-Civil War Ohio, but still in the thrall of slavery's
lingering horrors. It's the second major film in less than a year
to deal with slavery. In December, Steven Spielberg unveiled
``Amistad,'' his retelling of an 1839 slave-ship revolt. That film
is available on video and pay-per-view.
</P>
<P>
   Slipping into theaters on the same day as ``Beloved'' but with
far less fanfare was ``Shadrach.'' John Franklin Sawyer plays
Shadrach, a 99-year-old former slave who returns to the Virginia
plantation of his birth to die, in the film, which stars Harvey
Keitel and Andie MacDowell.
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary literature is also part of the move toward
analyzing slavery and its legacy. ``Shadrach'' is based on a short
story by William Styron, who also wrote ``The Confessions of Nat
Turner.'' One of the most acclaimed books of the year is Russell
Banks's ``Cloudsplitter,'' a historical novel about the life of
John Brown, the Connecticut-born abolitionist and martyr who
believed himself an instrument of the Lord whose mission was to
eradicate slavery by any means necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Among this year's nonfiction finalists for the National Book
Award are ``Slaves in the Family,'' Edward Ball's provocative
dissection of his own family's history as slave owners, and the
descendants of slaves he now counts among his kin; and Henry
Mayer's ``All on Fire: William Lloyd Garrison and the Abolition of
American Slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all of the historical explorations are so
serious-minded or reverent. Perhaps the most controversial (not to
mention unfunny) TV shows of the new season is ``The Secret Diary
of Desmond Pfeiffer,'' a UPN entry featuring the life of an
African-English butler at the White House, which is occupied by a
libidinous Abraham Lincoln. The NAACP has accused the program of
trivializing slavery for cheap laughs. UPN has temporarily pulled
``Desmond Pfeiffer'' until after the November sweeps. A network
spokesman said the show has not been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   The writers and producers of ``The Secret Diary of Desmond
Pfeiffer'' may have viewed comedy as a spoonful of sugar to help
the bitter medicine of slavery go down. Wrongheaded, perhaps, but
it speaks to the difficulty many have in dealing with the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a language to talk about slavery. It's a subject
of enormous reticence; people are afraid they're going to embarrass
themselves, they're afraid they're going to reveal something about
themselves, whether it's ignorance or anger or stupidity, or
something which will be construed as racist,'' Berlin said. ``It's
a very difficult subject for people, and that they're groping at
what is a very difficult and sensitive subject is a probably a
healthy sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Turner, author and director of African-American and
African studies at the University of California at Davis, said
attention to slavery is evidence of ``people trying to grasp these
issues, and to grasp this episode.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oprah sounds so sincere when she talks about wanting audiences
to understand the horrors of slavery, and what it could drive a
woman to do,'' she said. ``People are eager to present that; now
whether audiences are yet ready to embrace it is another
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Many believed ``Amistad'' would be a critical and commercial hit
for Speilberg on the level of his 1993 Holocaust opus,
``Schindler's List.'' The positive reviews were there, but the
audiences were not. For its opening last week, ``Beloved'' came in
fifth, behind such unchallenging fare as ``Practical Magic,'' and
``Bride of Chucky.'' ``Beloved'' was showing in fewer theaters and
had a higher per-screen average, but most expected the film to
garner more than the $8.1 million it did. Last weekend, the film
dropped to seventh, and earned $4.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of American culture right now across the board moves
away from serious issues,'' Turner said, ``and race and slavery are
serious issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Complicating any presentation of slavery, whether as a book or
film, are the extreme feelings of discomfort they raise for both
whites and African-Americans. Some blacks shy away from films
detailing their oppression and victimization, while some whites
shun movies that lay blame for this nation's racial problems on
their doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think they know what they're going to see when they see
a movie about slavery,'' said Turner, who also taught at the
University of Massachusetts-Boston. ``Whites have often told me
they feel like when the subject of slavery comes up, there's an
implicit blame of them, that they're somehow connected to the
enslavers of the 19th century, and that makes them feel bad. So,
they don't read the books and they don't go to the movies. ``You
can watch a movie like `Schindler's List' and not have to ever
worry about being associated with being a Nazi,'' she said.
``Whereas some people might feel if you are white, you can't go to
a movie like `Amistad' and not be associated with the institution
of slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   Such attitudes, Berlin said, have reflected a kind of ``moral or
historical immaturity.'' Yet the current trend may portend a long
overdue ``willingness to talk about things which have been denied
or are unspeakable,'' although the result of such remains to be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it'll end up doing anything in a positive way;
it may, in fact, make things worse,'' Berlin said. ``It cuts all
kinds of ways with people being embarrassed by slavery, being
shamed by slavery, being afraid that someone is going to present
them with a kind of moral bill for this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
