<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9358 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-PRESS-BOS &LR;      10-27 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEPRESSING DIAGNOSIS FOR THE NEWS MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHAT THE PEOPLE KNOW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Freedom and the Press &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Reeves &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University Press, 128 pp., $19.95 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, nearly everyone from Washington Post media
critic Howard Kurtz to former U.S. News &AMP; World Report editor James
Fallows has written a book offering a foul-smelling tour of the
journalistic sausage factory, revealing how gossip, spin, and
speculation have become crucial ingredients of the news. To the
swelling ranks of the journalism Jeremiahs, add the name of Richard
Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, a former New York Timesman and noted columnist, author,
and academic, is the latest to wax bearish on the news media in
``What the People Know: Freedom and the Press,'' a book based on a
lecture Reeves delivered at the Library of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, reading ``What the People Know'' is a little like
going to your doctor and listening to a half-hour description of
complicated diagnoses before hearing the fateful words: ``You've
got six months to live.'' There is no mistaking Reeves's pessimism
throughout the book, but one can always turn straight to his last
chapter to learn the prognosis. ``Were it a person, journalism
would be diagnosed as depressed,'' he writes. ``Changes in
technology and ownership, declining public interest, low morale
among reporters losing faith in their own journals and broadcasts,
and impaired public trust seem to have put the press on the wrong
side of history, at least for the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, ``What the People Know'' avoids the perils of
droning pendantry. It is fast-moving and full of history and
anecdotes. (Once in a while, the anecdotes are less than
revelatory, as in a pointless recollection by the author of
badgering a Newark cop about a cat in a tree during his cub
reporter days.)
</P>
<P>
   Reeves wisely spends much of his energy focusing on the kind of
corporate corruption of journalism that has not really permeated
the consciousness of an American public willing to believe every
conspiracy theory about the media except the most dangerous one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American press is tougher on government than on business
for obvious reasons that should be regularly repeated,'' he notes.
``Corporations own newspapers and television stations, government
does not.''
</P>
<P>
   The book skewers Los Angeles Times publisher and Times Mirror
CEO Mark Willes, the former General Mills executive who came to be
called ``The Cereal Killer'' as he shuttered papers, slashed jobs,
and knocked down the wall between business and editorial functions
while carving out a reputation as the savior of the Times-Mirror
stock price. By tempering some of his more flammable
pronouncements, Willes has learned how to soften the tough press
coverage that greeted his ascension to publisher last year. But he
gets no such reprieve from Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   To push his point, the author compiles a list of top editors _
The Philadelphia Inquirer's Eugene Roberts, Bill Kovach of the
Atlanta Journal and Constitution, and Shelby Coffee III of The Los
Angeles Times _ who have ``fallen or been pushed out, basically for
insubordination in the face of fiscal managers.'' In fact, Reeves
gets so disconsolate that he wonders whether journalism won't
ultimately be forced to find a safe haven from the bean counters in
the world of nonprofit foundations and educational institutions, a
scenario so gloomy even he tends to discount it.
</P>
<P>
   The book's next most important argument is that journalism's
post-Watergate assault on government came with a price. ``We took
down politicians and politics, without pausing to think that maybe
we would go down with them, like mating eagles falling from the sky
with their claws locked together,'' Reeves writes. And now (to vary
the avian imagery) the chickens have come home to roost. Having
labored tirelessly to convince citizens that Washington is
incompetent and irrelevant, journalists seem stunned that the
country isn't nearly as fixated on an inside-the-Beltway sex
scandal as they are.
</P>
<P>
   Considerably less compelling is Reeves's attention to a series
of oft-heard laments about modern journalism: the turning of
reporters into celebrities; the degradation of television news; and
the journalistic shortcuts encouraged by the sheer speed of modern
media technology.
</P>
<P>
   And what's most depressing about the book are Reeves's attempts
to prescribe relief for the news business. ``A little less polling
and `Gotcha!' and a little more judgment and perspective.'' ``Be
common scolds.'' (He even says ``It's a dirty job but somebody has
to do it.'')
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds like a halftime pep talk given by the coach of a
football team losing by four touchdowns. Maybe journalism really is
in the dire straits that Reeves suggests it is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 1503EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
