<HEADLINE>
GOP SENATE CANDIDATE SAYS HE'LL PUSH FOR GAY RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LANCE WILLIAMS and ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Matt Fong, who donated $50,000 to an
anti-homosexual group this year, has told gay Republicans that if
he is elected to the U.S. Senate, he would work to pass a wide
range of gay-rights laws.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to cool the controversy over his donation to the
Traditional Values Coalition, Fong vowed Monday to support a list
of federal gay-rights laws, including measures to protect gays from
job discrimination and hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The promise, made in writing, persuaded the Log Cabin Club not
to withdraw its endorsement of Fong, who is in a tight race with
the incumbent Democrat, Barbara Boxer. The Log Cabin Club is a
national group of Republicans who are gay.
</P>
<P>
   Fong's effort came as Boxer ratcheted up her criticism of the
donation, which she linked to the recent beating death of a
homosexual student in Wyoming and the shooting death of an abortion
doctor in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a hate group. You write a check to a hate group, you
are making a statement,'' Boxer told a news conference Monday night
with National Organization for Women President Patricia Ireland and
other women leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Examiner reported Sunday that Fong had donated
$50,000 in campaign funds to the Orange County-based Traditional
Values Coalition, which is headed by the Rev. Lou Sheldon.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon is a conservative Presbyterian minister who has likened
abortion to murder and once advocated quarantining people with AIDS
in ``cities of refuge'' to prevent the spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon also spearheaded a campaign in the Senate to scuttle the
nomination of James Hormel, a gay philanthropist from San
Francisco, as ambassador to Luxembourg. Sheldon argued Hormel's
appointment would advance what he styles as an immoral ``homosexual
agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay Republicans privately had been lobbying the Log Cabin Club
to renounce Fong for the donation to Sheldon, who said he had used
it to fund a poll on a proposed state ban on gay marriages. But
after extracting the written commitment from Fong, the group
decided to stand firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are opposed to everything Lou Sheldon and the Traditional
Values Coalition stand for,'' Richard Tafel, executive director of
the Log Cabin Club, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said the Republican Senate candidate had ``as good
or better position on gay and AIDS issues'' than many Democratic
candidates in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as the Democrats want to paint Matt Fong as an
extremist, he clearly is not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all gay Republicans went along. Monday, the San Francisco
chapter of the Log Cabin Club yanked its endorsement of Fong.
</P>
<P>
   Chapter President Mike German said members were ``very much
concerned about his closeness to Rev. Lou Sheldon.''
</P>
<P>
   Ireland contrasted Fong's contribution to Sheldon's
anti-abortion group with Boxer's support for abortion rights.
Ireland said the donation was ``taking the mask off'' of Fong's
claim to be moderate on abortion and gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer went further, saying groups such as Sheldon's played a
role in the death of Matthew Shepard, the gay student who was
beaten and left to die in a presumed hate crime in Wyoming, and the
sniper killing last week of Barnett Slepian, an abortion doctor in
Amherst, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you call abortion murder, as Mr. Sheldon has done, that
sends a signal,'' Boxer said. ``When you are saying people with the
AIDS virus should be quarantined and separated from the rest of
humanity, you are sending a signal. To give $50,000 to that group
for any reason is simply wrong and is encouraging that group to
stay in business and continue to publicize their hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego, Fong said he had no regrets about donating the
money to Sheldon's organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reverend Lou is a friend,'' Fong said. ``We were working on
the Defense of Marriage Act initiative that he was contemplating.
It is an act that was supported in principle by President Clinton.
I support the defense of a traditional marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Fong accused Boxer of trying to distort his position on
abortion, and sought to portray her as an extremist for voting
against a bill to ban a type of late-term procedure that abortion
foes call partial-birth abortion.
</P>
</TEXT>
