<HEADLINE>
CAPE COD OPENS ITS DOORS FOR TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's going to be a weekend to remember on Cape Cod _ an open
house like none before. Inns, bed-and-breakfasts, museum homes, and
private homes from Falmouth to Truro will be on view.
</P>
<P>
   The Heritage Cape Cod House Tour will be held Nov. 6-8 and will
include 50 properties located throughout the Cape peninsula.
Several sites will have costumed hosts welcoming visitors, and
members of local historical societies talking about the historic
inhabitants and architecture. High school and college students will
be docents at each site.
</P>
<P>
   One $20 ticket is good for admission to all properties, and good
throughout the weekend. There's no rush _ take your time and savor
Cape Cod history. The tour runs from 1 p.m. to 5 p.m. each day.
</P>
<P>
   In Chatham, one stop is at the Atwood House Museum, built by a
sea captain in 1752 and held by five generations on the family. The
Beechcroft Inn was built in 1828 as the Universalist Society's
Brewster church. After the congregation moved into a larger
meetinghouse (now the Brewster General Store), the Greek
Revival-style building was moved to its present location and
converted into an inn with 10 rooms, a dining room, a library, and
a fireside pub. Celeste and Bob Hunt are your hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Every stop is a treasure, providing revealing glimpses into Cape
Cod life from the past and the present. If you've never stayed in
an inn on the Cape, this is the time to discover what you've been
missing.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Wedgewood Inn, a magnificent property on Route 6A
in Yarmouth Port. The building has Greek Revival and Federal
touches and was built around 1812. In 1983, the entire structure
was elegantly refurbished by the owners. Milt and Gerri Graham are
the hosts.
</P>
<P>
   In Falmouth, Mr. and Mrs. Robert Bidwell will have their home
open for visits. The house features a grand spiral staircase, and a
round Cape Cod cellar under with a secret pantry stairway entrance.
After the visit, walk through Dean's Woods in the rear and view the
garden in the shape of Cape Cod, and before passing through the old
cemetery, do ask Mr. Bidwell to tell you his ghost story.
</P>
<P>
   And there are still 46 more story-filled places to stop by.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for this first regional tour are available now and on
the days of the open house at the Dan'l Webster Inn, Sandwich; The
Wayside Inn, Chatham; Ocean Edge Resort, Brewster; The Over Look
Inn, Eastham; the Augustus Snow House, Harwich; Puritan Clothing
stores throughout the Cape; and at the chambers of commerce in
Falmouth, Hyannis, Yarmouth, and the Cape Cod Chamber at Routes 6
and 132 in Hyannis (call 508-362-3225). Program books will be
available at these locations.
</P>
<P>
   The Heritage Cape Cod Historic House Tour benefits Heritage Cape
Cod, established to promote a year-round appreciation of the
history, art, architecture, and environment of the Cape. Heritage
Cape Cod (508-888-1233) is a sponsor of the Cape's Heritage Week in
June, Maritime Week in May, and other events.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good deal &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Air New Zealand is extending its Welcome Aboard fares that offer
flights from Los Angeles to New Zealand or Australia starting at
$898 round trip. The fares are good between Oct. 28 and Dec. 10 but
must be purchased by Nov. 10. For details, call 800-262-1234.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Glenn exhibit &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In honor of 77-year-old Senator John Glenn's scheduled return to
space on Oct. 29, the John F. Kennedy Library and Museum will have
a special display of materials from the library's collection on
Glenn's first orbital space flight in 1962. The exhibit opened
yesterday. Also displayed is a memo from President Kennedy asking
if ``we are working 24 hours a day on existing space programs'' and
whether the United States had a ``chance of beating the Soviets''
by putting a man on the moon. For exhibit information, call
617-929-4500.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Haunting thoughts
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just in time for boo-day, out comes Hans Holzer's ``Travel Guide
to Haunted Houses'' (Black Dog &AMP; Leventhal Publishers, $9.95). So
if you haven't had your fill of haunted houses by now, check out
this guide to 101 locations around the world _ including two in
Massachusetts and Connecticut. The guide gives detailed directions
to each house and, most importantly, what to do in case you run
into a ghost. Holzer is described as a top authority on ghosts and
ghostly occurrences.
</P>
<P>
   Murder mystery weekends are on tap at the Austin Hill Inn in
West Dover, Vt., Oct. 30-Nov. 1 and Nov. 13-15. The weekends
include two nights' accommodations, a mystery dinner, and more. For
information, call 800-332-RELAX.
</P>
<P>
   ``Days of the Dead II,'' a special exhibit celebrating the art
of the Mexican Dias de Los Muertos (Days of the Dead), is on view
at the Peabody Essex Museum in Salem through Jan. 3. The Days of
the Dead celebration in Mexico takes place every year from Oct. 31
to Nov. 2. The holiday combines pre-Columbian traditions and
Christian beliefs introduced by the Spanish. While the American
Halloween turns death into something to be feared and avoided, the
Mexicans embrace death by highlighting its place in everyday life.
During this period, families invite the spirits of their loved ones
to eat favorite foods set out on decorated home altars. For more
information on the Salem exhibit, call 800-745-4054. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Brussels weekend &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A great deal from Sabena Belgian World Airlines is to spend
Thanksgiving weekend in Brussels for just $750 a couple. The
package includes round-trip air fare from Boston, two nights at the
Brussels Hilton International or similar hotel, and departure taxes
and fees. The package is good on flights departing Nov. 26 from
Boston and other Sabena cities and returning on Nov. 29. Only 50
seats on each flight will be available. Call 800-955-2000 between 9
a.m. and 5:30 p.m. weekends and 8 a.m. to 8:30 p.m. weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Nov. 1 Sabena, will again offer Eurostarters. The
packages, which begin at $369 a person from Boston, include
round-trip air fare to Belgium. A package with two nights'
accommodation begins at $409 a person. Other packages offering a
rental car or train service are also available.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Whale of a weekend &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now that Keiko, perhaps the world's most famous whale, is home
again in the waters off Iceland, Icelandair is offering a Whale of
a Weekend package that includes round-trip air fare from Boston and
other cities, two nights' hotel in Reykjavik, breakfasts, and a
round-trip flight to Heimaey for a day tour of the Westman Islands
for a glimse of Keiko's new pen. The package is $516 for adults and
$356 for children from Boston, and is available weekends Nov. 1
through March 31, with some blackout dates. For information, call
800-223-5500, ext. 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Winterfest &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nation's capital will celebrate its third annual Winterfest
Nov. 1 through Feb. 28. The festival allows visitors to experience
the arts and entertainment in Washington at discounted rates. More
than 60 hotels are participating in the program, featuring
discounted rates of up to 50 percent off regular room prices. At
check-in, guests receive a WinterARTS Passport with 45 offerings,
including discounts at Smithsonian museum shops, and theater
discounts. For a calendar of events and a list of participating
hotels, call the Washington DC Convention and Visitors Association
at 800-422-8644.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Weekending
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For those interested in participating in workshops at Martha's
Herbary in Pomfret, Conn., the correct telephone number is
860-928-0009.
</P>
<P>
   A Gourmet Getaway is featured at the Jackson House Inn in
Woodstock, Vt., Sunday, Monday, and Thursday nights (except during
Thanksgiving). The package includes champagne on arrival; a
hearthside dinner from the restaurant menu or the all-vegetable
menu prepared by chef Brendan Nolan; a two-course breakfast; and a
night's accommodation in an antiques-filled room. The package is
$240 for two. For information, call 800-448-1890.
</P>
<P>
   A cooking school with tips for holiday parties will be held at
the Seven Hills Country Inn in Lenox, Nov. 11-12. Cordon Bleu chef
Aura Weiss will lead the sessions. The inn has many rooms with
fireplaces and jet tubs. The package is $375 to $450 a person,
depending on accommodations. For information, call 800-869-6518.
</P>
