<HEADLINE>
A NEW TOUCH OF CLASS FOR LAS VEGAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every year or so a new marvel materializes on the Las Vegas
Strip: a volcano, a pirate ship, a medieval castle, an Egyptian
pyramid, and even the entire city of New York, condensed into a
single casino. But this year's marvel adds a touch of class, Las
Vegas style, to the sparkling Strip.
</P>
<P>
   The newly opened Bellagio is a $1.6 billion, 36-story megaresort
with a lot more than slot machines (although it does have 2,700 of
them) and gaming tables (although it does have 139). Here are some
of the things you'll find:
</P>
<P>
   _A $300 million collection of art, including paintings by
Gauguin, Mattisse, van Gogh, Cezanne, Warhol, and Sinatra (yes,
that Sinatra).
</P>
<P>
   _A 90,000-square-foot, glassed-in garden, whose displays will
change monthly and reflect the seasons. Some 111 horticulturists
will tend to the plants and flowers.
</P>
<P>
   _An 8 1/2-acre lake, meant to resemble Italy's Lake Como. But
Lake Como never had more than 1,000 fountains shooting water
designs up to 200 feet high to musical accompaniment. The
``shoreline'' features Tuscan villas with red-tiled roofs and comes
complete with a Florentine bridge.
</P>
<P>
   _A total of 120 acres, including the lake, gardens, fountains,
pools, and lushly landscaped grounds. Bellagio stands on the site
of the old Dunes resort.
</P>
<P>
   _A $70 million Cirque du Soleil production called ``O'' that
includes 68 divers, contortionists, gymnasts, and swimmers. A
1.5-million-gallon water tank is raised and lowered, allowing acts
to perform above, on, or below the water.
</P>
<P>
   _A total of 3,000 rooms, including 400 suites. Listed prices
range from $159 to $1,150, depending upon room or suite size, day
of the week, and season.
</P>
<P>
   _Twenty-three shops, 16 restaurants, and two wedding chapels.
</P>
<P>
   _A total of 8,600 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The man behind the resort is Stephen A. Wynn, who is closely
associated with transforming the slightly sinister image of the old
Las Vegas into something a whole lot cheerier. For more information
on Bellagio, call 888-987-6667 or visit www.mirageresorts.com..
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Travel trivia: &LR;  Which Las Vegas hotel has the most rooms?
(Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Quotable: &LR;  ``Nothing quite so drastic, in its way, exists
anywhere else in our country.'' _ Neil Morgan, on Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Presley payoff: &LR;  Coming next year at the latest: The Elvis
Presley Slot Machine. These slots will not only feature images of
The King but will also play his songs. One assumes that in Vegas
the featured song will be ``Viva, Las Vegas!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; And speaking of Elvis: &LR;  Wednesdays through Sunday nights, an
Elvis impersonator deals blackjack at the Key Largo casino.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tired travel joke:  &LR; Know how to beat the odds in Las Vegas?
Don't get off the plane.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  The MGM Grand Hotel &AMP; Theme Park, with 5,005
rooms, has the most rooms of any Las Vegas hotel. It is, in fact,
the world's largest hotel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
