<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST JUVENILE CLASSICS HAVE LIFELONG APPEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Name-dropping is a pastime for me. Quite by accident I have
rubbed shoulders with various historical Somebodies when they were
still nobodies, usually at very early ages; and by exploiting my
own memory, I exploit those long-ago associations, possibly
inflating them.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my colleagues are impressed that I played tennis with
Richard Gonzales after the Christmas that brought him his first
racquet (the way it was spelled then) as the present for which his
mother paid one dollar. That was quite a few years before he
became, as Pancho Gonzales, national singles champion many times
over.
</P>
<P>
   Others are more intrigued that I double-dated with James Dean
when we were teen-agers. Or that in Army service during the Korean
War, I took basic training at Ford Ord with Clint Eastwood. And
other examples, all because I was in a certain place at a certain
time and because I possess a memory that gets me overrated for
intelligence and intellect.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't believe I've told anyone about my brief acquaintance
with Derek Bok, or have written about it. Many years before he
became president of Harvard University, Derek and I were pupils in
Mr. Donley's eighth-grade literature class at Ralph Waldo Emerson
Junior High in west Los Angeles. I was the better basketball
player, but Derek was smarter _ he already had intelligence and
intellect in abundance _ and our daily classroom hour became a kind
of duologue between Derek and Mr. Donley.
</P>
<P>
   There was the occasion when Mr. Donley was telling us about
Rudyard Kipling and remarked that ``The Light That Failed'' was
Kipling's only novel. Whereupon I raised my hand and asked, ``What
about `Captains Courageous'? Whereupon Derek Bok, without raising
his hand to be recognized, sneered that ```Captains Courageous' is
a juvenile.''
</P>
<P>
   I knew then that I was a juvenile and that Derek was one also,
but I had not known that a book could be a juvenile. Nor had I made
any distinction between ``Captains Courageous'' and some of the
``adult'' novels I was reading about that time _ George Sessions
Perry's ``Hold Autumn in Your Hand''; Daphne du Maurier's ``Hungry
Hill''; and Henry Bellaman's ``Kings Row,'' which was breathlessly
passed around in eighth grade as our literary introduction to real
sex.
</P>
<P>
   The point I wish to make is that the appeal of ``young adult''
literature is not necessarily restricted to children and
teen-agers. I believe I was 11, possibly 12, when I read ``Captains
Courageous,'' a super adventure (for myself) in which I became
Harvey, the hard-to-control protagonist, slightly older than myself
and soon to be tamed by the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Many years later, when I had a 12-year-old son of my own, I
bought a ``Captains Courageous'' paperback for him to read. I don't
believe he ever did, but I reread it with genuine pleasure,
although no longer fortified by the identification factor. It
prodded me to read ``Kim'' _ another Kipling ``juvenile'' _ and
enjoyment was not diminished by my seniority.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Louis Stevenson, too. ``Treasure Island'' and
``Kidnapped'' are targeted for young readers, perhaps boys
specifically, but readers of any age _ and any sex _ may be
captivated. For full-bodied characterization, Stevenson overshadows
even Kipling.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the seafaring ``Captains Courageous'': In America today
it seems better known as the movie that brought Spencer Tracy his
first Oscar. In today's Academy Award politics, Tracy's role of
Portuguese seaman Manuel would be graded as a supporting chore; and
protagonist Harvey was enacted by Freddie Bartholomew, who had
quite a run of literature's boy heroes _ as David Copperfield, as
Jack of ``The Swiss Family Robinson'' and as David Balfour in
``Kidnapped.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1937 movie holds up as a movie, and the century-old
``Captains Courageous'' holds up beautifully as a ``novel,'' with
or without juvenile designation.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7731. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
