</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINING UP TO TAKE CREDIT FOR STRIDE RITE'S SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's amusing to watch the top executives now making their way to
the exits stepping on one another to take credit for ``the
turnaround'' at Stride Rite Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Our favorite: John Ranelli, the Lexington footwear maker's
number two man, who just departed.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, hours after we reported in this column that Ranelli
was leaving because he was being passed over for the chief
executive's job, he paid a New York public relations firm to issue
a press release calling him the ``creator of Stride Rite's
turnaround plan.'' He said he planned ``to pursue other
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day Stride Rite fired off its own release,
characterizing Ranelli as one of 11 members of top management who
``collectively'' developed strategy ``under CEO Bob Siegel's
direction.'' The release pointedly noted that the company will
record a $295,000 charge ``to provide for severance benefits
potentially payable to Mr. Ranelli over the next 12 months if he
remains unemployed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   At 61, Siegel himself is retiring to a lovely island off
Charleston, S.C., saying the turnaround is now far enough along to
allow him to leave. But if Siegel and other managers are feeling
good about the turnaround in a tough shoe environment, shareholders
who have stuck around probably aren't going to be able to retire to
island living anytime soon, not at least on their Stride Rite
gains.
</P>
<P>
   The Siegel record: The stock was 19 when he started in December
1993 and is 9 today, just about where it was 2 1/2 years ago when
the company made the California Public Employees Retirement
System's list of worst performers.
</P>
<P>
   A handsome, affable executive who made his name as the man who
put Dockers on the map for Levi Strauss &AMP; Co., Siegel has spent
most of his five years at Stride Rite talking turnaround. But as
one senior executive put it last week: ``How long does a turnaround
take?''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel points out that footwear stocks have gotten hammered this
year. ``If one gets measured on the price of the stock, yeah, I'm
disappointed. But if one gets measured on fixing the ills, I feel
very good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Siegel was left with a company largely built around
one product, Keds. The plain white canvas sneaker helped make
Stride Rite one of the top-performing stocks on the New York Stock
Exchange in the 1980s, but when grunge replaced preppie neatness,
Keds's sales fell from $370 million in 1992 to $178 million last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Keds is finally moving again. In its quarterly report last
month, the company said the Keds division posted its strongest
performance in more than five years, with sales increasing 49
percent from 1997. Siegel looks for sales to hit $200 million this
year and predicts annual sales growth of 12 to 16 percent ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Stride Rite's third-quarter sales were up 17 percent
and net income jumped 56 percent. For the first nine months of the
year sales were up 5 percent, profits up 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those inside and outside the company give Siegel high marks for
making some key hires, in particular Joanna Jacobson, president of
Keds, and Diane Sullivan, who runs the licensed brands division.
But in the most basic of ways, Stride Rite is right where it began
when Siegel came on board: dependent on Keds for its success.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Keds, the company's high-end Stride Rite children's shoes
are in a low-growth business and its Sperry Top-Siders are losing
market share, analysts say. Overall, Stride Rite's margins remain
below industry levels, says Steven Ritcher, an analyst for Tucker
Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel's biggest initiative, licensing brands like Tommy
Hilfiger and Levi Strauss, has turned out to be disappointing.
While it has helped multiply the brands under Stride Rite's
control, it has proven no substitute for building brands that it
owns.
</P>
<P>
   The licensing deals are expensive and the margins tight. This
month Stride Rite announced it would abandon the Levi's line and
take a $3.2 million charge to pay for the move. The Hilfiger line,
while it could do $100 million in sales this year, has not lived up
to early expectations, particularly on the profit side.
</P>
<P>
   The licensing initiative is reminiscent of the decision by
Siegel's predecessor, Ervin Shames, to focus his energy on building
a state-of-the-art distribution center in Kentucky. While Stride
Rite fiddled, taking years to get the bugs out, angry customers
walked and the business burned. The lesson: This is shoes, not
brain surgery. Low-tech China does a pretty good job getting shoes
out.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel stands by the strategy. ``The Tommy license is one of the
best things we have done,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Stride Rite's new chief executive, however, is likely to focus
not on signing up more brands to license, but on leveraging the
balance sheet. With its strong cash flow and no long-term debt,
Stride Rite has plenty of room to borrow for an acquisition or to
expand its current stock buyback program.
</P>
<P>
   Those familiar with the search for a new CEO, being run by the
executive recruiting firm Korn-Ferry International, say candidates
aren't exactly standing in line to run Stride Rite. Other shoe
companies are having the same problem attracting talent.
</P>
<P>
   Among the insiders, Jacobson, the Keds president, is said to
have taken herself out of the running because she has three
children and believed the next chief executive should have the kind
of strong financial background she does not have. Sullivan, like
Jacobson, is a product person, not a financial one.
</P>
<P>
   And then Ranelli, of course, is looking for his next
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
