<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TACKLING THE GROWING PROBLEM OF REPETITIVE STRESS INJURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three years ago while working in public relations and marketing,
Katherine Greenough felt a strange tingling in her wrist. By
evening, her arm had begun to shake, and pains were shooting from
her hand to her shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point I couldn't even bring a fork to my mouth, or cut
my own meat,'' says Greenough, who hasn't worked since. ``I could
not cook without pain. I could not open doors, use keys, or dry my
hair. Driving, especially parking, became painful. My whole life
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenough, 48, of Back Bay, has a repetitive stress injury, a
condition that strikes close to 300,000 people each year, according
to the US Department of Labor. Over the next five years, one in six
computer operators will develop a soft-tissue injury to the
tendons, muscles, nerves, or vascular system, reports the US
Occupational Safety and Health Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Who suffers from RSI? Poultry workers, package handlers,
machinists, construction workers, meat cutters, computer operators,
telemarketers, journalists, cashiers _ anybody who uses certain
motions repeatedly over the course of a workday.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Greenough volunteers at the Massachusetts Coalition
on New Office Technology in Boston, a group of labor and
work-safety organizations that has spent the past few years
lobbying the Labor Department and OSHA for an ergonomics standard
that would govern everything from office-furniture design to how
often a worker is required to repeat a motion.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, a Republican Congress imposed a ban on funding
for an ergonomics standard, raising the ire of groups like the
coalition. The ban was lifted this year and OSHA is expected to
release a draft standard soon, but supporters now worry the measure
will lack the breadth to have any real effect on the RSI dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, members of the Massachusetts Coalition on New
Office Technology and injured workers held a forum and panel
discussion at the Unitarian Universalist Association in Boston
yesterday to voice their concerns, to circulate a petition
demanding OSHA include computer workers in its standard, and to
plan new strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want OSHA to say computer jobs must be included in the
standard,'' says Hillary Marcus, a spokeswoman for the coalition.
``We all know that many of the jobs today involve computers. You
can't find work today without using one. We also want to see a
draft of the standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Massachusetts, 32,000 people are struggling to
live with some form of RSI, a condition that not only is difficult
to diagnose but also may take years to treat. OSHA estimates that
nearly half of all workers' compensation claims will someday
involve soft-tissue injuries such as carpal tunnel syndrome. In
1994, the last year for which statistics were available, US
companies spent $10.8 billion on medical and other costs related to
RSI, the Bureau of Labor Statistics reports.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Punnett, a professor of ergonomics and epidemiology at the
University of Massachusetts at Lowell, says computer workers can
take action by adjusting their work stations:
</P>
<P>
   _First, make sure your chair supports your back properly, and
that your feet are flat on the floor. Some workers may require an
adjustable footboard.
</P>
<P>
   _When seated, make sure your keyboard is at or a little below
elbow height.
</P>
<P>
   _Make sure your monitor is at eye level.
</P>
<P>
   _Your mouse should be at the same level as your keyboard. It can
be slightly lower, but not far away.
</P>
<P>
   _Every two hours or so, take a 15-minute break from keying. Read
for a while, use the telephone, take written notes, or get up and
walk around. This not only eases some of the stress on fingers,
hands, and arms, it also prevents eye strain.
</P>
<P>
   Greenough consulted 11 doctors in 10 months before she learned
the extent and severity of her illness. Unable to work, she has
depended on financial gifts from relatives and is now living on a
small inheritance she had hoped to set aside for her retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think we are malingerers,'' Greenough says. ``They
think (RSI) is all in our heads and we are making it up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
