A9394 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-27 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT CHILL IN THE AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One lawyer notes a rise in the bankruptcy reports that come
across his desk. Another mentions the skittishness among developers
on big real estate deals around town, including the convention
center. A third cites softer housing prices.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the layoffs at big blue-chip companies like
Raytheon and Gillette. How much longer before firms in Boston's
large financial services sector follow the pattern of 5 percent and
10 percent layoffs that have occurred in London and New York?
</P>
<P>
   Is it too soon to be worrying about a recession in
Massachusetts? Yes, probably. Recessions _ as opposed to periods of
slower growth _ take far bigger shocks than seem to be working
their way through the system today.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts has lived through three recessions in the years
since John F. Kennedy was elected president in 1960 _ only three
recessions in nearly 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   The doozy was the one associated with the end of the Vietnam
War. Starting in 1970, unemployment climbed to nearly 7 percent. It
remained there until the oil price-induced recession of 1974 sent
it soaring to 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It was in those years that one heard stories of space scientists
driving cabs, of metal-working shops closing by the score, of half
of all carpenters leaving the state.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Massachusetts scarcely felt the recession of
1980-81. True, unemployment briefly touched 8 percent in 1983. But
it fell rapidly then to less than 4 percent and stayed there for
four years. In the 1980s New England experienced a degree of
prosperity that hadn't been seen since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The came the banking crash associated with the end of the
disinflation of the 1980s. This was Massachusetts's turn in the
rolling recession that had hit the Rust Belt and the Oil Patch in
turn; California would be next. The hangover was aggravated by the
extra dose of monetary stimulus that had been administered by the
Federal Reserve Board in the months after the 1987 market break.
</P>
<P>
   Big banks closed their doors; important computer companies
failed. Unemployment skyrocketed to 9 percent from 3 percent in
just a year.
</P>
<P>
   After 1992, however, job and income growth resumed at a steady
rate. Last year unemployment again fell below 4 percent.
Massachusetts in the 1990s has resembled Massachusetts in the late
1970s and 1980s: a vibrant economy riding a strong trend of
business investment to a confident consumer boom. Only the state's
social welfare system collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   And the outlook now?
</P>
<P>
   Sara Johnson, research director for Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI in
Lexington, Mass., says the forecasting firm puts the probability of
a recession over the next two years at around 50 percent. If China
devalued its currency and the international situation got out of
hand, the odds would worsen. But if the Asian currency crisis
stabilized, she says, the United States could get away with two or
three quarters of 1 percent growth, followed by a new leg of
expansion. ``This doesn't look like other business cycles,'' says
Johnson, &UR;  &LR; referring to the usual burst of inflation followed by a
step on the monetary brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Rudiger Dornbusch, the peripatetic Massachusetts Institute of
Technology professor, goes slightly further. Appearing as part of a
panel at the Catherine Stratton Lecture at MIT last week, Dornbusch
asserted that ``the Goldilocks economy (in which everything is just
right) is gone, but on balance we are going to be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   A newly competitive US economy has produced both low inflation
and a budget surplus, Dornbusch had argued earlier _ and that
budget surplus is now conveniently waiting to be raided. A race is
on between President Clinton and the Republicans to see who will
offer an anti-recession tax cut first. And the Fed is using
interest rate cuts to push down the dollar against the European
currencies, thereby forcing the Europeans to cut their rates. With
a little luck, these ``just-in time policy levers'' would give the
current expansion ``years of life.'' It is already the
second-longest on record.
</P>
<P>
   That chill in the air? In all likelihood, it is nothing more
than winter coming on. With luck, Boston and the United States may
not see another recession for another couple or three years. The 60
years of increasingly robust growth in New England that commenced
with the onset of World War II do not yet seem about to end.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for the Globe. His e-mail
address is warsh(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
