<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE MONEY DOWN THE DRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have a new problem. At least, that's what the giant drug
company Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn wants me to believe.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know whether I should even discuss this problem in
public. On second thought, after the Starr report and the Clinton
videotape, I fear I'll be called un-American if I hide behind a
veil of decorum.
</P>
<P>
   No, my problem has nothing to do with Viagra, thank you very
much. And no, I am not afflicted with homosexuality, a scourge
still beyond the reach of the drug makers but curable, according to
the religious right, by an overdose of faith. Nor do I suffer from
Tourette's syndrome, that little understood neurological disorder
that provokes an embarrassing array of jerks, twitches, and shouts
of obscenities, though some insensitive readers have suggested that
my columns exhibit all the symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Since I've come this far, I might as well just blurt it out: I
tinkle too much.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's what I have learned lately from Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn.
I had no idea I had this problem until a few weeks ago when
Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn started telling me in a jeering ad in major
publications. The ad attempts to shame me into begging my doctor
for a new drug called Detrol to control a perfectly human condition
hyped as overactive bladder. The ad scared me. After reading it, I
could barely look myself in the mirror. I thought that if sometimes
I gotta go, I mean really gotta go (and who doesn't?), then I'm not
a properly functioning citizen and need a drug to put myself right.
</P>
<P>
   The ad's headline screamed: ``Overactive Bladder Isn't Normal at
any Age.'' Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn wanted me to know that prodigal
piddling isn't just for old folks anymore. And that's not all. If I
relieve myself recklessly (and I confess that on occasion I have),
I should be warned that I am a deviant. Of course, Pharmacia &AMP;
Upjohn knew these gross insults begged the question: What, really,
is abnormal urination?
</P>
<P>
   The ad provided a checklist of five statements. If I answered
yes to even some of them then I had a problem. A sampling:
</P>
<P>
   I frequently have a strong, sudden urge to urinate. (Yes, and
I've learned with age that jumping up and down and clutching at
oneself is not appropriate.)
</P>
<P>
   I often go to the bathroom more than 8 times in a 24-hour
period. (This is a tough call. Have you ever tried to count your
piddles in a given day? I asked my wife to help me keep track, she
declined. I asked my boss, he pretended not to hear. I asked a
woman on the street, she slapped me.)
</P>
<P>
   If, as one statement put it, I am not always able to hold on
until I reach a bathroom, that is a problem. But that's also quite
different from simply having a powerful urge, or needing to go
eight times a day.
</P>
<P>
   After studying the symptoms, I concluded that Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn
wanted to confuse me into thinking I needed a new drug. What an
economic proposition! If I pee, Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn wants to make
sure that I pee right into their piggy bank. Nowadays a man can't
go without someone trying to make a buck off of it.
</P>
<P>
   I have one request for Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn: When I'm racked by
that overwhelming, crazy-as-a-loon urge to piddle, don't prescribe
me a pill _ find me a potty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Levingston is director of the Business and Economics
Journalism Program at Boston University. He can be reached at
leving(at)bu.edu
</P>
</TEXT>
