<HEADLINE>
WOMAN'S AGE DECEPTION PIQUES INTEREST IN TV SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't watch a lot of television. I have nothing against
television, for the most part. There is actually a lot of good
programming on television if one searches diligently. However, I
simply have too much to do to spend a lot of my time watching other
people do stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it, one hour of soap operas, Geraldo, or sumo
wrestling a day adds up to seven hours a week. That's 28 hours a
month or about 336 hours a year! You can do a lot with an extra 336
hours. That's 14 complete, 24-hour days!
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, because I don't watch much television, I have never seen
the new, highly touted program called ``Felicity.'' The story line
is about Felicity Porter, a college student at the fictional
University of New York. She was supposed to go to Stanford but she
followed her high school crush to New York only to discover that he
doesn't know her from John Glenn. Even if I did watch a lot of
television, this premise does not appeal to me. Besides, it's
obviously a program for high school and college students.
</P>
<P>
   However, a startling revelation has piqued my otherwise
nonexistent interest in Felicity. Daily Variety, the news source
for the Hollywood set, published a story revealing that one of the
cast members lied about her age in order to secure her role. It
seems that TV actress and writer Kimberlee Kramer is a 32-year-old
woman and not the 17-year-old wunderkind that she pretended to be.
Now, because of Hollywood's well-known age bias, ``old'' Kimberlee
is being put out to pasture.
</P>
<P>
   Curious, I just had to look Ms. Kramer up on the internet. Sure
enough, she looks every bit the teen-ager. To complete her ruse,
she reportedly had false identification made up and talked a lot
about baby-sitting and her teen-age crushes. According to Kramer,
she couldn't even get any auditions when she told her real age so
she legally changed her name from Riley Weston and created a new
identity. Bingo! She gets a plum role on a new hit series. Whether
it's common practice in Hollywood or not, Kimberlee did tell a
falsehood to a lot of people. Upon being exposed, she said the most
incredible thing to Variety. She said, ``I take full
responsibility. I'm completely sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno, I can't recall ever
hearing those words from a public figure.
</P>
<P>
   Even though she makes her last appearance on Felicity in a few
weeks and Disney is probably going to cancel her six-figure writing
contract, all hope is not lost for the youthful-looking actress.
She's receiving lots of media attention and new offers for roles
where it's OK to tell your real age.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, I might even watch that last episode. Nah, probably
not, but it's an interesting development anyway. Only in America,
right?
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
