<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORTWORTH-FILMFESTIVAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS TO BE LEARNED FROM FORT WORTH'S FIRST FILM FEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only thing that runs longer than the Major League baseball
season is the film festival season. And unlike baseball, which
sometimes seems to never end _ that is, unless you were a San Diego
Padre, for whom it ended way too quickly _ the film festival season
does never end.
</P>
<P>
   There is at least one major festival somewhere every month. In
September, there are four: Telluride, Montreal, Toronto and New
York. So, walking past the pile of empty popcorn boxes and
discarded programs where many have gone before is the Fort Worth
Film Festival, which had its inaugural run over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The opening night was the best and worst of worlds. The premiere
film, ``Rushmore,'' was easily one of the finest movies of this
year. ``Rushmore'' will get a limited run in New York and Los
Angeles at the end of the year to qualify for Oscar consideration;
it opens wide in early 1999. Director Wes Anderson's fluky comedy _
details keep popping up for days after you've seen it _ stars
actress Talia Shire's son and feels like a British film of the
'60s, complete with lifts from the mod era and Brit-pop score. But
there wasn't much of a turnout; a second screening Friday afternoon
also played to a small audience.
</P>
<P>
   The Thursday night screening of ``The Birds,'' with star Tippi
Hedren in attendance, had difficulties, too. It's said that
projection problems at Caravan of Dreams brought the picture to a
stop several times. However, throughout the technical glitches that
are such a regular part of film festivals that they should be added
to the schedules, the crowds sat patiently and waited for things to
be righted. They did so even when the screening of ``Straight
Time'' was canceled because the print that showed up was flawed,
although word is ``Time'' co-star M. Emmett Walsh was a little
unhappy about it.
</P>
<P>
   At the screening of ``Bram Stoker's Dracula,'' screenwriter and
Fort Worth native Jim Hart dashed around the Palace 9 looking for
the projectionist because it looked as though the print was being
underprojected; it looked as dark as Dracula's soul.
</P>
<P>
   But the festival probably bit off a little more than it could
chew in its first year. Next year, a three-day run, instead of
four, would serve it better. For one thing, it would cut down on
the number of shorts programmed, many of which were a grim sit.
(And trying to slip out of the Caravan of Dreams in the dark is
like crawling through a mine field on your back.) There were a few
notable shorts, such as ``Accident,'' which had the foreboding of
``The Vanishing'' _ the original version. Or ``Phil Touches Flo,''
a hilarious little film about the dangers of playing with someone
else's dog.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's event, an outdoor showing of ``The Good, the Bad and
the Ugly,'' must have had only about 50 people or so. Too bad,
because it was a great idea. Momentum picked up by the end of the
festival, and venues with sparse crowds early on had bigger
audiences by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Too much was crammed into Thursday's party for Tippi Hedren _ a
cocktail party and then a light supper before ``The Birds,'' then
the movie, then a cocktail party after. Next year, they should
consider saving the biggest event for Saturday night, when more
people are free to attend. (Festivals often schedule the biggest
screenings for Saturday, and place a cocktail event before and
after the show, so that those interested can choose to attend one
or the other.) But the first year is almost always the shakedown
year, and as long as lessons are learned, things can only get
better.
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7614. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
