<HEADER>
A9598 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT &LR;      10-27 0168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A READY RIOJA 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Martinez Bujanda Gran Reserva 1990, Rioja, Spain. About $26.
</P>
<P>
   Known best for its Conde de Valdemar wines, the Bodegas Martinez
Bujanda also produces a premium line of wines under its own name.
Principal among them is this Gran Reserva, made from 50 percent
cabernet sauvignon and 50 percent tempranillo, the best of the
native Spanish grapes.
</P>
<P>
   This full-bodied, well-structured wine comes from grapes grown
in Martinez Bujanda vineyards in northern Spain. The wine was aged
in oak for 32 months, then given an additional four and a half
years of aging in the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Until about 10 years ago, cabernet was banned in the Rioja
vineyards because it was not a local grape. But the cabernet
tannins add structure, or backbone, to the wine, a quality often
lacking in even the best Riojas.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a better balanced wine. Not surprisingly, after
eight years of preparation, it is ready to drink now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
