</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBASSIES-BOX-1029-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REFORMS IN THE STIMSON CENTER STUDY
 &HT;    With EMBASSIES-BOX-1029.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Among the proposals for revamping U.S. diplomacy, a
study chaired by former Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci urges:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Consolidating the American diplomatic corps, which is
currently divided among dozens of U.S. agencies whose officials
work out of embassies in fields such as foreign aid, the
environment and agriculture. The study proposes that all foreign
service officials work under the direction of the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A stronger hand for ambassadors, who have little authority
over the various federal agency workers stationed in their
embassies.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Overhaul embassies, down-sizing some and expanding others to
serve regional roles.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Establish a $400 million fund to bring diplomats into the
modern computer age.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Reverse the trend of budget cuts for the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Coordination with businesses, some of which told the panel
that embassies were not crucial to their overseas operations.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 1709EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9621 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBASSIES-REFORM-1029     10-27 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBASSIES-REFORM-1029-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSTY U.S. DIPLOMATIC SYSTEM NEEDS AN UPDATE, SAY EXPERTS
 &HT;    With EMBASSIES-BOX-1029.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an era in which information moves at the speed
of light and unpredictable security threats lurk around the world,
the creaky machinery of U.S. diplomacy is ``barely out of the
quill-and-scroll stage'' and needs a major overhaul to protect
American interests, a panel of experts warned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Without greater resources and more modernization, ``we're going
to have increasing foreign policy problems and failures,'' said
Frank Carlucci, former U.S. defense secretary, as he announced the
recommendations of a review conducted by the Henry L. Stimson
Center, a private non-partisan research group.
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings, the study -- the second such to be released
in as many days -- criticized the U.S. State Department for
continuing to rely on cable-grams in the age of e-mail and the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Undersecretary of State State Bonnie Cohen said that her
department welcomed the reports and said that the conclusions were
``deserving of serious consideration'' and would be studied by
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   However, several of the recommendations would require a
sea-change for diplomatic traditions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Stimson Center's report challenged the
decades-old credo that the United States should have a full-fledged
embassy for every nation. ``Rather, the number, location and size
of U.S. posts in a given country or region must be configured to
reflect U.S. interests,'' said the report, which called for
rethinking the need for 260 embassies and other overseas posts that
the United States now maintains.
</P>
<P>
   Staffs of the outposts should be ``right-sized,'' with smaller
countries having staffs of three to five members headed up by
``ministers'' instead of ambassadors, and the State Department
could set up mobile teams of diplomats who could provide backup in
emergencies, said the report. Further, it suggests establishing
``magnet embassies'' in regions to specialize in areas such as
environment, health or drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Such streamlining of embassies could provide a partial response
to the increased security concerns for American diplomats,
especially in the aftermath of the bombings of U.S. embassies in
Kenya and Tanzania last August that killed more than 250 people.
Since then, U.S. outposts have been the target for numerous
terrorist threats, with the latest one coming in Ukraine, where
officials on Tuesday ordered tightened security.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing we want to do is go hide. Our embassies are our
face to the world,'' Carlucci said, but he added that there was a
need to reduce the ``unnecessary'' dangers for American abroad. The
report, titled ``Equipped for the Future,'' concluded that
``right-sizing'' the staffs of embassies and consulates ``will help
ensure that the minimum number of American personnel are put at
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   In its call for modernizing American diplomacy, the Stimson
Center study reinforced the findings of another private research
group, the Center for Strategic and International Studies, which on
Monday issued a call for ``Reinventing Diplomacy in the Information
Age.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The conduct of American diplomacy faces unacceptable
performance gaps between its outdated practices and the
requirements of the new age of information,'' concluded the CSIS
study, in calling for updating computers, raising professional
standards for diplomats, and improving relations with the news
media, business and private organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Both studies focused sharply on antiquated communications
equipment. ``It is ironic that the nation which has done more than
any other to bring the world into the information age still
conducts much of its diplomatic activities via cable,'' the Stimson
Center report said and recommended spending $400 million for modern
computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   The funding would ``go a long way to modernize'' the State
Department's systems, said Cohen, who oversees management for the
department. She acknowledged that many in her department are still
using Wang computers, several years after that company quit the
word-processing business.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
