<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN-1029 _ MOSCOW _ Appearing increasingly ill and
politically irrelevant, President Boris Yeltsin was admitted
Tuesday to a sanitarium a day after doctors ordered him to cancel a
foreign trip to meet with European leaders. Attended by doctors,
Yeltsin, 67, will undergo ``a course of restoration treatment.''
Yeltsin, long plagued by heart problems and other health
complications, cancelled a trip to Vienna suffering from what aides
described as ``unstable blood pressure and undue fatigue'' caused
by his refusal to stop working during his recovery from bronchitis.
The ongoing Russian economic crisis and Yeltsin's poor health have
increased the public demands for his resignation and prompted
several prominent politicians to begin preparations for an election
to succeed him in 2000, if not sooner. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With RUSSIA-BOX-1029 _ MOSCOW _ A list of possible successors to
Yeltsin. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
