<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESADILLAS, SALSAS AND MORE  
 PIZZA GHOSTS  
 PORCINI OUT OF SOUTH AFRICA  
 CALLING ON GOAT CURD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You just have to look on the shelves of a supermarket
to see the popularity of prepared Mexican food. And skyrocketing
sales of salsa confirm it. For the last six years, Authentico, a
New York company started on a shoestring by Myra and Craig Dalland,
has made first-rate products without preservatives, lard or
vegetable shortening. They include sauces, tortillas, tamales and
quesadillas.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the Dallands moved from Manhattan, where they
were cooking their products in the kitchen of another caterer, to a
larger space in Long Island City, Queens. In addition to fancy food
shops, they now sell to Northwest Airlines and Kings Super Markets
in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Some new items, which are fresh, not frozen, and can be heated
in minutes, include a mellow quesadilla of cheese and squash
blossoms; a quesadilla with plantains and mole poblano that plays
sweetness off heat; a fajita stuffed with portobello mushrooms, and
a richly spicy tamale filled with chilies and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Authentico also has new salsas, including a forceful, dark one
of tomatoes and pasilla chilies, a chunky Oaxaca-style mix of smoky
chipotles and onions that packs plenty of fire, and a nutty, tangy
green pipian verde.
</P>
<P>
   The salsas are $3 to $4 for 8 ounces; the other products are $2
to $4 each. The complete line is sold at Commodities Natural Foods,
117 Hudson St. (North Moore Street), and at Zabar's, 80th Street
and Broadway. Other sources are Amish Market, 731 Ninth Ave. (49th
Street), and the Vinegar Factory, 431 East 91st St.
</P>
<P>
   Pizza Ghosts
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Halloween goodies are everywhere. But for something
different, Pintaile's Pizza, home of the heart-shaped pie for
Valentine's Day, has placed mozzarella ``ghosts'' on a marinara
base on one of its pizzas. Another has an orange jack-o'-lantern of
American cheese on top.
</P>
<P>
   The pies, $15 for a 16-inch pizza, will be made through Sunday
and must be ordered at least a day in advance. Delivery is
available. Pintaile's is at 26 East 91st St., 1577 York Ave. (84th
Street), 1443 York Ave. (77th Street) and 124 Fourth Ave. (13th
Street).
</P>
<P>
   Porcini out of South Africa
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A new source for meaty porcini mushrooms, a joy of
fall, is Urbani Truffle of Long Island City. It imports fresh
porcini mushrooms from South Africa and Zimbabwe. Rosario Safina,
owner of the company, said these mushrooms grow high in the
mountains, and thus are never attacked by the worms that sometimes
ruin mushroom crops at lower elevations.
</P>
<P>
   They are $28 a pound at Urbani, 29-24 40th Ave., Long Island
City, Queens. They can be ordered for free delivery within 24 hours
(minimum 1 pound) from (800) 281-2330. The porcini are also sold
for $19.95 a pound at Gourmet Garage, 453 Broome St. (Mercer
Street); 301 East 64th St., and 2567 Broadway (96th Street).
</P>
<P>
   Calling on Goat Curd
</P>
<P>
   Laura Chenel, who in the early 1980s was one of the first
Americans to make French-style goat's-milk cheeses, has 500 goats
on her farm in Sonoma County, Calif. They are not enough to meet
the demand, so she is importing goat-milk curd from Norway to
increase production. The curd comes from Norwegian Dairies, which
makes Jarlsberg, a cow's-milk cheese, and gjetost, a dark brown,
sweet-tasting goat-milk cheese.
</P>
<P>
   The new Laura Chenel Select Norwegian chevre is a pleasant,
undemanding cheese that is fresh and smooth. It is available in
supermarkets for about $4 for a 4-ounce log.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
