<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BOX-1028-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    YELTSIN'S HEALTH HIGHLIGHTS RUSSIA'S PRESIDENTIAL ASPIRANTS
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-YELTSIN-1028.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The probable candidates to succeed Boris Yeltsin as
Russia's president:
</P>
<P>
   GENNADY ZYUGANOV, 54, leader of the Communist Party
</P>
<P>
   Background: Leader of the opposition in the Duma, parliament's
lower house, Zyuganov was dismissed as politically impotent after
Yeltsin defeated him in the 1996 presidential race. But Zyuganov's
clout has risen since the onset of Russia's financial crisis in
late August. He leads a fractured party, but his popular support
remains strong among the elderly and poor who have not benefited
from Russia's post-Soviet economy. Polls show he is the leading
candidate to replace Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   YURI LUZHKOV, 62 mayor of Moscow and business tycoon
</P>
<P>
   Background: The powerful mayor of Moscow is a nationalist who
enjoys strong popularity in Moscow and a reputation for fiercely
protecting the interests of his city and Russia's regional
governments. Luzhkov and Yeltsin mutually endorsed each other's
campaigns in 1996, but the mayor has distanced himself from the
Kremlin since the economic crisis erupted and sought to exploit the
current chaos to his political advantage. He is organizing his
presidential campaign and making political alliances with centrists
in the Duma, and suggesting that Yeltsin should resign.
</P>
<P>
   ALEXANDER LEBED, 48, governor of the Krasnoyarsk region and a
former army general
</P>
<P>
   Background: A tough-as-nails former paratrooper general with a
popular following among nationalists in Russia (he finished third
in the 1996 presidential balloting), Lebed has been one of
Yeltsin's most vocal critics. He has called for Yeltsin's
resignation, and suggested that Russia's army could revolt and its
regional governments could secede if the Kremlin does not move more
quickly to restore economic order.
</P>
<P>
   VIKTOR CHERNOMYRDIN, 60, former prime minister
</P>
<P>
   Background: Chernomyrdin served as Yeltsin's prime minister from
December 1992 until March OF this year, when he was fired for
failing to fix the economy. He is a political moderate who once
headed the state natural gas monopoly Gazprom, but his credentials
are tarnished. In late summer, he struggled to win confirmation as
Yeltsin's choice again as prime minister. Facing defeat in
parliament, the unpopular Chernomyrdin was shunned in favor of
Yevgeny Primakov.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
