<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9705 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-1028-C     10-27 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-1028-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AILING YELTSIN TO UNDERGO TREATMENT AMID CALLS FOR HIS
RESIGNATION
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-BOX-1028.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Appearing increasingly ill and politically irrelevant,
President Boris Yeltsin was admitted Tuesday to a sanitarium a day
after doctors ordered him to cancel a foreign trip to meet with
European leaders.
</P>
<P>
   At the medical retreat outside Moscow, Yeltsin, 67, will undergo
``a course of restoration treatment.'' The duration of Yeltsin's
stay will depend on the schedule outlined by doctors, presidential
spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Long plagued by heart problems and other health complications,
Yeltsin canceled a trip to Vienna suffering from what aides
described as ``unstable blood pressure and undue fatigue'' caused
by his refusal to stop working during his recovery from bronchitis.
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing Russian economic crisis and Yeltsin's poor health
have provoked public demands for his resignation and prompted
several prominent politicians to begin preparations for an election
to succeed him in 2000, if not sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, who would become acting
president if Yeltsin were incapacitated, took Yeltsin's place at
the Vienna summit with European Union leaders to discuss Russia's
deep economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's inability to attend was regarded in Moscow as further
evidence that his failing health has left him incapacitated and
unable even to carry out ceremonial duties.
</P>
<P>
   After the economic and political crisis erupted in August,
Yeltsin handed unprecedented authority to Primakov. Yeltsin became
``more of a figurehead in the background. Now, even his figurehead
status is in question,'' said Sergei Kolmakov, a political analyst
in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin underwent a quintuple heart bypass operation after his
reelection in 1996. Russian press have speculated broadly that his
current health problems could relate to his heart surgery, or a
history of heavy drinking or old-age dementia.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause, Yeltsin's ailments have distanced him from
the day-to-day affairs of state and further eroded public
confidence in his ability to rule.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Yeltsin cut short a visit to the Central
Asian nations of Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan after he stumbled during
a ceremony and experienced a coughing fit. He has appeared sluggish
on television, seeming to have difficulty even signing his name to
documents.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin, despite efforts in recent weeks to portray Yeltsin
as engaged in the job, clearly feared a repeat performance in
Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   This visit ``would have been a litmus test observed by many
politicians and primarily by (Yeltsin's) opponents,'' said his
spokesman, Yakushkin.
</P>
<P>
   The president was anguished over the decision but ``perfectly
realized that everybody would have concentrated on how he moves and
talks instead of following the agenda for the talks,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president did not want to take the risk because he was
rather upset by having read what the newspapers wrote about him
following his visits to Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan,'' Yakushkin
said.
</P>
<P>
   But criticism has come not only from political adversaries, but
from traditional allies, too. Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, who has
begun forming a campaign team for the presidency, this month
publicly questioned Yeltsin's ability to govern.
</P>
<P>
   ``A temporary ailment is one thing, but if a person cannot work
and constantly perform his duties, it is necessary to find enough
will and courage to confess it,'' Luzhkov said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Lebed, a retired army general and regional governor
who also harbors presidential aspirations, also has called on
Yeltsin to step down for the good of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov said Tuesday that Kremlin
aides were ``mocking'' Russians by insisting that Yeltsin has no
debilitating illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Yeltsin's inability to work has been obvious to us for
quite a long time,'' Zyuganov said at a news conference. He called
on Yeltsin to undergo an independent medical examination and for
the results to be made public.
</P>
<P>
   Russian newspapers suggested that Yeltsin's aides were intent on
trying to keep him in office until his term ends in mid-2000 by
making him stay at home and using Primakov as the de facto
president. Leading candidates to replace Yeltsin would benefit by
having time to organize their campaigns and not having to run amid
the chaos of early elections and economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among the political elite, it appears, there is a non-verbal
pact on the preservation, if possible, of the status quo until the
year 2000,'' the newspaper Sevodnya reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Should Yeltsin fail to serve out his current four-year term,
Primakov would become interim president and elections would be held
within three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have already started their campaign. We are not going to
stand in their way,'' Yakushkin said Tuesday of the jockeying by
presidential hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov's selection as a compromise candidate for prime
minister in September calmed Russia's political chaos but has done
little to solve its economic problems. The Russian ruble plummeted
in value in late August and the banking system collapsed, cutting
the already low standard of living, and raising fears about fuel
and food supplies for the coming winter.
</P>
<P>
   Following his stay at the Barvikha sanatorium, Yeltsin will
probably take a vacation of at least two weeks, his spokesman said,
though it was not clear where or when he will go.
</P>
<P>
   Russian television showed pictures of Yeltsin meeting at his
Gorky-9 residence outside Moscow with Primakov Tuesday morning
before the prime minister left for Vienna and the president was
admitted to the medical retreat. Yeltsin, wearing a sweater,
appeared tired and smiled little.
</P>
<P>
   Insisting that Yeltsin will be back on the job after his rest,
Yakushkin said that Yeltsin is still scheduled to meet with
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi and Chinese President Jiang
Zemin in Moscow next month.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
