<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REFORMS IN THE STIMSON CENTER STUDY
 &HT;    With EMBASSIES-BOX-1028.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Among the proposals for revamping U.S. diplomacy, a
study chaired by former Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci urges:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Consolidating the American diplomatic corps, which is
currently divided among dozens of U.S. agencies whose officials
work out of embassies in fields such as foreign aid, the
environment and agriculture. The study proposes that all foreign
service officials work under the direction of the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A stronger hand for ambassadors, who have little authority
over the various federal agency workers stationed in their
embassies.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Overhaul embassies, down-sizing some and expanding others to
serve regional roles.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Establish a $400 million fund to bring diplomats into the
modern computer age.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Reverse the trend of budget cuts for the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Coordination with businesses, some of which told the panel
that embassies were not crucial to their overseas operations.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
