<HEADER>
A9710 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-1028-     10-27 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-1028-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AID GROUPS SEE REFUGEES TRICKLE BACK INTO KOSOVO AS SERB TROOPS
PULL BACK
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 600 words.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Amid signs that Serb forces were pulling out of Kosovo,
humanitarian aid groups there were encouraged Tuesday by the sight
of ethnic Albanian refugees starting to make their way back to
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time we saw hope in their eyes instead of
fear,'' said Terry Heselius, the head of the Mercy Corps
International's office in Pristina, the embattled province's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   The return of 250,000 to 500,000 refugees to their homes before
winter would dramatically reduce the challenge faced by the
approximately 30 aid groups amassed in Pristina. As long as the
ethnic Albanians remained in the open or in temporary shelter, aid
workers could do little more than struggle to provide basic
subsistence.
</P>
<P>
   Even badly damaged homes provide better shelter than either the
woods or temporary lodging with already struggling host families,
aid workers said.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the logistical nightmare of serving a hugely,
poorly counted population of wandering refugees becomes far more
manageable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can get them on a monthly distribution cycle as opposed to
running around after them,'' said Mick Lorentzen of the World Food
Program's Pristina office.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a jumbo cargo jet filled with relief supplies landed
at the Pristina airport, which had been closed for several months
because of the fighting. It was an heartening sign for air workers
who have feared the worst for the thousands of refugees who fled
there homes during eight months of fighting between Serb forces and
Kosovo separatists. On the flight was Hugh Palmer, the head of the
U.S. A I D.
</P>
<P>
   Serb military leaders withdrew their forces from Kosovo in large
numbers Tuesday, and NATO was preparing to take a step back from
its threat of imminent air strikes against Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Bill Clinton said, ``As a result of the
improving security climate, up to 40,000 displaced people already
have been returned to their homes from the mountains, escaping the
mortal jeopardy of a winter without shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said as the cease-fire holds, ``more humanitarian relief
workers and international verifiers move into Kosovo, Serb forces
stay out, and roadblocks and checkpoints stay down, the confidence
level of the remaining displaced people should now increase, and
they too will be able to come in from the cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Private radio station B-92 quoted Serb
sources as saying the Serb withdrawal was complete and that
government forces in Kosovo were back to the level before Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic launched his crackdown against ethnic
Albanian militants on Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers said they encountered few Serb police or soldiers
during Tuesday's convoys from Pristina to places where refugees
have congregated. ``The checkpoints seem to be coming down,''
Heselius said.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Pagarushe, where more than 15,000 refugees had
made a makeshift town of clear plastic tents, Heselius said there
was strong evidence of progress Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people living in the plastic village are packing up and
heading home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials seemed satisfied by the Serb withdrawal Tuesday,
but will retain the authority to use force should the Serbs renege
on their commitments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no air raids,'' Amadeo de Franchis, Italy's
envoy to NATO, told the BBC. ``There will be a consensus that there
has been sufficient (Serbian) compliance for these air raids not to
start.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows).
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, Belgium, a meeting of ambassadors from the 16 NATO
nations agreed to indefinitely extend the ``activation order''
keeping over 400 allied warplanes on alert for possible raids
against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have instructed our military to remain prepared ... and
maintain forces,'' said NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana.
</P>
<P>
   He said the decision would maintain pressure on Milosevic as it
appeared his troops were complying with the alliance's demand for
troop redeployments in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that President Milosevic only moves when he is
presented with the credible threat of force,'' Solana told
reporters. ``The security forces are returning to the level they
were at before the present crisis began.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke, who negotiated with
Milosevic, said the Serbs' performance so far looked good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I hate to use the 'O' word in the Balkans, but there
is reason for some more optimism than we've had in the past,''
Holbrooke told CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serb security forces are pulling out,'' he said. ``The
international verification regime is pouring in. The (Serbs) have
allowed Kosovo, which they have always said was their private
backyard, to become an international issue and once the
international community is in there, it is going to make a huge
difference in stabilizing the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
