<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9720 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-27 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POLS AND THE POLLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The possible impeachment of President Clinton
floats like a pewter thundercloud over the elections next Tuesday,
and yet the common wisdom holds that not enough political rain will
fall from that scandal to drown out ordinary local issues.
</P>
<P>
   How can this be?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's job approval rating remains incredibly high at 65
percent in recent polls, and two thirds of the voters say they
don't want him to be impeached. Furthermore, nearly half of the
voters disapprove of the job Republican congressional leaders are
doing, and 52 percent say the GOP has pushed too hard for Clinton's
ouster.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the impeachment in the week before the election remains a
minor campaign sideshow rather than the central focus it has been
for months in Washington and will become again when the election is
over.
</P>
<P>
   The major pollsters agree that voters are not factoring the
president's fate into their thinking this fall. This is not a
referendum on Bill Clinton, whose name is not on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Voters do not seem prepared to lurch collectively either to the
right or left but to leave Congress pretty much as they found it.
They are not plotting to shape a new legislative body radically
different from the present one in order to ensure a dramatic
impact, one way or the other, on the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   The once-anticipated GOP landslide now looks like a pickup of
perhaps fewer than 10 in the House and 2 in the Senate. The
Republicans would remain in control of both bodies but be left with
at best a 21-seat margin in the House, still too slim to achieve
the conservative revolution they once promised. Under this
scenario, they would also fall short in the Senate of having enough
votes to shut off filibusters by the minority Democrats seeking to
block GOP legislation they don't like.
</P>
<P>
   Such a modest shift would not change the internal dynamics of
either body very much, or of Capitol Hill's fractious relationship
with Clinton. But it could send a signal to Congress that it might
be good politics to figure out some way of punishing him short of a
prolonged impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   Were the Republicans to gain huge new majorities, they would be
emboldened to go after Clinton with a vengeance, pushing for
impeachment in the House and a trial in the Senate. And Democrats
would run scared from a president they had no power to defend.
</P>
<P>
   A muddled vote for essentially the status quo signifies not just
a public desire to retain divided government _ a Democratic
president and a Republican Congress _ but to balance the power
between the two parties so that one cannot destroy the other.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates in both parties have been nervous about even
mentioning the impeachment question. Republicans are very much
aware that the polls suggest a backlash if they appear overeager to
raise lying under oath about illicit sex to a constitutional
offense. Democrats are leery of being tagged the party of
immorality if they call too much attention to their affiliation
with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Some commentators think there may be retroactive clues to voter
mood in the fate of the 31 House Democrats who voted with the
Republicans to launch impeachment hearings. But the legislators all
voted the way they felt their constituents would want. If they read
that correctly, they should survive.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, as always, politics is local.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic senators in deepest trouble were in trouble
before the world heard of Monica Lewinsky, because of their own
personal political problems. The Democratic House members in
trouble were also in trouble long ago because generally Republicans
have more campaign money than Democrats, the midterm historical
trend is against them and the country is increasingly conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Voter apathy this year works in favor of incumbents of both
parties. But the size of the turnout among supporters of various
causes and philosophies can tip the outcome one way or another.
</P>
<P>
   Only fools and super-confident pollsters go out on a limb with
predictions a week before an election. There is still plenty of
time for surprises.
</P>
<P>
   But it does seem settled that voters are sick of Clinton's
behavior, sick of Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's pursuit of
him, sick of exaggerated political attempts to compare Clinton's
conduct with that of Richard Nixon and sick of congressional
hypocrisy on the subject. A plague on all their houses.
</P>
<P>
   But unless voters are collectively sublimating their real
intentions, this election is about other things.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
