<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9746 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-HUNTER-$ADV01-SF     10-27 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HUNTER-$ADV01-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNTER'S ROLES ARE LOUD WITH LIFE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOVEMBER 1) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RUTHE STEIN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Holly Hunter specializes in playing live wires.
</P>
<P>
   Her path was set in the 1984 stage role that made her famous: a
feisty contestant in the off-Broadway play ``The Miss Firecracker
Contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter goaded Nicolas Cage into kidnapping a baby for her in
1987's ``Raising Arizona,'' and was especially memorable that same
year as a high-strung, high-powered television producer in
``Broadcast News.'' Attempting to seduce her, the pretty-boy
``News'' anchor played by William Hurt whispered, ``I'd love to be
inside all that energy.''
</P>
<P>
   And in her Oscar-winning performance in 1993's ``The Piano,''
Hunter communicated her character's spunk without speaking, through
her eyes and the way she pounded the ivories.
</P>
<P>
   Not to diminish Hunter's talent, but being energetic seems to be
her natural state.
</P>
<P>
   During an interview, she prowls her hotel room as she chatters
away. Hunter, 40, grew up in Georgia and still has a Southern
accent, but she talks as fast as a New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Her mind jumps around from her new film, ``Living Out Loud,'' in
which she plays another pistol, to her new dress. The 5-foot-2
actress looks even thinner than her 100 pounds in a black sarong by
her favorite designer, Vera Wang, who also made the wisp of a dress
Hunter wore to pick up her Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call Vera and I say, `I've got a thing to go to,' and she
sends me a dress in a box. It always fits. It's so easy,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Her best lines are played across the room to her husband, Janusz
Kaminski, a Polish-born cinematographer who often works with Steven
Spielberg, including on ``Saving Private Ryan.'' Kaminski met
Hunter at the New York Film Critics award ceremony when she won for
``The Piano.'' They married four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   They're so tight he almost always goes with her to work-related
events like the Toronto International Film Festival, where ``Living
Out Loud'' was shown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very sweet man in this regard _ in all regards,
really,'' Hunter says, smiling in his direction. ``It's lovely to
have some kind of trusting thing in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Given her state of marital bliss, there's no question that
Hunter was acting in her two most recent roles.
</P>
<P>
   She's currently on the New York stage in ``Impossible
Marriage,'' playing a woman in a difficult relationship with an
older man. Like ``The Miss Firecracker Contest,'' the play was
written by Beth Henley. ``We go back forever,'' Hunter says.
``She's been totally pivotal to my career.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Living Out Loud,'' Hunter plays Judith, a wealthy doctor's
wife whose husband leaves her for a younger woman. The movie, which
co-stars Danny DeVito and Queen Latifah, is the first to be
directed by Richard LaGravenese, a highly regarded screenwriter who
worked wonders adapting ``The Bridges of Madison County'' and
``Beloved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Judith was really well-written, and I don't read a
lot of those,'' Hunter says, explaining why she took the role. ``I
loved the subtlety of the story. It's about an internal conflict
rather than an external one where there's a predator. The problem
was inside her.''
</P>
<P>
   She got to put in her two cents about how Judith should look and
act. ``I said I want her to be a major, major blonde,'' recalls
Hunter, whose hair is startlingly platinum in the movie. It was
also her idea that Judith smoke, as politically incorrect as that
is these days.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling that Hillary Rodham Clinton objected to Julia Roberts'
character smoking in ``My Best Friend's Wedding,'' Hunter says she
doesn't think the first lady will weigh in this time. ``Smoking
probably feels minor to Hillary right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hunter believes her most important contribution to Judith
was to make her feisty even during the humiliating aftermath of a
divorce that wasn't her idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to give her strength from the beginning. I did
not want her life to happen to her. I wanted her to take charge of
it. If Judith was going to fall off the ledge, I wanted it to be
because she stepped off, not because she was pushed.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter accomplishes this in little ways. When Judith goes to an
expensive restaurant by herself, she looks utterly comfortable
reading a book instead of anxious that people are staring at her.
And when she ends up at a women-only club late at night when
everyone is letting loose on the dance floor, she joins right in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved that number on the dance floor. It was a delight,''
Hunter says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living Out Loud'' gave her a chance to explore what it would
be like to live on the Upper East Side of Manhattan. ``A lot of
people really do live alone in Manhattan. It's actually quite easy
to be anonymous, to live a life that is unexamined by others even
though there's a ton of people there. That's one of the provocative
things about New York that I love.''
</P>
<P>
   Some moviegoers may wonder whether a wealthy divorced woman like
Judith would consider a romance with her apartment building's
elevator operator, especially one who looks like DeVito.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she absolutely would,'' Hunter insists. ``Classism
doesn't really interest me very much as an actress. The only time I
might want to explore it is if I was doing a French restoration
comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   With her continued interest in the theater, Hunter could be
appearing in such a comedy one day. Unlike other movie stars who
talk about how much they would love to be in a play but never do
one, Hunter makes an effort to return to the stage every couple of
years, even if it means turning down movie roles.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, she and other like-minded friends, including Ed
Harris and his wife, Amy Madigan, have formed a theater company in
Santa Monica near where they live. Right now they're trying to
raise money to build a theater for the company, called the Loretta
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company makes sense because there are a lot of great
actors who live in L.A. who aren't always working in movies,''
Hunter points out. ``A lot of them started out in theater. You know
L.A. is trash, but the fact is a lot of really good people live
there.''
</P>
<P>
   She and Kaminski stay there because it's where the work is.
Hunter has just finished ``Women Wanted,'' directed by Kiefer
Sutherland.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter hopes to soon be directed by her husband, who is gaining
enough clout in Hollywood to make this happen. ``It's an
unscheduled date,'' she says, throwing him another look. ``But it
will occur.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;
</P>
