<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATY2K-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta product debugs Y2K
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A slew of Y2K fixes for IBM-compatible PC hardware
have come to market, and among them a little Atlanta company's
product seems to have found a better solution than such giants as
Symantec and McAfee.
</P>
<P>
   PCfix 2000, the Atlanta company's new entry, costs a relatively
whopping $94.95.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not in stores. If you want it, you'll have to purchase
it directly from the Web http://www.pcfix2000.com (cq).
</P>
<P>
   Or you can buy it from the company, the About Time Group,
located at 4151 Ashford Dunwoody Road. Phone numbers are
404-255-2660(cq), toll free 1-888-558-2660 (cq), fax
404-255-2689(cq).
</P>
<P>
   Retail outlets, the company said, will have the product early
next year.
</P>
<P>
   PCfix 2000 tests and fixes a PC's BIOS. This ``basic
input-output system'' controls such things as the computer's disk
speed, memory and time.
</P>
<P>
   The product also tests and fixes the computer's real time clock
and system clock.
</P>
<P>
   To do much the same thing, Symantec has just released the $49.95
Norton 2000. This product has extra bells and whistles _ for
instance, it does some reporting on your applications and even
personal spreadsheets.
</P>
<P>
   The product is so new on the market the company hasn't yet put
up a Web page on the individual version, so for more info you have
to go to the corporate version's page http://www.symantec.com/sabu
</P>
<P>
   /n2000/index.html (cq).
</P>
<P>
   For just $29.95, McAfee offers the 2000 Tool Box, and in many
particulars it resembles the Norton 2000 http://www.mcafeemall.com
(cq).
</P>
<P>
   But you still may want to spend triple that amount for the
Atlanta company's product.
</P>
<P>
   Only PCfix 2000 is straight software. The others are memory
resident programs or device drivers. These not only eat system
memory but can create software conflicts and outright computer
crashes.
</P>
<P>
   PCfix immediately corrects date and time when a PC is booted and
does not remain in memory.
</P>
<P>
   The product has been recently selected by AT&AMP;T for its desktop
and laptop remediation program.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if memory resident programs don't bother you, you can
get a free BIOS fix from Phoenix based Viasoft at http://www.onmark
</P>
<P>
   .viasoft.com/fix-it. It's offering the freebie because it wants
some attention for Onmark 2000. That Viasoft Y2K reporting product,
which sells in the $70 range, also competes with Norton and
Symantec.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
