<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9771 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLUETOOTH28-COX     10-27 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUETOOTH28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Companies meet to forge standard for wireless communications
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gathering momentum, a growing team of communications
and computer companies is gathering here this week in Buckhead to
forge a world standard for wireless communications that could
unleash many new products next year.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Bluetooth wireless communications initiative, an
original group of five companies which first met in May, including
Ericsson, IBM, Intel, Nokia and Toshiba, has now grown to some 200,
officials said this week.
</P>
<P>
   And some 350 representatives of those companies are huddling
privately at the Grand Hyatt Hotel through Thursday, to share
information, conduct training and discuss refinements of the work,
now dubbed the draft specification 0.7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have had more, but a larger number would have been
unwieldy,'' said Chuck Napier, of Convergence Corp., a local
meeting host and a member of the initiative. Convergence makes
communications software.
</P>
<P>
   Bluetooth comes from the name of a Danish king who succeeded in
uniting his people during the 11th century.
</P>
<P>
   The privacy is necessary, they say, to make sure all the players
subscribe to the standard and agree to cooperate royalty-free so
that the technology can spread fast and cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incentive for people to take part in this is the hope that
better wireless connectivity can enhance the value of all the
products from hand held devices to mobile computers,'' said Simon
C. Ellis, data communications marketing director for Intel.
</P>
<P>
   While Intel stands ready to make new processors for the
equipment, others like IBM, Ericsson, Nokia and Toshiba will have
new, appealing machines to offer. And communications software
specialists like Norcross-based Convergence hope to help write the
programs that make the systems work.
</P>
<P>
   Basically the Bluetooth technology allows freer communication
among wireless devices, including handheld computers and laptops
without using the wired networks.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical arrangement, with the new technology, users will be
able to receive e-mail automatically on their notebooks by way of
handheld devices, or synchronize their desktop computer with their
handheld device without removing it from the brief case.
</P>
<P>
   It will also keep teams of executives in touch as never before.
Among the applications possible, technical specialists said, was an
arrangement where announcements by competitors could automatically
be transmitted to executives, and opening videoconferencing
channels immediately for meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bluetooth is technology we have been studying for eight
years,'' said Anders Edlund, senior manager of technology marketing
at Ericsson. ``With this special interest group, we will be able to
implement it quickly and smoothly.''
</P>
<P>
   The kind of cooperative talks being conducted by the Bluetooth
special interest group 20 years ago would have set off antitrust
alarms in Washington and elsewhere. But in the age of deregulation,
such meetings are now encouraged so that technical innovations can
be implemented faster.
</P>
<P>
   Where necessary, regulators such as the Federal Communications
Commission and international wireless conventions can give formal
approval of the agreements if they do not violate communications
spectrum rules.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Atlanta was picked as the site for the Bluetooth
meeting, Ellis of Intel, whose company is based in Santa Clara,
Calif., said this city is close to many players and reachable by
companies domestically and overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good, available hotel space and your fine international
airport were big factors in selecting Atlanta,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say the final Bluetooth specification version 1.0 is
scheduled for public release during the second quarter of 1999. And
the first products, many near completion, could be announced during
the second half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   They could include new mobile computers, handheld PCs, digital
cellular phones, and peripheral equipment such as printers,
projectors, PC cards and hands-free phone handsets.
</P>
<P>
   The Bluetooth working group has a Web site at
http://www.bluetooth.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
