<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REMODEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Remodeling spending builds steadily, keeps contractors busy
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Building houses isn't the only thing that has kept
contractors busy the past year; remodeling spending also is up.
</P>
<P>
   Americans spent $88 billion (cq) on remodeling during the 12
months ending in September, according to a new economic indicator
devised by Harvard University's Joint Center for Housing Studies.
Remodeling spending has grown 15 percent during the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the boom has been the combination of low
interest rates, housing appreciation and growth in large-scale
projects such as new kitchens, said Kermit Baker, project director
for the center's Remodeling Futures Program.
</P>
<P>
   Spending on remodeling took a big jump in mid-1997, just as
interest rates began a steady fall. That triggered increased
activity in refinancing, which homeowners often use to improve
their current houses.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, business is expected to flourish as baby boomers'
families grow and older residents prepare their homes for aging,
said Mike Turner of TLC Builders and past national chairman of the
National Association of Home Builders' remodelers council.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have put in more (Americans with Disabilities Act) compliant
bathrooms in the past 18 months than I have done in the past 15
years, right here in Roswell,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Lower interest rates are expected to continue to influence
remodeling activity, even in the face of dropping consumer
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   First Union reported that while people are reasonably secure in
their jobs and plan to spend money this holiday season, the
financial markets' recent performance has made them skittish about
buying big-ticket items, such as houses.
</P>
<P>
   But if a family can refinance its existing home at a lower rate,
come away from the transaction with some cash to invest in
remodeling, then its comfort level stays intact.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, says Warner McConaughey (cq), an owner of HammerSmith
remodelers, there is a population that is tired of wasted time
commuting in traffic and wants to buy inside the Perimeter. They
then remodel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get a smaller lot, but they can renovate the house and
still have pretty much what they want,'' he remarked. ``I sometimes
see more money spent on the renovation than was spent to buy the
house, but these people don't care. They know they might not get
the money out, but they prefer to have a couple of extra free hours
every day.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
