<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS IS BLOSSOMING AROUND US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY CHARLES W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ We know it's autumn.
The calendar says so, and not many days ago we were out on a frosty
morning, cutting a fall bouquet of bittersweet. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The flowering crabapple tree in the front yard has dropped its
leaves. But, perversely, standing there in all its nakedness, it
has put forth a little burst of bloom. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the side, along the drive, the Hosta lilies, too, have thrust
up blossoms again. And, out walking, I've seen similar
unaccountable displays in other yards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clearly something peculiar is afoot. Maybe it is the El Nino
effect. Or a preternatural alignment of the planets. Whatever the
cause of it, I have not seen this eruption of out-of-season
florescence reported in the news. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I can remember when we had someone on the reporting staff whose
specific duty it would have been to inform readers about such a
horticultural phenomenon. But that was a long time ago, and of
course the definition of news is not fixed. It changes with
changing tastes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For example, I cannot help noticing the way in which killer bees
have passed from fashion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over a period of decades, from at least the 1960s onward or
possibly the '50s, not a year went by without an update in the
nation's press, including this newspaper, about the alarming rate
at which killer bees were advancing upon us from south of the
border. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The accounts were graphic, of peasant farmers wholly enveloped
in the deadly swarm _ the unfortunate human not even visible inside
the humming, woolly garment of bees _ just running and stumbling
blindly until felled by a hundred thousand stings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This sometimes happened to cattle, too, and donkeys, and
presumably cats and dogs as well. But it was the ghastly fate of
the human victims that set the imagination humming, as it were. A
reader could not help wondering how imminent was the peril for
himself and his loved ones. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First, as I recall, the bees were reported in Guatemala, or
maybe it was Brazil. Then they made their way into Mexico. Another
10 years and they were near the U.S. border. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the late '80s, I think it was, a nest of them was
said to have been discovered _ horror of horrors! _ in southern
Texas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reports in the Yankee press took on a fevered tone. Because now
it wasn't just nameless foreign folks we were talking about wearing
bee coats. It was us! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then, as so often happens, the crisis inexplicably just went
away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not once this year has so much as a single story about killer
bees found its way into print in our paper, or any other paper I've
happened to read. Nor was there a mention of them last year. Or, as
nearly as I could detect, the year before. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's what happens when a business has an attention span as short
as ours. Journalists do not like to dwell on any one subject very
long. A famine in Africa is news for a week, or two at most. The
Middle East or Northern Ireland gets wearisome before very long. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scandal of one sort or other seems to be the only topic that
engages us in a durable way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And that is why, preoccupied with salacious matters, we might
discover too late that we overlooked the really big news. Which is
that this outburst of unseasonable blooming could be the result of
late pollination by _ you guessed it _ by killer bees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In other words, they're no longer just coming. They're here. A
pity we missed it! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
