<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9793 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPLIT-INFINITIVES-KAN     10-27 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPLIT-INFINITIVES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IT COMES TO INFINITIVES, IT IT BETTER TO SPLIT _ OR TO NOT
SPLIT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRAD COOPER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ The news had been out for barely a day when the
students in Terri Gillespie's Blue Springs High School English
class were ready to eradicate one more rule of grammar.
</P>
<P>
   Word on the radio Monday had it that Oxford dictionaries, the
self-proclaimed ``last word on words,'' had abandoned the taboo on
split infinitives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids thought it was hilarious that once again there is
another rule going by the wayside,'' Gillespie said. ``They thought
it was great. They love any rule that you can break.''
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, an infinitive is a verb with ``to'' in front.
</P>
<P>
   The rule works this way. The infinitive ``to eat'' should be
modified as ``to eat quickly '' and not ``to quickly eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence, Shakespeare's Hamlet poses the question, ``To be or not
to be'' instead of asking, ``To be or to not be.''
</P>
<P>
   As with many taboos, the guidance against split infinitives has
fallen victim to modern usage.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a more recent cultural icon: Capt. James T. Kirk of
``Star Trek'' who speaks of the mission ``to boldly go where no man
has gone before.'' A strict grammarian would insist on ``to go
boldly.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond popular culture, many grammarians long have argued
against a rule based more in Latin tradition than in English usage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule has been changing for a long time,'' said Jeffrey
McQuain, an author who has worked as a researcher for William
Safire's On Language column. ``Oxford is perhaps one of the final
places to admit the split infinitive is here to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been around a long time, and I think it's more a
nicety of language that has been taught in English classes, but
it's not very widely practiced in the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The change is included in the new Oxford American Desk
Dictionary, which came out last month and says the prohibition on
split infinitives can lead to ``awkward, stilted sentences.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Abate, editor in chief of Oxford's U.S. dictionaries
program in Old Saybrook, Conn., says the company really isn't
breaking new ground.
</P>
<P>
   While previous Oxford dictionaries may not have said anything
about split infinitives, Abate noted that Oxford acknowledged in
usage books as early as 1910 that split infinitives were natural.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if we've changed and we've gone against what we
have been saying. It's more that we're coming out with a usage note
that states, `Don't worry about this rule.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ( The Associated Press contributed to this article. )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
