<HEADER>
A9798 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILTON-ANDERSON-KAN &LR;      10-27 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILTON-ANDERSON-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PORT AUTHORITY CHAIRMAN'S TIES TO HILTON CASINO
INVESTIGATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Jackson County Prosecutor Claire McCaskill
confirmed Monday that her office is investigating the relationship
between the owners of Kansas City's Flamingo Hilton Casino and the
former chairman of the Port Authority.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill said her probe began several weeks ago after her
office received information from state gambling regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are, at the request of the Missouri Gaming Commission,
investigating the Hilton matter,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The development Monday was the first suggestion that state
charges could be possible after U.S. Attorney Steve Hill Jr. agreed
in August to a $655,000 settlement with Hilton Hotels Corp. and its
local subsidiary, rather than file criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Hill had been investigating whether Hilton officials had
rewarded Elbert Anderson for his support of the casino project by
giving a $250,000 grant to a firm Anderson controlled through a
business associate. Anderson at the time was chairman of the Kansas
City Port Authority, which controlled the riverfront property on
which the Flamingo was built.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Fisher, executive director of the Gaming Commission, said
Monday through a spokesman that the commission would not comment on
McCaskill's probe.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for the casino said Monday that McCaskill's
investigation appeared to be part of a state review of the Hilton's
license that the commission announced in August. At that time
Chairman Robert L. Wolfson Sr. said the commission would review a
transcript of grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is part of the normal regulatory process, looking
at the issues that they had resolved in 1996 (when the casino was
first licensed by the state),'' said Jerry Riffel, one of Hilton's
Kansas City attorneys. ``I think they're taking a second look at
that in light of the transcript.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hilton remains confident that it is suitable to hold a
Missouri (gaming) license and has done nothing wrong,'' Riffel
added. ``We have cooperated and will continue to cooperate with
Missouri's regulators, and it is up to the Missouri regulators what
process they choose to use in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill would neither characterize the commission's referral
nor say whether it came with a recommendation for any specific
action on her part. She would not say whether a county grand jury
had convened on the issue or estimate how long her review would
take.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Hill's office declined to comment on McCaskill's
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Hilton agreed to pay the federal government $500,000
to avoid criminal charges that an executive had rewarded Anderson
for his support for the casino. Hilton also agreed to pay an
additional $155,000, the cost of the federal investigation, and set
up a training program to educate employees about how to respond to
public officials seeking money.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said he opted for the out-of-court agreement because the
base fine of $500,000 was the maximum Hilton would have paid in a
guilty verdict and because a conviction might have amounted to a
``nationwide death penalty'' for Hilton's 14 casinos in other
states.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement essentially closed the book on the two-year
federal probe, but the possibility was left open that state
prosecutors or gambling regulators could pursue their own leads.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has been convicted of unrelated federal charges for
bribing D. Jeanne Robinson when she was a city councilwoman and
James D. Tindall when he was chairman of the Jackson County
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Following his conviction, Anderson agreed to cooperate with
federal authorities in their investigation of Hilton and appeared
before grand juries.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Keller, an Anderson attorney, declined to comment
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The August agreement with Hilton stated that in 1993 Anderson
arranged for the company to pay $250,000 to K.C. Perspectives. The
company was owned by Anderson business associate Michelle Lathan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when the Gaming Commission was deciding whether to
issue a license to the Flamingo, it conducted hearings at which
Anderson testified that Hilton's K.C. Perspectives was legitimate
and not intended to influence him as head of the Port Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Because the payment came after Anderson's vote on awarding the
casino to Hilton, Hill termed it a reward rather than a bribe and
said Anderson ``was paid to influence his future support as Port
Authority chairman.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill said prosecutors did not pursue individual Hilton employees
because none of them individually benefited from the arrangement
and because none of them still worked for Hilton. Some of the
employees resigned after the payment became known, and others
resigned during the Gaming Commission hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The casino's license, which was due to expire this month, was
conditionally extended by the Gaming Commission last month.
</P>
<P>
   One of the conditions was a satisfactory conclusion ``to the
outcome of the (commission's) investigation into (Hilton's)
relationship with former Kansas City Port Authority Chairman Elbert
Anderson and related matters.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission resolution extending Hilton's license did not
indicate that the Port Authority matter was to be referred to any
investigative agency.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Taylor, a spokesman for the anti-gambling campaign
committee Show Me the River, said Monday that his group would watch
McCaskill's investigation closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``People's concern about the corruptive influence of this
industry on government is not unfounded. There needs to be strict
regulation,'' Taylor said. ``This is an industry that wants to
deregulate.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Flamingo's license also is contingent on how
Missouri's ``boats-in-moats'' issue plays out at the polls next
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Flamingo is one of 10 Missouri casinos faced with the loss
of games of chance, including slot machines, if voters reject
Amendment 9. That proposal would retroactively legalize casinos
moored off-river.
</P>
<P>
   If that measure fails, and the Flamingo and other threatened
casinos lose expected administrative appeals before the Gaming
Commission, they would be relicensed to offer only games of skill,
including blackjack and poker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
