<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Nov. 1,
1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   FEATURE Stories
</P>
<P>
   ALANIS-MORISSETTE-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ The woman who sings
Alanis Morissette's new album sounds like a mess. In the 17 songs
on ``Supposed Former Infatuation Junkie'' (Maverick), which is to
be released on Tuesday, she has been attached to abusive men, she's
been stuffing and starving herself, she has taken too many
antibiotics, and she's been working herself to the point of
collapse. She has felt jealous, misunderstood, worthless; nothing,
from shopping to sex to wealth and worldwide popularity, has made
her happy. And every bit of trauma and frustration comes out in her
voice: in its harried vibrato and sudden yelping breaks, in its
banshee wails and caustic nasal turns. While her litany of
self-doubt is set in the past tense, the wounds still sound raw. By
Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   FILM AND VIDEO
</P>
<P>
   ARAB-ACTORS (Undated) _ The Arab-American actor Sayed Badreya
has had no problem finding work in Hollywood. With his dark beard
and his accented English, he has had his pick of parts as
terrorists, hijackers, kidnappers and Islamic militants. ``Usually
I play the bad guy role, a terrorist or someone,'' Badreya said by
telephone from Egypt, where he is on a film shoot with Al Pacino,
playing the head of the military wing of Hezbollah. After years of
virtual invisibility, Arab-Americans are finally finding prominence
in Hollywood movies _ as terrorists and villains. They are only the
latest in a long line of ethnic groups and nationalities cast in
sterotypical bad-guy roles, from American Indians to Germans to
Japanese to African Americans to Russians. By Laurie Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   HANGING-ROCK-VIDEO (Undated) _ A sweetly knowing look crosses
the face of the lovely young Miranda. ``You must learn to love
someone else apart from me, Sara,'' she says to a schoolmate. ``I
won't be here much longer.'' It never becomes clear how Miranda
knows that, but in Peter Weir's ``Picnic at Hanging Rock,'' as
mysterious as ever in two new video editions, just about everything
keeps us guessing. What we do know is that the year is 1900, that
the location is central Australia and that by sundown on Saint
Valentine's Day, Miranda (Anne Lambert) and two other students at
the brutally proper Appleyard College for young women will have
drifted away during a picnic as if hypnotized, disappearing among
the crags of the 500-foot-high volcanic formation called Hanging
Rock. By Peter M. Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE
</P>
<P>
   SWAN-LAKE-DANCE (Undated) _ Matthew Bourne'S production of
``Swan Lake'' opened on Broadway as something of an anomaly. Word
from Los Angeles, where the production played last year, was that
the show was touching but campy. Earlier reviews in England, where
the show originated, tended to dwell on what this ``Swan Lake'' was
not, particularly among the older dance critics. By Jennifer
Dunning. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ADAM-COOPER-DANCE (Undated) _ Adam Cooper looks more like a
young club hipster than an elegantly refined ballet prince, despite
his shining pedigree as a principal dancer who played such regal
roles at England's Royal Ballet. He is dancing a lead in ``Swan
Lake'' these days once more, but not as the ballet's lovesick
prince. Instead, Cooper plays a powerful male swan and his
counterpart, a sneering piece of rough trade, in Matthew Bourne's
exuberantly irreverent adaptation of ``Swan Lake,'' now playing on
Broadway at the Neil Simon Theater. By Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER
</P>
<P>
   CANBY-THEATER (Undated) _ Vincent Canby reviews Matthew Bourne's
``Swan Lake''; ``Footloose'' and ``Getting and Spending.
</P>
<P>
   MARTIN-SHORT-THEATER (Undated) _ On Broadway, Martin Short has
been lifting off every night in previews of the Roundabout Theater
Company revival of ``Little Me,'' the 1962 musical comedy for which
Neil Simon wrote the book. In the show, which opens on Nov. 12, he
plays not one but seven men in the life of Belle Poitrine, nee
Schlumpfert, the curvaceous beauty turned tell-all memoirist from
Drifter's Row (portrayed by Faith Prince). As those he works with
know, Short is a master at appearing spontaneous in a completely
scripted situation, creating a sense of suspense during a
performance that keeps an audience wondering what will happen next.
By Janny Scott.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   SUSANNAH-OPERA (Undated) _ Quick, name the most often performed
full-length American opera. It's not ``Porgy and Bess,'' which was
banished from the opera house for decades and branded a highbrow
musical. It's not ``West Side Story,'' which was intended for
Broadway despite the fact that Bernstein, late in life, gave it
some operatic trappings. And it's not ``Amahl and the Night
Visitors,'' which, since it was commissioned by a television
network, could not run longer than an hour. It's ``Susannah,'' with
music and libretto by Carlisle Floyd, a native of South Carolina.
By K. Robert Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   NUTCRACKER-MUSIC (Undated) _ In a new recording by Valery
Gergiev and the Kirov Orchestra (Philips 289 462 114-2; CD), to be
replicated in a concert at Carnegie Hall on Saturday evening, ``The
Nutcracker'' takes on a symphonic aspect of unsuspected power and
depth. By Lawrence B. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   POP MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   TAJ-MAHAL-MUSIC (Undated) _ A master of blues and folk styles on
guitar, banjo, and harmonica and a commanding singer with a raw,
immediately recognizable baritone, Taj Mahal has the deepest and
widest roots of any pop-music performer today. As the 54-song,
three-CD retrospective ``In Progress and Motion (1965-1998)'' amply
shows, he's pop's Walt Whitman, an optimist endlessly proclaiming
his oneness with the world's vernacular music. By Tony Scherman.
</P>
<P>
   ART
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON-BASEBALL-ART (Undated) _ Memorabilia of Shoeless Joe
Jackson, one of several White Sox players who was accused of
intentionally losing a World Series to the Cincinnati Reds will be
auction on Tuesday at Christie's in New York. Jackson still owns
the third-highest career batting average in baseball history, at
.356. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   ZOOM-TV (Boston) _ Listen up, Zoomers, Ubbi Dubbi linguists of
all stripes, childhood pleasures are coming around again. PBS is
reviving ``Zoom,'' the daily variety series for 6-to-12-year-olds
that was one of the most popular children's show of the 1970s.
Considered a coupling of ``Sesame Street'' and ``Laugh-In,'' the
series was second only to ``Masterpiece Theater'' in its power to
attract public-broadcasting viewers. By Susan Diesenhouse.
</P>
