<HEADLINE>
[START 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Kauffman program brings moms and daughters together _ as partners  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ Gwen Richards thought the newspaper advertisement
looked interesting. The program sounded like a great way to learn
about entrepreneurship while spending time with her teen-age
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Several months and a lot of hard work later, Gwen and Rickeena
Richards are ready to launch Keena and Me. They plan to write and
publish books that will improve communications between mothers and
adolescent daughters.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City family developed the concept while participating
in MADE-IT, a program developed and offered by the Kauffman Center
for Entrepreneurial Leadership at the Ewing Marion Kauffman
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The Richards' project, as well as one by Ashley and Betty Fowler
of Blue Springs, were selected to take part today in a national
competition at the Hyatt Regency Crown Center hotel. The Fowlers
are ready to launch Sweet Dreams, which will produce customized
pillows for holidays and special events.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how the local teams do in the national competition,
they're already winners. They turned good ideas into potential
businesses at a time in life when many parents and teens hardly
speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives mothers and daughters a way to reconnect as
business partners,'' said Mary Beth Izard, scholar-in-residence at
the Kauffman Center for Entrepreneurial Leadership. ``The learn how
to do it, they learn they can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother-daughter teams must include a girl entering eighth
grade in the fall and are selected based on personal interviews and
written applications.
</P>
<P>
   Teams participates in a weeklong summer program, where they
learn how to develop a business plan and launch a business. They
also receive additional mentoring and support.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons's we're doing it is because this provides
time for you to have one-on-one with your daughter,'' said Gwen
Richards.
</P>
<P>
   But the experience also gave her a much greater appreciation of
the work involved in running a company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned that a small business takes a lot of work, a lot of
preparation,'' she said. ``But I also learned that if you hang in
there, you can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The cover of the MADE-IT brochure says: ``We think mothers and
daughters should mind their own business.'' And they're absolutely
right.
</P>
<P>
   Adults often encourage boys to mow lawns or shovel snow to earn
extra money. The experience teaches them about marketing, time
management and numerous other skills.
</P>
<P>
   Let's encourage our daughters to explore entrepreneurial
options, too. We all need this training, and who know's where
businesses like Sweet Dreams and Keena and Me may lead?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
