<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
     THE WAR BETWEEN THE SOUTH AND THE NORTH
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ``I voluntarily choose the City of Angels over the wee, &LR; 
 &UR; dainty, elfin town where little cable cars run halfway to the &LR; 
 &UR; stars. ... Ultimately, my problem with San Francisco is twofold: &LR; 
 &UR; It's pokey and it's twee. Great cities are universes containing &LR; 
 &UR; many, many overlapping solar systems. ... San Francisco, by &LR; 
 &UR; contrast, has a one-dimensional personality whose defining &LR; 
 &UR; element is a cloying, self-satisfied smugness. ... It's a city &LR; 
 &UR; that needs to get over itself.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Essayist and social critic  &UR; Joe Queenan &LR; , in the L.A. Times
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONVERSATIONS WITH THE STARS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The folks responsible for the defunct Might magazine have a new
baby: Timothy McSweeney's Quarterly Concern, a magazine that
promises to publish a range of stories for which authors have
received kill fees from other publications.
</P>
<P>
   The first issue includes ``Four Short Interviews,'' conducted by
 &UR; Jill Stoddard &LR;  ``in Cambridge, Mass., between April 1997 and July
1998.'' Here's a 50 percent sampling:
</P>
<P>
   Stoddard begins Interview One, with  &UR; Al Gore &LR; : ``You have to pay
for that over where it says `cash register.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' says Gore. ``Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   In Interview Two, the author says to  &UR; Stephen King &LR; : ``You know,
I didn't think the doll thing was scary at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Really,'' replies King.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; ON, WISCONSIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It's the cheeseheads.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin is the trendiest state in the nation, says
Entertainment Weekly, noting that state's presence as a location or
fondly remembered home state in the TV programs, &LR;  ``That '70s
Show,'' ``Frasier'' and ``NewsRadio.''  &UR; Michael Moore  &LR; is planning
a sitcom about workers in Kenosha;  &UR; Leonardo DiCaprio  &LR; is nostalgic
for Chippewa Falls in ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time they mention Wisconsin, it makes me puff up,'' says
Wisconsin tourism chief  &UR; Moose Speros &LR; . ``I know what they're
mentioning is ethics and pride in country. It's a warm, fuzzy
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Alan Rickman &LR;  and  &UR; Helen Mirren &LR;  have opened in London in a
long-awaited National Theatre production of ``Antony and
Cleopatra,'' but the reviews have been terrible. The Guardian
called it a ``plodding spectacle rarely informed by powerful
passion''; the Evening Standard described Rickman as ``mounting
Miss Mirren's attractive, supine Cleopatra as if she were a mare he
would sooner not have got astride.'' All 54 performances were sold
out before the opening of the show.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;   &UR; - Diane Ladd &LR;  was in Memphis, Tenn., shooting ``Daddy and
Them,'' when a car accident occurred nearby, reports Los Angeles
magazine. Ladd picked up the phone, dialed 911 and said, ``I'm
Diane Ladd, from Hollywood, and I want an ambulance immediately.''
Help did arrive, ``but it's hard to say if Ladd's qualifier did the
trick,'' said the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - John Glenn &LR;  participating in the ``senior space shoot'' is
part of a contingency plan in case Social Security collapses, says
 &UR; Dan Mankin &LR; . ``When they run out of money,'' they can ``start
shooting everyone over 65 into orbit.''
</P>
<P>
   - Royal watcher  &UR; Penny Junor &LR; 's new book, `` &UR; Charles &LR; : Victim or
Villain?'' just published in England, said that  &UR; Princess &LR; 
 &UR; Diana &LR;  made death threats to  &UR; Camilla Parker Bowles &LR; , and that Di's
first affair was with her bodyguard Barry Mannakee, who was
transferred and then died in a car accident. Buckingham Palace says
it's hogwash.
</P>
<P>
   - It's not ``Tippecanoe and Tyler Too,'' but it's a try. San
Francisco supervisorial candidate  &UR; Rose Tsai &LR; 's campaign slogan:
``Vote for a Sigh (Tsai) of Relief.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Singers love ice cream. They love the way it feels sliding &LR; 
 &UR; down their gullets, cooling their excitable cords and calming &LR; 
 &UR; their nerves. ... Vanilla is a favorite.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  -  &LR; From ``Cinderella &AMP; Company, Backstage at the Opera With
 &UR; Cecilia Bartoli &LR; '' by  &UR; Manuela Hoelterhoff  &LR; (Knopf; $25). The
author cites  &UR; Maria Callas &LR; ' penchant for vanilla, and the passion
of  &UR; Rosa Ponselle &LR; , whose coach ``finally introduced her to butter
pecan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
