A9809 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-FEVER-HNS &LR;      10-27 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-FEVER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN AMAZED AT INTENSITY OF INTEREST IN HIS SPACEFLIGHT  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ John Glenn seems mystified about why his
return to space aboard the shuttle Discovery is receiving so much
attention and good will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he confessed recently. ``It's overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   His best guess? A vast wave of national nostalgia over his 1962
Mercury flight, a milestone that placed the United States in orbit
alongside the former Soviet Union. American astronauts later beat
the Soviets in a dramatic race to the moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It occurred at a time when I think we needed a success,'' the
77-year-old Glenn recalled. ``In retrospect it was almost like we
turned a corner in our national psyche.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's amazed at the intensity of interest in his second
flight, which is scheduled to blast off on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio senator figured there would be flurries of publicity
when he was selected for the mission in January and right before
the shuttle launch.
</P>
<P>
   But the levels of attentiveness have continued to rise, perhaps
fueled by cover stories in national news magazines and a prime time
segment on CBS-TV's ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn has arguably become the nation's most prominent senior
citizen and anticipation about his return to space is spreading as
liftoff approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Apollo astronaut Buzz Aldrin has urged the nation to whisper
``Godspeed, John Glenn'' when Discovery lifts off, echoing the
comments of Mercury astronaut Scott Carpenter when his colleague
and friend blasted off for the first time 36 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The citizens of Perth, Australia, plan to illuminate their city
as Discovery flies over, just as they did when Glenn's tiny Mercury
capsule soared above them.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the shuttle will not pass directly over Perth in
its orbit has not dampened enthusiasm at all, and Commander Curt
Brown promises to put the Discovery on an angle that will allow the
crew to view the light show, weather permitting. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The Aussies are not the only international participants in the
Glenn phenomenon. Several of the 54 satellite TV trucks jamming
parking areas at the Kennedy Space Center are operated by crews
from Japan or the member nations of the European Space Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Marketers also recognize a hot property when they see one. In
addition to the usual souvenir T-shirts, medallions and buttons,
the toy company Mattel has expanded its line to include an action
figure of Glenn and models of his Friendship 7 capsule and the
shuttle Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn insists the tidal wave of interest in him, then and now,
would have been afforded whoever logged the country's first orbital
mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not for me,'' he says of the ticker tape parade in
New York, an appearance before a joint session of Congress and the
past accolades that established a foundation for his successes in
business and politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never get up every morning thinking that I am a hero,''
Glenn insists.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts, however, believe that Glenn has once again struck
a chord with a national psyche in search of a dose of euphoria.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are multiple reasons why the public is caught up in
this,'' speculates William Burrows, journalist and author of the
recently published book, ``This New Ocean: The Story of the First
Age of Space.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons is that people are fed up with the food
fight in Washington right now, and they are looking for something
that is kind of ennobling, he said. ``Here you have something that
is playing counterpoint to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers believe a catastrophic accident on this mission
would produce a national sense of gloom every bit as powerful as
the current exhilaration.
</P>
<P>
   But many others believe the country is better prepared deal with
an accident because of the Challenger disaster and the multiple
crises Americans faced aboard Russia's Mir space station.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense, the public has come along and understands the
reality of exploratory adventures,'' said Andrew Chaikin, the
author of ``America on the Moon: The Voyages of the Apollo
Astronauts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can hope (a catastrophe) would not shut down the program,''
said Chaikin. ``The potential is probably there, but maybe we are
at a different point now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it's necessary to say those of us who ride these
machines, including John Glenn, are expendable,'' said Carpenter,
who also participates in under sea exploration. ``And for good
cause.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
