<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Nov. 1)  
(JT) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Cassatt Retrospective In Chicago and Boston &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``No woman has the right to draw like that,'' said Edgar Degas
of Mary Cassatt. You can take the measure of her talent yourself
when viewing ``Mary Cassatt: Modern Woman,'' her first major
retrospective for nearly 30 years, at the Art Institute of Chicago.
The exhibition, which opened on Oct. 13 and runs through Jan. 10,
brings together about 100 paintings, pastels, drawings and prints
from more than 40 museums and private collections. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Born in Pittsburgh and brought up in Philadelphia, Mary Cassatt
left home in 1865 at age 21 to travel and study in Europe. In 1874
she settled in Paris. Working with artists like Degas, Monet and
Pissarro, Cassatt made her way to the top of the art world when
painting was the province of men. She was the only American invited
to exhibit with the Impressionists. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By the 1890s, Cassatt had started to produce more modern works
in subject matter and style, with bold patterns, flattened
perspectives and simplified designs. Cassatt's signature works of
mothers and children are well represented in the show, as are her
lesser-known early pieces painted in Italy and Spain, her interior
paintings and her innovative color prints. The three-piece mural
``Modern Woman,'' which depicted young women chasing fame, plucking
the fruits of knowledge and participating in the arts, has long
since disappeared, but the exhibition includes a large photomural
of it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Art Institute of Chicago, 111 South Michigan Avenue, is open
daily. Dated and timed tickets are required, and can be bought by
calling (800) 929-5800 (or at the door if available). Admission: $5
on Tuesday; $10 on Monday, Wednesday and Thursday; $14 Friday
through Sunday (plus a $3.25 charge for telephone orders).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cassatt retrospective will be at the Museum of Fine Arts in
Boston from Feb. 14 to May 9, and at the National Gallery of Art in
Washington from June 6 to Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Time and Again: New Year's at Versailles &LR;
</P>
<P>
   With all the focus on ushering in the 21st century, travelers to
France can celebrate a New Year's Eve this year that takes them to
the 18th century instead. The event is called Le Bal du Roy, the
king's ball, and it will take place in the palace at Versailles in
what the organizers say is the first New Year's Eve party there
since the French Revolution. There will be 650 guests dining in the
Galerie des Batailles on a meal inspired by Louis XV's table, to be
prepared by Gerard Vie, of Les Trois Marches restaurant in
Versailles, which has two Michelin stars. After dinner, guests will
stroll through the king and queen's private quarters. As the king
and queen did at midnight of Jan. 1, from the Hall of Mirrors they
will view fireworks over the gardens. Then they will repair to the
King's Chapel for a Baroque music concert. Throughout the
festivities, costumed dancers will demonstrate the latest moves of
the 1780s (contemporary guests will wear black tie).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the ball, which will run from 8:30 p.m. to 2 a.m.,
is $1,300. The event is being organized by Olivier Fresnay, a
French businessman, and part of the proceeds will go toward
restoring art and furniture at the palace. Information is available
at (212) 355-0400 or e-mail at lebalduroy(AT)aol.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For those who would like an approach to both the 21st and 18th
centuries, there are plans to hold a bigger ball there on Dec. 31,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Renting Cars in Europe For United States Prices &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Travelers to Europe with uncertain itineraries may benefit from
the Kemwel Holiday Autos' new Carpass, a three-day voucher that
circumvents the high cost of renting cars locally. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Carpass allows for three consecutive days of car rental that
can be used anytime. Vouchers must be bought in advance in the
United States, with the price depending on the kind of car and the
country involved. A subcompact, for example, costs $79 in Germany
and $159 in France; an intermediate-size car costs $179 in Britain
and $369 in Italy. Once in Europe, a renter activates the voucher
by calling a local Kemwel Holiday Autos supplier 24 hours before
the car is wanted. The pass is available for Austria, Britain,
France, Germany, Italy and Switzerland. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vacationers who want to cross borders need to make advance
arrangements with Kemwel when buying Carpasses. Unused portions are
refundable. Call (800) 678-0678.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Deerfield Museum Depicts Rural Refinements &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The western Massachusetts museum village of Historic Deerfield
has added something to its 18th- and 19th-century museum houses:
the Flynt Center of Early New England Life. The inaugural
exhibition, ``Pursuing Refinement in Rural New England:
1750-1850,'' tells of Deerfield families who strove, in the words
of the Rev. Jonathan Ashley, an 18th-century Congregational
minister, to embrace ``useful improvements,'' while avoiding pride
and vanity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although the elegant 18th-century looking glass and silk
garments in the exhibition may have tempted vanity, a desk and
bookcase made of mahogany and pine emphasized its owner's
education. Nothing was too insignificant to signal refinement: a
chamber pot may have been displayed by day to signify that its
owner didn't have to make nighttime trips to an outdoor privy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,500 pieces from Historic Deerfield's superb collection of
decorative arts and furniture made and used in the Connecticut
River Valley are now installed on the Flynt Center's second floor,
called the Museum's Attic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here too are examples of the pursuit of refinement, like the
double-blown glass door handles that often replaced simple wooden
doorknobs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Historic Deerfield and the Flynt Center are open daily except on
Thanksgiving, Christmas Eve and Christmas Day. A $12 fee includes
all 14 museum houses and the Flynt Center and is valid for the week
of purchase. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Pursuing Refinement in Rural New England: 1750 to 1950'' will
run until 2000. For further information call (413) 774-5581.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
