<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-FOXX28-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  FOX, HOEFFEL RACE A RECORD $ETTER
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Kane
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Oct. 27 -- With a flood of last-minute $1,000 checks
arriving by the bushel, Rep. Jon Fox and Democratic challenger
Joseph Hoeffel have engaged in the most aggressive fundraising
drive for a U.S. House seat in Pennsylvania history.
</P>
<P>
   One of the campaigns went searching so far for campaign cash
that it snagged a $1,000 check from an American living in London.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the opponents have so far raised $2.69 million for the
rematch of their 1996 battle, in which Fox, the incumbent, beat
Hoeffel, the Montgomery County commissioner, by 84 votes.
</P>
<P>
   That slim margin has focused national attention on the 13th
District race, as House Republicans are trying to hold onto and
expand their thin 21-seat majority. And a hefty majority of the
11th hour contributions from political parties, other congressmen
and special interests have splashed into Fox's campaign coffers.
</P>
<P>
   From Oct. 1 to Oct. 24, Fox raised at least $223,271, according
to reports filed with the Federal Election Commission in
Washington. Over the entire two-year election cycle Fox has raised
$1.65 million, meaning 13.5 percent of that war chest came in
little more than three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And he probably raised many more thousands of dollars, since,
from Oct. 15 until election day, candidates are only required to
report donations of $1,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Of those big-money contributions, Fox took in $105,750 in just
nine days, Oct. 15-24. This huge money drop has allowed Fox to
virtually erase his cash deficit to Hoeffel, who has long benefited
from the fact that Fox had to spend about $800,000 last spring to
beat several primary challengers.
</P>
<P>
   In October Hoeffel has raised at least $130,155, almost 13
percent of the $1.03 million he has raised over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   And, without a primary opponent, Hoeffel has been able to
stockpile his money for the most important days of the campaign. In
the first two weeks of October Hoeffel spent more money, $289,688,
than Fox, $237,293.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to be outspent two-to-one,'' said Ken
Horowitz, Hoeffel's spokesman, referring to the 1996 spending
margin Fox enjoyed, ``which is one of the clear differences between
then and now.''
</P>
<P>
   In such a tight race, campaign watchdogs say it's normal for
lots of money to pour in during the home stretch of the race, but
they warn that the money can also come from some of the most
dubious sources. ``At that point, you're scrounging around wherever
you can for money,'' said Ed Davis of Common Cause, the
Washington-based group that lobbies for campaign reform.
</P>
<P>
   The last-ditch fundraising has come from predictable sources: in
the past two weeks Hoeffel has raised more than 25 percent of his
money from unions, while Fox has raked in donations from businesses
such as GM, Bell Atlantic and CoreStates.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeffel also received $5,000 on Oct. 17 from People for the
American Way, the liberal civil liberties group that has mounted an
ad campaign defending President Clinton against impeachment
charges. Fox took $1,000 on Oct. 24 from the Log Cabin Republicans,
an openly homosexual group supporting Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, lawmakers who face little or no opposition are
dumping their money into the Fox-Hoeffel race. Fox has received
$1,000 checks from the political action committees of Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott and Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, as well as
a $1,000 personal check from his old colleague, Montgomery County
Commissioner Mario Mele.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeffel's campaign received $1,000 checks from the PACs of
Pittsburgh Mayor Tom Murphy and Philadelphia Rep. Chaka Fattah --
not to mention another $1,000 from the U.S. citizen in London,
whose check was funnelled through Democratic headquarters in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The total amounts raised by Hoeffel and Fox, at least $2.69
million, is the greatest amount ever by Pennsylvania opponents for
a House seat. This year's House candidates in Scranton -- Democrat
Patrick Casey, the son of former Gov. Bob Casey, and Republican Don
Sherwood, a local car dealer -- will spend more money than Fox and
Hoeffel. But that's because Sherwood has dumped more than $1
million of his own money into the race. Their combined fundraising
from outside sources might not top $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to FEC records, the only other House race in
Pennsylvania that compares to this year's Fox-Hoeffel duel came in
1994, when Fox beat then-Rep. Marjorie Margolies-Mezvinsky. The
opponents raised more than $2.58 million that year.
</P>
<P>
   And there's still more money to be had in the next few days.
Both campaigns say they will keep taking in checks until election
day, and that a well-financed get-out-the-vote effort could
determine the winner in a year when turnout is expected to be low.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (campaign) finance director always wants more money,''
said Fox, adding, ``Getting out the vote is key to this election.''
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
