<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9820 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY28-COX     10-27 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON MIXES POLITICS AND POLICY OVER SOCIAL SECURITY
 &HT;    500&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Mixing politics with policy, President Clinton used
a forum on women and Social Security on Tuesday to challenge
Republican leaders to deal with him on reforming the system next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking off the forum, in which five women told how Social
Security and the Family and Medical Leave Act had helped them in
times of crisis, Clinton said he expected to work with Republican
leaders, including Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott on a
bipartisan plan to restore the system's long-term solvency.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming the Republican-led Congress had made time for the
insurance industry to kill a patient's bill of rights, the tobacco
industry to kill anti-smoking legislation, and for special
interests to kill campaign finance reform, Clinton said: ``I think
the Senate majority leader will be able to find time to work with
me to save Social Security. And I certainly hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott, R-Miss., quickly issued a statement saying, ``I am
committed to genuine Social Security reform and, after the
election, I will work with anyone who shares that commitment. The
president's credibility crisis leaves many wondering whether he can
be trusted with such an important policy issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-level exchange came one week before congressional
elections. In the campaign, Democrats have been warning that
Republicans may try to use much of the federal budget surplus for
tax relief rather than for Social Security reform.
</P>
<P>
   At the forum Tuesday in the White House East Room, Clinton
stressed that the only way to ensure reform would be to elect a
Congress ``100 percent committed'' to reserving the surplus for
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has called for a White House conference on Social
Security reform for Dec. 8 and 9, and plans to follow that with
negotiations with congressional leaders next year leading to
passage of a bipartisan reform bill. Without reform, the program
will be unable to fully pay benefits beginning in 2032.
</P>
<P>
   In a prelude to the December conference, the women selected for
the forum stressed not only Social Security's guaranteed benefits
for the elderly, but also survivors benefits for children of
deceased workers and disability benefits for the families of
seriously ill or injured workers. Clinton noted that about
one-third of the 44 million Americans receiving Social Security
benefits are either disabled or survivors.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the administration has been careful not to tip its hand
by revealing the kinds of reform it would support, and Clinton
noted the difficult decisions that will be faced between offering
individuals greater flexibility in investing their savings _ with
the possibility of higher returns _ while still providing the
guaranteed security that Social Security now offers, particularly
for women.
</P>
<P>
   A report by the president's National Economic Council
highlighted the importance of Social Security to women. It noted
women generally live longer, earn and save less, and are more
dependent on the program to keep them out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Women live longer than men. The average 65-year-old woman has a
life expectancy to 85 compare to 81 for men.
</P>
<P>
   Elderly women are more likely than elderly men _ 13 percent to 7
percent _ to live in poverty, while the rate among unmarried
elderly women (widowed, divorced or never married) is close to 19
percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Of those unmarried elderly women, 51 percent receive their total
income from Social Security, compared to 39 percent for unmarried
elderly men and 36 percent for married elderly couples.
</P>
<P>
   Because women move in and out of the workplace more frequently
than men, and because their pay levels are generally lower, women
are less likely to have adequate pensions or savings than men.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged Congress to expand the Family and Medical Leave
Act so that time taken for family emergencies would not be deducted
from a person's eligibility for vesting or other pension benefits.
He noted that women are more likely than men to use the act to care
for sick children, parents and spouses.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 1824EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
