<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: A MUSICAL `RAVEN'; MOSCOW THEATER CENTENNIAL; AWARDS
FOR CHOREOGRAPHERS; THEATER TICKETS FOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a performance believed to be the first since 1909,
the pianist Margaret Leng Tan will resurrect Arthur Bergh's setting
of the Edgar Allan Poe poem ``The Raven'' in a Halloween
celebration at 8 p.m. Saturday at St. Ann's, the landmark church at
Clinton and Montague streets in Brooklyn Heights.
</P>
<P>
   An orchestral version of the work, conducted by Bergh, had its
premiere at Carnegie Hall in April 1909, three months after the
premiere of the piano version. Poe will be the focal figure in the
celebration, assembled by Arts at St. Ann's and Hal Willner, a
record producer.
</P>
<P>
   Taking part in readings will be actors and musicians including
Steve Buscemi, Lili Taylor, Colin Quinn, John Ventimiglia, Umar Bin
Hassan and John Cale. Musical settings will be supplied by Garth
Hudson, Elysian Fields, Mark Bingham and Lenny Pickett.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow Nights
</P>
<P>
   Where Stanislavsky developed the Method and Chekhov achieved
acclaim with ``The Seagull,'' elite Russian actors and celebrities
gathered on Monday night. The site was the Moscow Arts Theater, and
the occasion was the celebration of its 100th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   With Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, members of Parliament and
Russian directors looking on, there were parodies of plays,
sentimental and comic odes to the influential theater, and a
message from President Boris Yeltsin: ``Without your theater, the
history of national culture would be inconceivable.''
</P>
<P>
   Second Act
</P>
<P>
   The kind of news that would set anyone to dancing has come to
the winners of the second annual Doris Duke Awards for New Work for
modern dance choreographers.
</P>
<P>
   Twyla Tharp and Meredith Monk will receive $100,000 each; Eiko
and Koma will receive $40,000, as will Martha Clarke; John Jasperse
and David Dorfman will each receive $15,000. The Doris Duke Awards
for New Work are financed by a $1.8 million grant last year from
the Doris Duke Charitable Foundation, based in New York, to the
American Dance Festival, in Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Twofer
</P>
<P>
   Should children be introduced to live theater? Those who answer
``yes'' can find their reward through the third annual Kids Night
on Broadway. This program offers children from 6 to 18 in nearly 50
participating cities _ from Amherst, N.Y., and Grand Rapids, Mich.,
to Wilmington, Del., and Tulsa, Okla. _ a free ticket to a Broadway
show when they are accompanied by an adult with a full-price
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Kids Night, created in 1996 by the League of American
Theaters and Producers and the Theater Development Fund, most
cities are offering a 7 p.m. curtain and parking and restaurant
discounts. In New York, where 16 shows are participating, Kids
Nights are Jan. 26 and Feb. 2. National information may be obtained
from (888) 411-2929; the New York metropolitan area number is (212)
302-4111.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
