<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9834 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SOCSEC-HNS &LR;      10-27 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SOCSEC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS 75 MILLION BABY BOOMERS FACE DIRE FINANCIAL TIMES IF
SOCIAL SECURITY ISN'T RESCUED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, focusing on a favorite
Democratic theme a week before Election Day, said Tuesday that
Congress must save Social Security now or 75 million baby boomers
could face dire financial times in their sunset years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reiterated the ``save Social Security first'' pledge he
made in his State of the Union Address last January and said that
insolvency in the retirement account would hurt women most.
</P>
<P>
   The president, at a White House event featuring and attended
mostly by women, assailed Republicans for trying to thwart his plan
to earmark funds in a projected budget surplus to rescue the
financially ailing government retirement program.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who spent much of his speech deriding GOP partisanship,
used partisan tones in criticizing congressional Republicans for
proposing that the surplus be used to fund tax cuts rather than
Social Security. The president's comments followed recent remarks
from GOP members of Congress who said they would find it difficult
to cooperate with him on many issues, including what to do with the
budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that's just election-season rhetoric,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not opposed to tax cuts,'' Clinton said at the White House
event that featured five women who have benefited from Social
Security. ``I'm just opposed to using the surplus to fund tax
cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, citing White House data, said Social Security accounts
for 51 percent of the income for unmarried women older than age 65
but only 39 percent of the earnings for single men at that age.
This disparity is especially troubling because women have a higher
life expectancy than men and therefore have greater need for a
pension, Clinton said, using information from his National Economic
Council's Interagency Working Group on Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   At the event, the president proposed permitting married people
to receive a 75-percent survivor benefit following the death of a
spouse, compared to the current system that allows surviving
husbands and wives to receive only 50 percent of the monthly
benefits they received as a married couple. Under the president's
proposal, married people who opt for the 75 percent survivor
benefit would receive reduced benefits while they are both alive.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also proposed letting workers who take time off to care
for a newborn child or sick relative under the federal Family and
Medical Leave Act have that time count toward Social Security
vesting requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should not be a partisan issue,'' Clinton said of saving
the Social Security trust fund. He urged Congress to start
``putting people over politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, in a nod to Democratic senators facing tough
re-election fights, said his proposals are mere extensions of ideas
first endorsed by Barbara Boxer of California and Carol
Moseley-Braun of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, appearing with Clinton at the event,
echoed the president in saying that the budget surplus must be
protected against ``risky budget-busting tax schemes.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Clinton and Gore at a table in front of more than 100
invited guests were the five women who said they were grateful for
Social Security: Molly Lozoff of Miami, a retired Realtor who
raised four children by herself after her husband died; Wilma Haga
of Bristol, Tenn., a retired school cafeteria worker whose husband
died about eight years ago; Bernice Meyer of Seattle, a 49-year-old
home healthcare aide whose primary pension will be Social Security;
Lucy Sanchez of Washington, a wife and daughter who has had to use
the Family and Medical Leave Act to care for her sick husband and
mother; and Tyra Brown of Washington, a Howard University student
who was a teenager when her mother died, leaving the family
dependent on Social Security survivor benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was there for me,'' Brown said of Social Security. ``I want
it to be there in the future.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
