<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9856 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NOTES-ART-NYT &LR;      10-27 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEPARATING BOYS AND GIRLS  
 PLOTTING INTO THE NIGHT  
 COVERING JOHN GLENN  
 A COMEDOWN FOR NBC 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(Eds: Program times are for New York area.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``All boys, all day'' is how Rich Cronin, president
of Fox Family Channels, described the new cable channel his company
plans to start next year. On cue, a dozen slightly awestruck
third-grade boys from East Harlem trotted into the midtown
Manhattan hotel room where Cronin was making his announcement
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Before feminists in the room could object, Cronin announced
another new channel _ and the boys' female classmates entered.
</P>
<P>
   The children had been borrowed from P.S. 101, the Andrew Draper
Academy, on East 111th Street (a former teacher there is the sister
of a Fox Family Web-site executive) for Fox Family's announcement
that it would start the Boyz Channel and the Girlz Channel,
offering entertainment and educational programming (wonder if
they'll tackle spelling?) geared specifically and separately to
each sex, for ages up to 14.
</P>
<P>
   At 9 p.m. the channels will switch to programs for parents, and
these, too, will be gender-specific, focusing on ``parenting
issues'' in raising boys or girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not stereotyping,'' Cronin said. ``You have Boy Scouts
and Girl Scouts, boys' clubs and girls' clubs, boys' schools and
girls' schools, camps for boys and camps for girls, magazines for
boys and magazines for girls.''
</P>
<P>
   It is ``a fact of life,'' he said, that there are some
television shows that boys love and girls hate, and vice versa. He
said Fox's research had shown that children want separate channels,
and that Fox would develop programs for them based on what children
say they like.
</P>
<P>
   Cronin also presides over the Fox Kids Network, carried by Fox's
broadcast stations on weekday afternoons and Saturday mornings,
where a problem for some advertisers is that the lineup attracts
far more boys than girls, with shows like ``Power Rangers,''
``Spider-Man'' and ``Young Hercules.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon, the network most watched by children, uses a
different strategy, trying to develop shows that both sexes will
watch, including some with female lead characters, like ``The
Secret World of Alex Mack'' and ``The Mystery Files of Shelby
Woo.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   Plotting Into the Night
</P>
<P>
   CBS is quietly putting the pieces in place for its new
late-night show with Craig Kilborn. The network has selected Billy
Kimball, a comedy writer and producer, to be the executive producer
of the show, which will replace Tom Snyder's talk show as the 12:35
companion to David Letterman's ``Late Show'' early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Kimball's appointment is expected to be announced Wednesday. A
one-time editor of the Harvard Lampoon, Kimball has mostly been
associated with the Comedy Central channel in recent years, having
worked on its satirical political specials like ``Indecision '92''
and ``State of the Union Undressed.'' Earlier in his career he was
an Emmy-nominated comedy writer for HBO's ``Not Necessarily the
News.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilborn's show could start as early as February or as late as
April. The network will not rush it onto the air until it is
convinced that the show is ready, a network executive said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder has agreed to stay on with his show until Kilborn's
starts, the CBS executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Lassally, executive producer of Snyder's show, who
previously held the same job on Letterman's show, will stay on as a
consultant to Letterman's production company, Worldwide Pants,
advising on both Letterman's and Kilborn's shows.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Covering John Glenn
</P>
<P>
   Anyone wondering about the extent of interest in 77-year-old
John Glenn's return to space, almost four decades after he became
the first American to orbit the earth, could get an idea from this
week's television listings.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are all the television news outfits, both broadcast and
cable, covering Glenn's scheduled launching aboard the space
shuttle Discovery on Thursday live, but a variety of specials is
being served up all week.
</P>
<P>
   Two networks took advantage of the link in many people's minds
between Glenn's original flight and Walter Cronkite's voice.
Cronkite's broadcast of the 1962 launching and landing ranks among
the best-remembered events in the legendary CBS anchor's career.
</P>
<P>
   But Cronkite will not be working for CBS News on Thursday at the
Kennedy Space Center. He will be part of the two-man commentary
team (with Miles O'Brien) covering the launching for CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite also narrated the first documentary in a series of
three on Monday night on the Discovery Channel.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, A&AMP;E's ``Biography'' series presented a new
episode, ``John Glenn: The All-American Hero,'' and CNN showed
``The John Glenn Story.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, PBS offers a one-hour documentary, ``John
Glenn: American Hero,'' written and produced by Blaine Baggett, a
filmmaker who was among the candidates to be the first journalist
in space, before that idea was abandoned in the wake of the
Challenger disaster.
</P>
<P>
   An MSNBC commentator for the launching will be Scott Carpenter,
one of Glenn's ``teammates'' among the original Mercury astronauts.
Fox News Channel, the third all-news cable channel, will have
another early astronaut, James Lovell Jr.
</P>
<P>
   On the day itself, NBC's ``Today'' show anchors, Katie Couric
and Matt Lauer, will both be at Cape Canaveral, as will Al Roker,
the weatherman. The show's ABC rival, ``Good Morning America,'' has
sent Kevin Newman (his co-anchor, Lisa McRee, will stay in New
York) and its weatherman, Spencer Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Thalia Assuras, the CBS ``This Morning'' news anchor, will be
there, but the program's co-anchors, Mark McEwen and Jane Robelot,
will not. Ms. Robelot had her first child, a son, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   A Comedown for NBC
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the changes at the top of NBC's programming
department, the network suffered through one of its worst ratings
weeks in recent years last week, finishing last among viewers, and
third among viewers between the ages of 18 and 49, the network's
main target group.
</P>
<P>
   Fox zoomed to the top, on the strength of two World Series
games. CBS was second in total viewers, ABC was third, and NBC,
which relied on a lot of repeat programming, especially on its
powerhouse Thursday night, finished last. Among young adult viewers
the order was Fox, ABC, NBC and CBS.
</P>
<P>
   NBC also got some bad news from Monday's ratings, when ``Will
and Grace,'' a new comedy it had been counting on to grow into a
substantial hit, was beaten badly by a repeat of CBS' ``Everybody
Loves Raymond.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
</TEXT>
