<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-MARIJUANA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE DRUG OFFICIAL URGES DEFEAT OF MARIJUANA INITIATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House drug adviser on Tuesday urged
voters in five states and the District of Columbia to reject ballot
initiatives that would legalize marijuana for medical uses, saying
that medical treatments shouldn't be decided ``by popular vote.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To be blunt, these initiatives would result in the
quasi-legalization of marijuana,'' Barry McCaffrey, White House
drug policy director, told a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
   He said passing the initiatives would send the wrong message to
young Americans, adding that the use of marijuana among minors has
risen over the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey said decisions to use certain drugs for medical use
should be based on science rather than politics. ``Medicine is not
determined by popular vote,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Following the lead of California, which passed a similar measure
in 1996, voters in Alaska, Arizona, the District of Columbia,
Nevada, Oregon and Washington state will find initiatives on their
Nov. 3 ballots. The measures would allow physicians, under defined
conditions, to obtain and dispense marijuana as a palliative to
their patients.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona voters already passed an initiative legalizing medical
marijuana in 1996, but the referendum was block by the state
legislature when it discovered that the measure also allowed
doctors to prescribe 116 other drugs, including LSD, heroin and
PCP.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno has strongly denounced the
initiatives, saying that scientists have not proven conclusively
the medical benefits of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that the determination as to whether there is a
medical use for marijuana should be made at the ballot box,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the initiatives say there are many cancer and AIDS
patients for whom marijuana is the most effective drug in relieving
nausea and other debilitating side-effects of treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has told us that they support the right of
suffering patients to use medical marijuana,'' said Wayne Turner,
who helped organize the ballot initiative in the District of
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey suggested that if a certain chemical in marijuana is
found to help patients, doctors could prescribe pills containing
only that chemical rather than allowing the patient to smoke the
narcotic.
</P>
<P>
   ``With pills or patches, there's no need to be giving a joint or
a bong to terminally-ill patients,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, proponents of the initiatives say that research has
shown that smoking marijuana is more effective than pills and
patches containing THC _ the chemical found in marijuana that some
scientists and physicians believe is beneficial to terminally-ill
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the passage of California's initiative two years ago,
state and federal authorities have made a persistent effort to
prevent people from selling to marijuana individuals who obtain a
doctor's prescription.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Fratello, spokesman for Los Angeles-based Americans for
Medical Rights _ which is coordinating the ballot drives Alaska,
Nevada, Oregon and Washington state _ said in a statement that his
group hopes to put the medical marijuana initiatives on more states
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to change national policy, but we know we will
have to win more battles in 1999 and 2000 before that happens,''
said Fratello, whose group will spend $2 million on advertisements
supporting the state initiatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
