<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9872 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN28-COX     10-27 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Once upon a time, `small meow' helped candidates roar
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The headline on a story about political contributions the other
day really struck me. It said, ``Georgia `fat cat' contributors
only make a small meow.'' Add my family to that small meow list.
</P>
<P>
   We always put a political contribution in the budget, along with
a tithe for the church. But looking at today's contributors, I am
woefully embarrassed. The Home Depot chairman and his wife,
$52,500, for goodness' sake!
</P>
<P>
   The most I ever remember my parents contributing to any
candidate was $10.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, $10 out of the salary of a sawmill operator during
the Depression wasn't chicken feed. And the spirit was certainly
all right. If you believe in the candidate, said my father, help
him out. Unfortunately, he helped out Herbert Hoover with his $10 _
and spent the rest of his life regretting it. A lifelong Democrat,
he was turned off by Al Smith's plan to repeal Prohibition,
although he would have been the first to admit that it wasn't
working. Our woods were full of moonshiners. His only hope was that
his $10 didn't help Mr. Hoover much.
</P>
<P>
   We thought a lot about that $10 gone awry, but we never doubted
the impulse behind it. If you believe ... help. Later, the $10
dwindled to $5, and after I grew up and was making $12 a week on
The Mobile(Ala.) Press, I dropped to $2.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that comforts me is that, in those days,
candidates did not have to buy television time and my $2 may have
bought them some ink for cardboard signs ornamenting all the
roadside trees in Mobile County. Or, even better, it would have
bought 10 gallons of gas for the campaigner's car. Remember when
``a dollar's worth of regular'' would practically fill your tank?
</P>
<P>
   Tithing for the church was absolutely essential. I don't
remember the theology behind that. You don't hear much about
tithing in church these days. They call it stewardship, and pledges
run into the thousands. But my parents were practically doomsday
tithers. They believed if you didn't give a 10th of your income,
God washed his hands of you.
</P>
<P>
   And the Reader's Digest came out and supported that view. It
reported that interviews with men in bread lines disclosed that
nobody who tithed was ever forced to stand in a bread line. I can't
believe that, but I share my mother's view that there's some
spiritual connection between giving a 10th to the church and
getting along happily with your life.
</P>
<P>
   She had a story about that. She was repairing an old house they
had bought down on St. Andrews Bay in Florida, and its needs were
many _ paint and plaster and plumbing parts. She had practically
run out of money except for $30 she owed on her tithe at the
neighborhood Methodist church. She was sorely tempted to use that
$30 to keep the work going on the old house. To combat that urge,
she walked straight to the post office and mailed it to the church,
fearing that if she waited for Sunday, she would weaken and buy
paint.
</P>
<P>
   She was walking back to the house, shuffling through dead leaves
and wondering how to cope with repairs, when she saw blowing down
the sidewalk toward her three $10 bills.
</P>
<P>
   My children have a hard time believing that story. But I don't.
</P>
<P>
   She said it happened, and as long as she lived, she earmarked
part of her little, never adequate, income for the church _ and a
dollar or two for the fellow down the road who was running for
office. I hope he recognized that the impulse was big if the
offering was ``a small meow.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
