<HEADER>
A9883 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADAM-COOPER-DANCE-ART     10-27 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADAM-COOPER-DANCE-ART-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOLTING HIS ROYAL PLUMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Scott Ambler and Adam Cooper is being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 1)  
 (af)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adam Cooper looks more like a young club hipster than an
elegantly refined ballet prince, despite his shining pedigree as a
principal dancer who played such regal roles at England's Royal
Ballet. He is dancing a lead in ``Swan Lake'' these days once more,
but not as the ballet's lovesick prince.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Cooper plays a powerful male swan and his counterpart,
a sneering piece of rough trade, in Matthew Bourne's exuberantly
irreverent adaptation of ``Swan Lake,'' now playing on Broadway at
the Neil Simon Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The characters are Bourne's re-envisioning of Odette, the white
swan, and Odile, her evil look-alike. Although they are not played
here by a ballerina, they have the same dire effect on the prince
on whom they lavish their attentions.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper did not hesitate to accept Bourne's invitation to play
the parts in the first production, in 1996 (he alternates in them
with Will Kemp in the Broadway staging). ``I just thought: `How
exciting. It's about time a man played the swan,' '' Cooper
recalled in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   To everyone's amazement, the show was so popular it was moved to
London's West End, the equivalent of Broadway, then toured to Los
Angeles before opening last month in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming up with the character of the swan was hard because you
had so many restrictions, like no facial expressions,'' Cooper said
of his work with Bourne. ``Basically you had to do it with your
eyes. The feeling had to come from within. And you can't use your
arms normally. When we were trying to get the duets together, I
couldn't just lift. It had to be with my wing. That was kind of
hard. But basically I think we were thinking of trying to represent
a sense of freedom as a swan. A sense of knowing, a sense of beauty
and of grace, but also a sense of caution toward the prince
initially.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's portrayal of the evil swan, whom he calls ``the
stranger,'' is modeled somewhat on Brad Pitt. ``Somebody who could
walk into a room and everybody wants him, men and women,'' he said.
``The stranger is not afraid to do anything to get what he wants.
And to use anybody to get what he wants. And he has no conscience
about it.'' He laughed. ``Which is (italics)fabulous(end italics)
to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to express yourself in today's way in ballet when
you're stuck in a pair of white tights and a tunic holding up a
ballerina for two hours. Men have always been the background to the
ballerina in ballet. He may get the odd solo now and then, but
that's the man's job, basically. There still aren't that many
ballets around where the man is the main (italics)guy,(end italics)
and that's hard for men.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper had to quit the Royal Ballet for Bourne's ``Swan Lake.''
He describes himself as an accidental star in the ballet company, a
dancer who got the big roles and the promotions because he was tall
and could learn fast enough to replace injured dancers at the last
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Once, in the middle of the ballet, he went on in the lead male
role in Kenneth MacMillan's ``Mayerling,'' guided a little by the
onstage murmurings of ``stand here, stand there'' from Fiona
Chadwick, another Royal principal and one of the dancers playing
the queen mother in Bourne's ``Swan Lake.''
</P>
<P>
   The English royal family has not been to see the production as
far as Cooper knows. Princess Margaret, an official patron of the
Royal Ballet whom Cooper is clearly fond of, has questioned him
about the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``She cornered me for half an hour at a leaving party for one of
the Royal Ballet dancers,'' he said. ``She wanted to know all about
it.'' Bourne's queen mother is said to have been modeled on both
Queen Elizabeth and Princess Margaret. ``I think they might be
afraid because there is that royal aspect to it,'' Cooper said with
a sly grin. ``It's not very flattering.''
</P>
<P>
   A Londoner who followed his slightly older brother into ballet
and studied dance for many years, Cooper does miss the Royal at
times. But he does not regret his decision to leave. ``I was doing
well and working hard and enjoying what I was doing, but there was
always something in the back of my mind saying there was more. So I
jumped at this, partly because the chance of having a role that big
created on you is so great.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel I haven't achieved everything I wanted to in
classical ballet. But the freedom of being able to chose what I
want to do is fantastic. Dancing in a big ballet company becomes a
bit of a chore after a while. You're always fighting for roles,
fighting the management. With something like this, the movement was
created on me, so it's really mine. And however much I do it, I
still love it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
