<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9887 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT28-COX     10-27 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT FROZE OUT NETSCAPE WITH AOL DEAL, EXECUTIVE SAYS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft won a vital contract with America Online,
the nation's largest Internet provider, after agreeing to embed
AOL's software into its popular Windows 95 operating system,
according to testimony released Tuesday in the federal antitrust
trial against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Microsoft demanded that AOL stop offering the rival
Netscape Navigator browser to its own 13 million customers, the
testimony said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of the Microsoft agreement, AOL must and does
strictly limit its distribution, promotion and advertising of
Netscape Navigator,'' said a court submission by David Colburn, the
company's senior vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Colburn is to be cross-examined by Microsoft lawyers on his
18-page statement when the trial, now in its second week, resumes
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape president Jim Barksdale, who spent five full days on
the witness stand, said at the landmark trial that ``AOL told me
(the Microsoft deal) was worth a lot of money to them.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Barksdale, using the code name of ``Josef Stalin,'' had
negotiated in vain with AOL president Stephen Case, who dubbed
himself ``Franklin Roosevelt,'' to strike his own Internet browser
deal with AOL.
</P>
<P>
   In their talks, Microsoft was dubbed the ``Axis,'' and the
aborted Netscape-AOL union was ``the Allies'' _ on the theory that
``the enemy of my enemy is my friend, Barksdale told the court.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Microsoft had become a direct rival of AOL by launching
its own online service, known as the Microsoft Network, or MSN,
when it released Windows 95. In response to market pressures, both
services have since gravitated to the Internet as a platform for
their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Since nearly all personal computers run on Windows, ``Microsoft
was thus to achieve virtually costless distribution of MSN to
almost every new computer user,'' according to Colburn's direct
testimony, which will be made part of the trial record and be
weighed as evidence by U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Colburn reported, AOL complained to the Department of
Justice ``about what it felt was Microsoft's ability to use its
marketing position in operating systems to gain an unfair advantage
in the online services business.''
</P>
<P>
   But then AOL decided to switch, rather than fight, and joined
forces with the Microsoft camp in the browser wars.
</P>
<P>
   Under their 1996 bargain, AOL can choose at the end of this year
to end its exclusivity deal with Microsoft. But in his prepared
testimony, Colburn suggested that the deal would remain in force
well into the next century, even though ``at this point Navigator
and (Microsoft's) Internet Explorer continue to be reasonably
comparable browser solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Colburn noted that the ongoing struggle has left Netscape ``in a
weakened state.'' He also said AOL sought to avoid any
``interoperability problems between (Windows) and AOL, (or) any
perception in the marketplace that this could occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Colburn's availability as a witness prompted the government to
postpone, probably until next week, its earlier plans to show about
seven hours of videotaped testimony from Microsoft chairman Bill
Gates.
</P>
<P>
   In bringing a virtual Gates to the stand as a hostile witness,
the government hopes to buttress its case that the company he
co-founded had offered to divide the market for Internet software
with a Netscape after having become the largest software firm in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
