<SLUG> BC-SCORSESE-SCHRADER-FILM-ART-2TAKES-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. AMBULANCE DRIVER IS FOCUS OF SCORSESE-SCHRADER FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   Jean Nathan writes about arts and entertainment from New York.  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 1)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By JEAN NATHAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Perched on a director's chair at Eighth Avenue and
44th Street one recent midnight, Martin Scorsese is somewhere he
never expected to be: directing a movie again on his native city's
mean streets. Nor did he ever expect to be working again from a
script by Paul Schrader, with whom he collaborated on cinematic
landmarks like ``Taxi Driver'' and ``Raging Bull,'' and with whom
he believed he would never work again.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop on Scorsese's far-flung professional itinerary _
after his most recent stops in the Dalai Lama's Tibet in ``Kundun''
(1997), 1970s Las Vegas in ``Casino'' (1995) and Edith Wharton's
``Age of Innocence'' (1993) _ was to have been the glitzy world of
Hollywood across a span of four decades for ``Dino,'' based on the
life of Dean Martin, with a screenplay by Nick Pileggi.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, illuminated by flashing red ambulance lights, his ears
ringing with the sounds of screeching sirens and raging traffic,
Scorsese's eyes are glued to the patch of Eighth Avenue black-top
at his feet. There, Nicolas Cage, playing an ambulance paramedic,
crouches to minister to a suicidal street person, played by Marc
Anthony, as Anthony, caked in blood (really sugar mixed with red
food coloring), writhes on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   How Scorsese came to be here, shooting ``Bringing Out the
Dead,'' which Schrader adapted from a recently published first
novel by Joe Connelly, is in part a typical movie-business tale of
switching gears because of logistical delays. (``Dino'' is now to
begin shooting next fall.)
</P>
<P>
   But it is also the unusual story of how the work of Connelly, a
former paramedic, found its way speedily and almost seamlessly to
this point. Filming began Sept. 15 and is expected to be completed
by Christmas for release in the fall of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Bringing Out the Dead' had this little voice that said, `Pay
attention to me now,''' recalled Eric Steel, a scout in the
producer Scott Rudin's office who had learned of the book from
Connelly's agent. Steel recommended that Rudin option the novel
while it was still in manuscript. ``It became this chain that had
no glitches in it,'' he said. ``There was this sense that it went
from Joe's hands to the publisher's hands to my hands and Scott's
hands to Marty's hands to Paul's hands. That's an incredibly
unusual scenario in this business.''
</P>
<P>
   With elements of ``Taxi Driver,'' ``Mean Streets'' and even
``After Hours,'' ``Bringing out the Dead'' is the gritty, darkly
humorous story of Frank Pierce, a troubled ambulance paramedic in
New York City's Hell's Kitchen whose psychological condition could
only be called critical.
</P>
<P>
   For nine years, Connelly, 34, too, spent his nights as a
paramedic on these same streets of Hell's Kitchen (lately referred
to as Clinton). Born in Queens, the son of a nurse and a bus
driver, he dropped out of Colgate University, where he had a full
scholarship, when he found himself ``majoring in drunkenness and
confusion.'' He traveled, supporting himself at odd jobs, including
a six-month stint in 1985 as a bartender in Dublin. Pouring through
Hemingway's Nick Adams stories and Maugham's ``Razor's Edge'' in
his off-hours got him interested in becoming, like the fictional
characters in those books, an ambulance driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no focus on the future,'' he said in his trailer on the
set, where he reports each night as a technical adviser for the
movie. ``Driving an ambulance seemed completely black and white.
You just go in there and you help people and save lives, and I
figured I would do that until I figured out my own life.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning home from abroad in 1986, he took the necessary
training and by 1988 he found himself working the night shift out
of St. Claire's Hospital, where his mother had worked as a nurse,
where his parents had first met, and where he had been born.
</P>
<P>
   He was also toying with the idea of writing about his nocturnal
experiences, and while studying at Columbia University's School of
General Studies enrolled in a writing class taught by Colin
Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe showed up looking like he had arrived from somewhere
between hell and breakfast,'' recalled Harrison. ``He said, `I
drive an ambulance.' Some lucky sixth sense told me he should be in
the class, even though he didn't have the writing sample I require.
But when he put up his first piece of work, I remember knowing
instantly that this was very good work. His material had tremendous
drive, there was an exuberance in the language. I took him aside
and said: `Listen, you're a writer, and I think you need an
agent.'''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next five years, Connelly worked on the novel while
continuing to work nights ``crunching the chests of dead strangers
while putting stories together from the pieces they left behind,''
as he wrote. During this time, Harrison found Connelly an agent,
and by November of 1996, Knopf had agreed to publish the book. By
February, 1997, Rudin had optioned the movie rights, for $100,000
with only Scorsese in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Eric when he brought it in, `If we don't get Marty to
do this, this won't be a movie,''' said Rudin, one of the film's
producers. ``Marty was the obvious and only choice for this book.
These are the themes he's explored his entire career.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Scorsese thought of ``Bringing Out the Dead'' as a
project for the unspecified future. ``Marty has all these projects
that he's been developing for years and years, and often we go
through these long, painful development processes,'' said Barbara
De Fina, who is producing her ninth Scorsese film. But as ``Dino''
hit snags, she said, ``Bringing Out the Dead'' seemed a good
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a production that would be relatively easy to mount.''
she said. ``We were ready to go back to work and we realized we
could just jump in and do it. I mean, we all know these streets and
these corners.'' Not only was the script ready, but Cage, the actor
Scorsese envisioned as Frank Pierce, was available. (The cast also
includes John Goodman, Ving Rhames and Tom Sizemore, as Frank's
alternating ambulance partners and Cage's wife, Patricia Arquette,
as the daughter of a dying man whose life Frank has tried to save).
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
