<HEADLINE>
103.1 KEEPS THE MUSIC COMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ The phone calls and e-mail messages are coming in
from far and wide congratulating Channel 103.1 on its new
music-intensive format.
</P>
<P>
   The adult alternative station, which adopted its new format Oct.
19, carries on where now-defunct KSCA-FM left off.
</P>
<P>
   Granada Hills resident Jay Marsh, who recalls literally crying
Feb. 4, 1997, during KSCA's final hour, reported he was ``thrilled
at the long overdue return of a true AAA (adult album alternative)
format to Southern California.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Folga of Costa Mesa said Channel 103.1 has cured her
road rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot believe how much happier I am,'' she e-mailed Channel
103.1's Web site (www.channel1031.com). ``(I've) been in a funk
since KSCA (went) off the air. Just keep the good music coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Jane Piedad of Torrance: ``Because of you guys, my horrible
daily commute is now a little less cruel.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood resident Shaun Mason, 37, speaks for many when he says
Channel 103.1 has ``filled a void. I'll stay loyal, (but) I ask
just one thing in return _ please don't break my heart in two
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The only problem for Valley listeners of the Santa Monica
station is the car reception, which sometimes comes and goes in a
cloud of static. Channel 103.1 is, however, available over the
Internet at its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Laughlin, president and general manager of the station, said
there is a plan to improve the signal, which is strong on the
Westside.
</P>
<P>
   ``This signal serves the area where the majority of listeners
live,'' he said. ``We know there's a market for adult alternative
in the Valley. But this is the best shot for having the format on
the air.''
</P>
<P>
   LEYKIS MOVING UP
</P>
<P>
   Tom Leykis called to straighten out an incorrect ratings
tabulation in Sunday's afternoon-drive package.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that among adult listeners, 25 to 54, Leykis on
KLSX-FM (97.1) and Larry Elder of KABC-AM (790) tied for No. 1 in
the talk format with a 2.8 percent share, while John &AMP; Ken of
KFI-AM (640) placed third in that key demographic with a 2.3 share.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time in a full ratings book that Leykis has
beaten John &AMP; Ken, and the syndicated KLSX host couldn't help
gloating: ``A year ago, they had shares in the fours.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
BELL'S BACK
</P>
<P>
   Overnight host Art Bell, who resigned from his syndicated
``Coast to Coast'' program Oct. 13 under mysterious circumstances,
returns to the airwaves at 10 tonight on KABC. Bell said Friday
that ``the situation (involving his family) has improved.'' ...
``Ferrall on the Bench,'' the often outrageous sports-talk show
hosted by Scott Ferrall, is back on the air locally at 7 p.m. on
KXTA-AM (1150).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 1851EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
