<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9896 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCORSESE-SCHRADER-FIL     10-27 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCORSESE-SCHRADER-FILM-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: to save.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   But it was more than just logistical synergy. ``I really
responded to the material,'' said Scorsese. ``Basically, Frank's
emotional conflict and his search fascinated me. He needs some
meaning in his life, and really a sense of contentment of some
kind, not happiness, but a rest.''
</P>
<P>
   To Schrader's way of thinking, ``It was in Marty's interests to
circle around this territory again anyway, to do a smaller, more
interior-driven New York story rather than another big canvas film.
I thought he needed to go back to the well and drink the fresh
water of his youth.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, Scorsese and Schrader teamed up for the first time on
``Taxi Driver.'' Twice more they came together, for ``Raging Bull''
(1980) and ``The Last Temptation of Christ ''(1988).
</P>
<P>
   But after those three movies, while in discussions for a fourth,
they decided to part company professionally. ``I think it became
clear to us that it was time to back off a bit,'' said Schrader,
adding: ``Our two egos had gotten too big for the size of the room.
As I said at the time: `We've made three great films together.
Let's be happy with that.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was to Schrader's great surprise, then, when Scorsese called
with this screenplay assignment: ``I never expected to work with
him again. But as soon as I read it, I understood why he thought I
was the guy to do it. It's material I'm very comfortable with.'' He
added: ``I know exactly how Scorsese thinks when it comes to this
kind of subject matter. We're kind of two souls in a creative lock
step. We know how to do this particular kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Scorsese and Schrader both anticipate the ``Taxi Driver''
comparison, but say they see this ambulance driver story as a
bookend to, rather than a photocopy of, the earlier film.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 20 years of our lives gone by, we're not putting our feet
down in that same river,'' Schrader said. ``It has to come to a
different conclusion. Yes, it's still a man driving around New York
at night at the cusp of urban decay, but he's not alone anymore, he
has partners. And he's not brimming with energy, he's brimming with
despair. And he's not malevolent, he's on the side of the angels.
What he wants in life is some peace and meaning out of his chosen
task. The thing he seeks in these dark New York nights is different
from what the taxi driver seeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging the elements of luck and coincidence that brought
this project his way, Scorsese said, ``I think this one just seems
to reflect where we are now as people, both Paul and myself.''
</P>
<P>
   And where is he? ``Let me put it this way: I'm always
questioning,'' said Scorsese.
</P>
<P>
   ``You save a man on one corner and on the next corner a man
dies,'' he said in his customary rapid-fire speech, punctuated only
with a nervous laugh. ``It begs the question, the constant
question, of what our existence is, the `Who-are-we?
Why-are-we-here?' kind of thing. Paramedics are faced with this
every second of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   But aren't these hard questions somewhat softened for him
personally by his success as a filmmaker? (Gone are the days of
``Mean Streets,'' when Scorsese had to wear white editor's gloves,
he said, to stop from ``chewing my fingers to the bone.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it changes somewhat,'' he said. ``But how it really
changes, I don't know. Otherwise I wouldn't have to make this
movie. I'd go home. I wouldn't be in the pouring rain shooting an
ambulance driving up and down the streets until dawn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
