<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Money brings loopiness to core of politics
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's a token of the headline writer's art that so much
of this year's confusing, muddled election picture can be summed up
in a single multi-purpose, one-column line: ``Low Tax Sought.''
</P>
<P>
   In the narrowest sense, this could have been a headline over a
story last week about Byron (Low Tax) Looper, former Georgia House
clerk turned Tennessee political candidate and fugitive from
justice who was arrested Friday for the murder of state Sen. Tommy
Burks.
</P>
<P>
   Broadening the focus, the saga of Low Tax, tragic though it is,
can be seen as a metaphor for elections all over the country in
which the bizarre has eclipsed the relevant.
</P>
<P>
   Every campaign autumn gives reporters a few tall tales to tell.
But the loopiness that used to make for entertaining distractions
at the margins of American politics has moved to the center and
become the stuff of the most vital races.
</P>
<P>
   This year candidates for major office have called each other
names like ``fat monkey'' and ``boob.'' The Michigan governor's
race, where Dr. Kevorkian's lawyer, Geoffrey Fieger, is the
Democratic candidate, sounds more like a name-calling contest. In
the Minnesota governor's race, a professional wrestler, Jesse ``The
Bod'' Ventura, has upstaged his Democratic and Republican opponents
and is polling better than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Alaska, the Republicans have attempted not only to get their
nominee disqualified but to delay the election, while in Wisconsin,
Sen. Russ Feingold has demanded the Democratic Party not buy ads
for his race. A pretty strange year all round.
</P>
<P>
   The zany, trivialized quality of so many races around the
country doesn't represent a flaw in our culture or any such pap.
The voters have better sense than this year's candidates would
indicate, which is really not saying much.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the march of the wacky from the outskirts to the center
of politics is another unhealthy consequence of Congress's failure
to deal with the problem of campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   As politics gets more expensive and meaner, fewer serious,
well-established citizens are running for office, leaving the field
to contenders like John J. Hooker, who was considered eccentric
when he first ran for governor of Tennessee in 1970, and no less so
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Even where there are competitive races, the relentless drive to
raise money and spend it in 30-second bites dumbs down the process.
Certainly that's been the case in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   In some races the voters seem to be turning to unconventional
candidates, such as Ventura in Minnesota, as their only means of
expressing their disgust with the present system. In Vermont,
Republican voters chose Fred Tuttle, a retired dairy farmer who
spent $200 and wears overhauls to debates, over a millionaire
candidate to face Democratic Sen. Patrick Leahy. Tuttle says his
wife plans to vote for Leahy.
</P>
<P>
   In its final layer of meaning, ``Low Tax Sought'' is a headline
likely to describe the posture of voters for a long time after this
election is over. The federal tax cut which didn't materialized
this year has become a promise to be fulfilled after the election,
when all the tax cuts being promised in state races also are
supposed to roll in.
</P>
<P>
   When elections aren't serious, however, promises seldom are.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
