<HEADER>
A9907 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERBEV28-COX     10-27 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERBEV28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cadbury Schweppes vows to offer alternatives to Pepsi, Coke
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The world's No. 1 noncola soft drink company is vowing
to do what it takes to ensure consumers have more soda options than
just Coca-Cola Co. and Pepsico products.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've experienced the soft drink industry's version of what we
call 'ethnic cleansing' over the last few years,'' John F. Brock,
managing director and chief executive of global beverages for
Cadbury Schweppes PLC. He spoke here Tuesday during InterBev, the
industry's largest trade show.
</P>
<P>
   While there has certainly been a proliferation of new flavors
and offerings in recent years, getting those products to market has
been a challenge for companies not among soft drinks' elite. That's
because most don't have the bottling pipeline of No. 1 Coca-Cola
and No. 2 Pepsico.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Cadbury Schweppes, No. 3 in global soft drink sales,
faces an uphill battle for market share. The London-based company,
with U.S. operations based in Dallas under the Dr Pepper/Seven Up
Inc. banner, relies largely on Coca-Cola and Pepsi bottlers to
bottle its brands, which include Dr Pepper, 7 UP, A&AMP;W Root Beer,
Crush, Canada Dry, Country Time and Sunkist.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 80 percent of U.S. volume for Dr Pepper and 7 UP flows
through the Coca-Cola and Pepsi bottling system; the rest is
handled by independent ''third-tier'' bottlers or American Bottling
Co., in which Cadbury Schweppes bought a 40 percent stake earlier
this year to become more self-reliant.
</P>
<P>
   The concern, which has become reality in some markets, is that
bottlers affiliated with Coke and Pepsi will drop Cadbury
Schweppes' beverages to concentrate on their own brands.
</P>
<P>
   While Cadbury Schweppes' non-cola business is substantially
larger than that of either Coca-Cola or Pepsi, maintaining that
position could be difficult in the face of what Brock called
''prediatory'' competition by the company's rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel it's important to do our part to stop this 'volume at
any price' strategy,'' said Brock, referring to such battle grounds
as the fountain soft drink arena.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico has filed a federal antitrust lawsuit against Coca-Cola
to stop the company from barring independent food service
distributors from delivering Pepsi products if they also carry
Coca-Cola brands.
</P>
<P>
   ''Frankly, any exclusivity deals concern us, but we understand
they're part of the industry,'' said Brock, who on Monday was named
chairman of the National Soft Drink Association.
</P>
<P>
   He said Cadbury Schweppes would ''look at any and all
alternatives'' _ short of joining Pepsico's lawsuit or filing its
own _ to address freedom of choice and the inflationary prices
caused by exclusive deals.
</P>
<P>
   Brock, a Georgia Tech graduate, said the cost of securing
fountain business has grown roughly 20 percent over the last three
years. That growth rate is ''well in excess of volume growth and
pricing inflation'' over that same period, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fierce competition, Cadbury Schweppes landed 4,000
new fountain accounts in 1997 and another 9,000 so far this year,
Brock said. The contracts have pushed the company's fountain volume
up more than 5 percent, he said, giving Cadbury Schweppes a total
12 percent share of fountain volume to Coca-Cola's 62 percent and
Pepsi's 19 percent. Cadbury Schweppes on Tuesday reported the
company's domestic soft drink sales grew 3 percent in the third
quarter, versus 2 percent in the second quarter and 1 percent in
the first. It was the best quarter for soft drink sales since
Cadbury Schweppes bought Dr Pepper and 7 UP almost four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
