<SLUG> BC-SOUCOM28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern Co. to manage Texas electric operation
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Southern Co., taking a big step into Texas' utility
markets, has agreed to manage Brazos Electric Power Cooperative's
wholesale electric power supply.
</P>
<P>
   Under a five-year agreement announced Tuesday, the Atlanta-based
utility holding company takes charge of all of Waco-based Brazos
Electric's 1,650 megawatts of electric capacity, which comes from
two power plants and agreements with other suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Southern then will provide Brazos with enough electricity to
meet its needs and sell surplus electricity in wholesale markets at
a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms of the deal were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Brazos Electric, the largest and oldest Texas power cooperative,
provides electricity to 19 customer-owned electric membership
corporations. Those EMCs in turn supply 225,000 residential and
40,000 business customers in a 66-county area that includes the
Dallas-Fort Worth suburbs and Texas A&AMP;M University, and a swatch of
rural territory that extends to the state capital of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Company Energy Marketing, a Southern subsidiary based
at Perimeter Center, also agreed to build a power plant to
accommodate growing demand for electricity in the Dallas-Fort Worth
suburbs. Southern has targeted the Southwest as one of four regions
for expansion of its U.S. wholesale energy businesses. In its first
Texas foray last month, Southern announced plans to build a small
power plant 130 miles northwest of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Southern is now squarely on the home ground of rival Enron Corp.
The Houston-based energy conglomerate eyed Southern's home turf
this year by considering entering Georgia's newly deregulated
natural gas market but then opted out.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Foster, an Enron spokesman, declined to comment on whether
his company was one of 16 confidential bidders on the Brazos deal,
though he said Enron is generally interested in such opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Southern's agreement with Brazos Electric is similar to
arrangements that Atlanta-based Oglethorpe Power Cooperative worked
out with two wholesale power marketing companies in 1996 and 1997
to manage its power supply.
</P>
<P>
   One of those suppliers, Louisville, Ky.-based LG&AMP;E Energy Corp.
shut down its energy trading company in July, citing difficulties
in delivering power to Oglethorpe at their agreed-upon price
following an unprecedented summer run-up in wholesale electricity
prices. Oglethorpe, which supplies 39 Georgia EMCs that in turn
have 1.2 million customers, is still receiving power from the LG&AMP;E
under a 15-year agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Southern spokesman Chuck Griffin said Southern's agreement with
Brazos Electric provides for a combination of prices to be fixed
and indexed to wholesale fluctuations. Unlike the Oglethorpe
agreements, Southern will take a hands-on role in managing the
Brazos power plants and supplying natural gas to run them.
</P>
<P>
   Clifton Karnei, Brazos Electric executive vice president, said
the agreement will mean savings and a ``higher level of
predictability and security'' for the cooperative's member
utilities in advance of deregulation of the electric power
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
