<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-AND-PERFORMER-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC AND PERFORMER, AND UNSTABLE COMPOUND  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The delicate dance between performer and performed has played
out in a number of places this young season. It is a dance in the
form of a competition, for what is it we go to hear? The pianist or
the piano sonata? The singer or the song?
</P>
<P>
   To say that the second cannot exist without the first is only
partly true. The perfect interpretation of Beethoven's
``Waldstein'' Sonata does not reside in a collection of past
impressions but grows inside our heads. It is fertilized by all the
performances we have heard of it but raised to full flower only by
our own imaginations.
</P>
<P>
   There is no disputing the fact that living personalities move
more tickets than dead composers. Vladimir Horowitz easily sold out
programs of trivia. Luciano Pavarotti, Yo-Yo Ma and Itzhak Perlman
anchor subscription series around the country, charging concert
presenters punishing fees yet guaranteeing them that the big name
will carry lesser names when blocks of concerts must be sold.
</P>
<P>
   Others argue that the ideal interpreter goes unnoticed, that in
the transcendent concert experience audiences forget not just the
player but also the instrument. Listening to Michael Tilson Thomas
conduct Gershwin at Carnegie Hall a few weeks ago made one
conscious of Thomas at every moment: of his bright personality, the
joy in what he was doing, the deftness of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Christoph von Dohnanyi conduct the ``Eroica''
Symphony in Cleveland soon after left me with only the vaguest
notion of who or what Dohnanyi was. The maker of music became lost
in music. One felt gratitude for wonderful Beethoven, but
admiration? One could find no one to admire.
</P>
<P>
   All is not so simple; the collaboration of player and played is
always present. In popular song, the singer has the advantage.
There is no urtext for a Gershwin number, no first or second
edition. There are a tune, words and chord changes.
</P>
<P>
   What Peggy Lee makes of them says as much about her as about
Gershwin, although if she is true to perhaps unnamable values, it
is Gershwin we finally remember.
</P>
<P>
   What Peggy Lee does in large amounts, concert musicians do in
smaller ones. They seek out the sympathetic vibration between the
music and themselves. Maurizio Pollini plays the ``Waldstein,'' and
we hear the elegance; Alfred Brendel plays it, and we hear the
struggle. The ``Waldstein'' has both. Brendel, on the other hand,
is not terribly elegant and Pollini does not struggle.
</P>
<P>
   When Nigel Kennedy, or Kennedy, as the violinist now chooses to
be called, plays (as he will Sunday evening at Avery Fisher Hall),
the intervention of performer between listener and music is clearly
intentional. So eagerly flamboyant is Kennedy, the stage presence,
and so subversive his appearance against the usual iconography of
the concert stage that a Kennedy concert is three events: the man
onstage, the interpreter of music, and the music.
</P>
<P>
   Only cynics will suggest that the stage show conveniently takes
our minds off how well Kennedy actually plays. There is in any case
a sensory overload destined to bewilder the listener.
</P>
<P>
   Bryn Terfel in his well-received recital at Carnegie Hall three
weeks ago sounded almost too good for our own good. As he
assiduously produced beautiful sounds, careful diction and
scrupulous applications of musical principles, the experience of
Terfel's doing all these wonderful things sometimes made it hard to
get past his imposing presence and put one's hands on music pure
and simple.
</P>
<P>
   With the Metropolitan Opera's ``Samson et Dalila,'' the
performer's ego was welcome. Olga Borodina's lovely singing
protected us from some of the questionable music around her, and in
the process one almost understood the rabid cults for whose members
the opera itself is fodder and the only domestic animal worth
feeding is the human voice.
</P>
<P>
   If the Pollinis, Brendels, Borodinas and Terfels leave their
mark on the music of others, there is one composer who has turned
the tables on them. Daniel Barenboim played a Liszt program at
Carnegie Hall two weeks ago, and one had the odd sensation of the
musician as object of scrutiny, not the music. Liszt is litmus
paper: a dangerous trap for the mediocre musical mind and an
exalted opportunity for the pure of heart.
</P>
<P>
   Barenboim loves Liszt for the right reasons. Large numbers of
listeners reject Liszt as shallow, gaudy and sentimental, because
they have grown up with his music played by shallow, gaudy and
sentimental pianists.
</P>
<P>
   Liszt's mannerisms are seductive to the easy virtuoso. The
supreme pianist wrote piano music that invites the hand to the
keyboard. The fit is graceful, and Liszt's devices make the
virtuoso sound even more virtuosic.
</P>
<P>
   Beethoven is awkward while sounding playable. Liszt flatters the
technique while asking hands to do what they want to do but to do
it even better. Liszt on the piano feels good.
</P>
<P>
   Those who love Liszt for the wrong reasons soon find their cover
blown, their second-rateness betrayed. Those who seek empty show in
this music will find it. Those with the wit to discover its noble,
generous and deeply inventive qualities ennoble themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more depressing experiences of my long reviewing life
have been the young debutants, flush with energy and technique,
rattling mindlessly through ``The Fountains at the Villa d'Este,''
dotting every ``i'' and playing every note of every octave passage
and arpeggio.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most uplifting experiences of my life has been to
hear Claudio Arrau play the same piece. Liszt is what the performer
makes of him, and few are up to the job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
