<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE'S SOUTHERN ROUTE MAKES GLENN'S PROSPECTS FOR ON-TIME
LAUNCH SOAR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ When Hurricane Mitch stayed further south
than expected Tuesday, John Glenn's prospects for an on-time launch
aboard the shuttle Discovery soared.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters' concerns that winds triggered by the potent storm
might gust over the safety limit for the shuttle's use of an
emergency runway Thursday disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's good news, good news and good news,'' said Ed
Priselac, NASA's lead weather forecaster.
</P>
<P>
   As Discovery's countdown got under way earlier this week,
Mitch's path into the Caribbean prompted weather experts to peg the
odds of high winds at 40 percent. They fell to zero on Tuesday when
Mitch did not turn north as expected.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's seven-member crew is scheduled to blast off Thursday
at 1 p.m. CST with Glenn seeking an encore to his 1962 mission that
made him the first American to orbit the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The flawless forecast, if it holds, is an especially fortunate
turn of events for Glenn and the rest of the Discovery crew.
Earlier in the day, the GOES 8 weather satellite used by NASA to
monitor cloud cover for its shuttle launchings malfunctioned.
</P>
<P>
   If not recovered by Thursday, the loss would mean the space
agency's forecasters will not have the succession of images of sky
conditions snapped every 15 minutes they have come to rely on.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some launch preparations temporarily fell about 90
minutes behind schedule when control teams encountered a pair of
equipment problems.
</P>
<P>
   The first involved the malfunction of a sensor system that
alerts launch controllers to potentially explosive leaks of the
fuel used to generate electricity aboard the shuttle and power its
three rocket engines.
</P>
<P>
   The repairs needed to permit loading large amounts of liquid
hydrogen and oxygen propellants into Discovery's large fuel tank
were planned overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The second difficulty involved an oxygen leak in the launch pad
fueling system that forced a brief postponement of some activities
by shuttle technicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to be back on schedule,'' said Doug Lyons, who was
supervising countdown activities.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery commander Curt Brown and his crew spent the day under
going medical exams, making sure their flight suits fit properly
and then relaxing privately with close family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in excellent shape,'' Jim Wetherbee, NASA's director of
flight crew operations, said of the 77-year-old Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   Like Brown, pilot Steve Lindsey, flight engineer Scott
Parazynski, payload commander Steve Robinson, European Space Agency
astronaut Pedro Duque and Japanese astronaut Chiaki Mukai remained
in medical quarantine.
</P>
<P>
   According to Wetherbee, who has logged four missions of his own,
the hours before launch often turn into an opportunity for personal
reflection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to spend time with my wife, and (Glenn) is spending
some time with Mrs. (Annie) Glenn,'' said Wetherbee. ``Of course
these conversations are personal.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point, most likely after the couple parts company for
the day, Glenn's thoughts will turn to the risk of his undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Astronauts tend to think about risk a little bit differently
than most folks, and I know that John Glenn in particular feels
that if the benefits outweigh the risks, then it's a good thing to
accept,'' Wetherbee said. ``I know he did that on his first flight.
He accepted the risk so others could follow in his footsteps.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the same job now,'' Wetherbee said.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the men who shared the responsibility for launching
Glenn in 1962 reminisced about how great the risk was with the
Atlas rocket, compared to the space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know how primitive it was back in those days,'' said
Paul Donnelly, 75, who served as NASA's Mercury capsule test
conductor. ``The only thing we had that was automatic in those days
was the coffee pot back in the ready room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I'm sort of amazed,'' said Walt Kapryan, 78, of
Glenn's new-found celebrity. Kapryan supervised preparation of
Glenn's capsule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the the public is looking for a hero,'' he said.
``John Glenn fits that.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
