<HEADLINE>
NETANYAHU DELAYS VOTE ON ISRAELI-PALESTINIAN AGREEMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu Tuesday postponed
a Cabinet vote on the new Israeli-Palestinian agreement, saying
that the Palestinians had failed to draw up a plan to counter
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Bank, Israelis and Palestinians held funerals for a
Jewish settler and a Palestinian farmer killed Monday in apparent
tit-for-tat attacks. Palestinian police arrested two suspects in
the slaying of the settler. Palestinians clashed with Israeli
forces outside the Palestinian-ruled town of Nablus.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's office issued a statement announcing the
postponement. ``It was determined at the Wye summit that the
Palestinians would _ within one week _ complete their working plan
for fighting terrorism,'' the statement said. ``However, it has
become clear that they are not meeting the agreed-upon schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's Cabinet, originally scheduled to convene on
Thursday, will meet to endorse the agreement once Israel receives
the plan, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat expressed hope
that the postponement was not a stalling tactic. ``This detailed
plan is an internal Palestinian plan dealing with security,''
spokesman Ahmed Tibi told the Associated Press, ``The Israelis do
not need to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   The accord, negotiated at the Wye River conference center in
Maryland, makes no mention of a Palestinian obligation to furnish
Israel with a working plan to combat terror within one week. It
states that the Palestinians will share the plan with the United
States as soon as the memorandum goes into force, which the accord
specified as 10 days after the signing.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. diplomat said such an obligation on the part of the
Palestinians may have been spelled out in a letter to Netanyahu
from Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, but stressed that in
any case the United States expected Israel to begin implementing
the terms of the accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider the Israeli government bound to begin the Wye
memorandum within 10 days after the signing,'' said the diplomat,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   According to Israeli law, Netanyahu is not required to present
the agreement to the Cabinet or to Parliament for ratification.
However, since Israel signed the Camp David Peace Treaty with Egypt
in 1979, it has become customary for the prime minister to bring
international agreements to both bodies for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli observers suggested that Netanyahu, faced with
right-wing opposition to the Wye agreement, was searching for a way
to delay the Cabinet vote. Others said the Israeli leader may be
signaling the opposition Labor Party that he will not put the
agreement into action while facing the threat of new elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Party, which supports the Wye agreement, has agreed to
give Netanyahu a two-week ``safety net'' so that his government
will not fall on issues of peace.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, Labor members of the Knesset Law Committee, in
alliance with the pro-settlement National Religious Party, helped
to draft a bill calling for elections as early as mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Netanyahu wants a safety net not just for the next two weeks,
but he wants the opposition to more or less be forced to back him
as long as he's implementing the peace agreement,'' said Reuven
Hazan, a political analyst at Jerusalem's Hebrew University. ``He
wants to buy another hundred days of grace.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he returned to Israel on Sunday, Netanyahu has been
inundated with right-wing protests against the Wye deal. On Monday,
hundreds of angry Israelis demonstrated outside the prime
minister's office with placards of Netanyahu and Arafat, drenched
in blood and bullet holes.
</P>
<P>
   The scenes, reminiscent of the frenzied rhetoric that preceded
the assassination of Yitzhak Rabin three years ago, raised the
specter of right-wing violence even as the Israeli secret service
beefed up security surrounding Netanyahu, Foreign Minister Ariel
Sharon and Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, thousands of mourners gathered in Kiryat Arba, a
settlement in the southern West Bank, to bury Danny Vargas, the
settler shot by Palestinian gunmen on Monday. He was killed as he
drove to the settlement from his security guard job in the
Israeli-controlled part of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian police Tuesday arrested two Palestinians suspected
of carrying out the murder. One admitted to killing Itamar Dorom as
he swam in a natural spring near Jerusalem last month, Palestinian
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   In the northern West Bank, hundreds of Palestinians gathered in
the village of Fariq near Nablus to bury Mohammad Zamout, 69, a
farmer bludgeoned to death on Monday outside the Jewish settlement
of Itamar. Police received a phone call from someone claiming that
the murder was carried out to avenge Vargas' death.
</P>
<P>
   The mourners called for revenge, and the Israeli army declared
Palestinian towns in the West Bank off-limits to Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Zamout's killing sparked clashes Tuesday between stone-throwing
Palestinian youths and Israeli soldiers outside Nablus and general
strikes in Ramallah, Bethlehem, Nablus and east Jerusalem. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Horan is a free-lance journalist based in Jerusalem. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
