<HEADLINE>
GLENN MISSION HELPS FLORIDA TOWN RECAPTURE YOUTH, HAPPY MEMORIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COCOA BEACH, Fla. _ Thirty-six years ago the original Mercury
astronauts made this beach town their personal playground, and the
locals hang on to those memories as though they were gold.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the current crop of astronauts aren't just as
brave, and probably just as likeable, but they aren't the guys who
put this beach town on the map. So seeing John Glenn launched into
space again is a personal triumph for people up and down the coast.
</P>
<P>
   For people who knew the first astronauts personally, and for
those who never got any closer than watching them in a parade, this
launch is a way to recapture the town's youth, and their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a population of about 3,000 people, exciting people,''
recalls Cocoa Beach Mayor Joe Morgan. ``The average age was 29. If
we saw anyone with white hair, we knew they didn't live here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cocoa Beach eventually became a haven for retirees, like
many other Florida towns, and the average age of residents is now
50-something.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime residents get wistful when they talk about the old days
when the Mercury 7 astronauts were fixtures in the local bars and
restaurants, and occasionally used the main highway through town as
a drag strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' said real estate developer Bernard Simpkins.
``We had a lot of mosquitoes and a two-lane road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all rubbed shoulders together, ate at the same
restaurants,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just good, strong-willed individuals and nice
people,'' said Carl Ransom, who managed the Cape Colony Inn and the
old Ramada, hotels (with bars) that the astronauts frequented in
the old days. ``They did enjoy a good meal and a good drink,''
Ransom said.
</P>
<P>
   But there are two distinct groups of memories on file here _
memories of the practical jokes and general craziness associated
with some of the Mercury astronauts, and the quieter memories they
have of John Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Rathmann, the owner of a local Chevrolet dealership in
Melbourne, is the man who provided those now legendary Corvettes
for the early astronauts to drive. But Glenn didn't accept a
Corvette, he said. He doesn't recall Glenn having the passion for
racing that astronauts like Alan Shepard and Gordon Cooper had.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sort of a fuddy duddy guy as far as I was concerned,''
Rathmann said. ``All the other guys were always having a lot of fun
and doing things. John wasn't that kind of guy. He was the studious
type.
</P>
<P>
   But if Glenn's more sober personality made him less accessible
as a local legend, it never interfered with putting him on a
pedestal. And making this second flight at age 77 has only kicked
him up a couple of notches in local esteem.
</P>
<P>
   In Melbourne, retired baker Eli Weissman, 79, keeps a battered
scrapbook in his living room that chronicles the giant cake he made
to celebrate Glenn's return to earth after that historic first
flight. It was a 1,700-pound frosted replica of the Friendship 7
capsule that carried Glenn into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   He also keeps a rusting cake pan with Glenn's signature carved
into it _ evidence of his first meeting the astronaut.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's daughter came to the bakery while her father was in
quarantine as backup astronaut for Gus Grissom's launch. She
requested a cake that read, ``From Annie and the kids _ Happy
Birthday!''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was only eight or nine,'' Weissman said, ``She came in
with a reporter from Look Magazine.'' She was disappointed at the
number of people who could be served from a half-sheet cake, he
said, so he offered to make a full sheet cake for free, if her
famous father would return the pan personally.
</P>
<P>
   Weissman said he and his crew were making apple turnovers the
day Glenn returned the pan. He agreed to autograph the pan, and
then pitched in to help make turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he'd never been in a bakery before,'' Weissman
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Weissman ran a gauntlet of Secret Service agents
accompanying Glenn and President Carter and presented Glenn with
his favorite onion pumpernickel rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few months ago, Glenn wrote Weissman a letter to thank
him for a delivery of the same onion-pumpernickel rolls arranged by
one of his staff members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, thank you for the rolls,'' Glenn wrote in a letter
dated Aug. 6. ``I would be grateful if you would keep me in your
thoughts and prayers in the weeks and months ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they could have gotten VIP seats for the launch had
Weissman just used that letter, his wife chided him. Never mind, he
said, he's got a pretty good view from his back yard.
</P>
<P>
   Cocoa Beach resident Louise Hurd has her own Glenn memento _ a
photo of Glenn perched on the hood of a car outside Riverside
Presbyterian Church, autographing Bibles for the kids in the
congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd come every Sunday, when he was in town,'' Hurd said. The
church was new enough that they didn't have pews yet, just chairs.
``People would turn their chairs around so they could see him when
he came in.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Sunday I took a picture of John signing the kids' Bibles.
My daughter was in that picture,'' she said. She got Glenn's mother
and father to sign it when they visited, she said, but didn't get a
chance to seek Glenn's autograph until years later when he was
running for president.
</P>
<P>
   Hurd said she took the picture with her to a party hosted by
Simpkins, and asked Glenn and his wife to sign it. ``Somehow it got
piled up in his office,'' Hurd said. ``Then along came this
envelope from John Glenn, and he and Annie had signed it.'' The
photo arrived back in 1989 _ four years after his unsuccessful run
for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really was lost but I'm glad somebody found it,'' Hurd
said. The photo was signed, ``To Louise, with best regards. I
enjoyed seeing this memory of too many years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The minister of the church has written a letter inviting Glenn
back, she said, but she doesn't know whether to expect to see him.
``We have a much bigger church now with pews and everything.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 1934EST &QL; 
