<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9950 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MOOSE-REBOUND-ART     10-27 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MOOSE-REBOUND-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
GREENVILLE, Maine: of evergreens. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a moose does for most of its life is eat _ a lot. A
thousand-pound adult consumes 25 pounds or even 50 pounds of
vegetation a day in the summer and 10 or 12 pounds of evergreen
branches or twigs in the winter. (Moose are partial to Christmas
trees, i.e., balsam fir.) One year, Schwartz said, it took a crew
of 10 people all summer to collect enough vegetation to feed four
moose for two weeks in a research project on moose digestion.
</P>
<P>
   In its constant search for food and security from predators, a
moose is served by only so-so eyesight. But its senses of smell and
hearing are acute. Its long ears move in an almost 360-degree arc,
helping the animal detect sounds far off. Moose ``are capable of
hearing sounds humans would be oblivious to,'' Schwartz said. He
has seen them perk up their ears and turn in a common direction, he
said, while he has heard nothing. ``Five minutes later, a vehicle
comes driving in.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet moose tend not to flee from much of anything. One reason,
experts say, is that _ at up to six feet at the shoulder and 1,500
pounds _ they are just bigger than most other objects in their
world. They have few natural enemies, and even against predators
like wolves they stand their ground; moving might prompt the
predator to attack, and in any case moose are formidable fighters.
Unfortunately, they also tend to stand their ground against
oncoming cars.
</P>
<P>
   In general, moose are considered the most docile of the deer
family, and the most tolerant of people's presence. But there are
exceptions. Douglas Kane, the state's regional biologist here, says
that mature bull moose hereabouts have become more skittish and
harder to see. ``When they smell a human, they're gone,'' he said.
It may be, he speculates, that bulls are shyer because they are the
primary quarry in Maine's short, one-week moose hunting season in
October.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, any given moose can be dangerous, and all should be
approached cautiously and in some cases not at all, experts say.
There are two situations in which moose are especially dangerous:
when a human comes between a cow and its calf, and during the rut,
or mating season, from about mid-September to mid-October. That is
when bulls establish dominance, with intimidating displays and
sometimes clashes of antlers, and cows signal with moans and wails
that they are in the mood, a condition that normally lasts less
than a day.
</P>
<P>
   Anything or anyone invading a moose's turf then risks injury or
even death. More people are killed by moose, in fact, than by
grizzly bears, said Dr. Joel Berger, a biologist at the University
of Nevada at Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, though, moose have become so comfortable with people
that, like deer, they have started raiding gardens and crops in
some localities. ``A few of them in northern Maine are beginning to
understand the concept of broccoli,'' Ms. Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   When a moose calf is a year old, its mother drives it away (to
make way for the next year's calf) and it must find a new territory
of its own. Moose are now so numerous in northern New England that
the youngsters are being forced southward.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, a young moose cow apparently got lost while
searching out new territory and wound up in Boston. She led police
and state biologists on a frantic chase, at one point crashing
through the yards of row houses near Boston College. ``You could
hear the chain-link fences going down,'' said Dr. John McDonald, a
wildlife biologist for the state. Eventually the moose was
tranquilized and taken to a zoo, where she died; although moose
have sometimes been used as draft animals, they generally do not do
well in captivity.
</P>
<P>
   With a breeding population estimated at 200, moose are no longer
a novelty in Massachusetts. ``As they become more common,''
McDonald said, ``people report them less frequently. Once you've
seen your third or fourth moose, it's not a big deal any more.''
</P>
<P>
   In northern New England, and especially in Maine, moose-car
accidents have become epidemic. Besides being unintimidated by
vehicles, moose are drawn to roads because they love to lick up the
salt left over from deposits made by snow-clearance crews.
Sometimes they lie down in the roadway to do this, presenting an
unexpected traffic hazard. Another problem is that moose are dark
in color, sometimes almost black, and they are so tall that their
eyes do not shine in car lights. So at night, motorists often do
not see them until it is too late.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morris, the state biologist, said Maine averages more than
600 moose-car accidents a year. About 15 percent of the motorists
involved require medical treatment. And while Ms. Morris could not
cite human death statistics for Maine, she said the state's
mortality rate in moose-car accidents was probably about the same
as the rate measured in Sweden: about 1 in 400 accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The moose dies much more often.
</P>
<P>
   Some wildlife specialists in Maine favor loosening restrictions
on hunting to reduce the numbers of both moose and accidents.
Permits for the one-week October hunt are rationed; this year's cap
was 2,000. But other interests, mainly the tourist industry, want
to keep the number of moose high.
</P>
<P>
   New logging practices that rely less on clear-cutting and more
on selective removal of trees may well shrink the area of prime
moose habitat in future years, and as today's second-growth forests
grow out of the reach of moose their population may decline, Kane
said. ``It may be close to a stable herd now,'' he said, ``stable
or low growth.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the foreseeable future, the evolving new relationship
between people and moose seems likely to continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 1934EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
