<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9979 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-ABANDONED-BABY-BOS     10-27 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-ABANDONED-BABY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORNING SURPRISE: BABY GIRL LEFT ON A DOORSTEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE EBBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTON, Mass. _ It was a scene from a fairy tale, another
time &UR;  &LR; and place. Helaine Miller stepped outside her West Newton
home Tuesday morning to find a feisty, crying, healthy newborn girl
waiting to be discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not believe it. I said, `I think I'm in a movie,'''
said Miller, who had walked outside to pick up her newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Shocked to find the child, but pleased to see that she appeared
healthy, the mother of three and grandmother of one instinctively
scooped her up and took her inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good,'' said the beaming 63-year-old. ``It felt very
good.''
</P>
<P>
   But Miller, who turned the infant over to authorities, realizes
it was fortuitous that she was home. Police believe the girl was
left on her doorstep between 6 and 7:05 a.m., when the temperature
was only 38 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucky we were here. It was a very cold morning and very sad a
mother would leave a baby here,'' Miller said. ``It's tragic. It's
not natural for a mother to abandon her child.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than two hours old, the baby was found wrapped in a terry
cloth towel soiled with blood, her umbilical cord still attached,
said Newton Police Chief Frank R. Gorgone.
</P>
<P>
   The healthy 7-pound, 6-ounce girl, who measures 20 1/2inches
long and has strawberry-blonde hair, was in stable condition in
Newton Wellesley Hospital Tuesday. Nurses, striving for a more
personal name than Baby Doe, are calling her Julia.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a beautiful baby, a gorgeous baby,'' said Dr. Thomas
Beatty, the hospital's chief of obstetrics and gynecology. ``In
spite of being a little cool, she was alert, looking around,
responding and behaving just like any normal newborn.''
</P>
<P>
   Touched by news reports of the baby's abandonment Tuesday, many
people called the hospital and police, asking to visit her or even
adopt her, said hospital spokeswoman Rachel Kagno. The state
Department of Social Services sought temporary custody of the baby
Tuesday, and will work with police to identify the parents or find
her a foster home and adoptive parents, said spokeswoman Lorraine
Carli.
</P>
<P>
   Gorgone said he is concerned for the mother's health but that
criminal charges may be considered if and when she is located.
Police canvassed the neighborhood Tuesday, finding few clues to the
mother's identity.
</P>
<P>
   Their only early lead was the sound of two slamming car doors at
about 6 a.m. One may have been the mother. The other was the
newspaper carrier. Vernon Wright, 28, a divinity student who
delivered the papers Tuesday for his wife, Kathleen, Tuesdaytold
police the baby was not there at about 6 a.m. when he walked up the
Millers' path.
</P>
<P>
   The Wrights, who have a 2-year-old son, were touched by the
news. Kathleen Wright had a miscarriage in August and was among
those calling DSS Tuesday, considering adoption.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have loved to have that baby, as many people would,''
she said. ``I'm just horrified that that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Police have no idea why the baby turned up on the Millers'
doorstep but guess it may have been because the lights were on and
someone was obviously home. The home, which Miller has shared with
her husband, Stanley, since 1966, is something out of a fairy tale,
too: A massive English tudor, with a second-story window balcony
and a surrounding stone wall. Thick hedges form an archway and
obscure from sidewalk view the stone steps where the baby was
found.
</P>
<P>
   Miller couldn't guess whether the mother left the girl there in
the hopes that the family could offer her a better life. Nor does
Miller, a former vice president at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical
Center, know anyone who was expecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm past that stage,'' she said. ``I'm in the grandparent
stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Some neighbors were appalled that the baby was left on a
doorstep. But some found it heartwarming that the infant was left
in a place where she could be saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, when somebody abandons a baby in a place where there
are caring people, like on the step of a church or a hospital, the
thinking of the mother or person leaving the baby is that
hopefully, somebody in a better position than them will pick up the
child and care for him or her,'' Carli said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's usually a positive sign,'' she added. ``It's different
than when you see the horrible cases where somebody discards a baby
where hopefully nobody would find it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
