<SLUG> BC-NEWYORK-SENATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER INCHES AHEAD OF D'AMATO, POLL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A week to go before the election, Democrat Charles E.
Schumer has inched out in front of three-term Republican incumbent
Alfonse M. D'Amato in their bitterly fought race for the US Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the contest, which may be the most closely watched in the
country, is seen as way too tight for anyone to venture a
prediction.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll taken Sunday of 709 likely voters _ the first survey
since the candidates' raucous Saturday night debate _ Schumer leads
D'Amato, 42.9 percent to 38.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's edge still lies within the poll's 3.8-percentage-point
margin of error. However, over the past few days, his numbers have
been rising consistently and D'Amato's have been falling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Schumer has the momentum,'' the pollster, John Zogby,
said Tuesday. The trend, he said, ``is dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato, he noted, has lost considerable ground over the past
week among all the demographic groups that usually decide close
elections in New York _ Jews, suburbanites and women. Even upstate,
the more rural and conservative regions where D'Amato is still
ahead, his lead has deteriorated from about 20 percentage points to
10.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 15 percent of those polled remain undecided. ``Anything
can happen,'' Zogby emphasized.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Carroll, head of the Quinnipiac College Polling
Institute, agreed: ``I wouldn't bet a dime on this race.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato vs. Schumer is not only one of the closest, but may be
the most politically significant Senate race. In a season when five
Democratic senators are in danger of losing, putting Republicans
close to the 60-seat majority needed to block filibusters, Schumer
is that rare candidate who might unseat a Republican _ and not just
any Republican, but the king of New York state's surging GOP.
</P>
<P>
   First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton was in town Tuesday to
campaign with Schumer, her third such visit. President Clinton, who
raised $1.1 million for Schumer in a campaign appearance this
month, is also due for a return trip this week.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer needs all the money he can get. Republican Governor
George W. Pataki set out with D'Amato Tuesday on a four-day,
16-city campaign tour. Pataki, also up for reelection, is way ahead
of his Democratic opponent, New York City Council speaker Peter
Vallone, so he will spend about $6 million for joint media ads this
week. The Republican Party is expected to pour a few million more,
for ads, phone banks, transportation, and other get-out-the-vote
aids.
</P>
<P>
   Two of D'Amato's past three Senate victories have been close.
His last one, in 1992 against Robert Abrams, was decided by one
percent of the ballots cast.
</P>
<P>
   If D'Amato loses this time, the turning point may have been last
Wednesday, when, speaking to 40 Jewish supporters, he referred to
Schumer as a ``putzhead.'' The Yiddish word ``putz,'' a put-down
for a fool, literally means a small male organ. When asked about
the incident, D'Amato at first denied using the word _ until some
of his supporters, who were in the room, confirmed it.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer trumpeted the remark and the denial as another example
of how ``New Yorkers cannot trust Al D'Amato'' _ his main campaign
slogan.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato won over 40 percent of the Jewish vote in 1992 _
staggering for a Republican in New York _ and has been consistently
getting 35 percent in the polls for this year's race.
</P>
<P>
   However, the latest poll, published in Tuesday's New York Post,
shows him favored by just 18 percent of Jews. Zogby said D'Amato's
insult might be the reason for the decline, because they see it not
so much as an ethnic slur as ``un-senatorial behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer is Jewish. D'Amato is Roman Catholic but has long been
active in Jewish causes, most recently in forcing Swiss banks to
return assets stolen from Jewish families by the Nazis during World
War II. His reelection has been endorsed by both of New York City's
Jewish newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week, D'Amato had also been attracting more support
from women than Republicans usually attract in New York, splitting
their vote with Schumer, 50-50. However, in the latest poll,
Schumer has taken a 10-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato had been doing well because he had pushed bills to spend
more money on breast-cancer research and to make HMOs pay for
reconstructive surgery after mastectomies, moves that Democrats had
criticized as election-year ploys.
</P>
<P>
   However, Zogby said, Schumer may have gained points in recent
days because of his upfront support for abortion rights, which
D'Amato opposes. New York is so overwhelmingly in favor of abortion
rights that even most Republicans here declare they are, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
