<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGES-COSTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGES UNITE TO DEFEND THEIR PRICE TAGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With institutions of higher education fighting an image as
elitist money-vacuums, a coalition of 1,200 of them announced a
national campaign Tuesday to convince the public that college isn't
really that expensive, after all.
</P>
<P>
   That pitch may come as a shock to already sticker-shocked
parents.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``College is Possible'' campaign argues that parents and
students overestimate the cost of college by 200 percent, and
underestimate how much money they can get to help defray that cost
_ in too many cases, deciding to forgo a college education.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign also plays defense for the schools, pointing to the
``complexities'' of college costs _ in short, arguing that colleges
aren't as greedy as some might say. In fact, the colleges say, it
costs them more than the money they get in tuition to educate
students, especially as applicants demand constant improvements in
computers, dormitories, and athletic facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tuition increases of the '80s and '90s were very
frightening to people, including the colleges,'' said Stanley
Ikenberry, president of the American Council on Education, the
organizer of the campaign and the umbrella group for the nation's
public and private colleges and universities. ``There is public
anxiety out there that is still a hangover from that, and worse,
there is confusion about what can be done. There is a real
knowledge gap, even among upper-income families.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign comes just as colleges are looking for a little
good publicity.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, the higher education world has been criticized
twice with national reports showing the cost of tuition climbing at
twice the rate of inflation. A Carnegie Commission report last year
accused the top research universities of spending too little time
on undergraduate education, leaving students to learn from ``badly
trained or even untrained'' teaching assistants.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In response, Princeton, followed by Yale, Harvard, and last
week Dartmouth, announced small _ but strongly symbolic _ boosts in
financial aid. Cornell University on Friday announced a $400
million, 10-year plan to improve undergraduate education and boost
financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``They're getting hit from a number of directions,'' said
Harvey Blustain, who has a PhD from Yale and is now head of
higher-education consulting practice for PricewaterhouseCoopers.
``There is definitely increased nervousness about their image. And
they have reason to be. As a parent looking at two kids, and as
someone who went to private schools for undergraduate and graduate
education, the University of Massachusetts is looking pretty good
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But after two decades of steep increases, and news about highly
paid celebrity professors, the campaign may have a tough time
persuading the public.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``When the price tag is over $30,000 in many schools and
pushing it in many others, it's going to be pretty hard to convince
people that it's inexpensive,'' said Allan Sutfin, a guidance
counselor at Brookline High School for 28 years. ``It's pretty hard
to sugar-coat $30,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The colleges, though, point out that while schools like Harvard
and Brown cost in the $30,000 range, 75 percent of students go to
colleges that charge less than $8,000 a year for tuition and fees.
That latter figure, however, doesn't include room and board, which
lifts the cost this year to an average of $10,458 at a public
four-year college and $22,533 at a four-year private school.
</P>
<P>
   After the steep increases in the late '80s and early '90s,
tuitions and fees increased by only 4 to 5 percent over the last
few years _ although that is twice the rate of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   And even at the higher-priced institutions, many students end up
paying below the sticker price, with schools and the federal
government paying out $60 billion in grants and loans to students
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Schools also like to point out the value of investing in
college. College graduates, according to the College Board, earn on
average $1 million more over a lifetime than people who have only a
high school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   The council started the campaign after doing a survey released
in May that showed a wide gap between what college costs and what
the public thinks college costs. Seven in 10 students are eligible
for financial aid, according to the council, with the average
student at a private college receiving $9,000 in loans or grants.
</P>
<P>
   But in focus groups, families who would easily qualify for aid
said they could not afford college. The perception was especially
strong among minorities, low-income families, and students whose
parents did not attend college.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some students who go to school in the Midwest and get some
financial aid, the cost is virtually nil,'' Ikenberry said. ``For a
student who goes to a highly selective school in the Northeast,
it's likely to be a different story. But our goal is to help
families become more informed consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Boettcher, director of guidance and testing for the public
schools in Watertown, Mass., said she welcomed the message. ``Is it
a lot of money? Sure,'' she said. ``But the statistics show college
is a good investment in the long run. When you think of the cost
over your lifetime, it's shortsighted not to get your education
because you think it will cost too much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It hits people, even those with substantial means,'' Sutfin
said. ``I tell my students, `Don't let that price tag scare you
away from your dreams.' Some of them don't listen to me. They think
college is only for students who live in a home where there's a lot
of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that the campaign was akin to ``pushing a boulder
up a hill,'' Ikenberry said campaign, including the television and
newspaper ads, will run through 2000: ``It's not likely that this
is going to turn around quickly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
