<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0024 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SHUTTLE-NOSTALGIA     10-27 0282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SHUTTLE-NOSTALGIA-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla.: scheduled date.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   O'Malley, the chief test conductor for the booster, who grew up
in Montclair, N.J., and came here in 1958, a few months after the
first Soviet Sputnik stunned Americans, remembered the blockhouse
that day. He called it ``a pressure pot.'' It was rudimentary by
today's control-room standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no computers,'' he said. ``The only thing that you
might say was one, was the timer, a clock running the launching
program. When Glenn said, `The clock is started,' it was that
timer.''
</P>
<P>
   From a shelf in his den, O'Malley pulled down the mounted
ignition button that had been at his control console. It was among
such treasures as Atlas, Apollo and space shuttle models; his last
job, before he retired in 1982, was to prepare the first space
shuttle, Columbia, for launching in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   At T-minus-18 seconds in the countdown, he said, ``I hit this
button, and then put my fist on the red button next to it, ready to
activate the escape tower if necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Tape recordings caught his words at that moment. ``May the good
Lord ride all the way,'' O'Malley said. Carpenter, in the
blockhouse to handle communications between the ground and Glenn,
followed with the famous benediction, ``Godspeed, John Glenn.'' At
T-minus-0, the Atlas rose from the pad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was elated,'' O'Malley said. ``We all went to
celebrate with a keg of beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six years later, some of the old blockhouse gang will be
coming around to O'Malley's house for a fish fry, to bask in
memories of when they were young with John Glenn and sent him off
into the sky and fame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 2031EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0025 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CRONKITE-SFCHRON &LR;      10-27 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CRONKITE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRONKITE IN ORBIT OVER GLENN LAUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You might wonder who's being relaunched this week, John Glenn or
Walter Cronkite.
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite, 81, seems every bit as ubiquitous as his friend Glenn,
77, the Mercury astronaut who's due to be sent back into orbit on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   When ``60 Minutes'' ran a Glenn segment eight days ago, there
was Cronkite, sharing space program memories with the Ohio senator.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn adorns the cover of TV Guide magazine this week, his face
over the stripes of a U.S. flag. A smiling Cronkite is right next
to him, planted over the field of stars.
</P>
<P>
   And on Thursday morning, CNN will begin its extensive live
coverage of Glenn's scheduled space shuttle launch. The co-anchors
of CNN's mission coverage are Miles O'Brien and Walter Cronkite.
</P>
<P>
   So all in all, the next two weeks should be a stunning
demonstration of geriatric durability and power.
</P>
<P>
   Should be an unusual few weeks for Glenn, too.
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite, who admits to getting excited as a puppy by the manned
space program, wouldn't mind occupying Glenn's spacesuit this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted that my friend John Glenn is getting his flight,
and clearly he's the qualified one in every sense of the word,''
Cronkite said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as I told him in a phone call ... I told him that I
thought this was most unfair. I'm older than he is, and if they
want to test old age in space, I'm the guy to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Cronkite's fame derives from his space coverage as a CBS
correspondent and as anchor of ``The CBS Evening News'' from 1962
to 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Before the National Aeronautics and Space Administration,
Cronkite said, the Air Force conducted rocket tests in semisecrecy.
He and other reporters ventured out on a jetty to observe unmanned
rocket launches at Cape Canaveral in Florida. Many ended in
spectacular explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Access improved with the formation of NASA and the advent of
manned space flight, Cronkite said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even the earliest (manned) flights were very primitive,''
he said of the coverage conditions. ``I covered (Alan) Shepard's
little pop downrange from the back of a station wagon, being chewed
up by mosquitoes on top and watching out for rattlesnakes below.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shepard suborbital flight was in 1961, three weeks after
Russia's Yuri Gagarin had become the first man in space. Glenn's
orbital ride, atop a type of rocket that was apt to explode, was in
February 1962.
</P>
<P>
   That first Glenn flight lasted less than five hours. Cronkite
was at the launch site, reporting from another makeshift vantage
point.
</P>
<P>
   More than two decades later, Cronkite had surrendered the CBS
anchor desk to Dan Rather, but he still had a chance at space
flight.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to launch a civilian into space, NASA concocted a
``journalist in space'' program as a start. Cronkite was a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elimination process went quite a long way,'' he said. ``I
think we got down to 20 of us who were still in line for further
weeding out ... I felt I had a pretty good shot at that at the
time, and I was very excited and hopeful that the flight would take
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the meantime, President Reagan, making a campaign speech
before a teachers' union meeting in Chicago, got carried away and
promised that a teacher would be the first civilian in space. The
priority was changed by the president's ad-libbed comments, and
Christa McAuliffe was selected for the first civilian-in-space
flight.''
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe and six others died in the Challenger shuttle tragedy
in 1986. With a little jiggling of human destiny, it could have
been Cronkite.
</P>
<P>
   But now Cronkite will observe his 82nd birthday on November 2,
during his CNN stint with O'Brien. Though Cronkite is still under
contract at CBS, the network has no plans for extensive live
coverage of the Glenn flight and granted Cronkite permission to
appear on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   He knows that publicity is a valuable byproduct of the Glenn
mission, but Cronkite bristles, ever so slightly, at suggestions
that nothing of value to science is involved.
</P>
<P>
   The mission will test the effects of prolonged weightlessness on
an older human and, among other things, will deploy a device to
measure solar activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not child's play,'' Cronkite said. ``This is not a
vacation trip for John Glenn in any manner of speaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite said the public has become blase about the space
shuttle flights. ``I think there's a whole generation out there,
the under-29ers, who are hardly aware that we're (set ital)in(end
ital) space,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those would be the same people, presumably, who have never seen
Cronkite anchor a live news event. If an 81-year-old semiretired
newsman can get cranked about space exploration, why not a
25-year-old?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's one of the great challenges we still face,''
Cronkite said. ``This is, other than the oceans, the last great
frontier. I can't imagine anyone (set ital)not(end ital) being
excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
