<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER CONFIDENCE SLIPS   TO 1996 LOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new wave of layoffs coupled with uncertainty on Wall Street
have made consumers skittish.
</P>
<P>
   The Conference Board reported Tuesday that its consumer outlook
index, a key measurement of confidence and spending, dropped to
117.3 in October from 126.4 in September, the lowest level since
December 1996. What's more, confidence in the economy for the
coming six months has reached an almost three-year low.
</P>
<P>
   Economists blamed consumers' gloomy outlook on layoffs and the
recent upheaval in the stock market. ``The job market has a great
influence on confidence levels,'' noted Lynn Franco, economist and
associate director of the Conference Board, a nonprofit research
organization in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this actually began in July and it has carried on
since then,'' she said. ``The turmoil in the financial markets, the
volatilty, and the fact that these gyrations are now resulting in
layoffs are partly to blame.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco also warned that ``any further decline in the confidence
index could spell a bleak (Christmas sales) season for retailers.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating a tough holiday season, many merchants, including
the world's number one retailer Wal-Mart Stores Inc., are issuing
very conservative sales estimates for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are feeling cautiously optimistic because you cannot look
at what's going on in the world economy without having some
concerns about the impact it will have on the consumer,'' Shawn
Kahle, a spokeswoman for Kmart Corp., told the Associated Press.
``There's a lot on the plate and there's a lot of reason to be
skeptical.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sara Johnson, chief regional economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's
DRI in Lexington, Mass., believes the drop is mostly concentrated
in households with earnings of $50,000 or more, suggesting that the
primary influence is the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has recovered somewhat, but that has reduced
household wealth,'' she said. ``Consumers are turning cautious.
They are less optimistic about their future and that reflects
unsettled markets everywhere as well as concerns about more layoffs
due to market declines.''
</P>
<P>
   Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas, a national outplacement firm,
reports that layoffs were 53 percent higher this year than they
were in the first nine months of 1997. In September, more than
73,000 job cuts were announced in the electronics, computer,
consumer products, banking, securities, and telecommunications
industries _ all industries that have led national job growth in
the past. Both Gillette and Raytheon recently announced plans to
cut thousands of jobs nationwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
