<HEADER>
A0035 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-BRUCE28-COX     10-27 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-BRUCE28-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Taking in the signs of Space Coast
</P>
<P>
   By Jeff Bruce
</P>
<P>
   COCOA BEACH, Fla. _ They call this part of Florida the Space
Coast, and it's easy to see why.
</P>
<P>
   Travel A1A, the main artery from Satellite Beach to the Kennedy
Space Center. Drive past I Dream of Jeannie Lane, then a take a
right over Christa McAuliffe bridge and head straight until you
reach Saturn Causeway. All along this route to the space center
there are signs that this place is spacey.
</P>
<P>
   Signs. Literally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Godspeed Discovery,'' proclaims the billboard outside the
Riverside Presbyterian Church. A few blocks up the highway, the
Lido Cabaret, a strip joint, also gets into the act: ``Halloween
Costume Party. Cash prizes. Godspeed John Glenn.'' In between, the
roadside is dotted with other markers: ``Godspeed STS 95.''
``Godspeed Discovery.'' This Godspeed stuff has really caught on.
</P>
<P>
   Inside shops and restaurants, Space Shuttle T-shirts and caps
commemorating Glenn's return to outer space are flying off the
shelves. The hottest new item on the market: Beanie Baby space
suits at $6 a pop. Even the Ron Jon Surf Shop has a space souvenir
section.
</P>
<P>
   The tourism industry here, hard hit by fires, hurricanes and El
Nino, has found the onslaught of tourists a godsend. All but a
dozen or so of the area's 8,500 hotel and motel rooms are sold out
and campgrounds are ``filled to capacity,'' according to Heidi
Brandow, president of the Cocoa Beach Area Chamber of Commerce.
``We expect this to have a $20 million impact on the area. I've
never seen such interest in any launch.'' And she's been on the job
for 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of sightseers will translate into traffic gridlock, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking cats and dogs living together, real wrath of God
stuff,'' said Joan Heller, a spokeswoman for the Brevard County
Sheriff's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Heller declined to estimate the size of the crowd that will line
the beaches _ guesses are generally in the hundreds of thousands _
but she said police plan to keep their sense of humor through what
will likely be a very long day.
</P>
<P>
   ``During one of the Apollo launches, one of the guys here
directed traffic at the same intersection for 17 hours. But people
were real friendly, handing out drinks and sandwiches. Not at all
like a crowd for a Grateful Dead concert.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of rock stars and other celebs, this place is about to
be overrun with them, according to local gossip columnists. Rumor
has it that joining President Clinton on launch day will be such
luminaries as Leonardo DiCaprio, Bruce Willis, Tom Hanks, Pierce
Brosnan and Ron Howard. The rock group Aerosmith is said to be
attending, too. But, based on their record of no-shows in Dayton,
don't hold your breath.
</P>
<P>
   Also joining the celebs will be Jimmy Buffet, he who made A1A
famous in song. He's been credentialed as a bona fide reporter for
Rolling Stone magazine.
</P>
<P>
   There will be astronauts galore, as well. The surviving members
of the original Mercury program are guests of honor this evening at
a reception at the U.S. Astronaut Hall of Fame. Scott Carpenter,
Gordon Cooper and Walter Schirra will be joined in town by other
spacey luminaries such as Buzz Aldrin, Jim Lovell (he of Apollo 13
fame) and Pete Conrad.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is ga-ga over John Glenn's latest space voyage.
According to Florida Today , residents of Cape Canaveral rebelled
at a proposal to rename Central Boulevard for the first American to
orbit the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Most folks, apparently, didn't want the hassle of changing their
stationery. ``It wasn't a real popular idea,'' Mayor Rocky Randels
told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Some people just don't know how to get into the spirit of
things.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
