<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clear skies predicted for Discovery liftoff
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS; GLENNBAR, GLENN-BRUCE
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, FLA. _ Two large weather systems that threatened
Thursday's scheduled space shuttle launch took decidedly positive
turns Tuesday and now NASA's experts predict beautiful,
trouble-free weather for the liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good news, good news, good news,'' said shuttle weather
officer Ed Priselac in opening his briefing on status of weather
conditions Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Priselac said there is no chance weather will halt the launch,
even though there was a 40 percent chance of that on Monday.
Hurricane Mitch, off the coast of Honduras, has moved further west,
and a large high-pressure system over Georgia has begun drifting
south.
</P>
<P>
   Both systems had been threatening to bring high winds that could
have interfered with the launch schedule by making conditions
dangerous, not for the launch itself, but for an emergency landing
if the flight had to be aborted before reaching orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Mitch ended the northwesterly drift that made it a
concern just a day before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting even further away from us,'' Priselac said.
</P>
<P>
   But the system that was likely to have been the biggest hurdle
to getting Discovery cleared for launch was a high-pressure pocket
that seemed not to be moving Monday. If it had remained north of
the launch site, its edges would have generated problematic winds
for the area, but by moving south it will blanket central Florida
with mild temperatures and light breezes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, John Glenn and the other six members of Discovery's
crew spent the day in the space center's dormitory-style crew
quarters wrapping up last-minute details for the mission and
spending time with family.
</P>
<P>
   They were briefed again on two experiments from the flight, and
suited up in their flight gear to verify that everything fits
properly. Tuesday morning they took physical exams, and Tuesday
night had a flight-crew barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Although NASA's test director, Doug Lyons, said shuttle
preparations have fallen behind by about 1 hours due to a leak on a
ground vent line in the liquid oxygen system, he said the problem
is minor and ground crews expect to make up the time during one of
several built-in countdown holds. He said the leak is not connected
to the fuel system on the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, we're in good shape,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday night, the payload team worked until morning
loading supplies and self-contained experiments into the Spacehab
module in the shuttle, which sits on the launch pad. The Spacehab
is installed in the cargo bay and connects to the crew living
quarters by a tunnel, giving the astronauts another room to work
in.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wetherbee, a veteran of four shuttle flights, is now
director of flight crew operations, which puts him in regular
contact with the crew while they await the launch in quarantine. He
said Glenn is relaxed and ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the distinct impression he's not really 77 years old,''
Wetherbee said.
</P>
<P>
   Wetherbee said that in these days before the launch, the
intensity and tension level rachets a bit higher while crew members
begin focusing individually on the pending space flight. But he
said the building of tension is not a problem because astronauts
are chosen specifically for their ability to thrive in the most
tense of situations. He said being under the gun makes astronauts
perform best.
</P>
<P>
   And he said, ``You can tell when you watch (Glenn) operate that
he's an astronaut.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
