<HEADER>
A0037 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENNBAR28-COX     10-27 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENNBAR28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tour guide, volunteer experiences NASA fascination full-time
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Like a gruff old shepherd, gray-bearded
Angelo Taianis was trying to round up a busload of reporters and
photographers at Launch Complex 14 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, we're late,'' he muttered in a coarse voice. His flock
was scattered all over the remains of the old launch pad, all of
them absorbed in shooting or taping the weathered concrete
structure. He shook his head. ``I've got to get them back on the
bus.''
</P>
<P>
   But Taianis understood the fascination with this place. This is
where it started. Launch Complex 14 is where an Atlas rocket
blasted the Mercury capsule Friendship Seven into the sky with John
Glenn inside it, making him the first American to orbit the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   It's an event Taianis remembers well. He was in the throng of
people who quietly went about making Glenn's flight happen.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Italy and raised in Pennsylvania, Taianis served in the
Navy in World War II and was working on the Navy's Polaris missile
program in Florida when President Eisenhower created NASA, a
civilian space agency.
</P>
<P>
   Taianis decided to apply for a job. He had a degree in chemistry
and advanced engineering training, but he knew what would interest
NASA was his missile work.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were interested in anyone with missile experience,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Taianis worked on a wide variety of programs and had a hand in
450 rocket launches, including the Mercury, Gemini, Apollo and
space shuttle programs.
</P>
<P>
   He's retired now, but for 14 years he has been escorting news
media groups around Kennedy Space Center and Cape Canaveral Air
Force Station as a NASA volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   Taianis was almost apologetic about Launch Pad 14, which is 12
miles south of Launch Pad 39-B which holds space shuttle Discovery.
While the control center is well preserved, the launch pad is in
bad shape, its red steel launch tower long gone.
</P>
<P>
   Taianis will watch the launch. But he admits to ``mixed
feelings'' at the prospect of seeing the old Mercury trailblazer
climbing onto a rocket again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you see a man on the pad, it's a pretty hairy
feeling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
