<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0038 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLNER28-COX     10-27 2079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLNER28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP candidate Millner is driven as he seeks to accomplish his
goals
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS; POLITICS, RECORD
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Guy Millner has stuck to a simple marketing strategy
in trying to close the toughest sell of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Present the product: ``I'm a businessman. I want to make
government more efficient,'' he says as he vigorously pumps hands
at each campaign stop.
</P>
<P>
   Pitch the product: ``Tell all your friends to put this message
on their answering machines _ Vote Republican on Nov. 3,'' he
recently advised supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Invest heavily: To date, Millner has spent more than $11.5
million of his own money on this, his third try for statewide
office, backing it up with 15-hour days on the campaign trail in
his bid for governor.
</P>
<P>
   In the business world, where Millner made a personal fortune
valued earlier this year at $167 million, that formula has been a
tried-and-true recipe for success. But twice now in the political
world, the skills that helped him build a national network of
staffing companies have not been enough to convince Georgia voters
to put him in office.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Millner, who at age 62 admits this is likely his final
political sales pitch, is convinced his persistence, combined with
a carefully honed campaign based on boosting education, eliminating
the auto tag tax and using his business skills to streamline
government, will be enough to finally seal the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't know why I ran before,'' said Millner, who's all
too familiar with criticisms that his past political quests were
merely attempts by a bored CEO to win one more elusive trophy to
place on the mantle. ``But they're saying, `Now he must be serious
about it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rarely is Millner ever anything but serious _ at least about
going after what he wants.
</P>
<P>
   When he wanted to go to college, his parents couldn't afford it.
So Millner, the youngest of three children, who started pumping gas
at his father's Holly Hill, Fla., service station by age 10 and
sold candy bars and drinks from a roadside stand in junior high
school, decided to foot the bill himself.
</P>
<P>
   The rest has been recounted on the campaign trail so often it's
become a part of Georgia political lore: The skinny kid, so
embarrassed by his stutter in grade-school that he wouldn't raise
his hand in class, signed on to sell cookware and began peddling
pots and pans door-to-door to pay his college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   An average student by his own estimation, Millner excelled
outside the classroom. By the time he completed his political
science degree at Florida State University, he had become the
cookware company's manager for the entire state. On the side, he
also had complied a list of college friends' birthdates and used
them to get their parents to buy birthday cakes from him. An
entrepreneur was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always had that vision that he wanted to be (the head of)
one of the larger companies around,'' said Bob Turner, who dates
his friendship with Millner to the struggling, two-man personnel
business Millner formed when he came to Atlanta straight out of
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always had that in the back of his mind. And he worked at
it, long days and long hours. When you or I would be out Friday
nights going to a movie, he'd be up in the office working,'' Turner
said.
</P>
<P>
   As in his political career, Millner didn't find instant success.
He sometimes struggled to meet his payroll, friends recall. His
office, started with a $6,000 loan and second-hand furniture, was
located downtown, but Millner remembers parking eight blocks away
and walking to save 50 cents on parking.
</P>
<P>
   Parking rates are no longer a problem for Millner. The company
that started off as a permanent job placement agency changed focus
just as temporary staffing came en vogue in the early 1970s, and
Millner was the first temp service to franchise. Now Norrell Corp.,
which Millner built from the two-person firm, produces annual
revenue of $1.3 billion and makes its headquarters in a Buckhead
office development.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, two sprawling homes he owns with names as well as
street numbers _ Windcrofte, the $6 million estate of former
Coca-Cola baron Robert Woodruff that Millner calls home, and
Newington, his $3.5 million Florida home _ provide more than ample
living space.
</P>
<P>
   But tight-fisted habits learned from hard-scrabble beginnings
can be hard to break. ``If we go to a restaurant, it's `Do we have
an extra iced tea on the tab?''' said Ginny Millner, Millner's wife
of 10 years. ``If we go to the theater in New York, do you think
we're going to have a limousine? Un-uh. Here we are, we're walking
in the rain. That's his mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the same scrimp-and-save philosophy Millner promises to
bring to Georgia state government. Auditing all state agencies to
pinpoint waste and trimming the state budget by 7 percent are
central themes in Millner's second campaign for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Critics scoffed at Millner's attempts to start at the top in
politics _ all three of his campaigns have been runs at prestigious
statewide offices of governor and U.S. Senate _ and they poke holes
in his ambitious plans if elected. His combination of income tax
credits and tag tax cuts would shrink the state's revenue stream
considerably at a time when Millner is calling for 7,500 new
teachers, teacher pay raises and $1.2 billion in new spending on
prisons to fulfill his promise to abolish parole. The end result,
Democratic rival Roy Barnes says, is a balance sheet in the red by
more than $12 billion over a four-year term.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters don't doubt that Millner can balance the bottom
line numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guy has a real sense of urgency,'' said Karen Finley, a
management consultant who remembers Millner from his start-up days
in business. ``I cannot even explain to you how strong it is. He
knows what he wants to accomplish. He's very driven.''
</P>
<P>
   Millner traces that trait to his mother, who sold magazine
subscriptions on the phone to help make ends meet in the family's
modest, working-class home north of Daytona Beach, Fla. He says she
taught him never to take no for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most folks that come from a lower-income family setting, and
certainly that's where we were, you build up more ambition, more of
a drive to succeed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons stuck. As he worked to expand Norrell, Millner's
persistence led to his habit of scheduling not one but two business
lunches to woo a client. He felt they would be more receptive in
that relaxed setting over a meal. Punctuality was an expected
virtue, and late-night brainstorming calls to top executives were
the norm.
</P>
<P>
   His discipline also bleeds into his personal life, where one of
his first questions on his first date with wife Ginny was an
inquiry about her five-year plan. He schedules time to exercise _ a
program of speedwalking and stretching routines _ just as he would
a business meeting. Friends say he's as competitive on the golf
course as he is in the boardroom. The routine, as described by
some, is simple: a smooth shot, and a glance over the shoulder
followed by a confident quip ``Any questions?''
</P>
<P>
   But his hard-driving nature has had personal costs. His first
marriage failed, he admits, in part, because it had to compete with
his job creating Norrell. While other politicians keep in touch
with college friends and hometown acquaintances, Millner has lost
contact with most boyhood friends and college pals. Some of his
children, now actively working on his campaign, have said they felt
neglected while growing up when Millner missed key occasions and
his gifts to them often were picked out by secretaries.
</P>
<P>
   While Millner has made amends with his children and says he's
learned to balance business with family in his third marriage, some
former employees and business associates recall a hard-bitten
executive more concerned with profits than with business ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Lolies, who spent 24 years with Millner's printing
division, says he cheated employees out of generous pensions when
he decided to sell off that part of the company seven years ago.
After verbally promising them they could remain a part of the
Norrell stock pension plan, Lolies claims, Millner issued checks to
former employees for their shares a few years before Norrell went
public and the stock soared.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd been allowed to keep mine, it would have been a quarter
million (dollars). Instead, I got $18,000,'' said Lolies, 58. ``I
stuck to my end of the deal. I put the company ahead of my family.
And they didn't stick to their end of the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Millner did not respond directly. But while associates admit
he's demanding they take issue with characterizations of Millner as
a ruthless businessman. ``I'd say he was very generous with his
ex-employees,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Millner himself has been his own worst enemy, feeding
the perception of insensitivity. Confronted with his membership in
an exclusive club in Florida with a reputation for excluding black
people and Jewish people, Millner at first was unapologetic. Later
he said would resign, only to withdraw the resignation request
after losing the 1996 U.S. Senate contest. He completed the
resignation, he says, before launching his latest bid for governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always trying to cram 10 pounds in a 2-pound bag,''
Millner explains. ``Sometimes when you're too focused, you tend to
appear to be uncaring. If you're too business-like, you tend to not
be warm and fuzzy.''
</P>
<P>
   But defenders say Millner's critics get too much attention,
while his generosity goes unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't see the same person the newspaper depicts,'' said
Mary Ann Schrecengost, principal at Cedar Grove High School, a
predominately minority school in south DeKalb County where Millner
funded a college scholarship for B-average students, among other
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw someone who was willing to sit down on the floor with
the kids and get their feedback,'' she said. ``He was always coming
up with bigger programs. He wanted to include more kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Millner and Norrell directed almost as much money into the
school for programs recognizing academic achievement as the county
did on a per-student basis for day-to-day operations, Schrecengost
said.
</P>
<P>
   His personal fortune allows Millner to infuse his wealth into a
variety of causes, many of them like his recent seven-figure
contributions to the Salvation Army and United Way.
</P>
<P>
   Talking to voters, Millner downplays his wealth. He declines
opportunities to be interviewed or photographed at his home, and
often couches his programs as an opportunity to help families
working ``two or three jobs'' to make ends meet. Khakis and
open-collar shirts are his preferred attire on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Associates say that's always been his pattern. Because of that
low key approach, Kaaren Johnson-Street remembers, her first
meeting with Millner almost didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I passed him twice before we finally recognized each other,''
the Florida marketer and member of Norrell's board of directors
said. ``I was expecting $500 shoes and monogrammed shirts. But he's
not pretentious at all.''
</P>
<P>
   But Millner's wealth always crops up as a major issue in
politics, with his willingness to spend freely on his own campaigns
characterized by opponents as an attempt to buy the office.
</P>
<P>
   In two earlier contests that each failed by less than 2 percent
of the vote, Millner mixed fund-raising with his own generous loans
to the campaign. But he acknowledges in his third bid at elected
office that he's now less reluctant to reach into his own wallet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sensitive about it, and I spent a disproportionate
amount of my time fund-raising,'' Millner said of his earlier
contests. ``But I've laid that little alligator aside, and I've
become less concerned about it because people know I'm working
very, very hard. ... It perhaps sounds like Pollyanna to a lot of
people, but I believe God gives you gifts and you ought to use
them.''
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNOR
</P>
<P>
   Term: 4 years
</P>
<P>
   Annual pay: $111,480
</P>
<P>
   GUY MILLNER (R)
</P>
<P>
   Party Affiliation: Republican
</P>
<P>
   Age: 62
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Education: Bachelor's degree, Florida State University
</P>
<P>
   Profession: Founder and board member of Norrell Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Political experience: None
</P>
<P>
   Personal: Wife, Ginny; three children, two stepchildren
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
