<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECORD28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Business background prompts scrutiny of company's practices
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A gleaming Buckhead office tower and a $1.3 billion
bottom line in the staffing company he built from a two-man firm is
the business success story Guy Millner pitches to Georgia voters.
</P>
<P>
   As the former chief executive officer of Norrell Corp., Millner
promises to transfer his experience from the corporate boardroom to
the Governor's Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news about me as a candidate is that I'm a business
person,'' he tells voters.
</P>
<P>
   But critics, chief among them Democratic nominee Roy Barnes,
argue that Millner's business success also brings an unattractive
downside. They say Millner, who has criticized Barnes' votes during
his 22 years in the Legislature, should be measured by his own
corporate record.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from his stand-out accomplishments with Norrell, which
employs about 60,000 people and supplies staffing for about half
the Fortune 500 companies such as IBM, that record includes a
string of lawsuits, state health department citations and irate
former associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made business experience the centerpiece of his
campaign,'' said Barnes, who has aired TV spots attacking Millner's
ethics and business practices.''But he cuts corners that put more
money in his pocket but cause injury to the little people.''
</P>
<P>
   Millner's foray into health care staffing _ at a time when many
companies joined the field expecting big profits from hospitals and
Medicare reimbursements _ provides the most fodder for his critics.
</P>
<P>
   _ During a six-year period leading up to 1993 when Norrell sold
its home health care staffing chain, health department
investigators in 14 states cited Millner's health care agencies for
more than 240 violations.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those were routine technical or record-keeping errors
that didn't directly compromise patient care, such as irregular
board of directors meetings or not properly informing patients of
their rights.
</P>
<P>
   But other problems raised more serious questions. In many
agencies, nurses or aides did not receive the required 14-hour
annual training. Many others lacked proof of licenses, and in some
instances were not licensed in the state where they practiced.
Medication or care was administered without, or contrary to,
doctor's written orders, and in other cases aides were weeks late
in reporting infections, abuse and changes in medical conditions to
doctors or supervisors, according to state documents.
</P>
<P>
   _ A jury awarded an Alabama woman with Lou Gerhig's disease
$340,000 in 1993 after a Norrell home health care agency
overcharged her insurance company, prematurely exhausting her
coverage. Norrell appealed, but later settled. In another Alabama
suit, the company settled for a higher dollar amount, attorneys
said, after Norrell-supplied nurses failed to properly care for a
respirator-dependent child.
</P>
<P>
   _ Norrell home health care fired an executive in California for
what she claimed was her refusal to falsify Medicare records, and
later settled that 1987 lawsuit for a reported $750,000. Also, a
caterer sued the health care agency and an Encino, Calif., hospital
for $1 million after she said a Norrell health aide abused and
assaulted her during a sponge bath. The case was settled
confidentially, but the nurse pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor and
was sentenced to three years' probation and three months in jail or
500 hours of community service. Other suits are pending or were
settled for smaller amounts. After repeated citations, Maryland
health officials threatened to revoke Norrell's health care license
in Silver Spring, Md. Carol Benner, head of the licensing division
at the time, called the problems ``very serious violations, the
scope and extent of which are rarely seen in home health-care
providers.'' Texas health officials also warned Norrell that
deficiencies jeopardized the Austin office's continued
participation in Medicare programs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Norell's contract agents complained of business
arrangements they said gave Norrell 60 percent of the health care
commissions and left them financially strapped as the company
constantly turned over managers and reneged on promises to train
the nursing staff and recruit business. ``Norrell cost me a small
fortune, and I'm still not out of hock,'' said Harry Ward, who
closed his South Carolina service eight years ago. ``Millner made
his money off people like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all major businesses, Millner says, Norrell at times hit
some rough spots and sometimes ``didn't please everybody.'' But
lawsuits and vendor complaints, particularly against
multi-million-dollar companies, aren't uncommon. And many companies
that entered the health care arena with big plans later did as
Norrell did: they backed away from a venture that didn't pan out as
planned.
</P>
<P>
   Millner insists those problems don't detract from his overall
plan to use business principles to make Georgia government more
efficient. ``I'm not perfect and I make mistakes,'' Millner said in
a recent interview. But ``any time we've had an issue at Norrell
where there was a difficulty when I was CEO, I quickly moved to
address it.''
</P>
<P>
   Health department citations from each state outline a plan that
Norrell promised to undertake immediately to correct the
deficiencies. Millner's campaign also pointed out that the
complaints and suits were against the company, not Millner
individually. In each of the case settlements, Norrell did not
admit wrongdoing. At least two other cases were discontinued or
granted summary judgment in Norrell's favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of my business success,'' Millner said. ``My record
will stack up pretty good against, frankly, any business success
story in this state. I hope that's the debate _ who's the best
business person _ because if it is, Guy Millner wins.''
</P>
<P>
   In such a tight contest, political scientists aren't surprised
at the emphasis on years-old business decisions, especially as they
relate to health care, a prominent issue this year. ``Millner has
opened himself up to this,'' said the University of Georgia's
Charles Bullock. ``When you say I will run the state as a business,
it makes it fair game to pick out the worst part and ask voters do
you really want to see this.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
