<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACHOVIA-BUY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wachovia to buy brokerage firm
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wachovia announced Tuesday it will acquire
Interstate/Johnson Lane, a full-service securities firm
headquartered in Charlotte, N.C., for stock currently worth about
$230 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which continues the trend of brokerage industry
consolidation, was announced after the market closed. Wachovia
stock closed at $82.75, down $2.56 1/4. Interstate/Johnson Lane
shares closed at $37, up $3.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fills a hole for Wachovia,'' said Robinson-Humphrey
analyst John Coffey.
</P>
<P>
   Wachovia has relatively little visibility in the securities
business, no full-service retail brokerage system and no
stock-underwriting capability. It will now have all these along
with 63 offices in Georgia, Virginia and the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is expected to close in the first half of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Robert McCoy, chief financial officer of Wachovia, said that
excluding merger costs, the acquisition will not diminish 1999
earnings and will add to them in 2000 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   James H. Morgan, chief executive of Interstate/Johnson Lane,
said his firm approached Wachovia about six or seven weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have made it alone,'' he said, but the ``changing
landscape'' of the world as well as the securities business
prompted the search for a partner.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan will become chief executive of a new subsidiary to be
called Wachovia Securities. But that's just the legal name, and the
banking company will continue to use the familiar name,
Interstate/Johnson Lane, in combination with Wachovia, McCoy said.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy said he expects ``a statistically insignificant number of
job losses at either firm,'' but Wachovia has established a $23
million kitty to keep the brokerage firm's employees from leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Wachovia employs about 22,000, including 5,000 in Atlanta.
Interstate/Johnson Lane has about 250 employees in Atlanta and
1,500 overall.
</P>
<P>
   Wachovia said that, in order to prevent earnings per share
dilution, it intends to repurchase in the open market a number of
its shares equal to those used for the purchase. Those would be in
addition to a stock buyback program previously announced. The
banking company said it may also purchase shares of
Interstate/Johnson Lane prior to the merger.
</P>
<P>
   With the purchase of Interstate/ Johnson Lane, just three major
independent Southeastern securities firms will remain:
Nashville-based J.C. Bradford, Memphis-based Morgan Keegan and St.
Petersburg-headquartered Raymond James &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
