was the man who on the morning of Feb. 20, 1962, pressed the black
button to start the Atlas booster's engines and send Glenn on his
way in a Mercury capsule to be the first American to orbit the
planet. He is 83 now, still full of sass and gruff charm, and
brimming with stories of the old days. Like O'Malley, many of those
who shared the anxiety, thrill and glory of the first Glenn flight
in 1962 are gathering here again to sip at the fountain of their
youth. By John Noble Wilford. (The story has moved in ``a'' news
file.) 1,400 words. With photo and graphic.
</P>
