<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-INVESTORS-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW EUROPEAN INVESTORS AREN'T SCARED BY MARKET FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ A fresh crop of European stock owners, the result of
government privatizations of industry and a general trend toward
equity investment, has been battered by recent global market
turmoil. Yet experts say it has survived to bear fruit another day.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, soaring stock markets, low returns on
government bonds and European policies that required people to take
a greater hand in shaping their pension plans prompted millions of
Europeans who had never before ventured near the stock market to
pour record amounts of money into individual equities and mutual
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, when stock-market indexes fell sharply last summer,
economists and government planners in European nations wondered how
this freshly minted generation of share owners would react. The
answer, said Claudio Fermi, a senior investment officer at Credito
Italiano, one of Italy's biggest banks, has been ``generally,
pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   No evidence has emerged, he and other experts said in recent
interviews, that these first-time investors have been permanently
frightened away. And indeed, though net flow of capital into stocks
and mutual funds has plummeted since August, much of the resulting
liquidity went into short-term money-market funds, apparently in
anticipation of an eventual market revival.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for such a reaction, experts say, is clear: With
interest rates at all-time lows, European investors, like their
American counterparts, have few alternatives to the stock market.
``There is a willingness to go back in if any change occurs,'' said
Andrea Fischer, a retail investment officer at Bayerische Hypo-und
Vereinsbank in Munich, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Others are more cautious. Recent experience, they say, shows
that Europe has far to go before stocks become the investment of
choice for the middle class, as they have among many in the United
States. Forty-three percent of American adults own stocks, either
directly or through mutual funds, compared with 25 percent of
Britons and 16 percent of the French.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the European march toward a single currency,
and the tight monetary policies and low inflation that went with
it, pushed interest rates lower and lower. Those rate cuts, coupled
with the increased availability of stocks, as European governments
sold shares in formerly nationalized industries, prompted Europeans
to shift savings from bonds, insurance policies and bank accounts
into individual stocks and, even more often, mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   By March, net monthly payments into mutual funds, one of the
best gauges of investor behavior, had soared above $13 billion,
compared with less than $1 billion a month in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the funds emerged as a significant force on stock
markets. Yet, in August, when global markets slumped, net payments
plunged to $2.5 billion, less than a quarter of the more than $10
billion recorded in July.
</P>
<P>
   In September, this trend apparently continued, though final
figures are not yet available, said Caroline Meroz, who follows
mutual-fund flows at Salomon Smith Barney in London. Italy, for
instance, recorded net outflows of $1.3 billion, she said, though
she described this as ``not too unsettling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows,'' she said, ``that the Italians have become more
sophisticated, that there is more switching in and out.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, at least, the Italian outflows were a result of
investors' diversifying out of Italian funds into European funds,
Ms. Meroz said, a process that is expected to accelerate across
Europe in coming months as the introduction in January of the
single currency, the euro, approaches and investors spread their
assets beyond national boundaries.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Moreover, in other European countries, investors proved
resilient. In France, for example, mutual-fund contributions have
continued to slow, but the net flow has remained positive.
Similarly in Spain, which is closely watched because of the
economy's dependence on battered emerging markets, like those in
Latin America, net positive flows continued despite a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   European financial professionals are still in the early stages
of educating retail investors not to flee stocks at the first sign
of a market downturn. Thus, in 1987 and again in 1994, when
European markets slumped, large numbers of investors fled in panic
to fixed-income investments. This time, bankers and investment
managers say they are encouraged that the reaction was not as
severe. They attribute this to several factors.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, while Europeans have turned to mutual funds, the
funds on the whole continue to be extremely conservative. Fermi of
Credito Italiano said that only about 25 percent of assets in Italy
were invested in stocks; the rest are in fixed-income instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while many European investors still prefer bonds,
bankers in several countries said they had seen a greater
inclination this time around, as in the United States, to park
assets in money-market funds and await a stock-market upswing. And
some investors have even been scouring the lists, pushing to invest
as prices dip. ``There is a desire to purchase,'' Fermi said,
``though it is not yet widespread.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some experts cautioned that mutual-fund flows in Europe
would continue to be more volatile than in the United States, not
least because of the absence as yet of tax-based incentives to
stock ownership, that ensure regular monthly flows into funds.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Britain, Ms. Meroz of Salomon Smith Barney
said, ``in Europe, you still don't have 401(k)s, IRAs, tax breaks _
so it's not going to be as smooth as that.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, the absence of alternatives for investors
ensures that the trend will continue. ``I don't think it will stop
long term, but it will slow down,'' she said, adding: ``It's the
wave of the future. You have to put your money somewhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
