<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE WON'T STEAL GLENN'S THUNDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Hurricane Mitch turned its back Tuesday
on John Glenn's return to orbit, clearing the way for the world's
oldest rocket jock to blast off from this barrier island where
space history gets made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now 100 percent to go,'' said Ed Priselac, a weather
forecaster with the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
A day earlier, a concerned Priselac said there was only a 60
percent chance the weather would cooperate for Thursday's scheduled
launch of Glenn and six crewmates aboard the space shuttle
Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   But with the powerful hurricane heading toward Honduras, and a
cooperative high pressure system settling over Launch Pad 39B,
Priselac and other NASA officials said their earlier fears of high
winds had evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   It was an equally placid day for the Discovery crew. After
arriving here Monday amid mechanical delays and minor glitches,
Glenn and his crewmates spent Tuesday morning reviewing their roles
aboard the shuttle, checking equipment and undergoing brief medical
exams. The afternoon was given over to family time, though a
quarantine designed to keep the crew free from colds or infections
kept Glenn at least eight feet from his grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Far more excitement was found throughout the rest of the Kennedy
Space Center and the surrounding area, which was girding for what
was expected to be the biggest onslaught of visitors since the 1969
moon launch.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 3,500 journalists and technicians requested credentials
to cover the launch, and the NASA press center was crawling with
media. More than two dozen television trucks lined the road, and
representatives of the major television networks were entrenched in
bunker-like structures from which their biggest stars will guide
live coverage throughout launch day.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and more than 60 members of Congress are
expected to be on hand, and other 1960s icons such as Walter
Cronkite and Glenn's three surviving Mercury 7 colleagues plan to
offer commentary.
</P>
<P>
   The last sitting president to watch a liftoff in person was
Richard Nixon, who was present for Apollo 12 in 1969. NASA launched
during a thunderstorm, and the rocket was hit by lightning, but
without serious consequences.
</P>
<P>
   This time for NASA, the excitement is tinged with at least a
little worry.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials estimate that each shuttle flight has a 1-in-483
chance of exploding upon launch. Reality, however, suggests even
worse odds; there have been 91 shuttle launches to date, with one
catastrophic failure _ the 1986 Challenger explosion.
</P>
<P>
   The image of that disaster is never far from anyone's mind here.
The road leading to the space center has been renamed Challenger
Memorial Parkway. And when Glenn told his children he was going to
fly again, his son David, a doctor, immediately imagined the
terrifying y-shaped plume of smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I was thinking about was the replay of Challenger in my
mind,'' David Glenn said in a NASA interview. He visualized the
explosion ``over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   While any major problems with a shuttle launch would be
disastrous for the space program, NASA officials are well aware
that the stakes are even higher with this mission.
</P>
<P>
   Technicians are on high alert in light of an unusually long
four-month gap between shuttle liftoffs. Ground crews have
undergone a series of drills and fake launches ``so the guys are
sharp,'' said launch director Ralph Roe. The space center also is
still recovering from February layoffs. But an independent safety
panel has given its blessing for the launch.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's nine-day mission will concentrate on science, with
Glenn participating in 10 experiments on the effects of
weightlessness on the human body and how those effects might relate
to aging on Earth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
