<HEADLINE>
BUSH, MAURO STUMP WEST TEXAS CITIES, PUSH DIFFERING POSITIONS ON
EDUCATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
and ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush and Democratic challenger
Garry Mauro stressed voter turnout and staked out their differing
positions on education as they stumped in several West Texas cities
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And a Lubbock official challenged Bush's commitment to Hispanic
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush toured Lubbock-Cooper Intermediate School to promote his
efforts to end ``social promotion'' in public schools. The Cooper
district already uses the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills test
to determine whether fourth-graders advance to fifth grade.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has proposed that all students in third, fifth and eighth
grades be required to pass the TAAS for promotion to the next
grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about a system that moved children through the
system who can't read,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants to spend $203 million on a reading program to prepare
students before they take the test. He also advocates remedial
programs and second-chance tests for students who fail.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro contends that promotion should be based on teacher
assessments rather than on a standardized test alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a fourth-grader and a fifth-grader and I'm like most
parents,'' he said. ``I'm sick and tired of the TAAS test.'' He
said that teachers spend too much time preparing students for the
TAAS and not enough on other academic endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   He has advocated an across-the-board teacher pay raise and
expenditures from the state's public education trust, the Permanent
School Fund, to add classrooms and reduce class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will end social promotion the right way,'' Mauro said at
Democratic headquarters in Abilene.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro, the state's land commissioner, also campaigned in
Amarillo, Lubbock, Odessa, San Angelo, and Del Rio.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates pushed for voter turnout, with Mauro predicting
that the victims of recent floods in South Texas, San Antonio and
suburban Houston may have other priorities than politics.
</P>
<P>
   But he also expressed optimism about Democratic turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that a lot of the Republican voters are going to think
that George Bush is a &UR;  &LR; shoo-in and are not going to be very
motivated to vote, but every Democratic voter is going to
understand I'm in a tough race and they're going to be motivated to
vote,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At rallies at Abilene Christian College and in Lubbock and
Amarillo, Bush said he is working to turn out the votes on Election
Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more people who turn out to vote, the better it is for
me,'' Bush said in Abilene. ``My object is to travel the state and
encourage people to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Political professionals are predicting a low turnout in this
non-presidential election, with a lopsided race at the top of the
ticket where polls give Bush a commanding lead over Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of making inroads with traditionally Democratic
Hispanic voters, the governor, who speaks Spanish, has campaigned
in South Texas, and has made Spanish-language campaign commercials.
</P>
<P>
   A Lubbock official who appeared with Mauro Tuesday was skeptical
of Bush's outreach. ``When he comes to Lubbock you can't get him
out of the country clubs,'' said County Commissioner Gilbert
Flores.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has never visited the Hispanic community here. We have
never seen him in the barrio, we have never seen him in the
churches, we have never seen him in the community centers,'' Flores
said. ``He has never come to see me or anybody in my precinct.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush acknowledged that he hasn't met with Flores, but said,
``I've done a lot for Hispanic parents by fixing an education
program that teaches every child to read. I've worked very hard to
make sure any of the nativist tendencies in the state of Texas
don't raise their heads. I've worked on uniting, not dividing.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
