<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Injuries will make Falcons dig deep
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With the Atlanta Falcons as injured now as they have
been in recent memory, the obvious question is: Where's the depth?
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves' team will be looking for replacements at
several positions this week because of knee injuries to starting
cornerback Ronnie Bradford and kick returner/wide receiver Tim
Dwight, each expected to miss six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And there's no guarantee that starting quarterback Chris
Chandler (shoulder/ribs), starting defensive tackle Travis Hall
(bruised knee) and starting middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle (ankle)
will be able to play Sunday against the St. Louis Rams (2-5).
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: The Falcons (5-2) will get an up-close
look at the first draft choice of the Reeves era. Second-year
cornerback Michael Booker, the No. 11 overall pick of the 1997
draft, replaces Bradford.
</P>
<P>
   If Chandler can't play, second-year man Tony Graziani or 17-year
veteran Steve DeBerg will start. If Hall can't play, first-year
tackle Shawn Swayda _ cut as an end last year by the Bears _ will
dress for the third time.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight will be replaced as kickoff returner by Elijah Williams,
a rookie, and at receiver by Jammi German, another rookie.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, the Falcons might have had the luxury of plugging
in a six- or seven-year veteran in these spots. But the advent of
the NFL's salary cap in 1993 has changed a lot.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, like most teams, have a payroll that is weighted
heavily toward the salaries of a handful of players at the top, and
as a result, the roster is heavily populated by inexpensive,
inexperienced players elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Counting salaries and pro-rated signing bonuses, Chandler ($3.5
million), linebackers Cornelius Bennett ($3.45 million) and Jessie
Tuggle ($3.45 million), cornerback Ray Buchanan ($3 million), left
tackle Bob Whitfield ($3 million) and defensive end Chuck Smith
($2.6 million), wide receivers Terance Mathis ($1.9 million) and
Tony Martin ($1.45 million) and Booker ($1.42 million) count $23.77
million against this year's cap.
</P>
<P>
   That means nine players account for almost half _ 47.5 percent _
of the $50 million payroll. The other 44 players on the active
roster and five on the practice squad account for most of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't afford to pay for a lot of depth and stay under the
salary cap,'' Reeves said. ``A lot of times, you're going to keep
(more rookies), because they're at the minimum (NFL salary).''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons this season kept eight of nine draft choices plus
undrafted rookie tackle Jose Portilla. Last year, they kept all
nine draft choices, and seven are still on the team.
</P>
<P>
   It has gotten too expensive to keep players around a long time
to see if they develop. The minimum NFL salary for a five-year
veteran is $325,000; for rookies, it's $158,000.
</P>
<P>
   A new NFL rule says a player with four or more years of
experience who is on the opening-day roster has his salary
guaranteed, even if cut. So, even if a mid-career guy isn't
performing, a team might not be able to afford to cut him.
</P>
<P>
   The salary cap leaves less room for error in personnel
decisions, and teams often have to live with those errors.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons thought Corey Louchiey would be an upgrade at right
tackle and gave him a $500,000 signing bonus in the spring. If he
made the team, his salary-cap number would have been $750,000.
Instead, rookie Ephraim Salaam, with a $158,000 cap number, is
starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams are holding onto most of their (good) players,'' said
Falcons vice president of football operations Ron Hill, who looked,
but couldn't find, a seasoned alternative to Louchiey.
</P>
<P>
   The money situation places greater emphasis on the draft. Teams
have to get it right the first time around.
</P>
<P>
   Booker's litmus test is coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before free-agency, once you drafted that guy he was yours for
his entire career,'' Hill said. ``Players didn't have a choice to
leave you other than by trade or waiver. You could take more time
to develop them. A lot of times now, you can't wait.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
