<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After tackle positions, are owners getting their money's worth?
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Minnesota Vikings are paying John Randle $12.5
million this year to figure out how to split a double-team block,
not the atom. It turns out, though, the five-time Pro Bowl
performer is almost as much a scientist as he is one of the NFL's
premier defensive tackles.
</P>
<P>
   After spending the first seven years of his NFL career seeking
fame and fortune, toiling in a crowded laboratory between the
offensive tackles, Randle discovered recognition during a brilliant
1997 season. Then, he found remuneration this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The formula, suggested Randle, 30, had been right under his nose
tackle all the while.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stopping the run is great, but when you knock down the
quarterback time and again, somebody is going to pay you almost as
much as they're paying those quarterbacks,'' said Randle, who last
year became the first defensive tackle to lead the NFL in sacks (15
1/2) since they became an official statistic in 1982. ``And if you
can do it from the tackle position, you really become a hot
commodity. People put a premium on us guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The offseason validated Randle's hypothesis that a high profile
translates into big dollars. Desperate for defenders to pressure
from the inside, counter the trend toward shorter pass drops and
still clog the inside against the run, teams created a nouveau
riche subset at the tackle position.
</P>
<P>
   The rationale was that, with quarterbacks getting rid of the
ball faster in the West Coast-style offenses, defensive ends were
frustrated having to claw their way to a passer who already had
unloaded. Tackles can exert more immediate pressure and take a more
direct route into the backfield. The evolution of the pass rush
appeared to be gravitating from the edge of the defense toward the
interior.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Randle lead the NFL in sacks, but another tackle,
Dana Stubblefield of San Francisco, was the runner-up. As
unrestricted free agents Randle stayed in Minnesota, Stubblefield
relocated to Washington, and both got rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely was a seller's market (for defensive tackles) in
free-agency,'' said Miami coach Jimmy Johnson, who bid
unsuccessfully for Randle and Sean Gilbert. ``Everybody wanted that
big inside guy who could get to the passer. It was the marquee
position.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so that veteran tackles with even modest credentials
cashed in big. Eight-year veteran Ray Agnew, who had just two of
his 11 career sacks with the New York Giants in 1997, landed a
four-year, $8.1 million deal, including a $2 million signing bonus,
from St. Louis. Bill Johnson, a journeyman run-stuffer with
documented off-field problems, signed for two years, $3.9 million
in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that,'' Johnson said, ``was chump change compared to a lot
of (tackles).''
</P>
<P>
   A dozen defensive tackles signed contracts worth more than $3
million per year, and eight got deals valued at more than $5
million annually. The 12 tackles collected an aggregate $80.55
million in signing bonuses and the collective worth of the dozen
deals is $325.24 million.
</P>
<P>
   For those tackles who had labored in obscurity for years,
saddled by the traditional job description as strictly a
run-stuffer, such sudden financial reward seemingly meant new-found
respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have become the new glamour position,'' Tampa Bay tackle
Warren Sapp said after signing a six-year, $35.47 million deal.
``Now it's our turn, man, to get some of that glitz and glitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight weeks into the season, the tackle position has lost some
luster. The results are mixed at best, especially with the failure
of Redskins tackles Stubblefield and Dan Wilkinson to make an
impact. The Redskins are paying the tandem $16.4 million this year
in signing bonuses and base salaries. Through seven games
Stubblefield and Wilkinson have combined for 39 solo tackles and
four sacks. The Skins are 0-7, and their defense ranks No. 26
overall in the league. It is 28th against the run, after finishing
No. 28 last year and 30th in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Accustomed during his five seasons in San Francisco to an
aggressive and penetrating style, Stubblefield has struggled
converting to the two-gap approach that's dictated by the
Washington scheme. It is a technique that neutralizes his innate
quickness, holds him accountable for the gaps to both sides of the
blocker and forces him to hand-fight at the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   An underachiever during four seasons in Cincinnati, ``Big
Daddy'' Wilkinson, the first selection in the '94 draft, has been a
source of frustration for long-time defensive-line coach Earl
Leggett. His work habits are only marginally better than when he
was with the Bengals and, while he has generated inside pressure,
Wilkinson frequently has been blown away by less-talented guards in
the running game.
</P>
<P>
   In their 31-10 victory at Washington Oct. 4, the Dallas Cowboys
secured the triumph with an 11-play, 96-yard touchdown drive. All
11 plays were runs and eight, for 79 yards, were directed at
Wilkinson or Stubblefield.
</P>
<P>
   Stubblefield denied last week that he feels the pressure of
living up to the investment that Washington, and, after a long
meeting with defensive coordinator Mike Nolan, his performance has
improved the last three outings. Still, Stubblefield's attempt to
justify the fat paycheck is a factor in his subpar play, one
opponent suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see it in the man's eyes,'' Dallas guard Nate Newton
said. ``You almost see the wheels turning like, `I've got to make
this play.' He's taking himself out of plays with bad angles,
sloppy technique. Oh, yeah, he's pressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Stubblefield and Wilkinson aren't the only defensive tackles who
haven't lived up to the press clippings.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert, who played the first month of '98 with a broken hand,
hasn't been much of a force at right end in Carolina's 3-4 front.
Some of Eric Swann's attitude problems have resurfaced in Arizona,
and he still just leans into people on too many snaps. Miami tackle
Tim Bowens has played the run well but doesn't have a sack. Chester
McGlockton, who went from Oakland to AFC West rival Kansas City,
underwent back surgery the day before the season began. He saw his
first action Monday night against Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, 13 of 39 defenders with eight sacks or more were
tackles. Nearing the halfway point of this season, just two tackles
are in the top 10 in sacks. Nine tackles are on pace to get eight
sacks for the season. The sack leaders among tackles, Jim Flanigan
of Chicago and Bryant Young of San Francisco, have 6 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   All franchises covet a dominating tackle, but some scouts now
think that free agents at the position benefited from the overall
dearth of front seven talent in a diluted league. They are quick to
rebutt the notion that the game has moved in the direction of more
athletic interior players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nearly every one of those big guys had questions hanging over
them,'' San Diego personnel director Billy Devaney said. ``You can
say the game was moving toward the tackles because that's where the
money went. But it's more a function of not having enough of the
speed-rushers around. If you can find anybody who can pressure the
quarterback, no matter what position, his marketability is going to
be unbelievable. If there is a tackle who can give you any
semblance of a pass rush, it jacks the value up. But when you look
at the tackles who got all the money ... most of them had some
history of not playing up to their contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   But faced with the Skins' interior shortcomings of the past few
seasons _ when club management was convinced that a porous front
four cost them a shot at the playoffs _ most personnel men agreed
that they might have taken the same road as Washington general
manager Charley Casserly.
</P>
<P>
   They acknowledged that, even with the mixed results of '98,
defensive tackles might be worth gambling millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona personnel director Bob Ferguson said, ``(Casserly) paid
what it takes. He needed two of those guys, and it cost him plenty.
But you know what? If he hadn't paid it, some other team would
have. (Defensive tackles) are like gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
