<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-DAMAGE-ESTIMATES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas flood damage estimated at $800 million
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The preliminary damage tally from the recent Texas
floods doubled to almost $831 million Tuesday, as federal disaster
officials opened five new relief centers offering aid and loans to
displaced homeowners and businesses in 25 counties.
</P>
<P>
   According to initial damage estimates by 20 of the counties that
have been declared federal disaster areas, $570 million worth of
homes, $53.7 million worth of businesses and $207 million worth of
roads and bridges were damaged.
</P>
<P>
   The flood killed 29 people; two more are missing.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 18,000 structures affected, the estimates show more than
half were destroyed or severely damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disaster area covers more than 21,000 square miles _ about
the size of West Virginia,'' said Tom Millwee, state emergency
coordinator. ``This is a large area with a lot of damage and a lot
of a debris.''
</P>
<P>
   State and federal officials cautioned against putting too much
credence in the rising damage estimate. Some of the figures are
probably more ``guess-timate'' than estimate, they said, until
on-site appraisals can be completed in coming weeks, including
appraisals of damage that is covered by private insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Millwee and other officials said the latest numbers
illustrate the severity of the flooding. Initially, they said it
could compare to the devastation from flooding that struck
Southeast Texas four years ago, killing about 30 people.
</P>
<P>
   The initial damage estimate last week was about $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Robert Hendrix, who heads Federal Emergency
Management Agency relief efforts, announced that five local relief
centers will open today in New Braunfels, San Antonio, Cuero,
Victoria and Wharton.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few days, federal relief officials expect to have more
than 300 people at work in a north Austin headquarters that opened
Sunday. They will coordinate and support hundreds of other state
and federal relief workers who have fanned out across the
devastated areas _ offering victims face-to-face help in finding
temporary housing, making repairs to their damaged homes and
businesses, assistance with federal loan paperwork and arranging
for removal of dead animals and other debris.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday morning, Hendrix said, 10,300 people had applied for
federal disaster assistance through a special toll-free phone line
set up last week. More than 4,800 people already have filed federal
flood insurance claims, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen shelters remained open, housing 481 people. A convoy of
mobile homes were being assembled for transfer to hard-hit Cuero to
provide temporary homes, as Army soldiers opened a shower tent to
let homeless residents wash up.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush issued an executive order waiving all title
fees involving manufactured homes for victims of the recent floods
that struck Central and South Texas, the Houston area and Del Rio.
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides said the order will save Del Rio victims $140 in fees
per home and will simplify their purchases. FEMA officials said
about 200 manufactured homes are being made available to Del Rio
residents whose homes were destroyed in the August floods.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
