<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOURFEA28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magee taking it easy in bonus rounds
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Andrew Magee, instead of fretting Sunday whether he
had blown his shot to make the Tour Championship and scrolling
nervously through the PGA Tour's website, took son Campbell to a
Scottsdale, Ariz., bowling alley.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually discovering Sunday night that Smyrna's Stewart Cink
had finished 51st at Walt Disney World and failed to catch him at
No. 30 on the money list, Magee classified all that happens this
week at East Lake Golf Club as pure bonus minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't expect to play,'' he said. ``It's nice to get
a reprieve to play one more week. Maybe I can find some magic out
here.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second year in a row, not only has Magee finished 30th
and grabbed the final spot in the $4 million season-ending event,
but an Atlanta player again has been closed out at No. 31. Last
year Magee finished ahead of Atlanta's Billy Andrade by less than
$5. Sunday, Cink, an East Lake member who had been relishing a
chance to play for $720,000 this week, came up $57,054 short. That
a friend wound up disappointed muted Magee's excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of feeling for Stewart, being from here,'' Magee
said Tuesday. ``He's a lot better player than I am. He could
probably do a lot better this week playing here and having all this
local knowledge. ... Stewart told me after I missed the cut Friday
that he wanted me to make the cut so I could pass Tom (Watson at
29th), and he wouldn't have to worry about knocking me out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we're all friends out here,'' Magee said, ``and it's
a tough grind we go through. We all root for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   When Magee shot a second-round 74 at Walt Disney, he figured
that his PGA Tour year had ended. Cink moved to a tie for eighth
after 54 holes and would have made East Lake with a solo eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `This guy's going to close it out and play
(well) and send me packing,''' Magee said. ``Which I was kind of
fine with. I really got a reprieve.''
</P>
<P>
   A 14-year veteran with four victories, the 36-year-old Magee
will have fun this week, if he has nothing else. He's been known to
pass $50 to loyal gallery followers to buy themselves a few beers.
Whatever transpires by Sunday, he will enjoy this week's
nothing-to-lose atmosphere and a guaranteed check of at least
$64,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to playing without much stress,'' he said.
``The last two weeks have been no fun at all ... I like to enjoy
myself playing. If you can't enjoy yourself here this week, you
better go see a doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   He shot 2-over-par 72 in Tuesday's pro-am _ not bad for a first
look at the course and with his game slightly tattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to come out this week and totally forget what I was
doing before,'' Magee said. ``Usually, in two days, I'll come up
with something.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
