<SLUG> BC-TUCKER-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carter key for Georgia vs. Florida
 &HT;    By Tim Tucker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Can Georgia beat Florida? Perhaps I should
rephrase the question: Can Quincy Carter beat Florida?
</P>
<P>
   Not to oversimplify matters _ naturally, someone has to catch
Carter's passes, and someone has to block for him, and someone has
to play defense _ but the truth is, this Georgia season hasn't been
very complicated. Accurately described by coach Jim Donnan as ``a
good and solid team, not great,'' the Bulldogs are 6-1 because when
they have needed someone to do something special, their 21-year-old
freshman quarterback usually has done more than a little.
</P>
<P>
   Consider his performance in Georgia's two most difficult wins.
Against LSU, he accounted for 85 percent of the Bulldogs' offensive
yards _ passing, rushing, receiving. Against Kentucky, he accounted
for 79 percent of the Dogs' offense _ and became the first Georgia
player to rush for 100 yards in a game this season.
</P>
<P>
   Given Georgia's void at running back _ and the fact that even a
team with a stellar RB would have difficulty running against
Florida's phenomenal defensive front _ there is no apparent way for
the Dogs to beat the Gators on Saturday without another mega-game
from Carter. Heck, some people around here look at this team and
see a losing record if not for its outfielder-turned-quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd make such an impact as a freshman,''
Carter says. ``I was looking for maybe a running back to have 1,500
yards by now. The luck of the draw fell on me to do more than I
expected. It's been ... very astonishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, he ranks 12th in passing efficiency, just ahead of
Kentucky's Tim Couch; locally, he is just 46 yards short of leading
the Dogs in rushing. A year ago, when Georgia broke its seven-game
losing streak against Florida, he was watching on television, his
minor-league baseball season over and his sights already privately
set on being the Dogs' quarterback against the Gators this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to beat them again and prove it wasn't a fluke,''
Carter says now. ``That's really the statement we are trying to
make.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, Georgia's chances aren't great _ a team without a real
running game vs. the SEC's No. 1 defense. But the Bulldogs'
best-case scenario probably goes something like this: Hold the
Florida offense in check, benefit from the Gators' turnover
tendency, capitalize on Champ Bailey offensively, put Carter in
position to make the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt he'd give us a chance to be better than we actually
were _ or are,'' Donnan says. ``His ability to get out of bad plays
has helped immensely.''
</P>
<P>
   While others marvel at such plays, teammate Jonas Jennings
shrugs. ``Guys look at me when Quincy does something spectacular,
and they say, `God, did you see that?' '' the offensive lineman
said. ``I always say, `Yeah, but I've seen it before.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings was a two-way lineman at Tri-Cities High School in East
Point, playing against Carter's Southwest DeKalb teams. ``I was one
of those guys who used to try to tackle him.'' And does Jennings
ever think about where this Georgia team would be without Carter?
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to think about that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
