<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0110 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAVISTAR28-COX     10-27 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAVISTAR28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UAW members pass contract, ending Navistar strike
 &HT;    By Don Baker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Ohio _ With the threat of losing their jobs fresh
in their minds, United Auto Workers members approved a contract
proposal Tuesday, ending a 24-day-old strike at Navistar's Truck
Sales Processing Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right before the vote, (union leaders) said the next
ratification would be a plant closing if we didn't ratify this
contract,'' said Marshall Gregory, a 20-year employee of the
center.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at the site of what was a picket line for the past
three weeks, Gregory and three other UAW members loaded wood and
signs into the back of a truck after voting Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   UAW Local 402 members voted 72-49 in favor of the contract,
while Local 658 members voted 10-0 to accept the proposal
negotiated Friday. Work at the center was expected to resume
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Bush, UAW Local 402 president, said it is possible the
company would have closed the center if the strike continued.
Navistar shipped trucks from the center to other
truck-customization operations during the strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have likely been sitting down negotiating a plant
closing,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Rosswurm, Navistar's Springfield spokeswoman, said the
company was pleased the five-year contract was ratified, but
wouldn't comment on whether the center faced closing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a desire to get back to work, not all employees are
pleased by the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it's over, but I'm not happy with the results,'' said
Jim Addy, a 15-year employee.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory also said he wasn't satisfied with the deal, saying the
company should have given workers more.
</P>
<P>
   The contract ratified Tuesday was similar to the proposal
rejected Oct. 4, resulting in the strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economic package basically stayed the same,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The package includes a 3 percent lump sum payment the first two
years of the contract, a 2 percent general wage increase the third
year, another 3 percent lump sum payment the fourth year and a 3
percent wage increase the final year.
</P>
<P>
   UAW International financial experts evaluated the original
proposal from the company and told local union leaders that
Navistar couldn't increase the economic offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told by the International union, `Fellas, there's
nothing else there to get,''' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   What the union did gain is more flexibility in scheduling of
personal days off, which was the final sticking point in ending the
strike. Bush said the company also agreed to have four workers
designated as current hires rather than new hires, making them
eligible for more profit-sharing money.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Marshall, Local 658 president, said he was ``very pleased''
with the contract. The local represents the center's office
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Local 402 members said they remain disgusted with the gap in pay
between workers at the center and those at the assembly plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you work over there across the fence, you've got it
made,'' said Herb Harris as he pointed toward the assembly plant
next to the processing center.
</P>
<P>
   Top pay at the assembly plant on U.S. Route 68 is about $22 per
hour, compared to about $15 per hour under the new contract at the
center.
</P>
<P>
   Workers also said they are still grieving the death of Jonathan
McCurry, a 31-year-old striker who was struck and killed by a car
while crossing U.S. Route 68.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
