<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-JUSTICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXEC SAYS AOL CHOSE MICROSOFT BECAUSE OF ITS MONOPOLY POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A top executive of America Online Inc. says his
company would not have formed an alliance with Microsoft were it
not for Microsoft's monopoly power.
</P>
<P>
   AOL Senior Vice President David Colburn said in written
testimony released Tuesday night that America Online chose to give
its customers a browser made by Microsoft rather than one made by
Netscape Communications Corp. because of Microsoft's unique ability
to ``bundle'' America Online with the Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Colburn's testimony bolsters the central allegation in the
government's case against Microsoft, that the company was able to
take advantage of a monopoly on computer operating systems in an
effort to gain share in the market for Internet browsers. Such
activity violates the nation's antitrust laws, the government
alleges.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, an on-line service provider with 13 million
subscribers worldwide, was a much sought customer by Microsoft and
Netscape in late 1995 and early 1996. At that time, America Online
had decided it needed to hire Microsoft or Netscape to make an
Internet browser for it, because the browser America Online had
previously been using was inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   Colburn said Netscape and Microsoft made comparable browsers,
and the primary reason that America Online chose Microsoft in March
1996 was because of its monopoly. America Online was desperate to
have its product bundled with Windows so as not to lose an
advantage to MSN, Microsoft's own on-line service provider, which
was heavily promoted through Windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The willingness of Microsoft to bundle AOL in some form with
the Windows operating system was a critically important competitive
factor that was impossible for Netscape to match,'' Colburn said.
``AOL would not have been willing to negotiate a browser license
with Microsoft had Microsoft not indicated a willingness to bundle
and to promote the AOL client software in some form with Windows.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to win America Online's business, Microsoft agreed to
put an icon for America Online in the Online Services folder on the
Windows desktop, Colburn said. Users can click on the American
Online icon to register for the service.
</P>
<P>
   Colburn said Microsoft insisted in return on ``exclusive
distribution and promotion for Internet Explorer, with few or no
exceptions.'' In other words, Colburn said, AOL was prohibited
``from providing any significant promotion or distribution of
Netscape's Navigator browser.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of the Microsoft agreement, AOL must and does
strictly limit its distribution, promotion and advertising of
Netscape Navigator,'' Colburn said. ``Microsoft has sought to
strictly enforce these restrictions, and has carefully monitored
references to Navigator or Netscape on the AOL service.''
</P>
<P>
   Netscape chief executvie James Barksdale testified this week
that the America Online deal was critical because the large number
of AOL subscribers greatly bolstered Microsoft's share of the
browser market, making it look like Microsoft was making great
strides in the browser wars.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, in a statement released Tuesday night, rejected
Colburn's allegations, saying that America Online has changed its
story over the past two years. Microsoft will have a chance to
cross-examine Colburn today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts show that AOL chose Microsoft because it provided
the technology AOL needed to meet the needs of their customers,''
Microsoft said. ``Microsoft won the competition fair and square.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft argued that Netscape was too slow to agree to build a
special type of browser required by America Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statements in Mr. Colburn's testimony and recent
statements by AOL officials seem to be an attempt at revisionist
history regarding the March 1996 agreement signed between Microsoft
and AOL,'' Microsoft said. ``At the time of the agreement, AOL
stated that a major reason they signed the contract was because of
the technological advantages of Microsoft's technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Colburn will be the second of 12 scheduled government witnesses.
The first witness, Barksdale, was questioned by a lawyer for the
federal government and a lawyer for Microsoft in his fifth and
final day on the stand Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale alleged that Microsoft used its monopoly power to
crush Netscape after Netscape refused to agree to an illegal
proposal not to compete.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic piece of evidence introduced yesterday was a
handwritten note which Apple Computer Chief Financial Officer Fred
Anderson used as a draft for a later phone call to Barksdale. In
the document, Anderson explained why Apple chose to make a deal
with Microsoft, rather than Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple needed to ensure that Microsoft would continue to
provide MS (Microsoft) Office for MAC (Apple's Macintosh
computers), or we were dead,'' Anderson wrote. ``They were
threatening to abandon MAC.''
</P>
<P>
   The government also introduced a Microsoft document that showed
the power of providing consumers the Internet browser with the
Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ```It came with my computer' is the 1 reason people switch to IE
(Internet Explorer),'' the document said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson ruled that the
government can show as much as it wants of the 20 hours of
videotape taken during the deposition of Microsoft Chairman Bill
Gates. Microsoft had objected that if the government wanted Gates
as a witness, they should call him in person, but the judge
disagreed, and said Microsoft could show a videotape of someone
else's deposition if it chooses.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson said ``I sincerely hope I'm not going to have to
listen to three days of (Gates') deposition,'' and Justice
Department special trial counsel David Boies said the government is
attempting to choose just six or seven hours to play in court. A
portion of the tape, which has been much anticipated because it
offers a rare glimpse of the richest man in the world's famously
combative style under pressure, could be shown as soon as Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
