<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS URGE CLINTON NOT TO RELEASE CONVICTED SPY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican congressional leaders called on
President Clinton on Tuesday not to release Jonathan Pollard, the
convicted spy, saying he still represents a threat to national
security.
</P>
<P>
   During last week's Middle East peace talks, President Clinton
agreed to review Pollard's case, after Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu of Israel made his release a last-minute stumbling block
in the negotiations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The White House insists the president made no agreement with the
Israelis for Pollard's eventual release, but the Republicans are
suspicious that Pollard might be granted parole at some later date.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in U.S. intelligence and law enforcement have been
angered that Pollard's case became a point of negotiation in the
peace talks. They believe he was one of the most damaging spies of
the 1980s by turning over huge volumes of highly classified
materials.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter issued on Monday to the president and signed by
House Speaker Newt Gingrich, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and
the chairmen of the House and Senate intelligence committees, the
Republicans said that Clinton should again deny clemency for
Pollard.
</P>
<P>
   They warned that ``should Pollard be released, there is every
reason to believe, based on his own statements, that he would
resume his treacherous conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, the White House said on Monday that ``the president
has made no commitments or predeterminations for the release of
Pollard.'' It said Clinton merely agreed to review Pollard's case.
Arrested in 1985 for spying for Israel while working as a Naval
intelligence analyst, Pollard was sentenced to life in prison in
1987. Clinton has twice before reviewed the case, and twice denied
clemency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 2119EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
