<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROFITS AT AMERICA ONLINE SURPASS STREET ESTIMATES
</P>
<P>
   America Online's quarterly profit and revenue hit records on
strong growth in membership, advertising and electronic commerce.
The provider of access to the Internet said it increased its
membership by 951,000 during the quarter, bringing its total to
13.5 million. During the last year, America Online has added four
million members.
</P>
<P>
   LONG-TERM CAPITAL LAYS OFF 33
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term Capital, the hedge fund established by John Meriwether
in 1993 that nearly collapsed last month, has laid off 33 people,
or about 18 percent of its 178 employees. The fund was rescued last
month by a group of big banks and brokerage firms that invested
$3.6 billion to keep it from failing. The investors now own 90
percent of Long-Term Capital.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS DECLINE ON PROFIT TAKING
</P>
<P>
   Investors cashing in on the stock market's recent gains sent
prices lower. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 66.17 points,
to 8,366.04, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index declined
6.98 points, to 1,065.34. The Nasdaq composite index, which rallied
strongly on Monday, dipped 7.35 points, to 1,717.63.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices rose as Associates Corp. of North America sold $4.8
billion of debt, one of the largest offerings.
</P>
<P>
   A DEFAULT AT A CHINESE COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   One of China's biggest investment companies, Guangdong
International Trust and Investment, has defaulted on an
international bond payment, the first time such a Chinese company
has done so since the Communist revolution in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLING'S REVOLVING DOOR
</P>
<P>
   The spread of the gambling business has created an enormous job
market for politically connected executives, lobbyists and
consultants who can help casino operators.
</P>
<P>
   CARDOSO OUTLINES FISCAL PLAN
</P>
<P>
   President Fernando Henrique Cardoso of Brazil pledged sweeping
budget cuts and unspecified tax increases under a fiscal plan meant
to save Latin America's biggest economy from a financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN TELECOM'S SHARES CLIMB
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Northern Telecom rose $3.9375, to $38.50, after the
seller of phone equipment reported that operating profit rose 58
percent in the third quarter, better than expected by analysts.
Northern Telecom acquired Bay Networks in August, gaining entree to
the data-networking market. Sales in the unit that includes the
bulk of Bay's equipment rose by a third.
</P>
<P>
   IBM BUYING BACK MORE SHARES
</P>
<P>
   IBM has authorized the repurchase of an additional $3.5 billion
worth of its common shares.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT SYSTEM FOR SMART CARDS
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft introduced a computer operating system for smart
cards, which contain microchips that store personal or financial
data, as well as support for the system from 20 hardware makers.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE PERMITS A RECORDING DEVICE
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge has refused the recording industry's request to
halt production of a device that can record and play back digital
music found, often illegally, on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   LOSSES AT 2 JAPANESE CONCERNS
</P>
<P>
   Toshiba and Hitachi reported losses for the six months ended
Sept. 30, illustrating how even Japan's vaunted high-technology
companies are vulnerable to its economic malaise.
</P>
</TEXT>
