<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0124 &Cx1f; tth-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBI-MAGNUSON-SPI &LR;      10-27 1563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBI-MAGNUSON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EISENHOWER ADMINISTRATION TRIED TO USE FBI TO GET DIRT ON SENATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Eisenhower administration unsuccessfully tried
to get the FBI to dig up dirt on Sen. Warren Magnuson as the
Republicans sought a way to defeat the Washington Democrat in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   When the FBI refused to cooperate, a top Eisenhower aide asked
the agency to recommend a private detective who would do the work.
The bureau declined.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' failed attempt to come up with a scandal that
might tar Magnuson is among historical tidbits revealed in the
FBI's extensive files on Magnuson, portions of which were provided
to the Post-Intelligencer under the federal Freedom of Information
Act.
</P>
<P>
   Magnuson, who died in 1989 at the age of 84, has a fabled place
in the history of Washington state politics. The FBI files offer
nothing to dramatically alter Magnuson's place in history, but
provide a variety of previously unreported details about his public
life.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars say the documents shed new light not only on Magnuson
but also on Eisenhower's de facto chief of staff, Sherman Adams,
the aide who asked FBI Director J. Edgar Hoover to investigate
Magnuson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect the political leadership in Washington to
cross an invisible line into dirty tricks or scandal-mongering, and
these documents suggest to me that some invisible line was
crossed,'' said Michael Birkner, the chairman of the history
department at Gettysburg College, who is researching a book about
Sherman Adams. ``It forces us to look a little differently at the
mainstream politicians of that era, by recognizing that the rules
were clearly more flexible than history would tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has slowly been releasing the contents of its files
since 1975, when the federal Freedom of Information Act was
expanded to cover investigatory files compiled for law enforcement
purposes. The FBI now has 400 employees screening requests for
release of files. Over the past 23 years the agency has released
more than 6 million pages of documents in response to more than
300,000 requests.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being heavily edited, the 232 pages released to the
Post-Intelligencer about Magnuson shed new light on the story of
the legendary lawmaker, who from 1931 to 1981 served as a state
legislator, King County prosecutor, congressman and senator.
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings:
</P>
<P>
   _Magnuson had a long and complex alliance with Hoover, the
longtime FBI chief. Magnuson was on Hoover's ``special
correspondent's list'' of favored legislators. The senator invited
Hoover to his second wedding, and Hoover sent the Magnuson a copy
of his 1962 book, ``A Study of Communism.''
</P>
<P>
   But the FBI carefully monitored Magnuson's comments about him,
sending thank-you notes whenever Magnuson spoke kindly of the FBI
director, but restraining its correspondence on an occasion in 1962
when Magnuson made an unspecified ``derogatory statement ...
concerning the director.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1965, Magnuson was addressing Hoover in writing as ``Edgar''
and the FBI was describing Magnuson as ``a good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   _The FBI repeatedly examined Magnuson's background, and even did
a cursory background check on Magnuson's fiancee when the senator
sent Hoover an invitation to the wedding. The only full-blown
investigation of Magnuson was conducted in 1966, when the FBI tried
to determine whether Magnuson had used his clout as chairman of the
Senate Commerce Committee to influence an action by the Interstate
Commerce Commission. The agency reported that ``no prosecutable
violation'' was found.
</P>
<P>
   _The FBI twice passed along to the Army a variety of allegations
about Magnuson's alleged contacts with organized crime,
horse-racing interests and a group sympathetic to Communists. The
FBI told the Army that it found ``objectionable'' various comments
Magnuson made, votes he took and groups he was associated with
early in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Magnuson biographer Shelby Scates said the allegations in the
FBI files were not far from the truth _ he said Magnuson gambled on
horses, met once or twice with mobster Bugsy Siegel and sought the
endorsement of the Communist Party in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   Scates said that Magnuson had a close relationship with Hoover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maggie didn't make enemies, and Hoover was a very powerful
man,'' Scates said. ``My hunch is that they both saw that they
could use each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The documents also shed light on a variety of bizarre incidents
in Magnuson's long career, ranging from the FBI's discovery of a
box of Magnuson's possessions lost on a railway car in 1946, to the
agency's investigation of a man who impersonated Magnuson in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the documents offer a window on the conflicted views of
Americans during the Cold War. In 1951, Magnuson forwarded to
Hoover a letter from a constituent urging the FBI to place
Communists in concentration camps; in 1954 Magnuson forwarded a
letter from another constituent accusing the FBI of ``police
state'' tactics for allegedly arresting suspects at ``unseemly''
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Magnuson's run-in with the Eisenhower administration occurred on
May 5, 1955, when Eisenhower's special assistant Adams called
Hoover ``with the request that we check our files to see what we
have on Warren Magnuson,'' according to a memo from Hoover to his
aides.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI told Adams that it knew nothing derogatory other than
some unsubstantiated allegations that, according to one memo,
claimed Magnuson was ``allied with gambling and racketeers in the
Seattle area,'' and according to another memo, ``ties Magnuson in
with bribes and associations with the criminal element.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams was unimpressed _ the White House had already heard the
same rumors _ and he wanted more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adams stated that it should be obvious that the reason for his
check with us is political,'' said an FBI memo written later that
same day. ``He stated that Magnuson is scheduled to run for
re-election in 1956, and that the White House would like nothing
better than to see him defeated. ... Adams asked what our reaction
would be if he should request that the FBI conduct a special
inquiry type investigation regarding Magnuson.''
</P>
<P>
   (In 1956, Democrats held a narrow majority in the Senate, and
the Eisenhower administration hoped the defeat of Magnuson and a
Democratic senator from Oregon would swing the Senate to Republican
control.)
</P>
<P>
   The FBI refused to conduct an investigation, prompting Adams to
ask the FBI to ``recommend to him the name of a private individual
whom he could use for investigations of this type.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI refused that as well. Adams ``seemed rather perturbed
when he hung up the phone,'' an FBI memo states.
</P>
<P>
   The Eisenhower White House wound up supporting Washington Gov.
Arthur Langlie in a nasty race against Magnuson in 1956. Magnuson
won every county in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Two scholars interviewed about the FBI reports said there has
been no previous indication of Adams trying to use the FBI for
political purposes. They said they considered it highly unlikely
that Eisenhower was personally involved in the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole incident sounds very Cold War-esque, and there must
have been an image that the FBI was available for Adams to do
this,'' said Princeton University political scientist Fred
Greenstein, author of an Eisenhower biography. ``Adams was viewed
as a very blunt, laconic person who could be a very aggressive
partisan, but there has never been anything that would have
indicated he was trying to use the FBI for political purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams was forced to resign his White House post because he had
accepted expensive gifts from an industrialist. He died 12 years
ago Tuesday at the age of 87.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its refusal to investigate Magnuson for Adams, the FBI
did conduct several background checks on Magnuson for the Army and
once conducted a full-fledged investigation. The background checks
reveal the intensity of the FBI's Cold War-era obsession with
anything suggesting sympathy with communists or communism.
</P>
<P>
   In 1951, prior to a trip by Magnuson to the Far East, the Army
asked the FBI what it had on the senator. The FBI described several
concerns about Magnuson's past _ he was loosely connected with the
Abraham Lincoln Brigade, which was alleged to be a communist group;
in the 1940s the congressman had spoken at a ``Tribute to
Yugoslavia'' dinner and had sponsored an anti-poll-tax bill. The
FBI also passed along a Post-Intelligencer article from 1942 in
which Magnuson had accused Langlie of spreading false rumors that
the congressman had associated with horse-racing interests.
</P>
<P>
   In 1953 the Army again requested a background check on Magnuson
and other members of Congress prior to allowing them to attend a
Pentagon briefing on war plans. Similar information was passed
along.
</P>
<P>
   Magnuson was directly investigated once, in 1966, in a
conflict-of-interest case involving possible improper use of
Democratic Party funds and improper influence exerted on the
Interstate Commerce Commission. The FBI has withheld most details
of the case, disclosing only that the primary target was Magnuson's
one-time aide, Fred Lordon, and that ``our review of these reports
discloses no prosecutable violation of the federal conflict of
interest statutes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
