<SLUG> BC-CISCO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HP, Cisco Link Up on Communications Products  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cisco Systems and Hewlett-Packard Co. are teaming up to make it
easier for consumers to use the Internet for everything from
placing long-distance calls to forwarding e-mail to any electronic
device imaginable.
<P>
   Cisco of San Jose and HP of Palo Alto said yesterday they plan
to collaborate on designing products that integrate voice, video
and data communications. By combining their technologies, HP and
Cisco said they can develop products for service providers that are
looking for ways to integrate the two distinct networks that now
manage voice and data communications.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement is another step in Cisco's campaign to fend off
competitors like Lucent Technologies and Northern Telecom. Those
companies, which have traditionally supplied equipment to
telecommunications providers, have been moving into Cisco's
networking turf as their primary customers look for ways to
integrate voice and data networks.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom companies have seen a sharp increase in the amount of
data flowing over their networks and are looking for ways to route,
manage and control the information. Cisco and HP plan to develop
products that can help with that task. They plan to start shipping
products in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole telecommunications industry is up for grabs,'' said
John Chambers, president of Cisco. ``Service providers have to move
to a new revenue stream and are going to look for companies that
will help them move into this new world.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, companies will have one network that controls both
their phone and computer systems. Cisco and HP want to make
products to hasten that advancement.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the two companies are well positioned since Cisco
makes devices that route and control data and HP designs software
that sends voice calls over traditional phone networks.
</P>
<P>
   The companies hope to capture market share by offering
additional services that make it easier to operate on a single
network.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first offerings will be a product called ``universal
follow me.'' It will allow a person to forward all phone calls,
e-mails, voice mails, pages and faxes to a single communications
device, such as a wireless phone. The information will be routed
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Guidon, a senior vice president at HP, said the
companies are also working on ``click-to-talk'' products that allow
a person to communicate with others over their computers. For
instance, a person surfing the J. Crew Web site could click on a
sweater and be instantly connected to a sales representative. The
two could have a conversation over the Internet while looking at
the product on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Another product the firms are collaborating on is call waiting
for the Internet. When a computer user is online, an icon would
flash indicating that someone is trying to get through on their
telephone line. The user could click on the icon and take the call,
then go back to surfing the Web without ever signing off.
</P>
<P>
   While the announcement piqued some interest among industry
watchers, most said they needed to hear more specific product ideas
before deciding whether this is an important step or just a lot of
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this announcement is that big of a deal,'' said
Scott Heritage, an analyst with Warburg Dillon Read LLC in New
York. ``It's too difficult right now to tell what exactly the
products are and how much revenue there might be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
