<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      10-27 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Russia: U.S. is asked for food aid.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has formally asked the United States for food aid for the
winter, Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said, as indications
grew that financial help from the International Monetary Fund and
World Bank will not be turned on again this year. The IMF, which
sent $4.8 billion to Russia in July, has suspended its $17 billion
financial bailout package because the government has not yet
published a budget and is printing money to pay its debts, sending
inflation soaring.
</P>
<P>
   Russia: Yeltsin in sanitarium.
</P>
<P>
   A day after he canceled a trip to Vienna, pleading exhaustion,
President Boris Yeltsin checked into a sanitarium outside Moscow
for an indeterminate period of rest. Yeltsin's office insists that
the 67-year-old president is suffering from general weakness as a
result of a crippling attack of bronchitis.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Pinochet ruling due.
</P>
<P>
   The High Court said it would rule on Wednesday on Gen. Augusto
Pinochet's bid to be set free and avoid extradition to Spain, where
a judge wants him to face charges of murder, torture and
kidnapping. The onetime Chilean ruler, 82, remained under police
guard at a London clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Bavarian abortion ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's highest court ordered Bavaria to fall in line with the
rest of the country and allow abortion clinics. The Constitutional
Court ruled that a Bavarian law prohibiting such clinics was
detrimental to women's health by forcing them to travel to get an
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey: Caspian oil incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey is offering oil companies new incentives to build a
pipeline from the Caspian Sea that the United States considers
strategically vital. According to diplomats in Istanbul, Turkey's
package of concessions for oil companies is likely to include tax
exemptions, reduced transit fees and other incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   North Korea: Food situation improves.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting North Korea, the head of the U.S. Development
Program called the food situation there ``much improved'' compared
with two years ago. But James Gustave Speth said in Beijing that
undernourishment was still common in North Korea, particularly
among older children. Aid programs have focused on children under
7.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: De Klerk waits a day.
</P>
<P>
   Former President F.W. de Klerk postponed his court bid to block
the Truth and Reconciliation Commission from accusing him of
illegal acts, saying he would go to court on Wednesday instead.
Lawyers agreed to give the commission a day to study de Klerk's
case. The commission, which has been investigating apartheid-era
atrocities, is due to make 3,500 pages of its final report public
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Chile: Latin selloffs increase.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a looming economic slowdown, Latin American governments
have increased the rate at which they are selling off their public
enterprises to foreign companies, according to the Chamber of
Commerce of Santiago. Its study reported that the region's
privatizations between January and September totalled $31 billion,
a 6 percent increase over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Bleaker economic outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican economic growth in 1998 will be no higher than 3.7
percent, compared with the 4.5 percent the government had forecast
for the year, according to two studies commissioned by private
business groups. Inflation, which the government had hoped to hold
to no more than 12 percent, is likely to run closer to 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: Menem in London for talks.
</P>
<P>
   President Carlos Saul Menem arrived in London for an official
visit aimed at increasing trade between Argentina and Britain and
putting their 1982 Falkland War behind them. During the visit, the
first by an Argentine leader to Britain since 1960, he will visit
the memorial to Britain's Falkland dead at St. Paul's Cathedral,
but there will be no negotiations over sovereignty of the
Falklands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
