<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 A Plan To Tarnish BofA?   By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The North Carolina bank that bought BankAmerica Corp. exaggerated
recent losses in order to discredit managers of the old BofA and
consolidate its control of the combined institution, insiders of
the former San Francisco bank said.
<P>
   NationsBank Corp., the Charlotte, N.C., bank that took over BofA
at the end of September and adopted its name, orchestrated
reporting of third-quarter investment banking and trading losses to
leave an impression that the old BofA was out of control, the BofA
insiders maintained.
</P>
<P>
   To tarnish the old BofA, the insiders said, the combined bank
reserved more money than necessary to cover investment and trading
losses, and wrote down the value of investments more than market
losses warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may have been trying to make things look worse than they
were,'' said Sandy Robertson, a former director of the old BofA.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank rejected the charge that it manipulated losses for
political reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assertions we took actions for internal purposes are
inaccurate,'' spokesman Robert Stickler said.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, NationsBank insiders pointed out that the recent
earnings report prompted more than a dozen lawsuits charging the
bank with failing to disclose losses as they became known, rather
than exaggerating them.
</P>
<P>
   The new BofA reported October 14 that third-quarter net income
fell 78 percent to $374 million after it set aside $1.4 billion to
cover loan-losses.
</P>
<P>
   When analysts and investors reacted harshly to the report,
NationsBank Chief Executive Officer Hugh McColl moved swiftly to
oust David Coulter, CEO of the old BofA. Coulter quit under
pressure last week, seven days after the new BankAmerica reported
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, no one at BofA is accusing NationsBank of falsifying
financial results. Nor do BofA insiders deny that the San Francisco
bank had significant losses.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, insiders admit, the bank's controversial $1.4
billion loan to D.E. Shaw &AMP; Co., a New York investment firm
specializing in computer-based securities trading, caused big
losses when prices of most nongovernment bonds plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   The more subtle point of  &LR; made by BofA insiders is that managers
have discretion over how much money they must set aside to cover
potential losses and used that leeway to make problems seem worse
than they were.
</P>
<P>
   The new bank, for example, reserved $500 million to cover
``uncertainties in global economic conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   BofA insiders said the amount was arbitrary and had the effect
of overstating the bank's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were lots of nonspecific loan-loss reserves,'' said
Robertson, a Coulter confidant.
</P>
<P>
   The new bank also wrote down the value of the portfolio of
mortgage loans the old BofA serviced by $250 million because
falling interest rates were spurring borrowers to pay off loans
ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   One longtime BofA employee familiar with the situation estimated
the bank would have written down the portfolio's value by just $80
million to cover real losses of income had it remained independent.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the larger write-down came from shifting from BofA's
accounting assumptions to NationsBank's to determine the
portfolio's value, a NationsBank spokesman confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   One matter that especially disturbed analysts was NationsBank's
description of the mortgage servicing portfolio as ``unhedged,''
meaning that the old BofA hadn't protected it from falling interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  That characterization was misleading, the employee said.
BofA's practice was not to hedge each specific business, but to set
up bankwide protections against interest-rate moves.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the old BofA protected itself from losses in the
mortgage portfolio by buying securities whose value rises when
interest rates fall. That securities portfolio had gains that
offset mortgage banking losses, the employee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hedges worked,'' the employee said.
</P>
<P>
   In response to specific allegations about its earnings report,
NationsBank said the $500 million nonspecific reserve simply
replenished unallocated funds the old BofA set aside that were used
to cover third-quarter losses.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's earlier statement that the mortgage portfolio wasn't
specifically hedged is correct, Stickler said.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, analysts said the way NationsBank officials
reported earnings left the impression that the old BofA had severe
financial and risk management problems.
</P>
<P>
   When the combined bank reported earnings two weeks ago, Thomas
Theurkauf, an analyst with the New York brokerage Keefe, Bruyette &AMP;
Woods, slammed the old BofA's management for failing to put in
place adequate risk controls.
</P>
<P>
   Theurkauf's opinion has since changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both companies suffered in terms of trading, but the initial
perception was that all problems related to the old BofA,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The statement that the bank hadn't hedged its mortgage servicing
portfolio ``contributed to that view,'' he said. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
