accident.
</P>
<P>
   No, wait. That would be good because if anyone needed it, the
blood
</P>
<P>
   would be right there. --Age 5
</P>
<P>
   If we could just get everyone to close their eyes and visualize
world peace for an hour, imagine how serene and quiet it would be
until the looting started. --Age 15
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Now This is DEFINITELY Dirty &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Hear about the fellow that was talking to his buddy, and he
said, `I don't know what to get my wife for her birthday - she has
everything, and besides, she can afford to buy anything she wants,
so I'm stumped.`
</P>
<P>
   His buddy said, `I have an idea - why don't you make up a
certificate saying she can have 60 minutes of great sex, any way
she wants it - she'll probably be thrilled.`
</P>
<P>
   So the fellow did. The next day his buddy said, `Well? Did you
take my suggestion?`
</P>
<P>
   `Yes, I did,` said the fellow. `Did she like it?` His buddy
asked.
</P>
<P>
   `Oh yes! she jumped up , thanked me, kissed me on the forehead
and ran out the door, yelling `I'll be back in an hour!!`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHAGGY SHARK STORY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   While sports fishing off the Florida coast, a tourist capsized
his boat. He could swim, but his fear of alligators kept him
clinging to the overturned craft. Spotting an old beachcomber
standing on the shore, the tourist shouted, `Are there any gators
around here?`
</P>
<P>
   `Naw,` the man hollered back, `they ain't been around for
years!`
</P>
<P>
   Feeling safe, the tourist started swimming leisurely toward the
shore. About halfway there he asked the guy, `How'd you get rid of
the gators?`
</P>
<P>
   `We didn't do nothin',` the beachcomber said.
</P>
<P>
   `Really?` said the tourist.
</P>
<P>
   The beachcomber added, `The sharks got 'em.`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUMPER TIME &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I intend to live forever, so far so good.
</P>
<P>
   If Barbie is so popular, why do you have to buy her friends?
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has a photographic memory. Some don't have film.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to meet expenses...they're everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This isn't right. If we're going to get older politicians out of
Washington by sending them into space, why not start with Strom
Thurmond?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a clear choice in this election,'' Mr. Clinton says.
Right. For instance, we could vote or we could stay home and
celebrate Michael Dukakis' 65th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Experts predict close congressional elections and low voter
turnout everywhere Nov. 3. This will come as a surprise to some
people who didn't know there was an upcoming vote.
</P>
<P>
   The next Congress must handle unfinished business from the
previous one, experts say. Apparently only then will it get to make
its own mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   If Democrats regained control of the U.S. House, it's likely the
Clinton impeachment inquiry would disappear. Would some lawyers
Starrve?
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clinton says that at one point in the Middle East
negotiations he was awake for 39 straight hours. People who want
him punished have reached half their goal of getting him tired and
feathered.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can read my writing,'' Mr. Clinton says. Still, we bet
we can tell ``Dear Monica'' from ``Dear Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidel Castro spent 55 minutes answering one question by American
journalists recently, but never addressed what was asked, it's
reported. What's he been doing? Taking Clinton lessons?
</P>
<P>
   Boris Yeltsin now is reported to be suffering unstable blood
pressure. His doctors must be having trouble controlling his proof.
</P>
<P>
   The judge in the Microsoft trial is worried the case is too
slow. Maybe he should install some lawyer upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
