A0174 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPERA-WORDS-$ADV01-NY     10-27 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-WORDS-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE OPERA, WORDS TO LAUGH BY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Words, words, words: opera finds it hard to do without them. In
the 1950s, the German composer Boris Blacher wrote a wordless
``abstract opera,'' to which he gave the imposing title ``Abstract
Opera No. 1,'' though he never repeated the experiment.
</P>
<P>
   He left that to Gyorgy Ligeti, who in the next decade wrote
``Adventures,'' followed by ``New Adventures,'' for three singers
who communicate with one another and with their audience by
nonverbal means: muttering, cajoling, shrieking in surprise. And in
the decade after that, Philip Glass, in ``Einstein on the Beach,''
and Karlheinz Stockhausen, in ``Thursday,'' dispensed for long
stretches not only with words but also with onstage singers, to
create opera as mime.
</P>
<P>
   But these will probably remain special cases. Opera in general
needs singers, and singers need words. The problems start when we
come to what the audience needs.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who say that opera has to be sung in the
original language. Only that way can a word appear where the
composer wanted it to appear, at a particular point in the melodic
phrase, with particular details of harmony and orchestration in the
accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, so the argument goes, the sound and
structure of the language are essential to the sound and structure
of the music. And indeed, a lot of the differences between Wagner
and Verdi stem from differences between German and Italian.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative view is that operas have to be done in the
language of the audience. Opera is theater; it's about people
expressing themselves to you in a language you understand. Why else
should a singer take trouble to enunciate and color the words? Why
else should a composer make sure those words will be
comprehensible?
</P>
<P>
   The history, the forms and the textures of opera all bear
witness to this constant urge to get the words across.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides in this longstanding debate are right, of course, but
both sides can be satisfied only if the original language is one
the spectator understands. Under this condition, very few people
would be able to enjoy everything the Met is putting on this
season: ``Le Nozze di Figaro'' (Italian) and ``Moses und Aron''
(German), ``Khovanshchina'' (Russian) and ``Katya
Kabanova''(Czech), ``Carmen'' (French) and ``Susannah'' (English).
</P>
<P>
   For a while now, supertitles (or at the Met, seat-back titles)
have been taken as providing the best solution: the singers sing
what the composer wanted, while the audience sees what it can
understand. But to see words on a screen is not at all the same as
to hear them sung.
</P>
<P>
   Words on a screen are blank of affect: unaccented, untimed, they
are passionless. Nothing could be more different from how words get
treated by opera singers. There are, too, enormous difficulties in
translating librettos for the purpose of titles, in finding the
right voice for these unsung words.
</P>
<P>
   Take the New York City Opera's ``Partenope'' this season. For
the most part, the titles overhead adopted a formal diction
appropriate to Handel: ``I yield not to your valor but to my
fate,'' or ``A tempest of ferocious passions rages in my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   But occasionally a more contemporary phrase cropped up: ``Shut
up! _ I'm not saying anything,'' or ``Let's forget this _ Whatever
you say.'' Early in the third act you could almost hear the gears
changing as the titles went from ``This is a new disaster for me,''
``What troubles you?'' and ``My end is near'' through ``You worry
too much'' to ``I'd like to have your problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Such slips into the modern vernacular bring unintentional
comedy. The audience may not laugh as much as it did when, on the
day the Starr report was released, one character in the opera
announced, ``I admit my mistake if you'll forgive me.'' But laugh
it will. And the singers will try, as they tried in ``Partenope,''
to act up to accommodate the laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The humor comes not only from the incongruity. It comes from the
fact that somebody is addressing us, literally, over the
characters' heads. Somebody is in the know about what these people
are really saying, behind their 18th-century masquerades. To quote
again from the ``Partenope'' titles: ``Something doesn't feel right
_ Don't be silly.''
</P>
<P>
   The titles, flashing us news about the opera, invite us to
collude in a feeling of superiority over the characters. Instead of
bringing us closer to what the characters are expressing, the
titles take us farther away.
</P>
<P>
   We are given the sense that thanks to the titles, we are privy
to secrets the characters are trying to hide, with all this Italian
of theirs. That impression may make us feel comfortable, but it
does not involve us in the opera.
</P>
<P>
   The Met seat-back titles avoid such unseemly complicity. Because
audience members are all in control of their own cribs, the titles
conjure a private voice whispering in the ear, not a public voice
giving the lowdown from high up. This is more like the situation in
an 18th-century theater, where each audience member could have been
armed with a printed libretto, to be followed during the action in
the undimmed auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   If there are going to be supertitles, though, they could be used
in other ways. After all, there is no reason to assume that a
projection of the dialogue in English translation _ least of all a
projection of the dialogue in vulgarized English translation _ will
tell us what is going on.
</P>
<P>
   One might rather have supertitles that read: ``Allegro molto,
2/4 time, G major,'' or ``Cavatina with solo horn,'' or ``Neat
doubling of muted trumpet with clarinet and violas.'' And let the
characters sing for themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
