<HEADER>
A0176 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-OWNERS-HNS &LR;      10-27 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-OWNERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ If Houston is going to beat out Los Angeles to
get the 32nd NFL franchise, it would help to have the support of
Texas' other team owners.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tennessee's Bud Adams and Minnesota's Red McCombs are not sure
if the NFL will expand to a 32nd city any time soon, but both have
pledged to support Houston when the time comes.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' Jerry Jones favors expansion to a 32nd city, but he
calls Houston a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   At the NFL meetings Tuesday, Bob McNair led the Houston
contingent that made its presentation to the owners. Houston was
sandwiched between the two Los Angeles groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got Los Angeles, the second-biggest market in the
country, out there, and that's what Houston has to overcome,''
Jones said. ``Los Angeles is such a great market. I don't see an
appetite to expand by two teams at this time, so we've got two
cities for one team. That's what we've got to reconcile.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones says he isn't wavering in his support of Houston to get a
team to replace the Oilers. Some believe Jones would work against
Houston because the Cowboys have so many fans in the Houston area,
but he insists that isn't the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to be realistic about it,'' Jones said. ``I
support Houston. The fans down there deserve an NFL team. It would
be great to have another NFL team in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of outstanding people are involved, and a lot of hard
work has been done. I know what a plus it would be to have that
Houston group in there, but that's what they have to overcome.
Otherwise, there wouldn't even be a question.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair said Houston is the nation's fourth-largest city and
10th-largest television market. He doesn't believe size should make
a difference when the owners make their decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is to look at the last two franchises that
were granted,'' McNair said. ``How big are the Jacksonville and
Charlotte markets? There were markets much larger that got passed
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they (owners) look at those three legs of the
foundation that (commissioner) Paul Tagliabue has talked about as
being the criteria: the ownership, market and stadium. I feel very
comfortable about all three.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams, the only NFL owner who resides in Houston, was impressed
with McNair's presentation. Although the Oilers are struggling in
Nashville on and off the field, he claims there is no lingering
bitterness over what happened to him in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   About McNair's presentation, Adams said: ``I sure like what I
saw. I wish I'd had that, but we had the wrong mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston Mayor Lee Brown has taken the opposite approach of his
predecessor, Bob Lanier. Rather than go to war with the NFL, Brown
is lobbying the owners on behalf of the city to get a team. Brown
points out every opportunity he gets that he went to college on a
football scholarship, has ``sacked a few quarterbacks'' and loves
football.
</P>
<P>
   Adams doesn't favor expansion in the next couple of years,
because he doesn't want to divide the network-television pie by
another slice. Eventually, though, the NFL will expand.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue favors expansion to 32 teams by 2002 at the latest.
What Tagliabue wants, he usually gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see a team come to Houston, but I don't know if
we're ready for expansion,'' Adams said. ``I would support Houston
if the timetable's right. Of course, I'd support Houston over Los
Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who left Houston for Nashville because the city and
Harris County refused to build him a downtown domed stadium, has
tried to help McNair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bud has been very helpful to me,'' McNair said. ``He's given
me any information I've asked him for. Any time I've asked him to
look at information we've put together and give his judgment
whether it's valid, he's responded.''
</P>
<P>
   No NFL owner is more excited than McCombs, who bought the
Vikings for $245 million. The Vikings are the NFC's only unbeaten
team, and they have a good chance of reaching the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   When McCombs purchased the Vikings, he said he would support
Houston over any city other than San Antonio, his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I'm not opposed to expansion,'' McCombs said. ``I applaud
Houston's presentation. I was very impressed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
