<HEADLINE>
AMERICA ONLINE EARNINGS SET RECORD IN FIRST QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   America Online Inc. reported record first-quarter profit and
revenue Tuesday, surpassing Wall Street estimates, on strong growth
in membership, advertising and electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Although many companies now provide Internet service, analysts
said, none have emerged with the brand recognition of America
Online. And because America Online still provides substantial
content and specialized online functions of its own, users tend to
spend more time with the service than they do on other so-called
Internet portals. This ability to retain users' attention helps
draw advertisers and vendors.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended Sept. 30, America Online reported earnings
of $108.4 million, or 39 cents a diluted share, more than triple
the $31.7 million, or 13 cents a share, it posted in the quarter a
year earlier. Revenue rose 65 percent, to $858.1 million, from
$521.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding tax benefits accrued from losses in previous years,
America Online earned $68 million, or 26 cents a diluted share,
compared with $19.2 million, or 8 cents a share, in the quarter a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expected America Online to earn 23 cents a share
excluding the tax benefits, according to First Call Corp., which
tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   America Online announced its results after the close of the
market. Its shares rose $1, to $122, on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   America Online said it increased its membership by 951,000
during the quarter, bringing its total to 13.5 million on Sept. 30.
Over the last year, the online service has added 4 million members.
America Online raised the price of its unlimited dial-up service to
$21.95 a month, from $19.95, on April 1, but the growth of its
subscriber base has continued unabated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trends were consistent with what I expected, but the ultimate
financial results were better,'' Steve Case, the chairman and chief
executive of America Online, said in a telephone interview.
``Subscription growth, in a seasonally slow period, was pretty
remarkable, particularly following on the heels of the earlier
price increase,'' he said. ``We're moving now into a seasonally
strong period, so things look pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from subscriptions climbed to $714.7 million, up 65
percent from last year's first quarter. Revenues from advertising
and electronic commerce climbed 133 percent, to $102.8 million,
compared with $44.1 million in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   America Online also said Tuesday that its board had voted to
declare a 2-for-1 split of the company's common stock, effective
Nov. 17. The split is America Online's second this year and its
fifth since November 1994. A stockholder who bought 1,000 shares
for $11,500 at the initial public offering on March 19, 1992, and
held the stock would, after the latest split, own 32,000 shares
valued at $1.9 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
