<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-MITCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE MITCH BATTERS HONDURAN COAST, MOVES OMINOUSLY TOWARD
YUCATAN PENINSULA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANDREW DOWNIE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANCUN, Mexico _ One of the most dangerous hurricanes to hit the
Caribbean in a decade meandered ominously in the region on Tuesday,
forcing thousands of residents and tourists to abandon homes and
resorts in Mexico and Central America.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Mitch, a Category 4 storm, one class below the most
powerful, battered the coast of Honduras and the Bay Islands
offshore Tuesday night, and sent tropical-storm force winds and
heavy rains into Guatemala, Belize and Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in the countries ordered thousands to evacuate their
coastal homes for shelters on higher ground.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico declared a ``maximum alert'' for three states on the
Yucatan Peninsula, closed 37 ports up and down the Gulf and
Caribbean coasts, and sent nearly 1,500 army troops into Quintana
Roo state to prepare for relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Fear-stricken vacationers besieged Cancun airport, seeking
flights that would take them away from Mitch, described by U.S.
forecasters as potentially one of the most catastrophic ever to
buffet the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maximum sustained winds are near 155 mph with higher gusts,''
a statement from Miami's National Hurricane Center said Tuesday
night. ``Some weakening is forecast during the next 24 hours, but
Mitch is still expected to remain a very dangerous hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, when Mitch's 180 mph winds made it a
Category 5 storm, forecasters said that only three other Atlantic
storms were stronger _ Gilbert in 1988, Allen in 1980 and the Labor
Day hurricane of 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Some parts of Honduras and Central America were warned to expect
up to 20 inches of rain, and forecasters said there was a
significant chance of life-threatening flash floods and mud slides.
Coastal flooding from strong offshore winds and large battering
waves was occurring over much of the northwest Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   At least five deaths were reported in the past days associated
with the storm's rains, two in Honduras, and one each in Jamaica,
Panama and Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch's eye was located about 45 miles north of the Honduran
coast late Tuesday. Hurricane force winds extended outward up to 60
miles from the center, and tropical storm-force winds extended up
to 175 miles.
</P>
<P>
   After slowly traveling west northwest for 24 hours, Mitch
changed course Tuesday to head west-southwest at 6 mph. It was
expected to move on that course until sometime Wednesday afternoon,
the hurricane center said.
</P>
<P>
   The storm's path was hard to predict because of its slow
movement and because of a malfunction on a key U.S. government
satellite, one of two the U.S. National Weather Service uses to
track weather. U.S. forecasters said planes and the other satellite
were tracking the storm.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mexican Caribbean resort of Cancun on the northeastern
tip of the Yucatan Peninsula, many tourists heeded the storm
warnings and fled the area Tuesday. Hundreds jammed the airport,
trying to grab a precious seat out.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the predictions of such a destructive hurricane we're
heading to Mexico City,'' said Elaine Gardner, a retiree from
Chicago. ``All morning people were checking out, everybody was
leaving. People are sitting in the lobby with their bags packed.
It's time to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner and her husband were among the lucky ones; they were
able to get on a plane bound for the Mexican capital.
</P>
<P>
   It was far more serious for the mostly poor people who live in
the low-lying coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday afternoon the weather took a rapid turn for the worse
with the sky turning as black as night as rain started to fall
heavily. Winds picked up, bending palm trees along the built up
promenade that runs the length of Cancun's Caribbean coast. Fierce
waves pounded the shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really, really wild,'' said Melissa Weber, an American
who fled nearby Cozumel island on Tuesday morning. ``The ocean was
violent. People wanted off that island!''
</P>
<P>
   Weber said she was prepared to take a plane to anywhere but
after being told there were no more spaces left on a flight to
Houston, she resigned herself to a anxious night in a wind-lashed
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh well,'' she said ``Where's the hurricane party?''
</P>
<P>
   Hotel managers promised guests they would find alternative
accommodations if they deemed it necessary. Cancun authorities set
up several shelters in schools, churches and community centers and
urged locals to go there if they felt unsafe in their own homes.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists said some Cancun residents advised visitors to get out
if at all possible. Many people here have lived through hurricanes
before, including the devastating Hurricane Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   ``The natives were telling us if you have an opportunity to get
out then go,'' said Louis Clemente, a New York accounts executive.
``They know more about this than we do. We've decided we are taking
off and hopefully we'll get out of here before Mitch arrives. It's
an eerie feeling. There's a lot of confusion and you can feel the
tension.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, workers at the modern new airport taped up windows
and reinforced plate glass walls with heavy wooden beams. Airport
personnel were calm yet apprehensive about what they believed was
in store for the coming hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say it is going to be very powerful,'' said laborer Reyes
Polanco. ``I lived through Gilbert and according to what they say
it was nothing compared to what this will be like.''
</P>
<P>
   Those gloomy predictions were laughed off by one south
California couple who after ``watching the weather channel for
days,'' decided they they were not going to let a hurricane ruin
their vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to have an adventure,'' said Linda Dewitt, a Los
Angeles resident who touched down at the airport as everyone else
was trying to take off. ``We could tell coming through the airport
that with all these people leaving we might have made the wrong
decision. (But) it won't be L.A. All we ever get there is sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Downie is a free-lance journalist based in Mexico City.
Houston Chronicle news services contributed to this report. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
