<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0211 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANBY-THEATER-$ADV01-     10-27 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-$ADV01-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: a goat.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Swan materializes as the sodden Prince considers suicide in
a park in the lost hours of the night. The creature is half man,
half swan, seducing and seduced, both savior and satyr. This
initial encounter, a series of love duets danced with increasingly
furious passion, ends the first half of ``Swan Lake'' on a level
that the performance doesn't achieve again until the spectacularly
choreographed death-and-resurrection finale.
</P>
<P>
   he performance has its soft spots for someone like me, who is
not a committed ballet fan. There are gestures in narrative ballet,
such as the miming of dialogue, as in a silent film, that seem only
to break the spell created by music and dance. I would rather such
conventions were eliminated completely. The story isn't all that
subtle anyway, but when it is, it is sometimes more fun to be
confused than filled in.
</P>
<P>
   Bourne has a high old time sending up royal routine and dropping
in isolated references to some of the Windsor family's recent
problems. There is a red-headed Duchess of York figure
(uncharacteristically, rail-thin), a young woman who behaves badly,
and even a mechanical dog recalling Queen Elizabeth's fondness for
corgis.
</P>
<P>
   If you laugh at Bourne's comic conceits, it is not because they
are so witty but because they are recognized. They are extremely
thin compared to the genuinely dramatic impact of the dark fable of
a love that truly cannot be. Bourne is less effective as a satirist
than as a poet of the dance.
</P>
<P>
   At the intermission of the performance I attended, a man said
rather brusquely to his woman companion, ``I guess this is what
they call homoerotic.''
</P>
<P>
   That's no more than partly true. In fact, transforming the swans
from dainty tutu-wearing toe dancers into marauding males
eliminates the camp aspect of the story. The magical thing about
this muscular ``Swan Lake'' is that Bourne's choreography, though
sometimes suggestive, seems far more romantic than erotic, and the
Prince's escape from life is, indeed, a kind of triumph. Carnal
knowledge is beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   Two sets of dancers are alternating in the lead roles throughout
the Broadway run. I saw Scott Ambler, who actually looks somewhat
like Prince Charles, as the prince. Adam Cooper, who has the
sinister good looks of the youthful Sting, played the dual role of
the Swan and his evil counterpart, who turns up at the Queen's
ball, wearing black leather and carrying a riding crop, where he
spurns the prince and dallies with the Queen.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper has the more spectacular assignment, but Ambler, as both
a dancer and an actor, gives the production its center of gravity.
Each performer is superb. ``Swan Lake'' is a memorable
one-of-a-kind event. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Footloose,'' the 1984 movie on which the musical at the
Richard Rodgers Theater is based, was directed by Herbert Ross, a
notable choreographer as well as a witty, sure-footed director.
When Ross makes foolish films, you can bet that he knows exactly
what he's doing and why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Footloose'' is a foolish film that was cannily targeted at the
teen-age market, with which it immediately connected. Set in a
small town where dancing is outlawed, it is about nervy teen-agers
who flirt, dance, play chicken with tractors, dance, smoke dope,
make out and dance.
</P>
<P>
   It has a gorgeous setting (somewhere in the west where the
distant mountains are always snow-capped), a cast of pretty young
performers headed by Kevin Bacon and Lori Singer, and a pulsating
rock soundtrack score that, like the boom-box in the street, hardly
ever stops. It made no sense whatsoever, and nobody cared.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the show tries its darnedest to make sense, to
integrate the songs into a story that doesn't exist, and even to
explore the character of the dopey Christian minister responsible
for the law against dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Bobbie, director of the smash revival of ``Chicago,''
wrote the book with Dean Pitchford (author of the screenplay) and
staged the result, while A.C. Ciulla is officially credited as
choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Footloose'' is without character, charm or wit and after two
acts, it just sort of stops. The dancing is busy, if without much
verve. It looks mostly like exercise. The score, contributed by
various composers and lyricists, makes use of a number of songs
from the film, supplemented by new songs, all of which eventually
sound alike.
</P>
<P>
   As Ren, the young outsider who fights the good fight to make
dancing legal again, Jeremy Kushnier sings and dances with energy
and the promise of an emerging style. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Chepiga's ``Getting and Spending,'' at the Helen
Hayes Theater, is not a disaster. It is an extremely mild,
resolutely uncontroversial comedy-drama about characters who are
simply too nice to be allowed anywhere near a Broadway stage, where
they come across as self-satisfied, politically correct bores.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Phillips (Linda Purl) pulls off a series of
insider-trading deals to net $18 million to help needy families.
Richard O'Neill (David Rasche) is in the process of giving up a
successful law career to get in touch with his inner being (and
God) as a monk. Before taking his final vows, he returns to the bar
to defend Vicki.
</P>
<P>
   The other characters include a couple of comic, ``Going My Way''
monks, a gruff judge (who is a sweet guy underneath) and one of
Vicki's faithful suitors, who also comes up trumps. Watching the
play is like being in an especially cheery 12-step program for a
problem you can't remember.
</P>
<P>
   The actors cannot improve the material, nor can John Tillinger,
a director of taste and humor. James Noone's scenic design
initially looks quite jazzy: a set of two perpendicular and two
horizontal bars, the height and width of the stage and studded with
tiny light bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   These may spell out stock prices or quotations from Bartlett's.
The bars also move swiftly up and down and from side to side to
define playing areas, sometimes (as if by accident) forming the
occasional cross. After 15 minutes, they become seriously annoying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
