A0212 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLYMPIAN-SUIT-HNS &LR;      10-27 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPIAN-SUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMINIQUE MOCEANU, PARENTS SETTLE TEEN'S SUIT TO BE CERTIFIED AS AN
ADULT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Dominique Moceanu and her parents on Tuesday settled
the 17-year-old gymnast's lawsuit to be certified an adult, lawyers
for both sides said.
</P>
<P>
   Details will be released Wednesday, but Dumitru and Camelia
Moceanu have dropped their opposition to her being certified as an
adult, said a source who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Yarrell, Dominique's court-appointed attorney, said she
approved the agreement on Dominique's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was reached at the first face-to-face meeting
between Dominique and her parents since she ran away from their
Spring, Texas, home Oct. 17. It will be presented to state District
Judge John Montgomery Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an emotional time for all three of them, and they
worked through their differences of opinion and reached an
agreement,'' said Yarrell.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers for Dominique and her parents said they would not
comment until Wednesday, releasing only a joint statement, saying,
``The parties have met amongst themselves and as a family unit have
resolved their differences. It is anticipated that an agreement
will be submitted to Judge John Montgomery for approval.''
</P>
<P>
   The parties met during what was scheduled to be a deposition of
Dominique by her parents' attorneys, at an undisclosed location.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement will remove an Oct. 19 temporary restraining order
keeping the Moceanus away from Dominique, said their attorney,
Jimmy Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement only addresses Dominique's request to be certified
as an adult, not her claims that her parents have squandered her
earnings since she turned professional at age 10, Yarrell said.
</P>
<P>
   Roy W. Moore, an attorney hired by Dominique, would not say if
she might take further action against her parents to get an
accounting of her money _ which would require that she be certified
an adult.
</P>
<P>
   As an adult, Dominique will also be able to sign contracts and
earn endorsement money, Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   To be certified an adult, Moore said last week, Dominique must
prove she is living apart from her parents and is financially
self-sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   The Moceanus have denied that they have squandered their
daughter's trust fund, which she won't have access to until she
turns 35.
</P>
<P>
   Dumitru Moceanu, 44, has said he has spent all of Dominique's
trust fund to build a gym _ which his daughter wanted _ at 6120
Louetta in Spring, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Huggins, a friend of Dominique's who has helped her hide
from her parents, has said the gym cost about $4 million to build
and equip. Huggins provided professional services during the
construction of the 70,000-square-foot gym, which opened last year.
</P>
<P>
   Dumitru Moceanu has declined to say how much the gym cost, but
his lawyer, Katherine Scardino, said Monday the cost was about $2
million.
</P>
<P>
   Scardino said all the gyms' revenues go to Dominique's parents.
She said Dumitru Moceanu has told her that he earned $15,000 last
year from the gym.
</P>
<P>
   Yarrell said she proposed to settle the lawsuit with the
Moceanus last Friday by asking them to agree to Dominique's adult
status and allowing a third party to supervise her trust fund. She
said they refused, because the trust fund was a ``family matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu, the only member of the 1996 U.S. gold medal women's
gymnastics team still competing in all gymnastics events, has said
she hopes to compete in the 2000 Olympics in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique and her parents had been scheduled to go to an
emergency hearing Wednesday on her parents' concern about her
safety. They said Dominique was not being adequately supervised by
Yarrell and was under the influence of an undocumented immigrant
and two men of suspect motives, the latter three having helped
Dominique run away.
</P>
<P>
   Yarrell said the Moceanus were initially opposed to allowing
Dominique to be certified as an adult because they feared the three
people who had been helping her flee and hide would leave her
``penniless.''
</P>
<P>
   Yarrell said that fear was groundless and that Dominique has
said she had acted entirely on her own. Dominique said she is
confident her coach, Luminita Miscenco, 26, will be able to stay in
the United States even though she is in the country on a work visa
and was fired by Dominique's father on Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   The two men accused of influencing Dominique, Huggins and Jeff
Pudlo, another coach who was fired Oct. 17, have said they are only
trying to help Dominique. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
