<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 10/27/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) COCOA BEACH, Fla. -- Oct. 27, 1998 --
SCI-SHUTTLE-NOSTALGIA, 10-27 -- As John Glenn prepares to return to
space, Thomas O'Malley at his home in Cocoa Beach, recalls pushing
the button in 1962 that launched Glenn as the first American to
orbit Earth. ``Those were great days, and we survived them,'' he
says. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) FORT COLLINS, Colo. -- Oct. 27, 1998 -- COLO-GAYS-2,
10-27 -- ``It is bad law,'' James Ringenberg says of a ballot
initiative - one of two on next week's ballot that would expand the
anti-discrimination ordinance to include ``sexual orientation.''
``I want Fort Collins to remain a place where people are free to
express their feelings without fear of government reprisal,'' says
Ringenberg, a lawyer who leads the opposition group. (Kevin
Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) FORT COLLINS, Colo. -- Oct. 27, 1998 -- COLO-GAYS-1,
10-27 -- David Swales preparing yard signs supporting initiatives
to extend antidiscrimination protection to homosexuals in Fort
Collins. Defenders of the proposed expansion of the ordinance say
that it will not restrict free speech and that it will not restrict
people's choice of housemates. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- Oct. 27, 1998 -- MD-GOV-RACE, 10-27 -- Gov.
Parris Glendening of Maryland, left, who in 1994 barely managed to
defeat Ellen Sauerbrey, right, appears to be in an even closer race
with her this year. A recent poll points to a statistical dead
heat. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MESQUITE, Nev. -- Oct. 27, 1998 -- GAMBLING-REGULATORS,
10-27 -- A former gambling regulator, who became a top industry
lobbyist, is seeking a license to own 12.3 percent of Casablanca
Resort in Mesquite, about 80 miles northeast of Las Vegas.
legalized gambling has created a robust new market for politically
connected executives, lobbyists and consultants. (John
Gurzinski/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SANTA ANA, Calif. -- Oct. 27, 1998 -- CALIF-HOUSE-RACE,
10-27 -- Sam Romero, who runs St. Theresa's Catholic Gift Shop in
Santa Ana, says California Republicans do not consider him an
American. In other words, he is the kind of blue-collar voter that
Rep. Loretta Sanchez and her Republican challenger, Robert Dornan,
the former incumbent, are spending much of their time and money
courting like lovesick teenagers. (Edward Carreon/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MORENO VALLEY, Calif. -- Oct. 27, 1998 --
VOTER-ISSUES-3, 10-27 -- Cathy Scharwark watching her son play
soccer. When asked about the issues that most concerned them,
almost no one here mentioned the White House scandal, and they did
not think the president should resign or be impeached. ``My life on
Nov. 4 is going to be the same as on Nov. 3,'' says Ms. Scharwark,
a 35-year-old math teacher who is an independent. ``I don't see how
voting one way will change it.'' (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MORENO VALLEY, Calif. -- Oct. 27, 1998 --
VOTER-ISSUES-2, 10-27 -- Pierre and Carol Simpson with their sons,
Davon, 5, and Pierre Jr., 3, at the pumpkin patch in Moreno Valley.
When asked about the White House scandal, virtually everyone here
offered similar answers. Though they condemned Clinton's conduct,
they had more pressing things to worry about. ``They need to leave
him alone,'' says Mrs. Simpson, 31, a cosmetics saleswoman who
votes Democratic. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MORENO VALLEY, Calif. -- Oct. 27, 1998 --
VOTER-ISSUES-1, 10-27 -- ``If we looked at all of Washington and
dug into all of the scandals, there might not be anybody to vote
for,'' says Andy Stetkevich, with his sons in Moreno Valley. ``I'm
pretty happy with the way things are going.'' In a startling
contrast to past years, voter after voter here could not name a
single burning issue that weighed heavily on them. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 27, 1998 -- CLINTON-SOCIAL-SECURITY,
10-27 -- At a White House forum on elderly women and Social
Security on Tuesday President Clinton says that he will continue to
oppose any effort to spend the budget surplus on anything but
Social Security. With him are Wilma Haga, a widow who relies on
Social Security, and Vice President Al Gore. (Stephen Crowley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. -- Oct. 27, 1998 -- TV-NOTES, 10-27
-- John Glenn's space flight is drawing extensive television
coverage. Not only are all the television news outfits, both
broadcast and cable, covering his scheduled launching aboard the
space shuttle Discovery on Thursday, but a variety of specials is
being served up all week. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) JERUSALEM -- Oct. 27, 1998 -- ISRAEL, 10-27 -- Under
pressure to carry out security crackdown, Palestinian police
arrested two men they say confessed to killing Dani Vargas, a
Jewish settler, on Monday. Vargas' wife, right, weeps during
funeral services Tuesday in Jerusalem. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BOSTON -- Oct. 27, 1998 -- MEMORY, 10-27 -- Elie Wiesel,
left, and novelist Aharon Appelfeld, participants in a symposium
that ended Tuesday titled ``The Claims of Memory,'' at Boston
University. The meeting to celebrate Wiesel's 70th birthday evoked
memory's difficult skirmishes - battles where it has clashed with
artistic freedom, morality, fact, writing and sanity. Even Wiesel,
whose writing is all about memory, concedes that there may be ``too
many memories.'' (Michael Quan/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK-- Oct. 27, 1998 -- NY-9TH-AVE-FOOD, 10-27 --
Peasant-style cooking prevails at Los Dos Rancheros Mexicanos in
New York. Along Ninth Avenue, you can pass from a sliver of Korean
fare to outposts of Pakistani, Thai, Senegalese, Swedish, Jamaican
and Puerto Rican food - all within six blocks! (Suzanne
DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) GREAT MILTON, England -- Oct. 27, 1998 --
BRITAIN-BLANC-CHEF-2, 10-27 -- Braised turbot with mussels, served
at Le Manoir aux Quat' Saisons, Raymond Blanc's luscious, recently
expanded and renovated country-house hotel near Oxford, which
originally opened in 1984. It was dazzling from the start, winning
a Michelin star in its first year and a second in its second.
(Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) GREAT MILTON, England -- Oct. 27, 1998 --
BRITAIN-BLANC-CHEF-1, 10-27 -- Raymond Blanc prepares a meal in the
kitchens of Le Manoir aux Quat' Saisons, his luscious, recently
expanded and renovated country-house hotel near Oxford. At 48,
Blanc is one of Britain's most honored chefs. But he started
neither at 15 nor in the kitchen. He started at 21 as a commis
debrasseur - an apprentice busboy, a waiter-in-waiting, clearing
tables. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) AMARILLO, Texas -- Oct. 27, 1998 -- TEXAS-HAMBURGERS-2,
10-27 -- What the croissant is to France, the hamburger is to
Texas. And in the Lone Star state, the long, winding road that
leads to the ultimate hamburger ends in Amarillo, at a place called
Arnold Burgers. Gayla Arnold, the proprietor, loads a pizza-sized
burger into a take-out container. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) AMARILLO, Texas -- Oct. 27, 1998 --
SUB-TEXAS-HAMBURGERS-1, 10-27 -- What the croissant is to France,
the hamburger is to Texas. And in the Lone Star state, the long,
winding road that leads to the ultimate hamburger ends in Amarillo,
at a place called Arnold Burgers. Gayla Arnold, the proprietor,
looks from the door of the eatery recently. (Fred R. Conrad/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PHOENIX -- Oct. 27, 1998 -- OBIT-JUDD, 10-27 -- Winnie
Ruth Judd, pictured here in 1931, spent three decades in an Arizona
state mental hospital as the notorious ``trunk murderess'' in one
of the most sensational criminal cases of the 1930s. She died in
Phoenix on Friday. She was 93. (Arizona Republic Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
