A0228 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUBURNWOES-COX     10-27 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUBURNWOES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bowden affair bitter loss even by Auburn standards
 &HT;    By Rheta Grimsley Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta criminal defense lawyer Timothy Herring is an
Auburn man. Bleeds orange and blue. (A lot.) Keeps his ear to the
ground and his eye on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   I called Tim to see which story he was buying about coach Terry
Bowden's midseason resignation, the shock heard 'round the Auburn
world.
</P>
<P>
   Tim hadn't picked a theory yet, said the whole l'affair de
Bowden seems hopelessly hydra-headed.
</P>
<P>
   But he had written a country song:
</P>
<P>
   ``I've given up football this year, and here's the reason/Can't
drink enough to finish this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Auburn fans are singing the blues. All of us. Not so much
because of the losing, though that's bad. When all you have to
celebrate is a victory over Louisiana Tech the day after your head
coach takes a hike, times are hard.
</P>
<P>
   But we've lost before, Lord knows. Auburn wrote the sequel to
Job. There was 1950 when coach Earl Brown went down 0-10-0. In more
recent years Auburn fans studied advanced stoicism under kind,
hapless Doug Barfield, those steadily depressing, low-down,
mind-messing seasons when we got whupped often as the family mule.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was that gargantuan shadow cast by the
cross-state legend, Bear Bryant. While he was alive and growling,
even in the years we won, we lost.
</P>
<P>
   This is much deeper, much worse. This is an internal squabble
that makes us look ridiculous to the outside world, and that hurts
like hell. It is hell. And maybe we are ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely turmoil in Terrytown,'' William White says.
White is editor of the Auburn Bulletin. He tried to set the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The last few years at Auburn have been pestilence and plague
years of constant infighting _ the governor vs. the board of
trustess, the board of trustees vs. the faculty, budget slashing,
Bowden-bashing. Bowden's abrupt adios last week was the straw that
broke the tiger's back.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that everyone's stunned proves, for my money, that very
few Auburn fans were ready to fire the coach. Yell at him, maybe.
But fire him?
</P>
<P>
   Some students rolled Toomer's Corner when the news got out.
That's the Auburn ritual reserved for a big victory. But students
can be notoriously short-sighted.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden met with his players, told them he was finished and then
sped away in his car to his farm in nearby Notasulga. The players,
bless their hearts, spent Friday night in a Lanett, Ala., motel,
where they wouldn't be disturbed by anything but their own
thoughts. Those were disturbing enough. They hadn't wished Bowden
gone.
</P>
<P>
   There are any number of potential villains here. Bobby Lowder's
name keeps cropping up. He's a rich man who builds things in
Montgomery and _ some say _ is working overtime in Auburn tearing
things down.
</P>
<P>
   If you were rich enough, you might buy a professional sports
franchise, or an island. Lowder prefers to run Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   Lowder has denied it, but many believe he was calling the Bowden
shots. (Several years ago ``Lowder University'' bumper stickers
were seen about campus; he's that ubiquitous.) He certainly had
been instrumental in hiring Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   Did Lowder buy himself a football coach, then decide to return
him, slightly used?
</P>
<P>
   Others blame the athletics director, David Housel. His strained
relations with Bowden were no secret. Housel is a straight-arrow
and probably does prefer his coaches cast in the Big Daddy mold.
But I, for one, don't think he made this decision.
</P>
<P>
   You give a few dollars to your alma mater and hope they'll buy a
new book for the library. If you're a sports fan, you'd prefer they
put a weight machine in the jock gym.
</P>
<P>
   If you give enough, you get good tickets to the games. If you
leave the school your entire fortune, they might even name a
building after you.
</P>
<P>
   But really big decisions at Auburn _ like running off the
football coach _ should swell from the ground up, be a consensus
that roars. And this was nothing like that.
</P>
<P>
   This was either wrong and premature, or we haven't heard
somebody's really good reason yet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
