<HEADER>
A0229 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GARAIL28-COX     10-27 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GARAIL28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spurrier says Dogs nicer under Donnan
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ After Georgia upset Florida 37-17 in Jacksonville
last season, for the Bulldogs' first win in the series in eight
years, many observers probably figured the rivalry had regained
some of its bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, says Gators coach Steve Spurrier, who seems to think the
Dogs are more cordial to him under coach Jim Donnan. Spurrier says
Georgia's players have stopped bad-mouthing him since Donnan
replaced former coach Ray Goff in Athens in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (Goff) was there, you could tell how nasty the players
talked about me,'' Spurrier said. ``That meant that Ray Goff was
talking that way about me to his team, which I think is sort of
silly that he thought that would help. I've noticed the difference
now. Their players, they don't talk nasty about me anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe it's actually Spurrier who has toned down his
comments. His feud with Tennessee coach Phillip Fulmer has been
well documented _ until this year, when the Vols handed Florida a
20-17 loss in overtime on Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've noticed Tennessee's players have stopped doing that, too,
for some reason,'' Spurrier said. ``Maybe I need to say something
to get them to start talking nasty about me again. We've not talked
too nasty. They've just interpreted everything we've said as being
nasty or arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I guess coaches have realized that getting mad at the
other coach doesn't help you beat them. I think that's been proven
over the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Blind routes
</P>
<P>
   Florida wide receivers Steve Shipp and John Capel were two of
the Gators' more heralded recruits in recent memory, with both
earning Parade All-America honors.
</P>
<P>
   But Shipp, a 6-foot-1, 193-pound redshirt freshman from
Charlotte, doesn't have a catch in his second season in
Gainesville, and Capel is being used only on reverse runs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Florida wide receivers coach Dwayne Dixon is using some
unique tactics to improve their pass-catching ability. Shipp and
Capel, one of the nation's fastest recruits a year ago, have been
running routes in practice with blindfolds to improve their route
running and feel for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to make us feel through our routes like if we
have a defender on us,'' Capel said. ``It's scary, but since I've
been doing it, I've actually been running my routes better.''
</P>
<P>
   Catching Quincy
</P>
<P>
   Georgia quarterback Quincy Carter rushed for a career-high 114
yards in last week's 28-26 win at Kentucky, but he could have a
tough time breaking the Gators' containment this week.
</P>
<P>
   Against LSU, Florida shut down Tigers tailback Kevin Faulk and
forced quarterback Herb Tyler to beat them. Tyler was sacked four
times, and LSU rushed for only 57 yards, averaging just 1.6 yards
per carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want (Carter) to run it quite as much as he did
against Kentucky,'' Donnan said. ``We don't want them taking their
shots at him. Kentucky dictated a lot of that, letting him keep it
on the option.''
</P>
<P>
   This and that
</P>
<P>
   Donnan says strong safety Kirby Smart is questionable with a
bruised shoulder. ... Florida tailback Terry Jackson, who leads the
Gators with 577 yards and three touchdowns, returned to light
running on Monday, but he remains doubtful with a badly sprained
right ankle. Sophomore Bo Carroll is back from a bruised knee and
will play. ... Florida kicker Jeff Chandler's father, Donald
Chandler, was a Georgia letterman in track.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
