</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATORS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite 6-1 record, many are unhappy with Florida's offense
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Going into Saturday's big game with Georgia
in Jacksonville, Florida has a 6-1 record and is ranked No. 5 and
No. 6 in the major polls. If the Gators win, they still have a shot
at going 10-1 and landing an at-large berth in the Bowl
Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it looks as if Florida is having another very
good season. But if you listen to the Gator fans, you would think
that the school ought to drop the sport right now and start pouring
all that money into volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Auburn game Oct. 17. After Florida took a 24-3 lead at
halftime, coach Steve Spurrier decided to pull in the reins of his
offense. It appeared to be sound strategy, because word has gotten
around the SEC that Auburn's offense is so bad that it can't score
on a good defense. And Florida has a very good defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way our defense was playing, the only way we lose is if
the offense messes up and gives them the ball deep in our
territory,'' Spurrier said.
</P>
<P>
   The 85,000-plus at Ben Hill Griffin Stadium did not agree. First
came the chorus of boos. Then, they stormed the exits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember looking up late and wondering, `Where did everybody
go?' '' Spurrier said. ``I knew that some day they'd get tired of
my act. I didn't know it would be when we had a 21-point lead
against Auburn.''
</P>
<P>
   Meet the monster that Spurrier has created. From 1991 through
1996, Spurrier and the Gators won five SEC championships and one
national title, in 1996, by rolling to huge numbers with an offense
known as the Fun 'n' Gun. Florida didn't just beat people, they
stomped them into submission. And Gator fans loved it.
</P>
<P>
   For a group of fans that never saw an SEC championship until
1991, it has been a quantum leap on the expectation scale.
</P>
<P>
   In the national championship year of 1996, Florida led the SEC
with 46.6 points per game. Now, the Gators are averaging 31.6
points per game, and they have fewer than 25 points in four of
their five SEC games.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators have struggled at times on offense because of three
key factors: inconsistency created by shuffling quarterbacks Jesse
Palmer and Doug Johnson, Palmer's subsequent shoulder injury and
running back Terry Jackson's ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, our fans have gotten kind of spoiled,'' defensive
tackle Reggie McGrew said. ``They're not happy unless we're rolling
up these huge numbers. Winning doesn't seem to be enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The past two years have seen the departures of such NFL talent
as quarterback Danny Wuerffel, running back Fred Taylor and
receivers Ike Hilliard, Reidel Anthony and Jacquez Green. As a
result, Florida finds itself in 1998 with an average and
mistake-prone offense _ by its standards.
</P>
<P>
   After three games this season, Florida led the nation in
turnovers with 15. So far, Florida has fumbled the ball 21 times,
losing 13. The Gators also have thrown eight interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot, I know people got used to us scoring 40-50 points a
game but right now we're just not playing the way we used to,''
Spurrier said. ``Maybe we don't have the same kind of talent. I'm
not down on our guys. We just have to coach them to play smarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida almost gave away its 16-10 victory at Alabama. Running
back Terry Jackson fumbled going into the end zone, and then Tony
George got beat deep late, giving Alabama a chance to win.
Afterward, Spurrier said his team wasn't ``playing like champions''
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I calmed down after about a day,'' he said. ``But if we had
lost that one, there would have been a lot of sad Gators around
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Spurrier is taking more of a low-key approach to the
offensive woes. And he says the situation is not as bad as people
think:
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida is one of only two schools in the nation ranked in the
NCAA's top 10 in both total offense and total defense. The other is
No. 1 Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida is sixth in the nation in passing offense (348.9 ypg)
and 10th in total offense (470.6 ypg).
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida ranks third in the nation in TD passes with 23.
</P>
<P>
   The yardage numbers remain respectable, but they have been hurt
by turnovers and the inability of the offense to score touchdowns
once it gets inside the opponent's 20-yard line. In Florida's last
14 trips inside the ``red zone,'' the Gators have scored only three
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Florida's 1996 team had 59 trips inside the red
zone and scored 43 touchdowns for a success rate of .729.
</P>
<P>
   For Saturday's meeting with No. 11 Georgia, Spurrier is hoping
for a low-scoring game, as strange as that might sound. If
Spurrier's offense can give him a lead _ any lead _ going into the
fourth quarter, he'll shut down the offense and turn it over to the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job here is to win football games,'' Spurrier said, ``not
just run up a bunch of stats.''
</P>
<P>
   Man, things have really changed around here.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
