<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GTFOOT28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hamilton status remains unclear
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two practice days into Georgia Tech's preparation for
Maryland, the quarterback question doesn't appear to be much
clearer.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Joe Hamilton, who suffered a hip pointer and left
Saturday night's Florida State game late in the third quarter,
returned to practice Tuesday but only to do very limited individual
work. During the first 20 minutes of practice, Hamilton took only a
couple snaps and made a couple short throws, moving gingerly all
the while.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe needs to pick up a lot more if he's going to play on
Saturday,'' Tech coach George O'Leary said after practice.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, O'Leary, while still calling Hamilton
questionable, was more optimistic about his return and that of
running back/receiver Charlie Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a good shot at getting both back,'' O'Leary
said during his lunchtime press conference. ``If anybody's taken
hits throughout these two years, it's been Joe. He handles these
things very well. Charlie does, too. I'd expect both of them
back.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary told Hamilton not to speak with the media until he was
able to participate in practice fully. That may come as early as
today.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was not expected back in practice until today but was
able to do some light running during practice Tuesday. He was not
wearing a sling like he had been while watching practice Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said Rogers' injury was initially thought to be a
shoulder separation but the problem is more related to a nerve in
his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're waiting for him to get a little bit more feeling back in
his arm,'' O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   The real test should come today when both Rogers and Hamilton
are expected to give team drills a try.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, backup quarterback George Godsey has taken over
running the first-team offense. After getting thrown into the fire
Saturday night against Florida State, Godsey is using extra film
work, extra meeting time with offensive coordinator Ralph Friedgen
and the extra practice time to get ready for a possible start and,
at the very least, playing time against Maryland on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Godsey, a redshirt freshman, has played in four games but his
most extensive playing time came against FSU when he was 5 of 10
for 63 yards passing. In his previous three appearances he had gone
2 for 8 for a total of 13 yards passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week was a learning experience for me against Florida
State,'' Godsey said. ``This week is going to be a challenge, too,
if Joe's healthy or if it's my turn. Either way, I've got to
prepare.''
</P>
<P>
   Godsey said he's gotten support from Tech's running backs,
receivers and offensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of timing and being used to someone,''
receiver Dez White said. ``Joe's real quick in his dropback and his
release. George is taller and his release is slower. I think George
will do fine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
