<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    White, team ready to take on Terrapins
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech receiver Dez White got an earful from
some Florida State defenders last Saturday night, one of whom
looked into a television camera and said ``Dez who?''
</P>
<P>
   After spending the game in constant company of good single and
double coverage and making only one catch for a 9-yard gain out of
the handful of passes that came his way, Tech's leading receiver is
looking forward to the Maryland game on Saturday, not to mention
next year's matchup with Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have another opportunity,'' White said. ``I'm
going to get a chance to talk my own trash.''
</P>
<P>
   White meant that in a figurative way, because he's not a talker
on the field. Even so, he wouldn't have had much to say Saturday
night; Florida State held him below four catches for the first time
this season and kept him out of the end zone for the first time
since the Boston College game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was frustrated the whole time,'' White said. ``There were a
lot of times I was open, and we couldn't take advantage of it. We
beat ourselves more than anything they did, with penalties and
turnovers and things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Maryland, White and company will be facing what has been
the league's weakest pass defense. Opposing quarterbacks have the
ACC's highest passing rating against the Terps, 145.2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very optimistic about the game,'' White said. ``I'm
looking forward to going out and playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   If White has hung his head about his performance against FSU,
Tech coach George O'Leary said he hasn't noticed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shows great emotion,'' O'Leary said, ``but he never shows
great sadness.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary nomination
</P>
<P>
   The Football Writers Association of America has included O'Leary
among its 10 nominees for the Eddie Robinson national coach of the
year award. The winner will be announced Dec. 10. The others were:
Arkansas' Houston Nutt, Kansas State's Bill Snyder, UCLA's Bob
Toledo, Oregon's Mike Bellotti, Wisconsin's Barry Alvarez, Tulane's
Tommy Bowden, Tennessee's Phil Fulmer, Arizona's Dick Tomey, and
Missouri's Larry Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Wiley on the net
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Charles Wiley, who will have surgery Thursday to repair
his torn anterior cruciate ligament, sent a message of thanks to
Georgia Tech fans on the Internet on Tuesday morning, writing, ``I
have been overwhelmed with your outpouring of concern and
sympathy.'' He received at least 40 responses from Tech fans.
</P>
<P>
   Wiley still has not made a decision on whether to apply for a
medical redshirt following this season, but he would have the
option because he suffered a season-ending knee injury his
sophomore year only three games into the season. Wiley is a senior
and is on pace to graduate in June.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards in line
</P>
<P>
   Junior linebacker Chris Edwards is coming off his best game this
season, with nine tackles, including one tackle for a loss, and a
quarterback pressure against Florida State, and he might work his
way into a starting spot.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards tied with Travares Tillman, Delaunta Cameron and Jesse
Tarplin for the team lead in tackles for the game.
</P>
<P>
   If Edwards starts, he would have to beat out either senior
Justin Robertson at weakside linebacker or senior Cameron at
outside linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Grantham to start
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle John Grantham, a former walk-on, got his first
career start against Florida State after a good week of practice
moved him ahead of Guenter Kryszon. He had to leave the game with a
sprained ankle and has been limited in practice this week. Grantham
was a back-up played backup on the offensive line last year before
moving over to the defense in the spring. The senior from Lakemont
earned a scholarship before the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
