<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0234 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-FEA28-COX     10-27 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-FEA28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who's No. 1? Sorry, Duval. Your colleagues seem to favor O'Meara
 &HT;    WITH GLFNOTES
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Afew months ago, a more heated discussion could have
erupted about metal spikes vs. Softspikes. Mark O'Meara with two
majors captured in one season? How could there be any doubt about
him winning the PGA Tour's Player of the Year Award, voted on by
the players?
</P>
<P>
   To listen to many of the players assembled here this week for
the Tour Championship at East Lake Golf Club, with David Duval
owning four wins and the chance for a $3 million season, the matter
is still pretty much settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't look strictly at money,'' Tom Lehman said. ``David's
had a phenomenal year, but I'd say it's O'Meara by two lengths.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No contest,'' said Nick Price, the last player before O'Meara
to win two majors in one year, in 1994. ``Even if Duval wins here,
it's not going to make any difference to me, and I don't think it's
going to make too much difference to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's really a question, in my opinion,'' Phil
Mickelson said. ``What I look at is that four wins have been done
as recently as '96, but two majors in the same year (has) been
donewhat, (twice since) '82? I'd be surprised if Mark didn't win.''
</P>
<P>
   The player to win four in 1996 was Mickelson, and he did not get
player of the year. Offering a slight disclaimer, Mickelson said,
``But if David were to win this week and surpass $3 million, I
might have to reconsider.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Mayfair brings up an interesting approach. Here in the
same town where Georgia Tech once shared a national title with
Colorado, he said, ``NCAA football has co-national champions. What
would be so wrong with having co-players of the year?
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to remember that David also finished second in the
Masters,'' Mayfair said. ``If Mark doesn't make the putt, David's
in the playoff. I think if David goes over $3 million this week
with five wins, that's pretty hard to beat. ... But then again, as
long as I've been out here, nobody's ever won two majors in a
row.''
</P>
<P>
   Price was player of the year in 1994, when he took wins at the
British Open and PGA, becoming the first to win two majors since
Tom Watson won the British Open and U.S. Open in 1982. Lehman's
victory in the Tour Championship in 1996, which had followed one at
the British Open, pushed him to the top of the player voting. Even
if Duval were to win $720,000 this week and surpass $3 million,
many players still treat the majors as unique. Most also give
strong weight to O'Meara's World Match Play win over Tiger Woods
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark O'Meara, Mark O'Meara,'' Jeff Sluman said. ``They've both
had unbelievable years, but from what I've read, I don't think
David would say he deserved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson said, ``I think the overall weight of winning a
couple of majors in a year is the most important thing. I remember
in 1980 I won the British Open and five other tournaments and won
PGA of America player of the year, but there was a lot of weight
given to Jack Nicklaus because he won the PGA and the U.S. Open
that year.''
</P>
<P>
   While O'Meara has spoken modestly in discussions about the
player of the year voting, there seems to be a part of him
wondering lately: What do I have to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking to a guy that for many years came in the media
room and everybody asked, `Why can't you win a professional major?'
'' O'Meara said Tuesday. ``Now I've won two major championships,
finished fourth at the PGA and had a reasonable showing at the U.S.
Open. Whether I get the vote or not, I'm not going to let that take
away from everything that's happened.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
