</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lehman hanging in despite hurt shoulder
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At least Tom Lehman hurt his right shoulder in the
process of being a good dad,at the British Open in July. Other
athletes strain their shoulders falling off bar stools. Lehman was
playing with his kids at an amusement park in Southport, England,
when the injury occurred. The physical damage was still the same,
however, and Lehman, with a slight tear in the shoulder, has not
been the same since. He has suffered a huge power loss that
probably will not improve until the shoulder gets complete rest.
``That big, hard draw has become a little fade,'' Lehman said.
After the shoulder kept him from playing at the Sprint
International the week following the PGA and Pebble Beach in
August, Lehman took off for a month, until Kingsmill. Fortunately,
he still had enough surplus cash _ $945,673 _ to maintain the 26th
position and a spot in the Tour Championship at East Lake. ``I'm
glad to be here,'' Lehman said Tuesday. ``I didn't know if I was
going to make it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrade almost certain for Sarazen
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Billy Andrade has all but officially secured a spot in
next week's Subaru Sarazen World Open through one of 10 Squire's
Selections extended by the tournament. The spot became available
when John Huston qualified from the money list, having moved to No.
9 through his win Sunday at Walt Disney World. Indications are that
this week's unseasonably warm weather will continue into next week,
warming up what frequently has been a chilly adventure at Chateau
Elan. Last year, temperatures were in the 40s for the first round.
``You knew it was cold,'' tournament director Lon Fellenz said,
``when Craig Stadler put on a sweater.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip shots
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, Jeff Sluman and Lee Janzen tied for low round in
Tuesday's pro-am with 3-under-par 67s. ... Mark O'Meara already has
won the PGA of America's Player of the Year Award, gathering 130
points to 88 for David Duval, 56 for PGA champion Vijay Singh and
44 for Tiger Woods. The Vardon Trophy, which goes to the lowest
scoring average and was won last year by Nick Price, is treated
nearly as respectfully by the players. Woods and Duval will battle
for the Vardon beginning Thursday. Woods holds a slight edge, 69.10
to 69.14. ... The PGA Tour Wives Association has tickets remaining,
at $100 apiece, for tonight's charity ``Golf Jam'' at the Hard Rock
Cafe. Lehman, Love and Jeff Sluman are among the players attending.
Call 404-527-7101 for information. ... Under the PGA Tour's new
television contract, purses are climbing dramatically in 1999. The
Doral-Ryder Open will go to $3 million, with $540,000 to the
winner. The three World Golf Championship events that debut next
year are $5 million purses, with $1 million first prizes. ... The
autograph policy this week permits autographs only after a player
has finished, from behind the iron fence from the scoring tent to
the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
