<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alignment not likely to change
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Barring a dramatic change of heart by NFL owners, the
new Cleveland Browns will play in the same division as the old
Cleveland Browns when the historic franchise is resurrected in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pittsburgh owner Dan Rooney will present a realignment
plan that would turn the AFC into a conference with four divisions
of four teams each in '99, his typically intransigent peers will
use the proposal only as a model for the long-term. The Browns will
be slotted into the AFC Central, making it a six-team division,
when the owners conclude two days of meetings in Kansas City this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody says we need to shake things up, reshuffle the
deck,'' Rooney said. ``But it's the same, old story: `I'm for
change as long as it doesn't affect me.' The fans must think we're
ridiculous when it comes to (realignment), and they're right.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their placement, the Browns may win some
concessions from the league on anti-tampering rules. Owner Al
Lerner lobbied- Tuesday for a relaxing of the rules so Browns
president Carmen Policy might get a jump on interviewing head
coaching candidates. The current rules prohibit discussions until a
coach's season ends.
</P>
<P>
   Owners heard detailed presentations on Tuesday from three groups
_ one representing Houston and two from Los Angeles _ vying for the
league's 32nd franchise. That team likely will begin play in 2002,
and Houston businessman Bob McNair was said by several owners to
have made an impressive pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The league is expected to announce the site for Super Bowl XXXVI
in 2002 today, with New Orleans a slight favorite over San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
