<SLUG> BC-FBC-FALLNT28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New coach Arena looking to youth for U.S. rebuilding
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The first lineup card that Bruce Arena will fill out
next week as the U.S. national team coach figures to have a number
of unfamiliar faces, but his long-term challenge of reviving
American international soccer fortunes might depend in part on how
well he can heal the wounds from last summer's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Arena, 47, who won the first two Major League
Soccer titles with D.C. United, was introduced formally Tuesday
after signing a four-year deal as coach and technical director
reportedly worth $1 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``New names and faces'' will grace the roster Arena will reveal
today for a U.S. friendly match with Australia Nov. 6 in San Jose,
Calif., but he also said, ``We haven't ruled out anybody'' as the
rebuilding process begins toward the 2002 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to talk to every player who was in the player pool
for France,'' Arena said. ``But right now is a great time to look
at young players and give them a chance to get some experience at
this level.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those players could be former Parkview High star Josh
Wolff, who played the final 11 minutes Sunday as the Chicago Fire
defeated Arena and United 2-0 in the MLS Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Arena will coach United a final two times in the Interamerican
Cup against South American club champion Vasco de Gama of Brazil on
Nov. 14 in Washington and Dec. 5 in Fort Lauderdale. Then in
January, he turns his full attention to the Confederations Cup in
Mexico, where the U.S. is grouped with Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to worry about wins and losses initially,'' said
Arena, who won five NCAA championships at the University of
Virginia. ``Our goal is to build a team that will be able to
qualify for the final 32.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to revisit the World Cup debacle, in which the U.S.
finished last among the 32 teams and was torn by internal strife
between team veterans and his predecessor, Steve Sampson.
</P>
<P>
   ``What went wrong? They didn't win any games,'' Arena said. ``I
don't want to get into the inside of that, but it was a big
accomplishment getting to France.''
</P>
<P>
   Arena's appointment comes in a transition period for the U.S.
The veterans who helped raise the American soccer profile in the
1990 and 1994 World Cups are gradually passing from the scene, but
young players buoyed by the creation of the three-year-old MLS
haven't had enough experience under their belts to step into their
place.
</P>
<P>
   One World Cup veteran who might not be on Arena's first roster
is defender Alexi Lalas, a wannabe rock star who will appear on
tour with Hootie and the Blowfish in Europe next month.
</P>
<P>
   Fire goes for double
</P>
<P>
   Most teams that win championships get a celebration in their
honor; The Fire gets to play another game. After a downtown Chicago
rally in their honor on Tuesday, the MLS champions began preparing
for Friday's U.S. Open Cup finals against the Columbus Crew at
Soldier Field.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
