<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GAFOOT28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulldog Jacksonville natives eager for home spotlight
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ They left Jacksonville a few years ago unheralded,
not regarded enough as college-football prospects to draw genuine
interest from in-state schools Florida or Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Now, defensive back Jeff Harris, wide receiver Tony Small and
offensive tackle Chris Terry return to their hometown Saturday as
starters for No. 11 Georgia, which faces No. 5 Florida in a SEC
showdown at Alltel Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good to go back and play in front of all the people
that watched you play growing up,'' Terry said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps none of the three players, all of whom were signed by
former Bulldogs coach Ray Goff in his final two recruiting classes
in 1994 and '95, could have imagined how far they've come. Harris
and Terry started their college careers at different positions,
while Small waited his turn in a deep Georgia receivers corps. Now,
all three have evolved into late bloomers at Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Small, a 6-foot-2, 215-pound senior, was perhaps the most highly
regarded of the trio, earning state preseason Super 11 honors as a
senior at Nathan Bradford Forest High. Small, whose older brother,
Eddie, was a star receiver at Mississippi, played as a true
freshman at Georgia in 1995, seeing action in six games.
</P>
<P>
   Small had just six receptions in his first two seasons, then he
finally came into his own last year as the Bulldogs' No. 3
receiver, behind seniors Corey Allen and Hines Ward. Small finished
'97with 26 catches for 362 yards and one touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just turned into a very good receiver,'' wide receivers
coach Greg Williams said. ``The guy had the patience and guts to
wait his turn. A lot of guys don't wait that long and turn sour.
</P>
<P>
   Small is making the most of his opportunity. The split end is
second on the team, behind two-way player Champ Bailey, with 26
receptions for 371 yards and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, a 6-foot, 181-pounder, started his career at wideout. A
kicker and defensive back at Allen D. Nease High, he moved to the
secondary as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody told me that he played soccer in high school,''
Georgia strong safety Kirby Smart said. ``There were guys here,
like (former Dogs tailback) Torin Kirtsey from Jacksonville, saying
that he was a kicker in high school. That's all they knew about
him. I was like, `What in the world did we sign this guy for?'''
</P>
<P>
   But Harris has solidified his position at right cornerback,
opposite Bailey, a junior All-America candidate. With opposing
quarterbacks often reluctant to throw to Bailey's side, Harris has
been a popular target this season. But he's answered the challenge
_ he's seventh on the team with 36 tackles and is tied with Bailey
with seven pass breakups and two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like being in the background and the shadows,'' Harris said.
``I'm not a person that likes to be in the spotlight.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry, a 6-foot-5, 285-pound senior from Ribault High, spent his
first three seasons on a crowded defensive line. He moved to
offense in 1996 when Goff was replaced by Jim Donnan, who liked
Terry's size and extremely long arms.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Terry played in the shadows of All-America left
tackle Matt Stinchcomb. But Terry has caught the attention of NFL
scouts, some of which say he could move past his teammate in next
year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's surprising to look back,'' Terry said. ``I never thought
I'd be playing on offense. But I'm not there yet. I've worked hard
to get this far, and I'm going to continue working.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
