<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Joyner big asset to Eagles
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Adrian Peterson and Greg Hill had a major impact on
Georgia Southern's victory over The Citadel last week, but senior
slotback Corey Joyner also was instrumental in the Eagles' victory.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-9, 183-pound Albany native had three receptions for
70 yards, including a 47-yarder that helped Georgia Southern in its
second-half comeback. Joyner also returned two kickoffs for 68
yards and had a 40-yard punt return that put the Eagles in position
for another score.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson had 231 yards and five touchdowns, and Hill added 212
yards of total offense and two rushing TDs, but Joyner's
performance was a third offensive key for the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good, solid player, especially with the ball in his
face,'' Georgia Southern coach Paul Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner's role as a pass catcher has become increasingly
important for the Eagles, who lost starting receiver Chris Johnson
to a fractured ankle two weeks ago. Joyner, a three-year starter,
has emerged as Hill's top receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question he's our best receiver,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest day of Joyner's career came this time a year ago
against East Tennessee State _ Saturday's opponent for the No.
1-ranked Eagles (8-0, 6-0) at Paulson Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In helping Georgia Southern prevail 38-30 in Johnson City,
Tenn., Joyner returned a kick 100 yards for one touchdown and
scored the go-ahead TD.
</P>
<P>
   Nice bounce back
</P>
<P>
   After being drubbed 53-6 by I-A opponent Mississippi State the
week before, East Tennessee State (2-5, 2-3), picked in the
preseason to finish second or third in the Southern Conference,
managed to bounce back this past weekend to beat Furman 22-19 in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really proud of our guys because when you're 1-5, it's
easy to lose a game like that,'' Buccaneers coach Paul Hamilton
said. ``But we're not a bad football. We had the tough schedule
(including Miami), but we had a chance to win the Appalachian State
game (lost 22-17), and we lost to Western Carolina (31-24) in
overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes
</P>
<P>
   All-Amercan offensive guard Mark Williams, who aggravated a neck
injury against The Citadel, is listed as questionable for
Saturday's game. If the 6-1, 307-pound senior from Albany isn't
ready to go, either Michael Anderson (6-0, 250) or fellow sophomore
Dietrich Everett (6-1, 285) will start.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
