r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      10-27 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Why Are eBay Insiders Champing at the Bit to Sell the Stock?  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
If eBay is so hot, why are its insiders so eager to sell the stock?
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It turns out that eBay insiders can unload their common stock
about two months sooner than the underwriting industry usually
requires. And considering the meteoric rise of eBay's shares,
venture capitalists and angel investors must wish they could sell
today.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stock fans and short-sellers that scrambled to cover
their bets helped eBay shares shatter the $90 barrier yesterday.
Shares of the electronic commerce darling finally settled down to
close at $82.50 a share, up $9.13 for the day. EBay shares are now
trading more than four times their initial offering price of $18,
which was set just four weeks ago. Goldman Sachs was the lead
manager.
</P>
<P>
   It stands to reason, then, that eBay must be the best thing to
happen to the World Wide Web since AOL or Yahoo. Right?
</P>
<P>
   Well, as they say at Hertz, not exactly. At least, that's what a
nugget buried deep in eBay's IPO prospectus implies. Federal
filings show that eBay insiders won't have to wait as long as
original investors of most other freshly minted public companies
have had to in the past. And that seems to indicate that some big
shareholders may be champing at the bit to sell their eBay shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a venture capitalist and I owned eBay at a dollar a
share or something, I would want out now,'' notes one hedge fund
analyst, referring to the stock's unearthly share price.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's not uncommon for early-stage investors, such as
venture capitalists or angel investors _ usually wealthy
individuals _ to cash out after a company goes public. What is
extraordinary about eBay's case is that the company's board managed
to wangle a shorter than usual lock-up period.
</P>
<P>
   A lock-up period is a stipulation in the offering's prospectus
that requires inside stockholders to hold their shares for a
specified number of days after the company goes public. The normal
length of a Silicon Valley lock-up clause is 180 says, says Michael
Murphy, editor of the California Technology Stock Letter in Half
Moon Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Such is not the case with eBay. ``As a result of (the) lock-up
agreements ... none of these (inside) shares will be saleable until
121 days after the date of the final prospectus,'' states the most
recent filing on the offering with the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, eBay insiders can begin cashing out of their shares before
the end of January. Yet if the Internet auctioneer is supposed to
be such an electronic commerce marvel, why wouldn't insiders hold
their stock? That's because some original shareholders may know
more about the long-term prospects of the company than the Internet
stock addicts who are driving up the share price, skeptics say.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, eBay's board managed to negotiate the shorter
lock-up at a time when the IPO market was tanking. (EBay's hugely
successful IPO in late September was widely heralded as a sign that
the IPO market was bouncing back.)
</P>
<P>
   Investment banks that underwrite offerings ask for the lock-up
clauses so their sales people can assure institutional investors
that there won't be wanton selling immediately after a stock is
issued.
</P>
<P>
   And given that September was such a rocky month, it is even more
remarkable that the bankers would concede to the abbreviated
lock-up at that time. ``In this kind of (volatile) market, you hope
that the insiders would stay in for six months to a year,'' Murphy
says.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, IPO prospects capable of attracting capital in the
stormy market were hard to come by and competition for the eBay
deal was assuredly intense. Investment bankers call the courtship
of IPO candidates ``bake-offs,'' where the prospective clients try
to negotiate the best terms by pitting underwriters against each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, at the time, Goldman Sachs itself was planning to go
public. (It has since shelved such plans.)
</P>
<P>
   So, it's not hard to conceive that the influential investment
bank had good reason to grant the shortened lock-up: to win the
deal and use it to jump start the idled IPO market.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while Goldman's motives to lead manage eBay's offering
are understandable, it isn't clear why insiders seemingly pushed so
hard for the right to sell their shares sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
