A0250 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-MCCALL-NYT &LR;      10-27 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-MCCALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RE-ELECT CARL MCCALL COMPTROLLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial for Wednesday, Oct. 28: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New York voters have traditionally elected governors and state
comptrollers from different parties. That may be an accident of
history, or an instinctive feeling that the comptroller ought to be
a watchdog over the state's fiscal health who is not politically
beholden to the chief executive. This year, at least, we believe
the precedent is worth following. We have endorsed the re-election
of the Republican governor, George Pataki, and now recommend that
Carl McCall, a Democrat, be re-elected as comptroller.
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller's most important job is managing and investing
the assets of pension programs for state and local government
employees. McCall demonstrates a judicious mix of concern for the
security of the portfolio and the social implications of the
system's investments. We certainly prefer his approach to that of
the Republican candidate, Bruce Blakeman, whose advocacy of reduced
municipal contributions to the system and increased pension
benefits seems irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   McCall has also been energetic in carrying out his
responsibilities to audit city and town agencies, and has
frequently called attention to the growth of debt and other
potential dangers in the state's fiscal picture. But one blot on
his record is his practice of soliciting campaign donations from
companies that do business with his office. This is the same
behavior we have criticized Pataki for, and the fact that the abuse
is bipartisan does not make it more desirable.
</P>
<P>
   Blakeman has said that if he is elected he will limit the size
of these contributions, and McCall has said he will call on the
state legislature to ban them for all officeholders. Neither
approach is sufficient. The comptroller should simply not
compromise his independence by taking contributions from people who
are hoping to get business from his office. We will never be fully
satisfied with McCall until he changes his practices. But Blakeman,
who is running his campaign firmly tied to Governor Pataki's
coattails, does not seem likely to be an improvement. On the basis
of the rest of his performance, we endorse McCall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 2255EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0251 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFING-NY     10-27 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA: GIFT COMES BACK TO HAUNT CANDIDATE  
 MASSACHUSETTS: POLITICAL BRAWL IN HISTORIC BOSTON  
 KENTUCKY: LOOKING FOR BACKLASH IN CLINTON SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1994, after he won election as treasurer of California, Matt
Fong had some campaign money left over. So he sent a $50,000 check
to a conservative Orange County group, the Traditional Values
Coalition, which was promoting a ballot initiative to ban same-sex
marriage in California, a ban he favored.
</P>
<P>
   Now that gift has come back to haunt Fong, a moderate Republican
who this fall is trying to unseat Sen. Barbara Boxer, a liberal
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   When he made the gift, he did not announce it. But a couple of
days ago, word of it leaked out and he has been scrambling to keep
from losing ground in a race so tight that a miscue at this point
by either candidate could mean defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the campaign, Fong picked up the endorsement of the
Log Cabin Republicans, a conservative gay group.
</P>
<P>
   Upon learning of the $50,000 gift, Log Cabin officials
considered retracting the group's endorsement. But then they
decided to stick with Fong, provided he would sign a pledge of
support for a list of gay issues, among them greater financing for
AIDS research and new protection for gay employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to clear the record,'' said Kevin Ivers, a Log Cabin
official.
</P>
<P>
   Fong signed, saying the written pledge merely ``codified'' what
he had orally pledged earlier. As for same-sex marriage, he said he
stood by his $50,000 contribution to the ``defense of traditional
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer said Fong supports ``the extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fong's contribution shows that he is out of the mainstream,''
she declared at a rally on Monday. ``This is a hate group. You
write a check to a hate group, you're making a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   A Political Brawl in Historic Boston
</P>
<P>
   They love a good political fight in Boston, always have. But on
Monday night, things got a bit out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   At Faneuil Hall, in the center of the historic downtown area,
Acting Governor Argeo Paul Cellucci and Attorney General Scott
Harshbarger were having a debate. Locked in a race for governor
that is too close to call, Cellucci, the Republican, and
Harshbarger, the Democrat, were vigorously disagreeing on every
issue that arose, when suddenly Harshbarger raised the verbal ante
and blurted: ``Tell the truth! Tell the truth! Try that for a
change!''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, borrowing a line from Jack Nicholson in ``A Few Good
Men,'' shot back: ``Scott, you can't handle the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   From then on, things went downhill and the give-and-take
deteriorated into a mean-spirited yelling match.
</P>
<P>
   Then the audience joined in, hooting and taunting the debaters,
raucous and rowdy as a revolutionary rabble. The moderator, Charles
Ogletree, a Harvard professor, could not quiet them.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the hall, supporters of Cellucci and Harshbarger _ at
least 10,000 of them, the police said _ were having at one another
with shouts and bullhorns and slashing, whacking placards and, now
and again, fists and feet.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, 75 of Boston's finest managed to get things under
control. So it goes in the city of the Last Hurrah.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for Backlash in Clinton Scandal
</P>
<P>
   Republican candidates have been trying for some time to
capitalize on the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal in their advertising. On
Tuesday the party kicked off a $10 million national advertising
campaign that focuses on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats think they see signs of a backlash, whatever the
Republicans might see, and some now believe there is political hay
to be made out of the hay the Republicans are trying to make.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, for instance, Chris Gorman, a Democrat who is taking
on Rep. Ann Northup of Kentucky, became the third Democratic
challenger in a highly competitive race to begin broadcasting a
commercial that suggests Republicans are overplaying their hand.
</P>
<P>
   Gorman, leaning on a fence post and looking into the camera,
says: ``If you want to spend another two years investigating the
president's sex life, vote for Ann Northup. After four years and 40
million dollars, Ann Northup voted with Newt Gingrich to continue
the investigation. They're so focused on getting Bill Clinton that
they've forgotten about the rest of us. The president needs to be
punished. But we need a Congress that'll end this mess.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 2258EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
