<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAIBORNE DECIDES CLAMORING IS CALLED FOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The lead-by-example days are officially over for
USC linebacker Chris Claiborne, who has become possibly the most
vocal player on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne was not bashful letting the Trojans' offensive
assistant coaches or offensive players know that it was time to
perform at the start of the second half of the Trojans' 17-13 loss
to Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not necessarily the coaches. It's the offensive
players,'' Claiborne said. ``I get on them and they should get on
us (the defense).''
</P>
<P>
   It's a major role change for the middle linebacker, who has
usually been a soft-spoken leader during his USC career. Claiborne
said he is more outspoken because he is a junior and no longer has
two or three years to hope for improvement by the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about the future anymore,'' Claiborne said. ``The
future's now.''
</P>
<P>
   The emotional strain of the season, and mounting losses, are
beginning to take a toll on him. He took Sunday's practice off
because he felt worn down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tired,'' Claiborne said. ``It's not the physical part,
it's the mental. The year's been hard on me. Certainly, it's hard
to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne remains noncommittal about whether he will turn pro
after the season but said Tuesday he's ``having fun at USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty happy and content where I am. College is something
you only do once in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne intends to check with NFL scouts after the season and
it will be surprising if Claiborne stays in school if he remains
projected as a top-10 pick. Claiborne said he will purchase an
insurance policy if he chooses to return, to protect against a
career-ending injury.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Defensive lineman Aaron Williams suffered a neck
stinger in practice and might miss today's practice. Linebacker
David Gibson (sore knee) and cornerback Daylon McCutcheon (sore
calf) rested Tuesday but are OK.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Mark Cusano (sore thigh) returned to practice,
however, and is expected to play this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty encouraged,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``We're
going to have him at the tail end of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Plan remains the same: Mike Van Raaphorst is the starting
quarterback, but Hackett at least left a sliver of doubt about the
possibility that Carson Palmer might start. ``I don't think we'll
make a change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No regrets: Hackett said he was unconcerned about criticism he
received for kicking a field goal instead of going for the
touchdown while trailing Oregon 17-10 with 4:18 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has an opinion about the field goal. Whether they
agree with it or believe in it, I'm the coach and they're not,''
Hackett said. ``It didn't work and it's easy to say when something
doesn't work that I should have done it differently. That's
hindsight. Now people come back and say what if and how come, but
that's ancient history.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, one regret: Hackett did say the one thing he would have done
differently is let Petros Papadakis carry the ball on a third-and-1
situation in the third quarter. Papadakis was stopped for no gain
on a third-down play at the start of the second half, so Hackett
let Chad Morton carry on the next third-down play. Morton was also
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would definitely take that one back,'' Hackett said.
``Instead, we tried something a little different with Chad and he
had the same result Petros did. In retrospect, I would have went
back to Petros, which got us where we were, and we do it again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 2312EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GOV-RACE-NYT &LR;      10-27 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOV-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLONE ENJOYS RARE SIGHT OF HEARTY CAMPAIGN RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (also see NY-VALLONE-PROFILE, a front-page story in the city
edition of The New York Times)  
 (duplication warning: also sent with `a' code)  
 (bl)  
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Speaking to what has been a rare sight in this year's
political campaigns _ a large live audience _ Peter Vallone
exhorted several hundred union members and low-income New Yorkers
on Tuesday to go to the polls next week, telling them that Gov.
George Pataki ``may have a lot of money, he may have a lot of
power, but he doesn't have you, he doesn't have your votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Vallone, the City Council speaker and Democratic candidate for
governor, was addressing a rally at St. Vartan's Armenian Church in
Manhattan organized by the Working Families Party, which was
started this year by several labor unions and the Association of
Community Organizations for Reform Now, an advocacy group with
low-income members.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone is at the top of the new party's ticket, and its
organizers are hoping to win 50,000 votes, which will insure the
party a spot on the ballot in future elections.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone received a boisterous reception from a chanting crowd of
about 450. The enthusiasm seemed to enliven Vallone, who is usually
a rather subdued speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is your election,'' he said. Then, building a crescendo
that brought the audience to its feet, he thundered: ``I promise, I
promise, I promise, I will do my job, I will vote for you. You vote
for me and we together, together, together, will take this state
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Schumer, the Democratic candidate for U.S. Senate,
is also running on the Working Families Party line. He was also
supposed to appear at the rally, but party organizers said he was
running late.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Vallone attacked Pataki for refusing to
debate him. ``It's now 7 days, 11 hours, 44 minutes and 36 seconds
until polls open next Tuesday at 6 a.m.,'' Vallone said. ``My
question for George Pataki is: Where are you and when do you expect
to debate? This is no longer a game. This is an insult to all New
Yorkers.'' He also assailed what he termed questionable
fund-raising practices by the Pataki campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Pataki, who has said previously that campaign aides
were working on arranging debates, said he was concerned that
Vallone would use a debate for personal attacks. ``I want to make
sure we discuss the issues,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, the governor went to Astoria, Vallone's home
base, to accept the endorsement of the Queens Aldos Independent
Democratic Club. He was met by Vallone supporters dressed as ducks
to draw attention to what the Vallone campaign describes as the
incumbent's ducking of debates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 2319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981027.0429 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0382 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GOV-RACE-NYT &LR;      10-27 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOV-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLONE ENJOYS RARE SIGHT OF HEARTY CAMPAIGN RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (also see NY-VALLONE-PROFILE, a front-page story in the city
edition of The New York Times)  
 (duplication warning: also sent with `p' code)  
 (bl)  
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Speaking to what has been a rare sight in this year's
political campaigns _ a large live audience _ Peter Vallone
exhorted several hundred union members and low-income New Yorkers
on Tuesday to go to the polls next week, telling them that Gov.
George Pataki ``may have a lot of money, he may have a lot of
