<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0385 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-LADN     10-27 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TONE NEGATIVE; MORE GAMES LIKELY CANCELED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Guarded optimism gave way to guarded pessimism within a 24-hour
span in the NBA's four-month-old labor schism, and the league will
probably cancel the rest of November's games by the close of
business today.
</P>
<P>
   A nine-hour negotiating session Monday in New York produced
signs of compromise _ ``There's hope,'' Atlanta center Dikembe
Mutombo said afterward _ but by Tuesday the reviews had turned
negative, following a four-hour meeting on noneconomic issues that
failed to bridge any gaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about a lot of issues. I can't say we made a lot of
progress,'' said Jeff Mishkin, chief counsel for the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Issues discussed Tuesday included player conduct and discipline
clauses _ raised in the wake of the Latrell Sprewell incident _ and
adding marijuana to the league's list of banned substances.
</P>
<P>
   Mishkin led the league's negotiating five-person contingent
while commissioner David Stern and deputy Russ Granik attended
owner meetings. The players association had about a dozen
representatives at the meeting, led by attorney Jeff Kessler. Union
director Billy Hunter did not attend.
</P>
<P>
   That the sides are talking at all, and often _ 13 hours in two
days _ is perhaps the best sign since July 1, when NBA owners
imposed the lockout. Still, the NBA's board of governors is set to
meet today and afterward the league will probably announce more
game cancellations as the lockout enters Day 120.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to salvage as much of the season as possible,''
Hunter said. ``I'm optimistic we're going to get a deal. I can't
say it's going to happen this week.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hunter's expression of optimism was tempered by other
statements in which he poo-poohed positive assessments of Monday's
marathon session, during which the key economic issues were
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no progress.... Nothing got done,'' Hunter said
Tuesday morning, responding to comments from some players that
headway had been made the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Granik also sounded negative: ``It's hard for me or anybody to
come out of this meeting encouraged,'' he said late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA has reportedly backed off insistence on a hard salary
cap, however, opening the door for compromise. The league and union
have proposed tax-based systems to inhibit salary growth, though
the two initial proposals were vastly different.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's meeting reportedly produced talk of a ``hybrid''
system, in which the players' luxury tax would be used for two
years, followed by a two-year period with the league's modified
hard cap.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's board of governors will meet this morning, while the
players and union leadership meet separately. The two sides will
resume negotiations around noon eastern time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-27-98 2322EST &QL; 
