<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON RETAINS ONLY TWO COACHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ New Los Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
named his coaches Tuesday, retaining only former manager Glenn
Hoffman and pitching coach Charlie Hough from last year's staff.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson hired former Dodgers catcher and minor-league manager
Rick Dempsey as third-base coach, replacing Joey Amalfitano who
retired after 16 years with the club.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Scioscia, longtime catcher and bench coach under Tom
Lasorda, Bill Russell and Hoffman, was replaced by Jim Tracy, who
held the same position the past four years for manager Felipe Alou
in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The final new coach is hitting instructor Rick Down, who
replaces Mickey Hatcher. Down began in the Angels organization but
gained a reputation as one of the best in baseball during six
seasons with the New York Yankees and Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, who replaced Russell on June 22, is expected to coach
first. Hough received high marks from the pitching staff after
replacing Goose Gregson a week later. Pitchers responded to his
easy manner and knowledge acquired during a 25-year major-league
career.
</P>
<P>
   Manny Mota, who begins his 30th season with the Dodgers, was
retained as a part-time coach and liaison to the Latin players on
the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were very important decisions,'' Johnson said Tuesday
from his home in Orlando, Fla. ``These are the guys there every day
at 2 o'clock preparing this team to do battle. The Dodgers have had
some great coaches over the years and these guys will honor that
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers officials head today to their spring-training base in
Vero Beach, Fla., for four days of organizational meetings. Down,
who lives in Las Vegas, will fly to Orlando and make the 1{-hour
drive to Vero Beach with Johnson. When Down was Johnson's hitting
instructor with the Orioles in 1996, Baltimore hit a
major-league-record 251 home runs. In Down's first two seasons in
New York, the Yankees led the American League in batting.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he wanted Amalfitano to return as third-base coach
in 1999 but balked when Amalfitano asked about the bench-coach
position.
</P>
<P>
   Amalfitano said the third-base job ``was discussed but not
offered.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm walking away,'' Amalfitano said. ``It's the right time,
they're going in a different direction. I decided to walk away. If
someone decides to pick up the phone and talk about a job and is
serious, I'll listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher and John Shelby, who joined Hoffman's staff in late June
after the firings of Gregson, Reggie Smith and Mark Cresse, have
been offered minor-league positions with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict hired: The Dodgers also hired Chatsworth High product
Jim Benedict as the organization's new minor-league pitching
coordinator. Benedict, who also attended Valley College and Arizona
State, replaces Guy Conti.
</P>
</TEXT>
